{"title_page": "Amber Heard", "text_new": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Amber Heard (43723454772).jpg\n| name               = Amber Heard\n| caption            = Heard at the 2018 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birthname          = Amber Laura Heard\n| other_names        = Amber Laura Depp<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/johnny-depp-amber-heard-actors-lawyer-seeks-to-bar-witnesses-from-testifying/|title=Johnny Depp's Lawyer Asks Judge to Prevent Amber Heard Witnesses from Testifying at Restraining Order Hearing|work=People}}</ref><br>Amber van Ree<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2016/06/07/amber-heard-arrested-2009-charge-hitting-girlfriend/85563338/|title=Amber Heard arrested in 2009 on charge of hitting girlfriend|work=USA Today}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1986|4|22|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Austin, Texas]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2003\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Johnny Depp]]|2015|2017|reason=divorced}}\n| partner            = [[Tasya van Ree]] (2008\u20132012)\n}}\n'''Amber Laura Heard''' (born April 22, 1986)<ref name=tvg><!-- Cite covers both birth date and full name Amber Laura Heard. -->{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/amber-heard-285286/bio/ |title=Amber Heard| work=[[TV Guide]] |access-date=February 1, 2015}}</ref> is an American actress and model. Born and raised in [[Texas]], she made her film debut in a minor supporting role in the sports drama ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2004), followed by a series of other small roles in television and film. Her first leading role was in the horror film ''[[All the Boys Love Mandy Lane]]'' (2006), but it was not released in the United States until 2013 due to distribution problems. Her second major role came in the short-running [[The CW]] television series ''[[Hidden Palms]]'' (2007).\n\nHeard's breakthrough came in 2008 with roles in the action film ''[[Never Back Down]]'' and in the [[stoner comedy]] ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]'', which were both box office successes. The same year, she received the Breakthrough Award at [[Young Hollywood Awards]]. Heard continued her career with roles in films such as ''[[The Informers (2008 film)|The Informers]]'' (2008), ''[[The Stepfather (2009 film)|The Stepfather]]'' (2009), ''[[Zombieland]]'' (2009), and ''[[The Joneses]]'' (2009). In 2011, she played the female lead opposite [[Nicolas Cage]] in ''[[Drive Angry]]'', and opposite [[Johnny Depp]] in ''[[The Rum Diary (film)|The Rum Diary]]''; neither were critically nor commercially successful. Subsequently, Heard appeared in ''[[3 Days to Kill]]'' (2014), ''[[Magic Mike XXL]]'' (2015) and ''[[The Danish Girl (film)|The Danish Girl]]'' (2015). She also starred in the indie film ''[[The Adderall Diaries (film)|The Adderall Diaries]]'' (2015), the television musical drama ''[[One More Time (2015 film)|One More Time]]'' (2015), and the [[Martin Amis]] adaptation ''[[London Fields (film)|London Fields]]'' (2018). The latter was due to be released in 2015, but became the subject of a series of lawsuit between its director, Heard, and the film's production company over disagreements in its editing and other issues. The film was finally released in 2018, and was both a critical and commercial flop.\n\nIn 2017, Heard acted as part of an [[ensemble cast]]\u00a0in the indie film ''[[I Do...Until I Don't]]'' (2017) and made an appearance as [[Mera (comics)|Mera]] in the superhero film ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' (2017). She reprised the latter role opposite [[Jason Momoa]]\u00a0in ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' (2018), which became the most profitable [[DC Extended Universe]] film up to that point, and the [[2018 in film#Highest-grossing films|fifth highest-grossing film of 2018]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2018&p=.htm |title=2018 Yearly Box Office Results |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=July 1, 2018}}</ref> The same year, Heard was also named a global spokesperson for the cosmetics giant [[L'Or\u00e9al Paris]]. In 2019, she appeared in supporting roles in the independent films ''[[Her Smell]]'' and ''[[Gully (film)|Gully]]''.\n\nIn addition to her acting career, Heard engages in activism for causes such as [[LGBTQ]] rights and domestic and sexual violence awareness. She is an [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) ambassador and has been named a Human Rights Champion for the Stand Up for Human Rights campaign by the [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]]. From 2015 to 2017, Heard was married to her ''The Rum Diary'' co-star [[Johnny Depp]]. Their divorce drew significant media attention, as Heard alleged that Depp had been physically and verbally abusive towards her through most of their relationship. In 2019, he sued her for defamation after she discussed being a victim of domestic violence in the media. He countered that Heard had abused him, which Heard says is not true.\n\n==Early life==\nHeard was born in [[Austin, Texas]], to Patricia Paige (n\u00e9e Parsons), an internet researcher, and David Clinton Heard, who owned a small construction company.<ref name=wonderland>{{cite web|url= https://www.wonderlandmagazine.com/2019/04/02/amber-heard-spring-19-interview/|title=Amber Heard on her position as a Hollywood voice for justice|work= Wonderland|first=Eve|last=Barlow|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate= May 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=tvg/><ref name=NewsAu>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/five-things-you-need-to-know-about-amber-heard/story-fnk825aa-1226809741190|title=Five things you need to know about Amber Heard|work=NewsComAu|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> She has a younger sister named Whitney.<ref name=tvg /><ref name=THRDec2018>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/amber-heard-aquaman-elon-musk-dedication-activism-1166004|title=Amber Heard on 'Aquaman', Elon Musk, Dedication to Activism|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Tatiana|last=Siegel|date=December 6, 2018|accessdate=May 26, 2018}}</ref> The family lived outside Austin.<ref name=glamour2018>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/amber-heard-january-2018-cover-story|title= Amber Heard Is Nobody's Victim|magazine=Glamour|first=Phoebe|last=Reilly|accessdate=April 19, 2019|date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> Heard's father broke horses in his freetime, and she grew up riding horses, hunting, and fishing with him.<ref name=glamour2018/> She also participated in beauty pageants, although as an adult she has stated that she could no longer \"support the objectification\".<ref name=glamour2018/> When Heard was 16, her best friend died in a car crash. Heard, who was raised [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], subsequently declared herself an [[Atheism|atheist]].<ref name=\"AH will be heard\">{{cite news|first=William|last=Keck|title=Amber Heard will be heard |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-05-29-amber-heard_N.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|location=Mclean, Virginia|date=May 30, 2007 }}</ref> Around the same time, she began reading books by writers such as [[Ayn Rand]], [[Ray Bradbury]],\u00a0and [[George Orwell]], and began questioning society around her.<ref name=wonderland/> At the age of 17, she no longer felt comfortable in Texas<ref name=glamour2018/> and dropped out of her Catholic high school to move to New York City.<ref name=NewsAu/><ref name=wonderland/> She eventually earned a diploma through a home-study course.<ref name=\"AH will be heard\" /> In NYC, she supported herself through modeling,<ref name=NewsAu/> but soon moved to Los Angeles to pursue an acting career.<ref name=glamour2018/>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Amber Heard 2010.jpg|thumb|upright|Amber Heard at the premiere of [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[The Ward (film)|The Ward]]'', [[2010 Toronto International Film Festival]]]]\n\n===Early work (2003\u20142007)===\nHeard's earliest acting work included appearances in two music videos, [[Kenny Chesney]]'s \"[[There Goes My Life]]\" and [[Eisley]]'s \"I Wasn't Prepared\", and small supporting roles in the television series ''[[Jack & Bobby]]'' (2004), ''[[The Mountain (TV series)|The Mountain]]'' (2004), and ''[[The O.C.]]'' (2005). She made her film debut in a minor role in the sports drama ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2004), followed by small supporting roles in films such as ''[[Drop Dead Sexy]]'' (2005), ''[[North Country (film)|North Country]]'' (2005), ''Side FX'' (2005), ''Price to Pay'' (2006), ''You Are Here'' (2006), and ''[[Alpha Dog]]'' (2006), and guest starring spot in an episode of the [[police procedural]] ''[[Criminal Minds]]''.\n\nHeard's first starring role was playing the main character's love interest in [[The CW]]'s teen drama ''[[Hidden Palms]]'', which the network wanted to replace summer reruns of other series aimed for teenage audiences. The series premiered in the United States on May 30, 2007 to mixed to negative reviews. It was also unpopular with audiences, leading the CW to air only eight of the planned 12 episodes before canceling it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/shows/hiddenpalms|title=Hidden Palms|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/index.cfm?section=12&screen=news&news_id=56707 \"Hidden Palms\" Accelerates Its Final Episodes]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''The City Paper'', June 18, 2007</ref> The same year, Heard also appeared in the short movie ''Day 73 with Sarah'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Day 73 With Sarah (2007)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/391074/Day-73-With-Sarah/overview|accessdate=October 11, 2014|work=The New York Times|year=2014}}</ref> the critically panned teen drama ''[[Remember the Daze]]'', and an episode of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Pete|last=Debruge|title=Review: 'Remember the Daze'|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/reviews/remember-the-daze-1200558085/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=July 5, 2007|accessdate=October 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Mainstream recognition (2008\u20142016)===\nHeard gained more mainstream recognition in 2008, when she appeared in supporting roles in the [[Judd Apatow]]-produced [[stoner film|stoner comedy]] ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Amber Heard: The interview|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/amber-heard-the-interview-20081007|website=FHM|accessdate=October 11, 2014|date=October 7, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017011920/http://www.fhm.com/girls/amber-heard-the-interview-20081007|archivedate=October 17, 2014}}</ref> and the martial arts drama ''[[Never Back Down]]'', both of which were box office successes. That year, she won a Breakthrough Award at the [[Hollywood Film Festival]]. Her other 2008 film releases were the critically panned [[Bret Easton Ellis]] adaptation ''[[The Informers (2009 film)|The Informers]]'', in which she was part of an ensemble cast,<ref name=\"Frost\">{{cite web|author1=Frosty|title=Amber Heard Exclusive Video Interview \u2013 NEVER BACK DOWN|url=http://collider.com/movie/article.asp/aid/7229/tcid/1|website=Collider.com|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=October 11, 2014|date=March 10, 2008}}</ref> and ''[[All the Boys Love Mandy Lane]]'', an unconventional [[slasher film]] in which she had one of her first leading roles. Its director, [[Jonathan Levine (screenwriter)|Jonathan Levine]], said he had chosen Heard for the title role because \"there was a certain type of beauty and a certain type of innate intelligence that Amber brought to it that is not something you find every day. Certainly, not something you would find in somebody her age. The wisdom she projects I thought was pretty remarkable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/48929/exclusive-director-jonathan-levine-talks-all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane/|work=Film School Rejects|title=Jonathan Levine interview|last=Tinnin|first=Drew|date=August 23, 2013|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref> ''Mandy Lane'' had already premiered at the [[2006 Toronto International Film Festival]], and had been initially picked for distribution by [[Harvey Weinstein]].<ref>{{cite web|title=After Seven Years, All the Boys Love Mandy Lane is Coming to US Theaters|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=101303|work=[[ComingSoon.net]]|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|date=March 8, 2013|accessdate=March 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane-finally-set-for-release-revisit-an-old-trailer/|work=Slash Film|title=All the Boys Love Mandy Lane finally set for release date|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref> After a negative test screening, Weinstein dropped the film, and it was then released in the United Kingdom in 2008 by a different distributing company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane-trailer.php|work=Film School Rejects|title='All the Boys Love Mandy Lane' Trailer Finally Debuts After Seven Years|last=Wilson|first=Samantha|date=August 23, 2013|accessdate=August 25, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828204803/http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane-trailer.php|archivedate=August 28, 2013}}</ref> It did not have a theatrical release in the United States until 2013. The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' stated that Heard gave her most \"definitive [performance] to date [2013]\" in the film,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-all-the-boys-review-20131011,0,6522321.story |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=October 10, 2013|accessdate=October 24, 2013|last=Olsen|first=Mark|title=Movie review: 'All the Boys Love Mandy Lane' a spellbinding thriller}}</ref> and ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that she gave a \"psychologically interesting performance\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane-movie-review/2013/11/20/d60bd8a8-4d56-11e3-be6b-d3d28122e6d4_story.html|work=The Washington Post|title='All the Boys Love Mandy Lane' movie review|first=Michael|last=O'Sullivan|date=November 21, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:AmberHeard09TIFF.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Heard at the [[2009 Toronto International Film Festival]]]]\nIn 2009, Heard had roles in the critically panned horror film ''[[The Stepfather (2009 film)|The Stepfather]]'' and in three comedies, the limited-release indie ''[[ExTerminators (film)|ExTerminators]]'', the critically and commercially successful ''[[Zombieland]]'', and the box office disappointment ''[[The Joneses]]''. Although she otherwise received relatively little attention from established critics due to her roles being mainly supporting at this point, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that \"she steals the show\" from the film's more established star, [[Demi Moore]], in ''The Joneses''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/film/reviews/the-joneses-1200476211/ |title=The Joneses Review|work=Variety |accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> The following year, Heard starred in the indie drama ''[[The River Why (film)|The River Why]]'' and continued her work in the horror genre in [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[The Ward (film)|The Ward]]'', which was a critical and commercial disappointment. Carpenter has later stated that he was disappointed in the film but \"loved working with Amber and would work with her again without hesitation.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.lesinrocks.com/2019/05/13/cinemas/cinemas/john-carpenter-ah-bon-cannes-est-le-temple-de-lauteurisme/|title=John Carpenter : \"Ah bon, Cannes est le temple de l'auteurisme ?!\" (in French)|magazine=[[Les Inrockuptibles]]}}</ref> She also co-produced and starred in the independent thriller ''[[And Soon the Darkness (2010 film)|And Soon the Darkness]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangoria.com/features/21-fearful-features/4303-amber-heard-in-step-with-the-horror-genre.html|title=Amber Heard: In STEP With the Horror Genre|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHeard's next role was as the female lead opposite [[Johnny Depp]] in the [[Hunter S. Thompson]] adaptation ''[[The Rum Diary (film)|The Rum Diary]]'' (2011), which received mixed reviews<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/The-Rum-Diary/| title=The Rum Diary (2011)| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]]| publisher = [[Flixster]]| accessdate = November 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-rum-diary| title = The Rum Diary Reviews| website = [[Metacritic]]| accessdate =November 7, 2011}}</ref> and was not a commercial success.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rumdiary.htm | title=The Rum Diary (2011) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2011/10/box-office-puss-in-boots-in-time-rum-diary.html | title=Movie Projector: 'Puss in Boots' to stomp on competition | last=Kaufman | first=Amy | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=October 27, 2011 | accessdate=October 27, 2011}}</ref> Heard's other 2011 film release was ''[[Drive Angry]]'', a supernatural action thriller in which she was paired with [[Nicolas Cage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35744/william-fichtner-and-amber-heard-ready-drive-angry |title=William Fichtner and Amber Heard Ready to Drive Angry? |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date=February 5, 2010 |accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> Although the film was critically panned<ref>{{cite web |title=Drive Angry |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/drive_angry |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=January 15, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and underperformed commercially,<ref name=\"Nikki Finke\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/02/hall-pass-weak-1-unknown-holds-2-drive-angry-3d-tanks-at-9-oscar-fave-kings-speech-rises-in-week-14|title='Gnomes' No. 1 In Third Week Of Release; 'Hall Pass' Drops To #2; 'Drive Angry' #9; Oscars Fave 'King's Speech' Doesn't Stutter|author=Nikki Finke|magazine=Deadline}}</ref> film critic [[Roger Ebert]] wrote that she \"does everything that can possibly be done\" with her character, a waitress who becomes entangled in an undead man's mission to save his daughter from a cult.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/drive-angry-3d-2011 |last=Ebert |first=Roger |authorlink=Roger Ebert |date=February 24, 2011 |title=Drive Angry Movie Review |accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref> In February 2011, Heard also appeared on the British television program ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Amber Heard|url=http://www.tatler.com/the-tatler-list/h/amber-heard|publisher=tatler.com|accessdate=June 5, 2013}}</ref> Heard appeared in no new films until 2013, when she starred in the thriller ''[[Paranoia (2013 film)|Paranoia]]'', the action-comedy ''[[Machete Kills]]'', and the satirical drama ''[[Syrup (film)|Syrup]]''. All three were critical and box office failures. Her only film release in 2014, the action-thriller ''[[3 Days to Kill]]'', was a box office success but panned by critics.\n\nHeard had prominent roles in four films released in 2015, which led James Mottram of the British newspaper ''[[The Independent]]'' to call it a \"watershed year\" in her career.<ref name=independent>{{cite news|title=Amber Heard Interview:The Danish Girl star on sexism, transgenderism and marriage to Johnny Depp|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/amber-heard-the-star-of-the-danish-girl-on-sexism-transgenderism-and-her-marriage-to-johnny-depp-a6792691.html|work=[[The Independent]]|first=James|last=Mottram|date=January 1, 2015|accessdate=April 18, 2015}}</ref> In the comedy-drama ''[[Magic Mike XXL]]'' she played a photographer who flirts with [[Channing Tatum]]'s protagonist; like its predecessor, ''[[Magic Mike]]'' (2012), the film was a large box office success.<ref>{{cite news|title=Amber Heard To Co-Star In 'Magic Mike 2'|url=http://deadline.com/2014/09/amber-heard-magic-mike-2-co-star-cast-836817/|accessdate=September 20, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=September 19, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Digital Spy]]'' described Heard as \"a convincing girl-next-door type\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/review/a654554/magic-mike-xxl-review-the-film-you-feared-the-original-would-be.html|title=Magic Mike XXL review|author=Stella Papamichael|date=June 29, 2015|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> Heard also had a small supporting role as a ballet dancer in [[Tom Hooper]]'s critically successful historical drama ''[[The Danish Girl (film)|The Danish Girl]]'' (2015), which premiered at the [[72nd Venice Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/venice-review-tom-hoopers-the-danish-girl-with-eddie-redmayne-alicia-vikander-20150905|title=Venice Review: Tom Hooper's 'The Danish Girl' With Eddie Redmayne & Alicia|work=[[Indiewire]]|last=Kiang|first=Jessica|date=September 5, 2015|accessdate=September 12, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907220149/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/venice-review-tom-hoopers-the-danish-girl-with-eddie-redmayne-alicia-vikander-20150905|archive-date=September 7, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/eddie-redmayne-danish-girl-1201446329/|title=Eddie Redmayne's 'Danish Girl' Set for Nov. 27|last=McNary|first=Dave|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 4, 2015|accessdate=March 21, 2015}}</ref> In her third 2015 release, the independent crime thriller ''[[The Adderall Diaries (film)|The Adderall Diaries]]'', she starred opposite [[James Franco]], [[Christian Slater]], and [[Ed Harris]]. [[Indiewire]] gave the film a mixed review and stated that Heard was \"miscast\" but \"displays much potential and has succeeded in a bid to be taken more seriously.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The Adderall Diaries review|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/tribeca-review-james-franco-embraces-masochism-in-tone-deaf-the-adderall-diaries-20150417|work=Indiewire|accessdate=April 18, 2015}}</ref> Her fourth role in 2015 was opposite [[Christopher Walken]] in the television film ''[[When I Live My Life Over Again|One More Time]]'', which aired on [[Starz]]. For her role as a struggling singer-songwriter, she took singing lessons and learned to play piano and guitar.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Christopher Walken, Amber Heard Sing and Strum in 'When I Live My Life Over Again'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/christopher-walken-amber-heard-sing-786065|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> ''[[International Business Times]]'' described Heard as \"talented enough to share a few heartfelt moments in a character that mostly operates on the defensive.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/when-i-live-my-life-over-again-tribeca-film-festival-review-amber-heard-christopher-1890473|title='When I Live My Life Over Again' Tribeca Film Festival Review: Amber Heard And Christopher Walken Can't Hit The Right Notes|author=Monica Castillo|work=International Business Times|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called her performance \"superb\" and ''The Film Stage'' stated that Heard did an \"admirable job\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/reviews/la-et-mn-mini-one-more-time-review-20160408-story.html|title='One More Time' with Christopher Walken plays a simple tune|last=Goldstein|first=Gary|date=April 7, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefilmstage.com/reviews/review-one-more-time/|title=[Review] One More Time|work=The Film Stage|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her other roles in 2015, Heard played the female lead in the [[Martin Amis]] adaptation ''[[London Fields (film)|London Fields]]'', which was initially scheduled to premiere at the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/sandra-bullocks-our-brand-tom-hiddlestons-i-saw-the-light-to-premiere-at-toronto-1201572271/ |title=Sandra Bullock's 'Our Brand Is Crisis,' Robert Redford's 'Truth' to Premiere at Toronto |accessdate=August 18, 2015 |work=Variety}}</ref> It was pulled from the festival roster after director [[Mathew Cullen]] sued the film's producers, accusing them of fraud and of using his name to promote a cut of the film he did not support.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2226288/london-fields-pulled-from-tiff-after-director-sues-producers/ |title='London Fields' pulled from TIFF after director sues producers |accessdate=September 17, 2015 |work=Global News}}</ref> The film's stars, including Heard, had also written to the producers, objecting to the cut that was seen at press and industry screenings in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/london-fields/toronto-review/ |title=London Fields review |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=September 17, 2015 |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> ''London Fields'' and Heard's performance received highly negative reviews,<ref name=\"Daily Telegraph September 17, 2015\">{{cite news |last= Mulkerrins |first= Jane |title= London Fields review: 'a cartoonish mess' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/london-fields/toronto-review/ |date= September 17, 2015 |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |location= London| accessdate= March 9, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"The Independent September 17, 2015\">{{cite news |last= Aftab |first= Kaleem |title= London Fields, Toronto Film Festival, review: Dystopian drama is no field day to watch| url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/london-fields-toronto-film-festival-review-dystopian-drama-is-no-field-day-to-watch-10506735.html| date= September 17, 2015| newspaper= [[The Independent]] |location=London| accessdate= March 9, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/london-fields-tiff-review-824093 |title=London Fields: TIFF review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=September 17, 2015 |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> and she stated that \"it was one of the most difficult movies to film and it has proven to continue to be difficult...I can't say I did her [the character] justice.\"<ref name=independent/> In November 2016, Heard was sued by the film's producers for $10 million, claiming that she and Cullen made unauthorized changes to the film's script and failed to finish voice-over work.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gardner |first=Eriq |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/amber-heard-sued-by-london-fields-producer-949623 |title=Amber Heard Sued Over Alleged Conspiracy to Undermine 'London Fields' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=November 21, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Pederson |first=Erik |url=http://deadline.com/2016/11/amber-heard-sued-london-fields-failure-to-promote-film-1201858278/|title=Amber Heard Sued For $10M As 'London Fields' Flap Heats Up Again |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=November 21, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Maddaus |first=Gene |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/amber-heard-sued-london-fields-1201923607/ |title='London Fields' Producers Sue Amber Heard for $10 Million |work=Variety |date=November 21, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref> Heard countersued claiming the producers violated a nudity clause in her contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/amber-heard-countersues-producer-of-london-fields-35584755.html |title=Amber Heard countersues producer of London Fields |work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] |date=April 1, 2017 |accessdate=April 1, 2017}}</ref> In September 2018, a settlement was reached,<ref name=\"variety-settlement\">{{cite web |last=Maddus |first=Gene |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/london-fields-producers-amber-heard-settlement-1202927600/ |title='London Fields' Producers Reach Settlement With Amber Heard |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 5, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> and ''London Fields'' was released, becoming a box office failure and earning Heard a nomination for the [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=daily&id=londonfields.htm |title=London Fields (2018) \u2013 Daily Box Office Results |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-amber-heards-london-fields-bombs-at-record-low-160k-1155714 |title=Box Office: Star-Studded 'London Fields' Bombs With $160K, Near-Record Worst for a Wide Release |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=October 28, 2018 |accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===DC Extended Universe and upcoming projects (2017\u20132020)===\n[[File:Amber Heard (42867568355).jpg|thumb|Heard discussing ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' at the [[San Diego Comic-Con|2018 San Diego Comic-Con International]]]] In 2017, Heard appeared as part of an ensemble cast in [[Lake Bell]]'s indie comedy ''[[I Do... Until I Don't]]'' and joined the [[DC Extended Universe]] (DCEU) cast as [[Mera (comics)|Mera]], [[Aquaman]]'s Atlantean queen, in the superhero film ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''. She reprised the role the following year in ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' (2018), which  co-starred [[Jason Momoa]], [[Nicole Kidman]] and [[Willem Dafoe]] and marked Heard's first major role in a studio film.<ref name=THRDec2018/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/amber-heard-talks-star-aquaman-848622 |title=Amber Heard in Talks to Star in 'Aquaman' (Exclusive) |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]| last=Kit|first=Borys|date=13 January 2016|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/movies/184773_amber_heard_confirms_her_aquaman_role_justice_league_dishes_on_interesting_mera_costume/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Amber Heard Confirms Her 'Aquaman' Role in 'Justice League', Dishes on 'Interesting' Mera Costume |work=[[Entertainment Tonight]] | last=Kile|first=Meredith B.|date=17 March 2016|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> She has stated that one of the reasons attracting her to the part was Mera being \"a strong, independent, self-possessed superhero in her own right\",<ref name=THRDec2018/> who rejects being called Aquawoman instead of by her own name.<ref name=glamour2018/> ''Aquaman'' became the fifth most profitable release of 2018, and the most profitable DCEU installment up to that point.<ref name=profit>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/aquaman-box-office-profit-2018-1202584701/|title=James Wan's $1B+ 'Aquaman' Became DC's Lifeboat After 'Justice League' Debacle: No. 5 In 2018 Most Valuable Blockbuster Tournament|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 28, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> The same year, Heard was appointed global ambassador for cosmetics giant [[L'Or\u00e9al Paris]].<ref name=glamour2018/>\n\nIn 2019, Heard played supporting roles in the independent dramas ''[[Her Smell]]'' and ''[[Gully (film)|Gully]]''. Her upcoming projects included the [[CBS All Access]] miniseries ''[[The Stand (upcoming miniseries)|The Stand]]'', based on [[Stephen King]]'s eponymous [[The Stand (novel)|novel]] and co-starring [[James Marsden]], [[Odessa Young]] and [[Henry Zaga]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/james-marsden-amber-heard-the-strand-cbs-all-access-1203288512/|title=James Marsden, Amber Heard Among Four Cast in 'The Stand' at CBS All Access|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Will|last=Thorne|date=August 1, 2019|accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nHeard has raised awareness about [[Domestic abuse|domestic]] and [[sexual violence]]. Together with actors [[Gabourey Sidibe]] and [[Freida Pinto]], she read a speech on behalf of sexual assault victim [[People v. Turner|Emily Doe]] at ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''{{'s}} Women of the Year Awards in 2016; Doe was the recipient of an award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/emily-doe-stanford-rape-case-speech-michelle-dauber-glamour-women-of-the-year-awards-watch-a7418861.html|title=Stanford rape case survivor gives powerful speech at Glamour Women of the Year Awards|first=Rachael|last=Revesz|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=November 15, 2016|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> Heard also made a [[public service announcement]] about domestic violence for the #GirlGaze Project,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/amber-heard-domestic-violence-psa-video-1201927174/|title=Amber Heard Films Domestic Violence PSA: 'We Can Change This'|first=Seth|last=Kelley|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 26, 2016|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> and has written about her experiences of domestic violence in the December 2016 issue of ''Porter'' magazine<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/amber-heard-domestic-violence-open-letter-porter-a7472426.html|title=Amber Heard pens emotionally charged letter about domestic violence|first=Maya|last=Oppenheim|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=December 13, 2016|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> and in an [[op-ed]] for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttps://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/ive-seen-how-institutions-protect-men-accused-of-abuse-heres-what-we-can-do/2018/12/18/71fd876a-02ed-11e9-b5df-5d3874f1ac36_story.html |title=Amber Heard: I spoke up against sexual violence \u2014 and faced our culture's wrath. That has to change.|first=Amber|last=Heard|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 18, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref> She has been an [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) ambassador for women's rights with a focus on gender-based violence since December 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.aclu.org/issues/aclu-ambassador-project|publisher=[[American Civil Liberties Union]]|title=ACLU Ambassador Project|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BrlgL-XgsV6/|publisher=Amber Heard Official Instagram Account|title=I'm honored to announce my role as an @ACLU_nationwide ambassador on women's rights. [...]|date=December 20, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref> and has also been named a Human Rights Champion for the Stand Up for Human Rights campaign by the [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standup4humanrights.org/en/hr-champions-aheard.html|publisher=Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights|title=Human Rights Champions|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref> In May 2019, she gave a speech in support of the SHIELD Act on [[Capitol Hill]], discussing her experience of having had her private nude photos hacked and distributed online without her consent during the [[iCloud leaks of celebrity photos]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/05/22/cause-celeb-amber-heard-backs-revenge-porn-bill-capitol-hill/|title=Cause Celeb: Amber Heard backs 'revenge porn' bill on Capitol Hill|first=Emily|last=Heil|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=May 22, 2019|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> On November 4, 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published an op-ed written by Heard on the subject.<ref name=NYTop-ed>{{cite news|title=Amber Heard: Are We All Celebrities Now?|last=Heard|first=Amber|date=November 4, 2019|accessdate=January 15, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/04/opinion/amber-heard-revenge-porn.html}}</ref> In September 2019, she appeared at [[WE Day|WE Day UN]], an event arranged by [[WE Charity]] and [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS|UNAIDS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/19296-stars-announced-for-we-day-un|title=Stars Announced For WE Day UN|website=looktothestars.org|date=24 September 2019|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:AmberHeardTIFFSept10.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Heard at the 2010 Toronto International Film Festival]] In a 2008 interview, Heard stated that she is [[agnostic]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Amber Heard: Pretty Girl Makes Good|work=[[Missbehave]]|url=http://www.robbrink.com/2008/04/22/amber-heard-pretty-girl-makes-good/|accessdate=October 3, 2019|date=April 22, 2008}}</ref> She is fluent in [[American Sign Language]] and Spanish.<ref name=\"things\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vogue.com.au/celebrity/interviews/what-you-probably-didnt-already-know-about-amber-heard/news-story/9fae5e20495c6cc921f5b21e8ac7664b |title=What You Probably Didn't Already Know About Amber Heard |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |date=January 22, 2014 |accessdate=January 18, 2020 |last=Frank |first=Julia}}</ref>\n\nHeard publicly [[Coming out|came out]]<!--NOTE: Per WP:BLP, especially WP:BLPCAT, Heard is not to be added to the lesbian or bisexual category until she publicly identifies as either lesbian or bisexual. She has publicly identified as being a part of the LGBT community. While sources have identified her as lesbian or bisexual, she has yet to publicly specify her sexual orientation. See past talk page discussions about this. --> at [[GLAAD]]'s 25th anniversary event in 2010,<ref name=\"Halterman\">{{cite web|last=Halterman|first=J.|title=EXCLUSIVE: Amber Heard talks about being out in Hollywood|publisher=[[AfterEllen.com]]|date=December 4, 2010|accessdate=October 10, 2014|url=http://www.afterellen.com/exclusive-amber-heard-talks-about-being-out-in-hollywood/12/2010/}}</ref> but has stated, \"I don't label myself one way or another\u2014I have had successful relationships with men and now a woman. I love who I love; it's the person that matters.\"<ref name=\"Frize\">{{cite news|author=Sam Frize|title=5 Things You Should Know About Amber Heard|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=January 19, 2014|accessdate=September 6, 2017|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2014/01/19/5-things-you-should-know-about-amber-heard/}}</ref> Of her decision to come out, she said: \"I think when I became aware of my role in the media, I had to ask myself an important question 'Am I part of the problem?' And I think that when millions and millions of hard-working, taxpaying Americans are denied their rights and denied their equality you have to ask yourself what are the factors that are an epidemic problem and that's what this is.\"<ref name=\"Halterman\" /> \n\nHeard was in a relationship with photographer [[Tasya van Ree]] from 2008 to 2012.<ref name=\"Halterman\" /><ref name=LAtimesengagement>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-johnny-depp-amber-heard-engagement-rumors-engaged-20140117-story.html|title=Johnny Depp and Amber Heard spark engagement rumors|last=Saad|first=Nardine|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 17, 2014|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> In 2009, Heard was arrested in the [[state of Washington]] for misdemeanor domestic violence, allegedly after grabbing van Ree and hitting her arm. Ultimately, no charges were filed against Heard. The police lawfully deleted records of the arrest in 2011 after a request, but the [[King County]] District Court retained their own records. In 2016, van Ree defended Heard as the incident went public, stating that Heard had been \"wrongfully\" accused and that the incident had been \"misinterpreted and over-sensationalized\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Puente |first1=Maria |title=Amber Heard arrested in 2009 on charge of hitting girlfriend |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2016/06/07/amber-heard-arrested-2009-charge-hitting-girlfriend/85563338/ |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=June 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Libby |title=Amber Heard was accused of domestic violence by a former girlfriend in 2009 |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-amber-heard-girlfriend-domestic-violence-20160607-snap-story.html |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Heard was one of the victims of the [[iCloud leaks of celebrity photos]], in which her private nude photos were hacked and distributed without her consent.<ref name=NYTop-ed/>\n\nFollowing her divorce from actor [[Johnny Depp]], Heard dated tech entrepreneur [[Elon Musk]] for several months, until early 2018.<ref name=THRDec2018/>\n\n{{anchor|Depp}}\n===Relationship with Johnny Depp===\n[[File:Black Mass 09 (21445362382).jpg|thumb|Amber Heard and [[Johnny Depp]] arriving at the premiere of ''[[Black Mass (film)|Black Mass]]'', [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]]]]\n{{see also|Johnny Depp#Relationship with Amber Heard}}\n\nHeard met Depp while filming ''[[The Rum Diary (film)|The Rum Diary]]'' in 2009, and they began living together the following year.<ref name=\"LAtimesengagement\"/><ref name=courtdocument>{{cite web|url=http://documents.latimes.com/amber-heard-and-johnny-depps-court-declarations-regarding-allegations-domestic-violence/|title=Amber Heard and Johnny Depp's court declarations regarding allegations of domestic violence|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> They were married in a private civil ceremony at their home in Los Angeles on February 3, 2015.<ref name=courtdocument/><ref>{{cite web|title=Johnny Depp and Amber Heard Tie the Knot: Source|url=http://www.people.com/article/johnny-depp-amber-heard-marry-wedding-civil-ceremony-los-angeles|work=People|accessdate=February 4, 2015}}</ref> In April 2015, Heard and Depp breached Australia's [[biosecurity]] laws when they failed to declare their two [[Yorkshire terrier]]s to the [[Australian Customs Service]] when they flew by private jet into [[Queensland]], where he was working on ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Johnny Depp's dogs face death in Australia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-32732313|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=BBC News|date=May 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Amber Heard charged with illegally bringing dogs to Australia|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/16/amber-heard-charged-with-taking-dogs-to-australia-johnny-depp|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=The Guardian|date=July 16, 2015}}</ref> Heard pleaded guilty to falsifying quarantine documents, stating that she had made a mistake due to sleep deprivation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Johnny Depp's dogs: Amber Heard pleads guilty over Boo and Pistol quarantine document|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-18/johnny-depp-and-amber-heard-gold-coast-court-dogs/7333662|accessdate=April 18, 2016|publisher=ABC News|date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> She was placed on a $1,000 one-month [[Discharge (sentence)#Australia|good behavior bond]] for producing a false document;<ref name=guardianterriers>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/apr/18/johnny-depps-wife-amber-heard-pleads-guilty-over-bringing-dogs-to-australia|title=Charges dropped against Amber Heard for bringing dogs to Australia with Johnny Depp|author=Joshua Robertson|work=The Guardian|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> Heard and Depp also released a video in which they apologized for their behavior and urged people to adhere to the biosecurity laws.<ref name=guardianterriers/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the case the \"highest profile criminal quarantine case\" in Australian history.<ref name=guardianterriers/>\n\nHeard filed for divorce from Depp on May 23, 2016, and obtained a temporary [[restraining order]] against him, stating in her court declaration that he had been verbally and physically abusive throughout their relationship, usually while under the influence of drugs or alcohol.<ref name=cnn>{{cite web|url= http://edition.cnn.com/2016/08/16/entertainment/amber-heard-johnny-depp-timeline/|title=Johnny Depp and Amber Heard Settle Divorce|publisher=CNN|first=Lisa Respers|last=France|date=August 16, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=wright>{{cite web|url=http://www.refinery29.com/2016/06/113149/domestic-violence-911-call-famous-friend|title=Why I Called 911|last=Wright|first=iO Tillett|publisher=[[Refinery29]]|date=June 8, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttp://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-amber-heard-bruise-photos-20160601-snap-story.html|title=New photos of Amber Heard show bruised eye and bloody lip|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 1, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016|first=Libby|last=Hill}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety2019\">{{cite web |title=Amber Heard Claims Johnny Depp Threatened to Kill Her During Years of Abuse|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/amber-heard-johnny-depp-abuse-threatened-kill-1203187472/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |date=April 11, 2019}}</ref> In response, Depp denied those accusations, and through his representatives, alleged that she was \"attempting to secure a premature financial resolution by alleging abuse.\"<ref name=cnn/><ref name=guardiancarroll>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/aug/16/amber-heard-assault-allegations-johnny-depp-divorce|title=Amber Heard settles domestic abuse case against Johnny Depp|work=The Guardian|first=Rory|last=Carroll|date=August 16, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> Heard testified about the abuse under oath at a divorce court deposition.<ref name=\"Variety2019\"/> Evidence of the alleged abuse from her court filings was also published in the media.<ref name=guardiancarroll/><ref name=cnn/> A settlement was reached on August 16, 2016,<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=http://nytlive.nytimes.com/womenintheworld/2016/08/19/amber-heard-to-give-7m-johnny-depp-divorce-settlement-to-charity/|title=Amber Heard To Give $7M Johnny Depp Divorce Settlement To Charity|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> and the divorce was finalized in January 2017.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38621519 |title=Johnny Depp and Amber Heard Finalise Divorce|date= January 14, 2017|accessdate=January 14, 2017| publisher=BBC}}</ref> Heard dismissed the restraining order, and the former couple issued a joint statement saying that their \"relationship was intensely passionate and at times volatile, but always bound by love. Neither party has made false accusations for financial gain. There was never any intent of physical or emotional harm.\"<ref name=NYT/> Depp paid Heard a settlement of US$7&nbsp;million, which she donated to the ACLU and the [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]].<ref name=NYT/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/blog/speak-freely/actress-amber-heard-donates-millions-support-aclu-and-its-work-fighting-violence|title=Actress Amber Heard Donates Millions to Support the ACLU and Its Work Fighting Violence Against Women|publisher=[[American Civil Liberties Union]]|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Amber Heard Honored for 7-Figure Donation to Children's Hospital Following Johnny Depp Divorce|url=http://people.com/movies/amber-heard-makes-7-figure-donation-childrens-hospital-after-johnny-depp-divorce/|work=People|author=Miller, Mike|date=April 9, 2018|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2019, Depp sued Heard for US$50 million for defamation over an [[op-ed]] she wrote for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in December 2018, which \"depended on the central premise that Ms. Heard was a domestic abuse victim and that Mr. Depp perpetrated domestic violence against her\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Griffith |first1=Janelle |title=Johnny Depp sues ex-wife Amber Heard for $50 million for allegedly defaming him |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/johnny-depp-sues-ex-wife-amber-heard-50-million-allegedly-n978976 |date=March 4, 2019|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"varietymarch2019\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/johnny-depp-amber-heard-defamation-washington-post-op-ed-50-million-1203153857/amp/|title=Johnny Depp Reportedly Sues Amber Heard for $50M Over Washington Post Op-Ed|last=Nyren|first=Erin|date=March 2, 2019|website=Variety|accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> The fact that the piece did not specifically mention Depp by name is not disputed by either party.<ref name=\"Variety2019\" /> Depp also alleged that Heard had been the abuser, and that her allegations constituted a [[hoax]] against him;<ref name=\"varietymarch2019\" /> his legal team also published alleged evidence of Heard's abuse of Depp.<ref>{{cite web |title=Johnny Depp's lawyer says Amber Heard 'perpetrated serial violence'; she fires back with abuse claims |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |date=February 3, 2020 |website=USA Today |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/celebrities/2020/02/02/johnny-depp-amber-heard-perpetrated-serial-violence-lawyer-says/4639763002/}}</ref> In response, Heard said that Depp's claims are not true and repeated her allegations and evidence, maintaining that Depp was abusive towards her.<ref name=\"Variety2019\" /> She asked a judge to dismiss the lawsuit\u2014which Depp filed in [[Virginia]], where the ''Post'' is located\u2014so that the case could be tried in California (where most of the witnesses reside), but this request was denied.<ref>{{cite web |title=Johnny Depp's ex-wife asks judge to dismiss his lawsuit |url=https://apnews.com/82e4e8ea36df417e86d6d2b334b065f9 |website=[[AP News]] |accessdate=April 12, 2019 |date=April 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Puente |first1=Maria |last2=Mandell |first2=Andrea |title=Johnny Depp v Amber Heard: Depp submits photos of black eye, details feces 'prank' |url=https://amp.usatoday.com/amp/3450310002 |website=USA Today |accessdate=May 21, 2019 |date=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Gardner |first=Eriq |title=Johnny Depp's $50M Defamation Suit Against Amber Heard Allowed in Virginia |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/johnny-depps-50m-defamation-suit-amber-heard-allowed-virginia-1227186 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=August 5, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n\n===Film===\n[[File:Amber Heard (17043468150).jpg|thumb|right|Amber Heard at the 2015 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]]]\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]''|| Maria ||\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2005 || ''Side FX''|| Shay ||\n|-\n || ''[[Drop Dead Sexy]]''|| Candy ||\n|-\n || ''[[North Country (film)|North Country]]''|| Young Josey Aimes ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=3|2006 || ''Price to Pay''|| Trish ||\n|-\n || ''[[Alpha Dog]]''|| Alma ||\n|-\n || ''[[All the Boys Love Mandy Lane]]''|| Mandy Lane ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=3|2007 || ''[[Spin (2007 film)|Spin]]''|| Amber ||\n|-\n || ''Day 73 with Sarah''|| Mary || Short film\n|-\n || ''[[Remember the Daze]]''|| Julia Ford ||\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2008 ||''[[Never Back Down]]''|| Baja Miller ||\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Informers|dab=2008 film}}''|| Christie ||\n|-\n ||''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]''|| Angie ||\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2009 || ''[[ExTerminators (film)|ExTerminators]]''|| Nikki ||\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Joneses}}'' || Jenn Jones ||\n|-\n || ''[[Zombieland]]''|| 406 ||\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Stepfather|dab=2009 film}}''|| Kelly Porter ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=3|2010 || ''[[And Soon the Darkness (2010 film)|And Soon the Darkness]]''|| Stephanie || Also co-producer\n|-\n|| ''{{sortname|The|River Why|dab=film}}'' || Eddy ||\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Ward|dab=film}}''|| Kristen ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=2|2011 || ''[[Drive Angry]]'' || Piper ||\n|-\n|| ''{{sortname|The|Rum Diary|dab=film}}'' || Chenault ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=3|2013 || ''[[Syrup (film)|Syrup]]'' || Six || Also executive producer\n|-\n|| ''[[Paranoia (2013 film)|Paranoia]]'' || Emma Jennings ||\n|-\n || ''[[Machete Kills]]'' || Miss San Antonio ||\n|-\n| 2014 || ''[[3 Days to Kill]]'' || Agent Vivi ||\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2015 || ''[[The Adderall Diaries (film)|The Adderall Diaries]]'' || Lana Edmond ||\n|-\n || ''[[One More Time (2015 film)|One More Time]]'' || Jude ||\n|-\n|| ''[[Magic Mike XXL]]'' || Zoe ||\n|-\n || ''[[The Danish Girl (film)|The Danish Girl]]'' || [[Ulla Poulsen|Ulla Paulson]] ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=2|2017 || ''[[I Do... Until I Don't]]'' || Fanny ||\n|-\n|| ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' || [[Mera (comics)|Mera]] ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=3|2018 || ''[[Her Smell]]'' || Zelda ||\n|-\n || ''[[London Fields (film)|London Fields]]'' || Nicola Six || Filmed in 2013\n|-\n || ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' || Mera ||\n|-\n| 2019 || ''[[Gully (film)|Gully]]'' || Joyce ||\n<!--|-\n|2022\n|Aquaman 2\n|Mera\n|\n|-\n-->\n|}\n\n===Television===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n|  rowspan=2|2004 || ''[[Jack & Bobby]]''|| Liz|| Episode: \"Pilot\"\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Mountain|dab=TV series}}''|| Riley|| Episode: \"A Piece of the Rock\"\n|-\n| 2005 || ''{{sortname|The|O.C.}}''|| Salesgirl|| Episode: \"Mallpisode\"\n|-\n| 2006 || ''[[Criminal Minds]]''|| Lila Archer|| Episode: \"Somebody's Watching\"\n|-\n|  rowspan=2|2007 || ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''|| Amber|| Episode: \"California Son\"\n|-\n || ''[[Hidden Palms]]''|| Greta Matthews|| 8 episodes\n|-\n|  rowspan=2|2011 || ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]''|| Herself|| Episode: \"Episode #16.5\"\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Playboy Club}}''||Bunny Maureen|| 7 episodes\n|-\n| rowspan=2| 2015 || ''[[Overhaulin'#Season 9|Overhaulin']]''|| Herself|| Episode: \"In Too Depp\"\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Prince|nolink=1}}'' || Serena ||\n|-\n| 2020 || ''[[The Stand (upcoming miniseries)|The Stand]]'' || Nadine Cross ||\n|}\n\n===Music videos===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Artist\n|-\n| 2003\n| \"[[There Goes My Life]]\"\n| [[Kenny Chesney]]\n|-\n| 2005\n| \"I Wasn't Prepared\" <small>(Version 1)\n| [[Eisley]]\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2008\n| [[Young Hollywood Awards]]\n| [[Young Hollywood Awards|Breakthrough of the Year]]\n| Herself\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| [[Detroit Film Critics Society|Detroit Film Critics Society Awards]]\n|  rowspan=2|Best Ensemble\n| rowspan=2|''[[Zombieland]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2010\n| [[Scream Awards]]\n| rowspan=4 {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Dallas International Film Festival]]\n| [[Dallas International Film Festival|Dallas Star Award]]\n| Herself\n|-\n| 2011\n| [[Hollywood Film Festival]]\n| [[Hollywood Film Festival|Spotlight Award]]\n| ''[[The Rum Diary (film)|The Rum Diary]]''\n|-\n| 2014\n| [[Texas Film Hall of Fame]]\n| [[Texas Film Hall of Fame|Inductee]]\n| Herself\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2019\n| [[39th Golden Raspberry Awards|Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress|Worst Actress]]\n| ''[[London Fields (film)|London Fields]]''\n|  rowspan=3 {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|  rowspan=2|''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]''\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Sci-Fi/Fantasy Movie Actress\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |commons=Category:Amber Heard |b=no |n=no |q=no |s=no |v=no |species=no |display=Amber Heard|voy=no|d=Q229166}}\n* {{IMDb name|1720028|Amber Heard}}\n* {{Allrovi name|418732|Amber Heard}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Instagram|amberheard}}\n\n{{Johnny Depp}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!-- NOTE: Per WP:BLPCAT, Heard is not to be added to the lesbian or bisexual category until she publicly identifies as either lesbian or bisexual. She has publicly identified as being a part of the LGBT community. While sources have identified her as lesbian or bisexual, she has yet to publicly specify her sexual orientation. See past talk page discussions about this. -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heard, Amber}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American former Christians]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:LGBT actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Texas]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Victims of domestic abuse]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n", "text_old": "{{pp-blp|small=yes}}\n{{short description|American actress}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox person\n| image              = Amber Heard (43723454772).jpg\n| name               = Amber Heard\n| caption            = Heard at the 2018 [[San Diego Comic-Con]]\n| birthname          = Amber Laura Heard\n| other_names        = Amber Laura Depp<ref>{{cite web|url=https://people.com/celebrity/johnny-depp-amber-heard-actors-lawyer-seeks-to-bar-witnesses-from-testifying/|title=Johnny Depp's Lawyer Asks Judge to Prevent Amber Heard Witnesses from Testifying at Restraining Order Hearing|work=People}}</ref><br>Amber van Ree<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2016/06/07/amber-heard-arrested-2009-charge-hitting-girlfriend/85563338/|title=Amber Heard arrested in 2009 on charge of hitting girlfriend|work=USA Today}}</ref>\n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|1986|4|22|mf=yes}}\n| birth_place        = [[Austin, Texas]], U.S.\n| residence          = [[Los Angeles]], [[California]], U.S.\n| occupation         = Actress\n| years_active       = 2003\u2013present\n| spouse             = {{marriage|[[Johnny Depp]]|2015|2017|reason=divorced}}\n| partner            = [[Tasya van Ree]] (2008\u20132012)\n}}\n'''Amber Laura Heard''' (born April 22, 1986)<ref name=tvg><!-- Cite covers both birth date and full name Amber Laura Heard. -->{{cite web |url=http://www.tvguide.com/celebrities/amber-heard-285286/bio/ |title=Amber Heard| work=[[TV Guide]] |access-date=February 1, 2015}}</ref> is an American actress and model. Born and raised in [[Texas]], she made her film debut in a minor supporting role in the sports drama ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2004), followed by a series of other small roles in television and film. Her first leading role was in the horror film ''[[All the Boys Love Mandy Lane]]'' (2006), but it was not released in the United States until 2013 due to distribution problems. Her second major role came in the short-running [[The CW]] television series ''[[Hidden Palms]]'' (2007).\n\nHeard's breakthrough came in 2008 with roles in the action film ''[[Never Back Down]]'' and in the [[stoner comedy]] ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]'', which were both box office successes. The same year, she received the Breakthrough Award at [[Young Hollywood Awards]]. Heard continued her career with roles in films such as ''[[The Informers (2008 film)|The Informers]]'' (2008), ''[[The Stepfather (2009 film)|The Stepfather]]'' (2009), ''[[Zombieland]]'' (2009), and ''[[The Joneses]]'' (2009). In 2011, she played the female lead opposite [[Nicolas Cage]] in ''[[Drive Angry]]'', and opposite [[Johnny Depp]] in ''[[The Rum Diary (film)|The Rum Diary]]''; neither were critically nor commercially successful. Subsequently, Heard appeared in ''[[3 Days to Kill]]'' (2014), ''[[Magic Mike XXL]]'' (2015) and ''[[The Danish Girl (film)|The Danish Girl]]'' (2015). She also starred in the indie film ''[[The Adderall Diaries (film)|The Adderall Diaries]]'' (2015), the television musical drama ''[[One More Time (2015 film)|One More Time]]'' (2015), and the [[Martin Amis]] adaptation ''[[London Fields (film)|London Fields]]'' (2018). The latter was due to be released in 2015, but became the subject of a series of lawsuit between its director, Heard, and the film's production company over disagreements in its editing and other issues. The film was finally released in 2018, and was both a critical and commercial flop.\n\nIn 2017, Heard acted as part of an [[ensemble cast]]\u00a0in the indie film ''[[I Do...Until I Don't]]'' (2017) and made an appearance as [[Mera (comics)|Mera]] in the superhero film ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]'' (2017). She reprised the latter role opposite [[Jason Momoa]]\u00a0in ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' (2018), which became the most profitable [[DC Extended Universe]] film up to that point, and the [[2018 in film#Highest-grossing films|fifth highest-grossing film of 2018]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/yearly/chart/?view2=worldwide&yr=2018&p=.htm |title=2018 Yearly Box Office Results |website=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=July 1, 2018}}</ref> The same year, Heard was also named a global spokesperson for the cosmetics giant [[L'Or\u00e9al Paris]]. In 2019, she appeared in supporting roles in the independent films ''[[Her Smell]]'' and ''[[Gully (film)|Gully]]''.\n\nIn addition to her acting career, Heard engages in activism for causes such as [[LGBTQ]] rights and domestic and sexual violence awareness. She is an [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) ambassador and has been named a Human Rights Champion for the Stand Up for Human Rights campaign by the [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]]. From 2015 to 2017, Heard was married to her ''The Rum Diary'' co-star [[Johnny Depp]]. Their divorce drew significant media attention, as Heard alleged that Depp had been physically and verbally abusive towards her through most of their relationship. In 2019, he sued her for defamation after she discussed being a victim of domestic violence in the media. He countered that Heard had abused him, which Heard says is not true.\n\n==Early life==\nHeard was born in [[Austin, Texas]], to Patricia Paige (n\u00e9e Parsons), an internet researcher, and David Clinton Heard, who owned a small construction company.<ref name=wonderland>{{cite web|url= https://www.wonderlandmagazine.com/2019/04/02/amber-heard-spring-19-interview/|title=Amber Heard on her position as a Hollywood voice for justice|work= Wonderland|first=Eve|last=Barlow|date=April 2, 2019|accessdate= May 26, 2019}}</ref><ref name=tvg/><ref name=NewsAu>{{cite web|url=http://www.news.com.au/entertainment/celebrity-life/five-things-you-need-to-know-about-amber-heard/story-fnk825aa-1226809741190|title=Five things you need to know about Amber Heard|work=NewsComAu|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> She has a younger sister named Whitney.<ref name=tvg /><ref name=THRDec2018>{{cite web|url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/features/amber-heard-aquaman-elon-musk-dedication-activism-1166004|title=Amber Heard on 'Aquaman', Elon Musk, Dedication to Activism|work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|first=Tatiana|last=Siegel|date=December 6, 2018|accessdate=May 26, 2018}}</ref> The family lived outside Austin.<ref name=glamour2018>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.glamour.com/story/amber-heard-january-2018-cover-story|title= Amber Heard Is Nobody's Victim|magazine=Glamour|first=Phoebe|last=Reilly|accessdate=April 19, 2019|date=November 27, 2018}}</ref> Heard's father broke horses in his freetime, and she grew up riding horses, hunting, and fishing with him.<ref name=glamour2018/> She also participated in beauty pageants, although as an adult she has stated that she could no longer \"support the objectification\".<ref name=glamour2018/> When Heard was 16, her best friend died in a car crash. Heard, who was raised [[Catholic Church|Catholic]], subsequently declared herself an [[Atheism|atheist]].<ref name=\"AH will be heard\">{{cite news|first=William|last=Keck|title=Amber Heard will be heard |url=https://www.usatoday.com/life/television/news/2007-05-29-amber-heard_N.htm |work=[[USA Today]] |publisher=[[Gannett Company]]|location=Mclean, Virginia|date=May 30, 2007 }}</ref> Around the same time, she began reading books by writers such as [[Ayn Rand]], [[Ray Bradbury]],\u00a0and [[George Orwell]], and began questioning society around her.<ref name=wonderland/> At the age of 17, she no longer felt comfortable in Texas<ref name=glamour2018/> and dropped out of her Catholic high school to move to New York City.<ref name=NewsAu/><ref name=wonderland/> She eventually earned a diploma through a home-study course.<ref name=\"AH will be heard\" /> In NYC, she supported herself through modeling,<ref name=NewsAu/> but soon moved to Los Angeles to pursue an acting career.<ref name=glamour2018/>\n\n==Career==\n[[File:Amber Heard 2010.jpg|thumb|upright|Amber Heard at the premiere of [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[The Ward (film)|The Ward]]'', [[2010 Toronto International Film Festival]]]]\n\n===Early work (2003\u20142007)===\nHeard's earliest acting work included appearances in two music videos, [[Kenny Chesney]]'s \"[[There Goes My Life]]\" and [[Eisley]]'s \"I Wasn't Prepared\", and small supporting roles in the television series ''[[Jack & Bobby]]'' (2004), ''[[The Mountain (TV series)|The Mountain]]'' (2004), and ''[[The O.C.]]'' (2005). She made her film debut in a minor role in the sports drama ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]'' (2004), followed by small supporting roles in films such as ''[[Drop Dead Sexy]]'' (2005), ''[[North Country (film)|North Country]]'' (2005), ''Side FX'' (2005), ''Price to Pay'' (2006), ''You Are Here'' (2006), and ''[[Alpha Dog]]'' (2006), and guest starring spot in an episode of the [[police procedural]] ''[[Criminal Minds]]''.\n\nHeard's first starring role was playing the main character's love interest in [[The CW]]'s teen drama ''[[Hidden Palms]]'', which the network wanted to replace summer reruns of other series aimed for teenage audiences. The series premiered in the United States on May 30, 2007 to mixed to negative reviews. It was also unpopular with audiences, leading the CW to air only eight of the planned 12 episodes before canceling it.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.metacritic.com/tv/shows/hiddenpalms|title=Hidden Palms|publisher=}}</ref><ref>[http://www.nashvillecitypaper.com/index.cfm?section=12&screen=news&news_id=56707 \"Hidden Palms\" Accelerates Its Final Episodes]{{dead link|date=July 2017 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''The City Paper'', June 18, 2007</ref> The same year, Heard also appeared in the short movie ''Day 73 with Sarah'',<ref>{{cite news|title=Day 73 With Sarah (2007)|url=https://www.nytimes.com/movies/movie/391074/Day-73-With-Sarah/overview|accessdate=October 11, 2014|work=The New York Times|year=2014}}</ref> the critically panned teen drama ''[[Remember the Daze]]'', and an episode of the [[Showtime (TV network)|Showtime]] series ''[[Californication (TV series)|Californication]]''.<ref>{{cite web|first=Pete|last=Debruge|title=Review: 'Remember the Daze'|url=https://variety.com/2007/film/reviews/remember-the-daze-1200558085/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|publisher=[[Penske Media Corporation]]|location=Los Angeles, California|date=July 5, 2007|accessdate=October 11, 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Mainstream recognition (2008\u20142016)===\nHeard gained more mainstream recognition in 2008, when she appeared in supporting roles in the [[Judd Apatow]]-produced [[stoner film|stoner comedy]] ''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]''<ref>{{cite web|title=Amber Heard: The interview|url=http://www.fhm.com/girls/amber-heard-the-interview-20081007|website=FHM|accessdate=October 11, 2014|date=October 7, 2008|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20141017011920/http://www.fhm.com/girls/amber-heard-the-interview-20081007|archivedate=October 17, 2014}}</ref> and the martial arts drama ''[[Never Back Down]]'', both of which were box office successes. That year, she won a Breakthrough Award at the [[Hollywood Film Festival]]. Her other 2008 film releases were the critically panned [[Bret Easton Ellis]] adaptation ''[[The Informers (2009 film)|The Informers]]'', in which she was part of an ensemble cast,<ref name=\"Frost\">{{cite web|author1=Frosty|title=Amber Heard Exclusive Video Interview \u2013 NEVER BACK DOWN|url=http://collider.com/movie/article.asp/aid/7229/tcid/1|website=Collider.com|publisher=Collider.com|accessdate=October 11, 2014|date=March 10, 2008}}</ref> and ''[[All the Boys Love Mandy Lane]]'', an unconventional [[slasher film]] in which she had one of her first leading roles. Its director, [[Jonathan Levine (screenwriter)|Jonathan Levine]], said he had chosen Heard for the title role because \"there was a certain type of beauty and a certain type of innate intelligence that Amber brought to it that is not something you find every day. Certainly, not something you would find in somebody her age. The wisdom she projects I thought was pretty remarkable.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/48929/exclusive-director-jonathan-levine-talks-all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane/|work=Film School Rejects|title=Jonathan Levine interview|last=Tinnin|first=Drew|date=August 23, 2013|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref> ''Mandy Lane'' had already premiered at the [[2006 Toronto International Film Festival]], and had been initially picked for distribution by [[Harvey Weinstein]].<ref>{{cite web|title=After Seven Years, All the Boys Love Mandy Lane is Coming to US Theaters|url=http://www.comingsoon.net/news/movienews.php?id=101303|work=[[ComingSoon.net]]|publisher=[[CraveOnline]]|date=March 8, 2013|accessdate=March 8, 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.slashfilm.com/all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane-finally-set-for-release-revisit-an-old-trailer/|work=Slash Film|title=All the Boys Love Mandy Lane finally set for release date|accessdate=August 25, 2013}}</ref> After a negative test screening, Weinstein dropped the film, and it was then released in the United Kingdom in 2008 by a different distributing company.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane-trailer.php|work=Film School Rejects|title='All the Boys Love Mandy Lane' Trailer Finally Debuts After Seven Years|last=Wilson|first=Samantha|date=August 23, 2013|accessdate=August 25, 2013|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20130828204803/http://www.filmschoolrejects.com/news/all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane-trailer.php|archivedate=August 28, 2013}}</ref> It did not have a theatrical release in the United States until 2013. The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' stated that Heard gave her most \"definitive [performance] to date [2013]\" in the film,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/moviesnow/la-et-mn-all-the-boys-review-20131011,0,6522321.story |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=October 10, 2013|accessdate=October 24, 2013|last=Olsen|first=Mark|title=Movie review: 'All the Boys Love Mandy Lane' a spellbinding thriller}}</ref> and ''[[The Washington Post]]'' wrote that she gave a \"psychologically interesting performance\".<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/goingoutguide/movies/all-the-boys-love-mandy-lane-movie-review/2013/11/20/d60bd8a8-4d56-11e3-be6b-d3d28122e6d4_story.html|work=The Washington Post|title='All the Boys Love Mandy Lane' movie review|first=Michael|last=O'Sullivan|date=November 21, 2013|accessdate=December 10, 2013}}</ref>\n[[File:AmberHeard09TIFF.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Heard at the [[2009 Toronto International Film Festival]]]]\nIn 2009, Heard had roles in the critically panned horror film ''[[The Stepfather (2009 film)|The Stepfather]]'' and in three comedies, the limited-release indie ''[[ExTerminators (film)|ExTerminators]]'', the critically and commercially successful ''[[Zombieland]]'', and the box office disappointment ''[[The Joneses]]''. Although she otherwise received relatively little attention from established critics due to her roles being mainly supporting at this point, ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' wrote that \"she steals the show\" from the film's more established star, [[Demi Moore]], in ''The Joneses''.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2009/film/reviews/the-joneses-1200476211/ |title=The Joneses Review|work=Variety |accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> The following year, Heard starred in the indie drama ''[[The River Why (film)|The River Why]]'' and continued her work in the horror genre in [[John Carpenter]]'s ''[[The Ward (film)|The Ward]]'', which was a critical and commercial disappointment. Carpenter has later stated that he was disappointed in the film but \"loved working with Amber and would work with her again without hesitation.\"<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://www.lesinrocks.com/2019/05/13/cinemas/cinemas/john-carpenter-ah-bon-cannes-est-le-temple-de-lauteurisme/|title=John Carpenter : \"Ah bon, Cannes est le temple de l'auteurisme ?!\" (in French)|magazine=[[Les Inrockuptibles]]}}</ref> She also co-produced and starred in the independent thriller ''[[And Soon the Darkness (2010 film)|And Soon the Darkness]]''.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fangoria.com/features/21-fearful-features/4303-amber-heard-in-step-with-the-horror-genre.html|title=Amber Heard: In STEP With the Horror Genre|publisher=}}</ref>\n\nHeard's next role was as the female lead opposite [[Johnny Depp]] in the [[Hunter S. Thompson]] adaptation ''[[The Rum Diary (film)|The Rum Diary]]'' (2011), which received mixed reviews<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/The-Rum-Diary/| title=The Rum Diary (2011)| work = [[Rotten Tomatoes]]| publisher = [[Flixster]]| accessdate = November 7, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.metacritic.com/movie/the-rum-diary| title = The Rum Diary Reviews| website = [[Metacritic]]| accessdate =November 7, 2011}}</ref> and was not a commercial success.<ref name=\"BOM\">{{cite web|url=http://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?id=rumdiary.htm | title=The Rum Diary (2011) | work=[[Box Office Mojo]] | accessdate=November 1, 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url=http://latimesblogs.latimes.com/entertainmentnewsbuzz/2011/10/box-office-puss-in-boots-in-time-rum-diary.html | title=Movie Projector: 'Puss in Boots' to stomp on competition | last=Kaufman | first=Amy | work=[[Los Angeles Times]] | date=October 27, 2011 | accessdate=October 27, 2011}}</ref> Heard's other 2011 film release was ''[[Drive Angry]]'', a supernatural action thriller in which she was paired with [[Nicolas Cage]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.dreadcentral.com/news/35744/william-fichtner-and-amber-heard-ready-drive-angry |title=William Fichtner and Amber Heard Ready to Drive Angry? |publisher=Dreadcentral.com |date=February 5, 2010 |accessdate=February 6, 2012}}</ref> Although the film was critically panned<ref>{{cite web |title=Drive Angry |url=https://www.rottentomatoes.com/m/drive_angry |website=Rotten Tomatoes |accessdate=January 15, 2019 |language=en}}</ref> and underperformed commercially,<ref name=\"Nikki Finke\">{{cite magazine|url=http://www.deadline.com/2011/02/hall-pass-weak-1-unknown-holds-2-drive-angry-3d-tanks-at-9-oscar-fave-kings-speech-rises-in-week-14|title='Gnomes' No. 1 In Third Week Of Release; 'Hall Pass' Drops To #2; 'Drive Angry' #9; Oscars Fave 'King's Speech' Doesn't Stutter|author=Nikki Finke|magazine=Deadline}}</ref> film critic [[Roger Ebert]] wrote that she \"does everything that can possibly be done\" with her character, a waitress who becomes entangled in an undead man's mission to save his daughter from a cult.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.rogerebert.com/reviews/drive-angry-3d-2011 |last=Ebert |first=Roger |authorlink=Roger Ebert |date=February 24, 2011 |title=Drive Angry Movie Review |accessdate=December 8, 2014}}</ref> In February 2011, Heard also appeared on the British television program ''[[Top Gear (2002 TV series)|Top Gear]]''.<ref>{{cite web|title=Amber Heard|url=http://www.tatler.com/the-tatler-list/h/amber-heard|publisher=tatler.com|accessdate=June 5, 2013}}</ref> Heard appeared in no new films until 2013, when she starred in the thriller ''[[Paranoia (2013 film)|Paranoia]]'', the action-comedy ''[[Machete Kills]]'', and the satirical drama ''[[Syrup (film)|Syrup]]''. All three were critical and box office failures. Her only film release in 2014, the action-thriller ''[[3 Days to Kill]]'', was a box office success but panned by critics.\n\nHeard had prominent roles in four films released in 2015, which led James Mottram of the British newspaper ''[[The Independent]]'' to call it a \"watershed year\" in her career.<ref name=independent>{{cite news|title=Amber Heard Interview:The Danish Girl star on sexism, transgenderism and marriage to Johnny Depp|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/amber-heard-the-star-of-the-danish-girl-on-sexism-transgenderism-and-her-marriage-to-johnny-depp-a6792691.html|work=[[The Independent]]|first=James|last=Mottram|date=January 1, 2015|accessdate=April 18, 2015}}</ref> In the comedy-drama ''[[Magic Mike XXL]]'' she played a photographer who flirts with [[Channing Tatum]]'s protagonist; like its predecessor, ''[[Magic Mike]]'' (2012), the film was a large box office success.<ref>{{cite news|title=Amber Heard To Co-Star In 'Magic Mike 2'|url=http://deadline.com/2014/09/amber-heard-magic-mike-2-co-star-cast-836817/|accessdate=September 20, 2014|publisher=deadline.com|date=September 19, 2014}}</ref> ''[[Digital Spy]]'' described Heard as \"a convincing girl-next-door type\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.digitalspy.co.uk/movies/review/a654554/magic-mike-xxl-review-the-film-you-feared-the-original-would-be.html|title=Magic Mike XXL review|author=Stella Papamichael|date=June 29, 2015|work=Digital Spy|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> Heard also had a small supporting role as a ballet dancer in [[Tom Hooper]]'s critically successful historical drama ''[[The Danish Girl (film)|The Danish Girl]]'' (2015), which premiered at the [[72nd Venice Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/venice-review-tom-hoopers-the-danish-girl-with-eddie-redmayne-alicia-vikander-20150905|title=Venice Review: Tom Hooper's 'The Danish Girl' With Eddie Redmayne & Alicia|work=[[Indiewire]]|last=Kiang|first=Jessica|date=September 5, 2015|accessdate=September 12, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150907220149/http://blogs.indiewire.com/theplaylist/venice-review-tom-hoopers-the-danish-girl-with-eddie-redmayne-alicia-vikander-20150905|archive-date=September 7, 2015|url-status=dead}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/eddie-redmayne-danish-girl-1201446329/|title=Eddie Redmayne's 'Danish Girl' Set for Nov. 27|last=McNary|first=Dave|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=March 4, 2015|accessdate=March 21, 2015}}</ref> In her third 2015 release, the independent crime thriller ''[[The Adderall Diaries (film)|The Adderall Diaries]]'', she starred opposite [[James Franco]], [[Christian Slater]], and [[Ed Harris]]. [[Indiewire]] gave the film a mixed review and stated that Heard was \"miscast\" but \"displays much potential and has succeeded in a bid to be taken more seriously.\"<ref>{{cite news|title=The Adderall Diaries review|url=http://www.indiewire.com/article/tribeca-review-james-franco-embraces-masochism-in-tone-deaf-the-adderall-diaries-20150417|work=Indiewire|accessdate=April 18, 2015}}</ref> Her fourth role in 2015 was opposite [[Christopher Walken]] in the television film ''[[When I Live My Life Over Again|One More Time]]'', which aired on [[Starz]]. For her role as a struggling singer-songwriter, she took singing lessons and learned to play piano and guitar.<ref>{{cite magazine|title=Christopher Walken, Amber Heard Sing and Strum in 'When I Live My Life Over Again'|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/christopher-walken-amber-heard-sing-786065|magazine=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]|accessdate=April 21, 2015}}</ref> ''[[International Business Times]]'' described Heard as \"talented enough to share a few heartfelt moments in a character that mostly operates on the defensive.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ibtimes.com/when-i-live-my-life-over-again-tribeca-film-festival-review-amber-heard-christopher-1890473|title='When I Live My Life Over Again' Tribeca Film Festival Review: Amber Heard And Christopher Walken Can't Hit The Right Notes|author=Monica Castillo|work=International Business Times|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> The ''[[Los Angeles Times]]'' called her performance \"superb\" and ''The Film Stage'' stated that Heard did an \"admirable job\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/movies/reviews/la-et-mn-mini-one-more-time-review-20160408-story.html|title='One More Time' with Christopher Walken plays a simple tune|last=Goldstein|first=Gary|date=April 7, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefilmstage.com/reviews/review-one-more-time/|title=[Review] One More Time|work=The Film Stage|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn addition to her other roles in 2015, Heard played the female lead in the [[Martin Amis]] adaptation ''[[London Fields (film)|London Fields]]'', which was initially scheduled to premiere at the [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://variety.com/2015/film/news/sandra-bullocks-our-brand-tom-hiddlestons-i-saw-the-light-to-premiere-at-toronto-1201572271/ |title=Sandra Bullock's 'Our Brand Is Crisis,' Robert Redford's 'Truth' to Premiere at Toronto |accessdate=August 18, 2015 |work=Variety}}</ref> It was pulled from the festival roster after director [[Mathew Cullen]] sued the film's producers, accusing them of fraud and of using his name to promote a cut of the film he did not support.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://globalnews.ca/news/2226288/london-fields-pulled-from-tiff-after-director-sues-producers/ |title='London Fields' pulled from TIFF after director sues producers |accessdate=September 17, 2015 |work=Global News}}</ref> The film's stars, including Heard, had also written to the producers, objecting to the cut that was seen at press and industry screenings in Toronto.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/london-fields/toronto-review/ |title=London Fields review |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=September 17, 2015 |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> ''London Fields'' and Heard's performance received highly negative reviews,<ref name=\"Daily Telegraph September 17, 2015\">{{cite news |last= Mulkerrins |first= Jane |title= London Fields review: 'a cartoonish mess' |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/film/london-fields/toronto-review/ |date= September 17, 2015 |newspaper= [[The Daily Telegraph]] |location= London| accessdate= March 9, 2016 }}</ref><ref name=\"The Independent September 17, 2015\">{{cite news |last= Aftab |first= Kaleem |title= London Fields, Toronto Film Festival, review: Dystopian drama is no field day to watch| url= https://www.independent.co.uk/arts-entertainment/films/reviews/london-fields-toronto-film-festival-review-dystopian-drama-is-no-field-day-to-watch-10506735.html| date= September 17, 2015| newspaper= [[The Independent]] |location=London| accessdate= March 9, 2016 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/review/london-fields-tiff-review-824093 |title=London Fields: TIFF review |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=September 17, 2015 |accessdate=October 17, 2015}}</ref> and she stated that \"it was one of the most difficult movies to film and it has proven to continue to be difficult...I can't say I did her [the character] justice.\"<ref name=independent/> In November 2016, Heard was sued by the film's producers for $10 million, claiming that she and Cullen made unauthorized changes to the film's script and failed to finish voice-over work.<ref>{{cite web |last=Gardner |first=Eriq |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/amber-heard-sued-by-london-fields-producer-949623 |title=Amber Heard Sued Over Alleged Conspiracy to Undermine 'London Fields' |work=The Hollywood Reporter |date=November 21, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Pederson |first=Erik |url=http://deadline.com/2016/11/amber-heard-sued-london-fields-failure-to-promote-film-1201858278/|title=Amber Heard Sued For $10M As 'London Fields' Flap Heats Up Again |website=Deadline Hollywood |date=November 21, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Maddaus |first=Gene |url=https://variety.com/2016/film/news/amber-heard-sued-london-fields-1201923607/ |title='London Fields' Producers Sue Amber Heard for $10 Million |work=Variety |date=November 21, 2016 |accessdate=November 27, 2016}}</ref> Heard countersued claiming the producers violated a nudity clause in her contract.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.belfasttelegraph.co.uk/entertainment/news/amber-heard-countersues-producer-of-london-fields-35584755.html |title=Amber Heard countersues producer of London Fields |work=[[Belfast Telegraph]] |date=April 1, 2017 |accessdate=April 1, 2017}}</ref> In September 2018, a settlement was reached,<ref name=\"variety-settlement\">{{cite web |last=Maddus |first=Gene |url=https://variety.com/2018/film/news/london-fields-producers-amber-heard-settlement-1202927600/ |title='London Fields' Producers Reach Settlement With Amber Heard |work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |date=September 5, 2018 |accessdate=September 5, 2018}}</ref> and ''London Fields'' was released, becoming a box office failure and earning Heard a nomination for the [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.boxofficemojo.com/movies/?page=daily&id=londonfields.htm |title=London Fields (2018) \u2013 Daily Box Office Results |work=[[Box Office Mojo]] |accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=McClintock |first=Pamela |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/news/box-office-amber-heards-london-fields-bombs-at-record-low-160k-1155714 |title=Box Office: Star-Studded 'London Fields' Bombs With $160K, Near-Record Worst for a Wide Release |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]] |date=October 28, 2018 |accessdate=October 29, 2018}}</ref>\n\n===DC Extended Universe and upcoming projects (2017\u20132020)===\n[[File:Amber Heard (42867568355).jpg|thumb|Heard discussing ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' at the [[San Diego Comic-Con|2018 San Diego Comic-Con International]]]] In 2017, Heard appeared as part of an ensemble cast in [[Lake Bell]]'s indie comedy ''[[I Do... Until I Don't]]'' and joined the [[DC Extended Universe]] (DCEU) cast as [[Mera (comics)|Mera]], [[Aquaman]]'s Atlantean queen, in the superhero film ''[[Justice League (film)|Justice League]]''. She reprised the role the following year in ''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]'' (2018), which  co-starred [[Jason Momoa]], [[Nicole Kidman]] and [[Willem Dafoe]] and marked Heard's first major role in a studio film.<ref name=THRDec2018/><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.hollywoodreporter.com/heat-vision/amber-heard-talks-star-aquaman-848622 |title=Amber Heard in Talks to Star in 'Aquaman' (Exclusive) |work=[[The Hollywood Reporter]]| last=Kit|first=Borys|date=13 January 2016|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.etonline.com/movies/184773_amber_heard_confirms_her_aquaman_role_justice_league_dishes_on_interesting_mera_costume/|title=EXCLUSIVE: Amber Heard Confirms Her 'Aquaman' Role in 'Justice League', Dishes on 'Interesting' Mera Costume |work=[[Entertainment Tonight]] | last=Kile|first=Meredith B.|date=17 March 2016|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref> She has stated that one of the reasons attracting her to the part was Mera being \"a strong, independent, self-possessed superhero in her own right\",<ref name=THRDec2018/> who rejects being called Aquawoman instead of by her own name.<ref name=glamour2018/> ''Aquaman'' became the fifth most profitable release of 2018, and the most profitable DCEU installment up to that point.<ref name=profit>{{cite magazine|url=https://deadline.com/2019/03/aquaman-box-office-profit-2018-1202584701/|title=James Wan's $1B+ 'Aquaman' Became DC's Lifeboat After 'Justice League' Debacle: No. 5 In 2018 Most Valuable Blockbuster Tournament|first=Anthony|last=D'Alessandro|magazine=[[Deadline Hollywood]]|date=March 28, 2019|accessdate=March 29, 2019}}</ref> The same year, Heard was appointed global ambassador for cosmetics giant [[L'Or\u00e9al Paris]].<ref name=glamour2018/>\n\nIn 2019, Heard played supporting roles in the independent dramas ''[[Her Smell]]'' and ''[[Gully (film)|Gully]]''. Her upcoming projects included the [[CBS All Access]] miniseries ''[[The Stand (upcoming miniseries)|The Stand]]'', based on [[Stephen King]]'s eponymous [[The Stand (novel)|novel]] and co-starring [[James Marsden]], [[Odessa Young]] and [[Henry Zaga]].<ref>{{cite magazine|url=https://variety.com/2019/tv/news/james-marsden-amber-heard-the-strand-cbs-all-access-1203288512/|title=James Marsden, Amber Heard Among Four Cast in 'The Stand' at CBS All Access|magazine=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|first=Will|last=Thorne|date=August 1, 2019|accessdate=August 5, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Activism==\nHeard has raised awareness about [[Domestic abuse|domestic]] and [[sexual violence]]. Together with actors [[Gabourey Sidibe]] and [[Freida Pinto]], she read a speech on behalf of sexual assault victim [[People v. Turner|Emily Doe]] at ''[[Glamour (magazine)|Glamour]]''{{'s}} Women of the Year Awards in 2016; Doe was the recipient of an award.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/emily-doe-stanford-rape-case-speech-michelle-dauber-glamour-women-of-the-year-awards-watch-a7418861.html|title=Stanford rape case survivor gives powerful speech at Glamour Women of the Year Awards|first=Rachael|last=Revesz|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=November 15, 2016|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> Heard also made a [[public service announcement]] about domestic violence for the #GirlGaze Project,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2016/digital/news/amber-heard-domestic-violence-psa-video-1201927174/|title=Amber Heard Films Domestic Violence PSA: 'We Can Change This'|first=Seth|last=Kelley|work=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]|date=November 26, 2016|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> and has written about her experiences of domestic violence in the December 2016 issue of ''Porter'' magazine<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/people/amber-heard-domestic-violence-open-letter-porter-a7472426.html|title=Amber Heard pens emotionally charged letter about domestic violence|first=Maya|last=Oppenheim|newspaper=[[The Independent]]|date=December 13, 2016|accessdate=December 19, 2016}}</ref> and in an [[op-ed]] for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in December 2018.<ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttps://www.washingtonpost.com/opinions/ive-seen-how-institutions-protect-men-accused-of-abuse-heres-what-we-can-do/2018/12/18/71fd876a-02ed-11e9-b5df-5d3874f1ac36_story.html |title=Amber Heard: I spoke up against sexual violence \u2014 and faced our culture's wrath. That has to change.|first=Amber|last=Heard|newspaper=[[The Washington Post]]|date=December 18, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref> She has been an [[American Civil Liberties Union]] (ACLU) ambassador for women's rights with a focus on gender-based violence since December 2018,<ref>{{cite web|url= https://www.aclu.org/issues/aclu-ambassador-project|publisher=[[American Civil Liberties Union]]|title=ACLU Ambassador Project|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.instagram.com/p/BrlgL-XgsV6/|publisher=Amber Heard Official Instagram Account|title=I'm honored to announce my role as an @ACLU_nationwide ambassador on women's rights. [...]|date=December 20, 2019|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref> and has also been named a Human Rights Champion for the Stand Up for Human Rights campaign by the [[Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.standup4humanrights.org/en/hr-champions-aheard.html|publisher=Office of the United Nations High Commissioner for Human Rights|title=Human Rights Champions|accessdate=April 19, 2019}}</ref> In May 2019, she gave a speech in support of the SHIELD Act on [[Capitol Hill]], discussing her experience of having had her private nude photos hacked and distributed online without her consent during the [[iCloud leaks of celebrity photos]] in 2014.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.washingtonpost.com/arts-entertainment/2019/05/22/cause-celeb-amber-heard-backs-revenge-porn-bill-capitol-hill/|title=Cause Celeb: Amber Heard backs 'revenge porn' bill on Capitol Hill|first=Emily|last=Heil|newspaper=[[Washington Post]]|date=May 22, 2019|accessdate=May 22, 2019}}</ref> On November 4, 2019, ''[[The New York Times]]'' published an op-ed written by Heard on the subject.<ref name=NYTop-ed>{{cite news|title=Amber Heard: Are We All Celebrities Now?|last=Heard|first=Amber|date=November 4, 2019|accessdate=January 15, 2020|newspaper=[[The New York Times]]|url=https://www.nytimes.com/2019/11/04/opinion/amber-heard-revenge-porn.html}}</ref> In September 2019, she appeared at [[WE Day|WE Day UN]], an event arranged by [[WE Charity]] and [[Joint United Nations Programme on HIV/AIDS|UNAIDS]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.looktothestars.org/news/19296-stars-announced-for-we-day-un|title=Stars Announced For WE Day UN|website=looktothestars.org|date=24 September 2019|access-date=12 March 2020}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\n[[File:AmberHeardTIFFSept10.jpg|thumb|upright|left|Heard at the 2010 Toronto International Film Festival]] In a 2008 interview, Heard stated that she is [[agnostic]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Amber Heard: Pretty Girl Makes Good|work=[[Missbehave]]|url=http://www.robbrink.com/2008/04/22/amber-heard-pretty-girl-makes-good/|accessdate=October 3, 2019|date=April 22, 2008}}</ref> She is fluent in [[American Sign Language]] and Spanish.<ref name=\"things\">{{cite web |url=https://www.vogue.com.au/celebrity/interviews/what-you-probably-didnt-already-know-about-amber-heard/news-story/9fae5e20495c6cc921f5b21e8ac7664b |title=What You Probably Didn't Already Know About Amber Heard |work=[[Vogue (magazine)|Vogue]] |date=January 22, 2014 |accessdate=January 18, 2020 |last=Frank |first=Julia}}</ref>\n\nHeard publicly [[Coming out|came out]]<!--NOTE: Per WP:BLP, especially WP:BLPCAT, Heard is not to be added to the lesbian or bisexual category until she publicly identifies as either lesbian or bisexual. She has publicly identified as being a part of the LGBT community. While sources have identified her as lesbian or bisexual, she has yet to publicly specify her sexual orientation. See past talk page discussions about this. --> at [[GLAAD]]'s 25th anniversary event in 2010,<ref name=\"Halterman\">{{cite web|last=Halterman|first=J.|title=EXCLUSIVE: Amber Heard talks about being out in Hollywood|publisher=[[AfterEllen.com]]|date=December 4, 2010|accessdate=October 10, 2014|url=http://www.afterellen.com/exclusive-amber-heard-talks-about-being-out-in-hollywood/12/2010/}}</ref> but has stated, \"I don't label myself one way or another\u2014I have had successful relationships with men and now a woman. I love who I love; it's the person that matters.\"<ref name=\"Frize\">{{cite news|author=Sam Frize|title=5 Things You Should Know About Amber Heard|work=[[Time (magazine)|Time]]|date=January 19, 2014|accessdate=September 6, 2017|url=http://entertainment.time.com/2014/01/19/5-things-you-should-know-about-amber-heard/}}</ref> Of her decision to come out, she said: \"I think when I became aware of my role in the media, I had to ask myself an important question 'Am I part of the problem?' And I think that when millions and millions of hard-working, taxpaying Americans are denied their rights and denied their equality you have to ask yourself what are the factors that are an epidemic problem and that's what this is.\"<ref name=\"Halterman\" /> \n\nHeard was in a relationship with photographer [[Tasya van Ree]] from 2008 to 2012.<ref name=\"Halterman\" /><ref name=LAtimesengagement>{{cite web|url=http://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-johnny-depp-amber-heard-engagement-rumors-engaged-20140117-story.html|title=Johnny Depp and Amber Heard spark engagement rumors|last=Saad|first=Nardine|website=[[Los Angeles Times]]|date=January 17, 2014|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> In 2009, Heard was arrested in the [[state of Washington]] for misdemeanor domestic violence, allegedly after grabbing van Ree and hitting her arm. Ultimately, no charges were filed against Heard. The police lawfully deleted records of the arrest in 2011 after a request, but the [[King County]] District Court retained their own records. In 2016, van Ree defended Heard as the incident went public, stating that Heard had been \"wrongfully\" accused and that the incident had been \"misinterpreted and over-sensationalized\".<ref>{{cite news |last1=Puente |first1=Maria |title=Amber Heard arrested in 2009 on charge of hitting girlfriend |url=https://www.usatoday.com/story/life/movies/2016/06/07/amber-heard-arrested-2009-charge-hitting-girlfriend/85563338/ |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=[[USA Today]] |date=June 8, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |last1=Hill |first1=Libby |title=Amber Heard was accused of domestic violence by a former girlfriend in 2009 |url=https://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-amber-heard-girlfriend-domestic-violence-20160607-snap-story.html |accessdate=February 18, 2020 |work=[[Los Angeles Times]] |date=June 7, 2016}}</ref>\n\nIn 2014, Heard was one of the victims of the [[iCloud leaks of celebrity photos]], in which her private nude photos were hacked and distributed without her consent.<ref name=NYTop-ed/>\n\nFollowing her divorce from actor [[Johnny Depp]], Heard dated tech entrepreneur [[Elon Musk]] for several months, until early 2018.<ref name=THRDec2018/>\n\n{{anchor|Depp}}\n===Relationship with Johnny Depp===\n[[File:Black Mass 09 (21445362382).jpg|thumb|Amber Heard and [[Johnny Depp]] arriving at the premiere of ''[[Black Mass (film)|Black Mass]]'', [[2015 Toronto International Film Festival]]]]\n{{see also|Johnny Depp#Relationship with Amber Heard}}\n\nHeard met Depp while filming ''[[The Rum Diary (film)|The Rum Diary]]'' in 2009, and they began living together the following year.<ref name=\"LAtimesengagement\"/><ref name=courtdocument>{{cite web|url=http://documents.latimes.com/amber-heard-and-johnny-depps-court-declarations-regarding-allegations-domestic-violence/|title=Amber Heard and Johnny Depp's court declarations regarding allegations of domestic violence|work=Los Angeles Times|date=May 27, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> They were married in a private civil ceremony at their home in Los Angeles on February 3, 2015.<ref name=courtdocument/><ref>{{cite web|title=Johnny Depp and Amber Heard Tie the Knot: Source|url=http://www.people.com/article/johnny-depp-amber-heard-marry-wedding-civil-ceremony-los-angeles|work=People|accessdate=February 4, 2015}}</ref> In April 2015, Heard and Depp breached Australia's [[biosecurity]] laws when they failed to declare their two [[Yorkshire terrier]]s to the [[Australian Customs Service]] when they flew by private jet into [[Queensland]], where he was working on ''[[Pirates of the Caribbean: Dead Men Tell No Tales]]''.<ref>{{cite news|title=Johnny Depp's dogs face death in Australia|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-australia-32732313|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=BBC News|date=May 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Amber Heard charged with illegally bringing dogs to Australia|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2015/jul/16/amber-heard-charged-with-taking-dogs-to-australia-johnny-depp|accessdate=April 18, 2016|work=The Guardian|date=July 16, 2015}}</ref> Heard pleaded guilty to falsifying quarantine documents, stating that she had made a mistake due to sleep deprivation.<ref>{{cite news|title=Johnny Depp's dogs: Amber Heard pleads guilty over Boo and Pistol quarantine document|url=http://www.abc.net.au/news/2016-04-18/johnny-depp-and-amber-heard-gold-coast-court-dogs/7333662|accessdate=April 18, 2016|publisher=ABC News|date=April 18, 2016}}</ref> She was placed on a $1,000 one-month [[Discharge (sentence)#Australia|good behavior bond]] for producing a false document;<ref name=guardianterriers>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/apr/18/johnny-depps-wife-amber-heard-pleads-guilty-over-bringing-dogs-to-australia|title=Charges dropped against Amber Heard for bringing dogs to Australia with Johnny Depp|author=Joshua Robertson|work=The Guardian|accessdate=April 18, 2016}}</ref> Heard and Depp also released a video in which they apologized for their behavior and urged people to adhere to the biosecurity laws.<ref name=guardianterriers/> ''[[The Guardian]]'' called the case the \"highest profile criminal quarantine case\" in Australian history.<ref name=guardianterriers/>\n\nHeard filed for divorce from Depp on May 23, 2016, and obtained a temporary [[restraining order]] against him, stating in her court declaration that he had been verbally and physically abusive throughout their relationship, usually while under the influence of drugs or alcohol.<ref name=cnn>{{cite web|url= http://edition.cnn.com/2016/08/16/entertainment/amber-heard-johnny-depp-timeline/|title=Johnny Depp and Amber Heard Settle Divorce|publisher=CNN|first=Lisa Respers|last=France|date=August 16, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref><ref name=wright>{{cite web|url=http://www.refinery29.com/2016/06/113149/domestic-violence-911-call-famous-friend|title=Why I Called 911|last=Wright|first=iO Tillett|publisher=[[Refinery29]]|date=June 8, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=\nhttp://www.latimes.com/entertainment/gossip/la-et-mg-amber-heard-bruise-photos-20160601-snap-story.html|title=New photos of Amber Heard show bruised eye and bloody lip|work=Los Angeles Times|date=June 1, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016|first=Libby|last=Hill}}</ref><ref name=\"Variety2019\">{{cite web |title=Amber Heard Claims Johnny Depp Threatened to Kill Her During Years of Abuse|url=https://variety.com/2019/film/news/amber-heard-johnny-depp-abuse-threatened-kill-1203187472/|website=[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]] |accessdate=April 19, 2019 |date=April 11, 2019}}</ref> In response, Depp denied those accusations, and through his representatives, alleged that she was \"attempting to secure a premature financial resolution by alleging abuse.\"<ref name=cnn/><ref name=guardiancarroll>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/film/2016/aug/16/amber-heard-assault-allegations-johnny-depp-divorce|title=Amber Heard settles domestic abuse case against Johnny Depp|work=The Guardian|first=Rory|last=Carroll|date=August 16, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> Heard testified about the abuse under oath at a divorce court deposition.<ref name=\"Variety2019\"/> Evidence of the alleged abuse from her court filings was also published in the media.<ref name=guardiancarroll/><ref name=cnn/> A settlement was reached on August 16, 2016,<ref name=NYT>{{cite web|url=http://nytlive.nytimes.com/womenintheworld/2016/08/19/amber-heard-to-give-7m-johnny-depp-divorce-settlement-to-charity/|title=Amber Heard To Give $7M Johnny Depp Divorce Settlement To Charity|work=[[The New York Times]]|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=August 20, 2016}}</ref> and the divorce was finalized in January 2017.<ref>{{cite news| url = https://www.bbc.com/news/world-us-canada-38621519 |title=Johnny Depp and Amber Heard Finalise Divorce|date= January 14, 2017|accessdate=January 14, 2017| publisher=BBC}}</ref> Heard dismissed the restraining order, and the former couple issued a joint statement saying that their \"relationship was intensely passionate and at times volatile, but always bound by love. Neither party has made false accusations for financial gain. There was never any intent of physical or emotional harm.\"<ref name=NYT/> Depp paid Heard a settlement of US$7&nbsp;million, which she donated to the ACLU and the [[Children's Hospital Los Angeles]].<ref name=NYT/><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.aclu.org/blog/speak-freely/actress-amber-heard-donates-millions-support-aclu-and-its-work-fighting-violence|title=Actress Amber Heard Donates Millions to Support the ACLU and Its Work Fighting Violence Against Women|publisher=[[American Civil Liberties Union]]|date=August 19, 2016|accessdate=May 23, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Amber Heard Honored for 7-Figure Donation to Children's Hospital Following Johnny Depp Divorce|url=http://people.com/movies/amber-heard-makes-7-figure-donation-childrens-hospital-after-johnny-depp-divorce/|work=People|author=Miller, Mike|date=April 9, 2018|accessdate=May 4, 2018}}</ref>\n\nIn early 2019, Depp sued Heard for US$50 million for defamation over an [[op-ed]] she wrote for ''[[The Washington Post]]'' in December 2018, which \"depended on the central premise that Ms. Heard was a domestic abuse victim and that Mr. Depp perpetrated domestic violence against her\".<ref>{{cite web |last1=Griffith |first1=Janelle |title=Johnny Depp sues ex-wife Amber Heard for $50 million for allegedly defaming him |url=https://www.nbcnews.com/news/us-news/johnny-depp-sues-ex-wife-amber-heard-50-million-allegedly-n978976 |date=March 4, 2019|publisher=NBC News|accessdate=April 12, 2019}}</ref><ref name=\"varietymarch2019\">{{cite web|url=https://variety.com/2019/biz/news/johnny-depp-amber-heard-defamation-washington-post-op-ed-50-million-1203153857/amp/|title=Johnny Depp Reportedly Sues Amber Heard for $50M Over Washington Post Op-Ed|last=Nyren|first=Erin|date=March 2, 2019|website=Variety|accessdate=March 3, 2019}}</ref> The fact that the piece did not specifically mention Depp by name is not disputed by either party.<ref name=\"Variety2019\" /> Depp also alleged that Heard had been the abuser, and that her allegations constituted a [[hoax]] against him;<ref name=\"varietymarch2019\" /> his legal team also published alleged evidence of Heard's abuse of Depp.<ref>{{cite web |title=Johnny Depp's lawyer says Amber Heard 'perpetrated serial violence'; she fires back with abuse claims |accessdate=February 10, 2020 |date=February 3, 2020 |website=USA Today |url=https://eu.usatoday.com/story/entertainment/celebrities/2020/02/02/johnny-depp-amber-heard-perpetrated-serial-violence-lawyer-says/4639763002/}}</ref> In response, Heard said that Depp's claims are not true and repeated her allegations and evidence, maintaining that Depp was abusive towards her.<ref name=\"Variety2019\" /> She asked a judge to dismiss the lawsuit\u2014which Depp filed in [[Virginia]], where the ''Post'' is located\u2014so that the case could be tried in California (where most of the witnesses reside), but this request was denied.<ref>{{cite web |title=Johnny Depp's ex-wife asks judge to dismiss his lawsuit |url=https://apnews.com/82e4e8ea36df417e86d6d2b334b065f9 |website=[[AP News]] |accessdate=April 12, 2019 |date=April 11, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Puente |first1=Maria |last2=Mandell |first2=Andrea |title=Johnny Depp v Amber Heard: Depp submits photos of black eye, details feces 'prank' |url=https://amp.usatoday.com/amp/3450310002 |website=USA Today |accessdate=May 21, 2019 |date=May 20, 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last=Gardner |first=Eriq |title=Johnny Depp's $50M Defamation Suit Against Amber Heard Allowed in Virginia |url=https://www.hollywoodreporter.com/thr-esq/johnny-depps-50m-defamation-suit-amber-heard-allowed-virginia-1227186 |website=The Hollywood Reporter |accessdate=August 5, 2019 |date=July 26, 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Filmography==\n[[File:Amber Heard (17043468150).jpg|thumb|Amber Heard at the 2015 [[Tribeca Film Festival]]]]\n\n===Film===\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|-\n! Year\n! Title\n! Role\n! Notes\n|-\n| 2004 || ''[[Friday Night Lights (film)|Friday Night Lights]]''|| Maria ||\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2005 || ''Side FX''|| Shay ||\n|-\n || ''[[Drop Dead Sexy]]''|| Candy ||\n|-\n || ''[[North Country (film)|North Country]]''|| Young Josey Aimes ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=3|2006 || ''Price to Pay''|| Trish ||\n|-\n || ''[[Alpha Dog]]''|| Alma ||\n|-\n || ''[[All the Boys Love Mandy Lane]]''|| Mandy Lane ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=3|2007 || ''[[Spin (2007 film)|Spin]]''|| Amber ||\n|-\n || ''Day 73 with Sarah''|| Mary || Short film\n|-\n || ''[[Remember the Daze]]''|| Julia Ford ||\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2008 ||''[[Never Back Down]]''|| Baja Miller ||\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Informers|dab=2008 film}}''|| Christie ||\n|-\n ||''[[Pineapple Express (film)|Pineapple Express]]''|| Angie ||\n|-\n| rowspan=4|2009 || ''[[ExTerminators (film)|ExTerminators]]''|| Nikki ||\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Joneses}}'' || Jenn Jones ||\n|-\n || ''[[Zombieland]]''|| 406 ||\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Stepfather|dab=2009 film}}''|| Kelly Porter ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=3|2010 || ''[[And Soon the Darkness (2010 film)|And Soon the Darkness]]''|| Stephanie || Also co-producer\n|-\n|| ''{{sortname|The|River Why|dab=film}}'' || Eddy ||\n|-\n || ''{{sortname|The|Ward|dab=film}}''|| Kristen ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=2|2011 || ''[[Drive Angry]]'' || Piper ||\n|-\n|| ''{{sortname|The|Rum Diary|dab=film}}'' || Chenault ||\n|-\n|  rowspan=3|2013 || ''[[Syrup (film)|Syrup]]'' || Six || Also executive producer\n|-\n|| ''[[Paranoia (2013 film)|Paranoia]]'' || Emma Jennings ||\n|-\n || ''[[Machete Kills]]'' || Miss San A