2005\n| \"I Wasn't Prepared\" <small>(Version 1)\n| [[Eisley]]\n|}\n\n== Awards and nominations ==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|- \"\n! Year\n! Award\n! Category\n! Nominated work\n! Result\n|-\n| 2008\n| [[Young Hollywood Awards]]\n| [[Young Hollywood Awards|Breakthrough of the Year]]\n| Herself\n| {{won}}\n|-\n| 2009\n| [[Detroit Film Critics Society|Detroit Film Critics Society Awards]]\n|  rowspan=2|Best Ensemble\n| rowspan=2|''[[Zombieland]]''\n| {{nom}}\n|-\n| rowspan=2|2010\n| [[Scream Awards]]\n| rowspan=4 {{won}}\n|-\n| [[Dallas International Film Festival]]\n| [[Dallas International Film Festival|Dallas Star Award]]\n| Herself\n|-\n| 2011\n| [[Hollywood Film Festival]]\n| [[Hollywood Film Festival|Spotlight Award]]\n| ''[[The Rum Diary (film)|The Rum Diary]]''\n|-\n| 2014\n| [[Texas Film Hall of Fame]]\n| [[Texas Film Hall of Fame|Inductee]]\n| Herself\n|-\n| rowspan=3|2019\n| [[39th Golden Raspberry Awards|Golden Raspberry Awards]]\n| [[Golden Raspberry Award for Worst Actress|Worst Actress]]\n| ''[[London Fields (film)|London Fields]]''\n|  rowspan=3 {{nom}}\n|-\n| [[Saturn Award]]\n| [[Saturn Award for Best Supporting Actress|Best Supporting Actress]]\n|  rowspan=2|''[[Aquaman (film)|Aquaman]]''\n|-\n| [[Teen Choice Awards]]\n| Choice Sci-Fi/Fantasy Movie Actress\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{Sister project links |wikt=no |commons=Category:Amber Heard |b=no |n=no |q=no |s=no |v=no |species=no |display=Amber Heard|voy=no|d=Q229166}}\n* {{IMDb name|1720028|Amber Heard}}\n* {{Allrovi name|418732|Amber Heard}}\n* {{Tcmdb name}}\n* {{Instagram|amberheard}}\n\n{{Johnny Depp}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n<!-- NOTE: Per WP:BLPCAT, Heard is not to be added to the lesbian or bisexual category until she publicly identifies as either lesbian or bisexual. She has publicly identified as being a part of the LGBT community. While sources have identified her as lesbian or bisexual, she has yet to publicly specify her sexual orientation. See past talk page discussions about this. -->\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Heard, Amber}}\n[[Category:1986 births]]\n[[Category:21st-century American actresses]]\n[[Category:Actresses from Austin, Texas]]\n[[Category:American atheists]]\n[[Category:American film actresses]]\n[[Category:American former Christians]]\n[[Category:American television actresses]]\n[[Category:American women activists]]\n[[Category:Former Roman Catholics]]\n[[Category:LGBT actresses]]\n[[Category:LGBT entertainers from the United States]]\n[[Category:LGBT people from Texas]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Victims of domestic abuse]]\n[[Category:American agnostics]]\n", "name_user": "Gondora16", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eFilmography", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Amber_Heard"}
{"title_page": "John Penrose", "text_new": "{{Other people|John Penrose}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = John Penrose\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of John Penrose MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Northern Ireland Office|Minister of State for Northern Ireland]]\n| primeminister = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start = 16 November 2018\n| term_end = 25 July 2019\n| predecessor = [[Shailesh Vara]]\n| successor = [[Nick Hurd]]\n|office1          = [[Cabinet Office|Minister for Constitutional Reform]]\n|primeminister1    = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start1       = 11 May 2015\n|term_end1         = 17 July 2016\n|predecessor1 = [[Sam Gyimah]] \n|successor1 = [[Chris Skidmore]]\n| office2 = [[Lord of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| term_start2 = 8 February 2014\n| term_end2 = 17 July 2016\n| predecessor2 = [[Karen Bradley]]\n| successor2 = [[Guy Opperman]]\n| primeminister2 = [[David Cameron]]\n| office3 = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] <br /> [[Department of Culture, Media and Sport|for Tourism and Heritage]]\n| term_start3 = 13 May 2010\n| term_end3 = 4 September 2012\n| predecessor3 = [[Margaret Hodge]]\n| successor3 = Office Dissolved\n| primeminister3 = [[David Cameron]]\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Weston-super-Mare (UK Parliament constituency)|Weston-super-Mare]]\n| parliament4 = \n| term_start4 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end4 = \n| majority4 = 17,128 (30.8%)\n| predecessor4 = [[Brian Cotter, Baron Cotter|Brian Cotter]]\n| successor4 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1964|06|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Sudbury, Suffolk]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = [[Dido Harding|Dido Harding, Baroness Harding]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Downing College, Cambridge]]; [[Columbia University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = Anglican\n| signature = \n| website = [http://www.johnpenrose.org/ www.johnpenrose.org]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''John David Penrose''' (born 22 June 1964) is the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Weston-super-Mare (UK Parliament constituency)|Weston-super-Mare]] who was first elected in [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]. He previously served as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] and more recently as a [[Lords Commissioners of HM Treasury|Lord Commissioner of Her Majesty's Treasury]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/about_us/our_ministers/default.aspx |title=About - Department for Culture, Media & Sport - GOV.UK |publisher=Culture.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref> From 16 November 2018 to 25 July 2019, Penrose served as Minister of State to Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46241693 |title=Stephen Barclay named new Brexit Secretary |work=BBC News |date=16 November 2018 |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nPenrose was born in [[Sudbury, Suffolk|Sudbury]], [[Suffolk]] on 22 June 1964. He was privately educated at [[Ipswich School]] and studied at [[Downing College, Cambridge]], receiving a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in Law in 1986. He received an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] from [[Columbia University]] in 1991.\n\nHe was a Bank Trading Floor [[Financial risk management|Risk Manager]] at [[J. P. Morgan]] from 1986\u201390, then a [[management consultant]] at [[McKinsey & Company]] from 1992\u201394. He was Commercial Director of the Academic Books Division at Thomson Publishing in [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]] from 1995\u201396, then Managing Director of Schools Book Publishing at [[Longman]] ([[Pearson plc]]), publishing school textbooks for the UK and parts of Africa. He was chairman of Logotron Ltd in [[Cambridge]]. (also owned by Pearson). In 1998, he was in charge of research at the [[Bow Group]] - a UK-based independent think tank, promoting conservative opinion internationally.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nPenrose unsuccessfully contested the seat of [[Ealing Southall (UK Parliament constituency)|Ealing Southall]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], before unsuccessfully contesting the seat of [[Weston-super-Mare (UK Parliament constituency)|Weston-super-Mare]] in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]. He was elected in the same seat in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], defeating the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Brian Cotter, Baron Cotter|Brian Cotter]] and he retained his seat in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] and [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]]. He served on the [[Work and Pensions Committee]] from July 2005 to January 2009, and in 2006 was appointed joint chairman of the [[All-Party Parliamentary Group]] (APPG) on Further Education and Lifelong Learning. In 2006 he was also appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Oliver Letwin]] MP and in 2009 was promoted to Shadow Minister for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform.\n\nAfter his re-election in 2010 and the formation of the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|coalition government]], Penrose served as the [[Minister for Tourism and Heritage]] from 2010 to 2012, covering the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen's Diamond Jubilee]] and the [[2012 Summer Olympics|London Olympic]] and [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Paralympic Games]]. During his tenure, he wrote and implemented the Government's Tourism Strategy; began a process to turn English Heritage's properties, such as Stonehenge, Dover Castle, Tintagel and many others, into a second National Trust; removed licences on live entertainment; sold the Tote bookmaker; protected the Lloyd's of London building with a 'Grade 1' listing amongst other activity.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nPenrose returned to the backbenches in 2012. He wrote a paper (We Deserve Better) on how to give people a better deal on their utilities. Less than a year later the Prime Minister invited Penrose back to a Government role with a new position as Assistant Whip (HM Treasury), before he was promoted in February 2014 as one of the [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury]] (Whip). In May 2015 he became Parliamentary Secretary (Cabinet Office), a role he held until July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/john-penrose/1584|title=John Penrose MP|publisher=GOV.UK |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> \t\t\t\n\nHe was opposed to Brexit prior to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=22 July 2018|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016}}</ref> Since the result was announced, Penrose has continued to support the official position of his party and now advocates leaving the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/11924/john_penrose/weston-super-mare|title=They Work For You|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=A secondary source would be preferable.|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Outside Parliament==\nPenrose is a Patron of the South West branch of domestic violence charity the [[ManKind Initiative]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mankind.org.uk/aboutus.html |title=About us |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817233358/http://www.mankind.org.uk/aboutus.html |archivedate=17 August 2010 }}</ref> He is also President of Weston-super-Mare's YMCA, President of The Abbeyfield Weston-super-Mare Society, President of the League of Friends of [[Weston General Hospital]], a governor of Weston College, a trustee of North Somerset Citizens Advice Bureau, and President of Weston-super-Mare and District Constitutional Club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnpenrose.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=81 |title=John Penrose MP - Your local man in Westminster |publisher=Johnpenrose.org |accessdate=23 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318161841/http://www.johnpenrose.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=81 |archivedate=18 March 2016  }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPenrose met the [[Dido Harding|Hon. Dido (Diana) Harding]], only daughter of [[John Charles Harding, 2nd Baron Harding of Petherton|Lord Harding]], while both worked at McKinsey. The couple married in October 1995, and have two daughters. Penrose splits his time between his home in the [[Weston-super-Mare]] constituency and a flat in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Penrose_John.aspx|title=John Penrose|publisher=The Conservative Party|accessdate=30 March 2011}}</ref> Harding is the Chair of NHS Improvement,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://improvement.nhs.uk/person-detail/27/baroness-dido-harding/?from_listing=89 |title=Baroness Dido Harding &#124; NHS Improvement |work=Improvement.nhs.uk |date=30 October 2017 |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> former [[Chief Executive]] of [[TalkTalk Group]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talktalkgroup.com/corporate-information/corporate-governance.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=30 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226132834/http://www.talktalkgroup.com/corporate-information/corporate-governance.html |archivedate=26 February 2011 }}</ref> and owned the 1998 [[Cheltenham Gold Cup]] winning horse, [[Cool Dawn]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Dido Harding|title=Cool Dawn: My National Velvet|publisher=Mainstream Publishing|date=8 March 1999|isbn=1-84018-179-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=10917296&ticker=TALK:LN&previousCapId=84118320&previousTitle=CABLE%20%26%20WIRELESS%20WORLDWIDE |title=List of Public Companies Worldwide |work=Investing.businessweek.com |date= |accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref> \n \nIn 2016, Penrose, who lives in [[Winscombe]], [[North Somerset]], caused some local controversy over the design of a proposed personal swimming pool complex at his home. Winscombe and Sandford Parish Council formally objected to the 'ugly and massive' design on the grounds it would harm local views. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that this was noteworthy as Penrose had argued in 2013, in a previous ministerial role, for greater protection of historic views, suggesting some of the finest urban views in the country should be listed like buildings. Ultimately, the district council approved the planning application and accepted the argument that an originally planned grass roof was not possible.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/22/tory-mp-and-talk-talk-boss-at-war-with-villagers-over-ugly-pool/ |title=Minister who called for protection of heritage views, builds 'hideous' pool next to listed church |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=22 April 2016 |accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.johnpenrose.co.uk/}}\n* [https://twitter.com/JohnPenroseNews/ Personal/Staff Twitter Account]\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=john-penrose/1584 |publicwhip=John_Penrose |theywork=john_penrose}}\n* [http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Penrose_John.aspx John Penrose MP] biography at the site of the Conservative Party\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-6182,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: John Penrose MP]\n* [http://www.weston-conservatives.co.uk Weston-Super-Mare Conservatives]\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Cotter, Baron Cotter|Brian Cotter]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Weston-super-Mare (UK Parliament constituency)|Weston-super-Mare]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South West Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Penrose, John David}}\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ipswich School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Downing College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People from Sudbury, Suffolk]]\n[[Category:Spouses of life peers]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Politics of North Somerset]]\n[[Category:ManKind Initiative people]]\n[[Category:John Harding family]]\n", "text_old": "{{Other people|John Penrose}}\n{{short description|British Conservative politician}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=November 2019}}\n{{Use British English|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix = \n| name = John Penrose\n| honorific-suffix = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|MP]]\n| image = Official portrait of John Penrose MP crop 2.jpg\n| office = [[Northern Ireland Office|Minister of State for Northern Ireland]]\n| primeminister = [[Theresa May]]\n| term_start = 16 November 2018\n| term_end = 25 July 2019\n| predecessor = [[Shailesh Vara]]\n| successor = [[Nick Hurd]]\n|office1          = [[Cabinet Office|Minister for Constitutional Reform]]\n|primeminister1    = [[David Cameron]]\n|term_start1       = 11 May 2015\n|term_end1         = 17 July 2016\n|predecessor1 = [[Sam Gyimah]] \n|successor1 = [[Chris Skidmore]]\n| office2 = [[Lord of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| term_start2 = 8 February 2014\n| term_end2 = 17 July 2016\n| predecessor2 = [[Karen Bradley]]\n| successor2 = [[Guy Opperman]]\n| primeminister2 = [[David Cameron]]\n| office3 = [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] <br /> [[Department of Culture, Media and Sport|for Tourism and Heritage]]\n| term_start3 = 13 May 2010\n| term_end3 = 4 September 2012\n| predecessor3 = [[Margaret Hodge]]\n| successor3 = Office Dissolved\n| primeminister3 = [[David Cameron]]\n| office4 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Weston-super-Mare (UK Parliament constituency)|Weston-super-Mare]]\n| parliament4 = \n| term_start4 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end4 = \n| majority4 = 17,128 (30.8%)\n| predecessor4 = [[Brian Cotter, Baron Cotter|Brian Cotter]]\n| successor4 = \n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1964|06|22|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Sudbury, Suffolk]], England\n| death_date = \n| death_place = \n| nationality = [[United Kingdom|British]]\n| spouse = [[Dido Harding|Dido Harding, Baroness Harding]]\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations = \n| children = \n| residence = \n| alma_mater = [[Downing College, Cambridge]]; [[Columbia University]]\n| occupation = \n| profession = \n| religion = Anglican\n| signature = \n| website = [http://www.johnpenrose.org/ www.johnpenrose.org]\n| footnotes = \n}}\n'''John David Penrose''' (born 22 June 1964) is the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] (MP) for [[Weston-super-Mare (UK Parliament constituency)|Weston-super-Mare]] who was first elected in [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]. He previously served as [[Parliamentary Under-Secretary of State]] at the [[Department for Culture, Media and Sport]] and more recently as a [[Lords Commissioners of HM Treasury|Lord Commissioner of Her Majesty's Treasury]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.culture.gov.uk/about_us/our_ministers/default.aspx |title=About - Department for Culture, Media & Sport - GOV.UK |publisher=Culture.gov.uk |date= |accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref> From 16 November 2018 to 25 July 2019, Penrose served as Minister of State to Northern Ireland.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/uk-46241693 |title=Stephen Barclay named new Brexit Secretary |work=BBC News |date=16 November 2018 |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life and career==\nPenrose was born in [[Sudbury, Suffolk|Sudbury]], [[Suffolk]] on 22 June 1964. He was privately educated at [[Ipswich School]] and studied at [[Downing College, Cambridge]], receiving a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in Law in 1986. He received an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] from [[Columbia University]] in 1991.\n\nHe was a Bank Trading Floor [[Financial risk management|Risk Manager]] at [[J. P. Morgan]] from 1986\u201390, then a [[management consultant]] at [[McKinsey & Company]] from 1992\u201394. He was Commercial Director of the Academic Books Division at Thomson Publishing in [[Andover, Hampshire|Andover]] from 1995\u201396, then Managing Director of Schools Book Publishing at [[Longman]] ([[Pearson plc]]), publishing school textbooks for the UK and parts of Africa. He was chairman of Logotron Ltd in [[Cambridge]]. (also owned by Pearson). In 1998, he was in charge of research at the [[Bow Group]] - a UK-based independent think tank, promoting conservative opinion internationally.\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nPenrose unsuccessfully contested the seat of [[Ealing Southall (UK Parliament constituency)|Ealing Southall]] in the [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997 general election]], before unsuccessfully contesting the seat of [[Weston-super-Mare (UK Parliament constituency)|Weston-super-Mare]] in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]. He was elected in the same seat in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]], defeating the [[Liberal Democrats (UK)|Liberal Democrat]] [[Brian Cotter, Baron Cotter|Brian Cotter]] and he retained his seat in the [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010 general election]], [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]] and [[2017 United Kingdom general election|2017 general election]]. He served on the [[Work and Pensions Committee]] from July 2005 to January 2009, and in 2006 was appointed joint chairman of the [[All-Party Parliamentary Group]] (APPG) on Further Education and Lifelong Learning. In 2006 he was also appointed [[Parliamentary Private Secretary]] to [[Oliver Letwin]] MP and in 2009 was promoted to Shadow Minister for Business, Enterprise and Regulatory Reform.\n\nAfter his re-election in 2010 and the formation of the [[Cameron\u2013Clegg coalition|coalition government]], Penrose served as the [[Minister for Tourism and Heritage]] from 2010 to 2012, covering the [[Diamond Jubilee of Elizabeth II|Queen\u2019s Diamond Jubilee]] and the [[2012 Summer Olympics|London Olympic]] and [[2012 Summer Paralympics|Paralympic Games]]. During his tenure, he wrote and implemented the Government's Tourism Strategy; began a process to turn English Heritage's properties, such as Stonehenge, Dover Castle, Tintagel and many others, into a second National Trust; removed licences on live entertainment; sold the Tote bookmaker; protected the Lloyd's of London building with a 'Grade 1' listing amongst other activity.{{citation needed|date=January 2019}}\n\nPenrose returned to the backbenches in 2012. He wrote a paper (We Deserve Better) on how to give people a better deal on their utilities. Less than a year later the Prime Minister invited Penrose back to a Government role with a new position as Assistant Whip (HM Treasury), before he was promoted in February 2014 as one of the [[Lords Commissioners of the Treasury]] (Whip). In May 2015 he became Parliamentary Secretary (Cabinet Office), a role he held until July 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.parliament.uk/biographies/commons/john-penrose/1584|title=John Penrose MP|publisher=GOV.UK |accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref> \t\t\t\n\nHe was opposed to Brexit prior to the [[2016 United Kingdom European Union membership referendum|2016 referendum]].<ref name=\"thespectatorwhichtorympsbackbrexit\">{{cite news|last1=Goodenough|first1=Tom|title=Which Tory MPs back Brexit, who doesn't and who is still on the fence?|url=http://blogs.spectator.co.uk/2016/02/which-tory-mps-back-brexit-who-doesnt-and-who-is-still-on-the-fence/|accessdate=22 July 2018|work=The Spectator|date=16 February 2016}}</ref> Since the result was announced, Penrose has continued to support the official position of his party and now advocates leaving the European Union.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theyworkforyou.com/mp/11924/john_penrose/weston-super-mare|title=They Work For You|publisher=GOV.UK|accessdate=22 July 2018}}</ref>{{Better source|reason=A secondary source would be preferable.|date=January 2019}}\n\n==Outside Parliament==\nPenrose is a Patron of the South West branch of domestic violence charity the [[ManKind Initiative]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.mankind.org.uk/aboutus.html |title=About us |accessdate=12 July 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20100817233358/http://www.mankind.org.uk/aboutus.html |archivedate=17 August 2010 }}</ref> He is also President of Weston-super-Mare's YMCA, President of The Abbeyfield Weston-super-Mare Society, President of the League of Friends of [[Weston General Hospital]], a governor of Weston College, a trustee of North Somerset Citizens Advice Bureau, and President of Weston-super-Mare and District Constitutional Club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.johnpenrose.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=81 |title=John Penrose MP - Your local man in Westminster |publisher=Johnpenrose.org |accessdate=23 April 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160318161841/http://www.johnpenrose.org/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=46&Itemid=81 |archivedate=18 March 2016  }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPenrose met the [[Dido Harding|Hon. Dido (Diana) Harding]], only daughter of [[John Charles Harding, 2nd Baron Harding of Petherton|Lord Harding]], while both worked at McKinsey. The couple married in October 1995, and have two daughters. Penrose splits his time between his home in the [[Weston-super-Mare]] constituency and a flat in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Penrose_John.aspx|title=John Penrose|publisher=The Conservative Party|accessdate=30 March 2011}}</ref> Harding is the Chair of NHS Improvement,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://improvement.nhs.uk/person-detail/27/baroness-dido-harding/?from_listing=89 |title=Baroness Dido Harding &#124; NHS Improvement |work=Improvement.nhs.uk |date=30 October 2017 |accessdate=24 January 2019}}</ref> former [[Chief Executive]] of [[TalkTalk Group]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.talktalkgroup.com/corporate-information/corporate-governance.html |title=Archived copy |accessdate=30 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110226132834/http://www.talktalkgroup.com/corporate-information/corporate-governance.html |archivedate=26 February 2011 }}</ref> and owned the 1998 [[Cheltenham Gold Cup]] winning horse, [[Cool Dawn]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Dido Harding|title=Cool Dawn: My National Velvet|publisher=Mainstream Publishing|date=8 March 1999|isbn=1-84018-179-6}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://investing.businessweek.com/research/stocks/people/person.asp?personId=10917296&ticker=TALK:LN&previousCapId=84118320&previousTitle=CABLE%20%26%20WIRELESS%20WORLDWIDE |title=List of Public Companies Worldwide |work=Investing.businessweek.com |date= |accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref> \n \nIn 2016, Penrose, who lives in [[Winscombe]], [[North Somerset]], caused some local controversy over the design of a proposed personal swimming pool complex at his home. Winscombe and Sandford Parish Council formally objected to the 'ugly and massive' design on the grounds it would harm local views. ''[[The Daily Telegraph]]'' reported that this was noteworthy as Penrose had argued in 2013, in a previous ministerial role, for greater protection of historic views, suggesting some of the finest urban views in the country should be listed like buildings. Ultimately, the district council approved the planning application and accepted the argument that an originally planned grass roof was not possible.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/2016/04/22/tory-mp-and-talk-talk-boss-at-war-with-villagers-over-ugly-pool/ |title=Minister who called for protection of heritage views, builds 'hideous' pool next to listed church |work=The Daily Telegraph |date=22 April 2016 |accessdate=23 April 2016}}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* {{Official website|http://www.johnpenrose.co.uk/}}\n* [https://twitter.com/JohnPenroseNews/ Personal/Staff Twitter Account]\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=john-penrose/1584 |publicwhip=John_Penrose |theywork=john_penrose}}\n* [http://www.conservatives.com/People/Members_of_Parliament/Penrose_John.aspx John Penrose MP] biography at the site of the Conservative Party\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-6182,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: John Penrose MP]\n* [http://www.weston-conservatives.co.uk Weston-Super-Mare Conservatives]\n* {{C-SPAN}}\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Brian Cotter, Baron Cotter|Brian Cotter]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Weston-super-Mare (UK Parliament constituency)|Weston-super-Mare]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013present}}\n{{s-inc}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{South West Conservative Party MPs}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Penrose, John David}}\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:1964 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:People educated at Ipswich School]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Downing College, Cambridge]]\n[[Category:People from Sudbury, Suffolk]]\n[[Category:Spouses of life peers]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2015\u20132017]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2017\u20132019]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2019\u2013]]\n[[Category:Politics of North Somerset]]\n[[Category:ManKind Initiative people]]\n[[Category:John Harding family]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eParliamentary career:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/John_Penrose"}
{"title_page": "Glenn Fredly", "text_new": "{{short description|Indonesian singer-songwriter}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image            = Glenn Fredly.jpg\n| name             = Glenn Fredly\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Glenn Fredly Deviano Latuihamallo\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1975|09|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Jakarta]], Indonesia\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2020|04|08|1975|09|30|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = Jakarta, Indonesia\n| origin           = [[Ambon Island|Ambon]]\n| occupation       = Singer-songwriter-producer-actor\n| genre            = {{flat list|\n*[[Jazz]]\n*[[Pop music|pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| instrument       = Vocals, Guitar, Bass Guitar, Piano\n| years_active     = 1995\u20132020\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = [https://www.glennfredly.com glennfredly.com]\n}}\n\n'''Glenn Fredly Deviano Latuihamallo''' (30 September 1975 \u2013 8 April 2020), known professionally as '''Glenn Fredly''', was an [[Indonesia]]n [[R&B]] singer and songwriter as well as producer and actor. Entering the music industry after winning a singing contest in 1995, he released more than 10 albums. He produced new talented artists like female vocalist [[Yura (Indonesian singer)|Yura]] and male soloist Gilbert Pohan. He also produced ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]''. In 2013, he served as a coach for ''[[The Voice Indonesia]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nFredly was born on 30 September 1975 to Hengky and Linda Latuihamallo. He was the first of five children.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} Fredly was of [[Moluccas|Molucca]]n descent.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | last = Yudo\n  | first = Aji\n  | title = Glenn Fredly Menjadi Produser Album Maluku Hip-Hop Community\n  | publisher = [[Rolling Stone (magazine)|RollingStone]] Indonesia\n  | date = 11 June 2011\n  | url = http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/05/11/125927/1637229/1093/glenn-fredly-menjadi-produser-album-maluku-hip-hop-community\n  | access-date = 7 September 2011\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110517214210/http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/05/11/125927/1637229/1093/glenn-fredly-menjadi-produser-album-maluku-hip-hop-community\n  | archive-date = 17 May 2011\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1995, he won the [[Cipta Pesona Bintang]] singing contest.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} That same year, he joined the rock band Funk Section.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} The following year, he was a finalist in the [[Asia Song Festival]].{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} In 1998, Fredly left Funk Section to be a solo R&B singer, feeling that it suited his vocal style better. He released his first album, ''GLENN'', that year. It was relatively well received, selling 50 thousand copies; R&B was generally not popular in Indonesia at the time.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}}\n\nIn 2000, Fredly released his second solo album, ''Kembali'' (''Return''), with the single \"Kasih Putih\" (\"White Love\") receiving much airplay.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} In 2001, he placed third in the Russian Asia Dauzy International Song Festival.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}\n\nHe married singer [[Dewi Sandra]] in [[Uluwatu]], [[Bali]] on 3 April 2006. Glenn filed for divorce in 2009.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-25, Glenn files}}\n\nIn March 2009, Fredly was one of the main performers in a tribute concert to deceased Indonesian singer [[Chrisye]] during the [[Java Jazz Festival]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}} That same year, he performed tribute concerts to [[Michael Jackson]] in five cities throughout Indonesia, covering Jackson's hit songs.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}\n\nIn 2011, he joined with Tompi and [[Sandhy Sondoro]] to perform a set of concerts under the name Trio Lestari (The Eternal Trio).{{sfn|Fawilia 2011-06-26, An evening}}\n\nFredly celebrated his 17th anniversary in the music business with a sold-out concert in front of 7,500 people at [[Istora Gelora Bung Karno]] on 2 September 2012.\n\nIn 2014, he entered film producing with the film ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]'', which received the best movie award from the [[Indonesian Film Festival]].\n\n==Death==\nFredly died on 8 April 2020 at the age of 44 in Jakarta. It was reported that his cause of death was [[meningitis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Glenn Fredly Meninggal karena Sakit Meningitis|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparanhits/glenn-fredly-meninggal-karena-sakit-meningitis-1tBV6Z3yxZD|language=id|website=Kumparan.com|date=8 April 2020}}</ref> He is survived by his wife for 7.5 months (married on 19 August 2019), the 25-year-old Mutia Ayu, and their 40-day-old daughter, who was born on 28 February 2020.\n\n==Influences==\nFredly credited [[Michael Jackson]] as being one of his influences, saying that Jackson inspired him \"through his music, his style, his dancing, everything\". He also credited Jackson's humanitarian work for inspiring his own charitable work.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} He also admired [[Marvin Gaye]] and [[Quincy Jones]],{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} and was a fan of [[Chrisye]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}}\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:G.Fredly.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Fredly during performance in the Netherlands in 2011.]]\n===Music===\n*''GLENN'' (1998)\n*''Kembali'' (''Return'', 2000)\n*''Selamat Pagi, Dunia'' (''Good Morning, World'', 2003)\n*''Selamat Pagi, Dunia Repackaged'' (2004)\n*DVD & CD Selamat Pagi,Dunia Repackaged (2004)\n*''OST Cinta Silver'' (2005)\n*''Aku dan Wanita'' (''Women and I'', 2006)\n*''Terang'' (''Clear'',  2006)\n*''Happy Sunday (2007)\n*''Private Collection (2008)\n*''DVD Tribute to Chrisye (2009)\n*''Lovevolution'' (2010)\n*DVD Lovevolution Live in Esplanade  (2010)\n*''Luka, Cinta & Merdeka'' (2012)\n*''DVD Glenn Fredly & The Bakuucakar live at Lokananta'' (2012)\n\n===Movies===\n* ''[[Tanda Tanya]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]'' (2014)\n\n==References==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/06/26/an-evening-with-trio-lestari.html|last=Fawilia|first=Aliendheasja |title=An evening with Trio Lestari |date=26 June 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|Fawilia 2011-06-26, An evening}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/03/25/glenn-files-divorce.html|title=Glenn files for divorce|date=25 March 2009|work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-25, Glenn files}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://selebriti.indonesiaselebriti.com/selebriti/bio/283212744214/Glenn-Fredly|title=Glenn Fredly|date=|work=IndonesiaSelebriti.com|ref={{harvid|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}}|language=Indonesian|accessdate=29 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316153631/http://selebriti.indonesiaselebriti.com/selebriti/bio/283212744214/Glenn-Fredly|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/03/07/glenn-sing-chrisye-java-jazz.html|title=Glenn to sing for Chrisye in Java Jazz|date=7 March 2009 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/08/09/glenn-fredly-get-ready-welcome-new-glenn039.html|last=Kurniasari|first=Titik |title=Glenn Fredly: Get ready to welcome the `new Glenn' |date=9 August 2009 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.glennfredly.com/v4/ }}\n\n{{The Voice Indonesia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fredly, Glenn}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moluccan people]]\n[[Category:Indonesian Christians]]\n[[Category:Indonesian male singers]]\n[[Category:Anugerah Musik Indonesia winners]]\n[[Category:People from Ambon]]\n[[Category:Deaths from meningitis]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Indonesian singer-songwriter}}\n{{Use British English|date=May 2012}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=May 2012}}\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| image            = Glenn Fredly.jpg\n| name             = Glenn Fredly\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Glenn Fredly Deviano Latuihamallo\n| alias            = \n| birth_date       = {{birth date|df=yes|1975|09|30}}\n| birth_place      = [[Jakarta]], Indonesia\n| death_date       = {{Death date and age|2020|04|08|1975|09|30|df=yes}}\n| death_place      = Jakarta, Indonesia\n| origin           = [[Ambon Island|Ambon]]\n| occupation       = Singer-songwriter\n| genre            = {{flat list|\n*[[Jazz]]\n*[[Pop music|pop]]\n*[[Contemporary R&B|R&B]]\n}}\n| instrument       = Vocals, Guitar, Bass Guitar, Piano\n| years_active     = 1995\u20132020\n| label            = \n| associated_acts  = \n| website          = [https://www.glennfredly.com glennfredly.com]\n}}\n\n'''Glenn Fredly Deviano Latuihamallo''' (30 September 1975 \u2013 8 April 2020), known professionally as '''Glenn Fredly''', was an [[Indonesia]]n [[R&B]] singer and songwriter. Entering the music industry after winning a singing contest in 1995, he released more than 10 albums. He produced new talented artists like female vocalist [[Yura (Indonesian singer)|Yura]] and male soloist Gilbert Pohan. He also produced ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]''. In 2013, he served as a coach for ''[[The Voice Indonesia]]''.\n\n==Early life==\nFredly was born on 30 September 1975 to Hengky and Linda Latuihamallo. He was the first of five children.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} Fredly was of [[Moluccas|Molucca]]n descent.<ref>{{Cite web\n  | last = Yudo\n  | first = Aji\n  | title = Glenn Fredly Menjadi Produser Album Maluku Hip-Hop Community\n  | publisher = [[Rolling Stone (magazine)|RollingStone]] Indonesia\n  | date = 11 June 2011\n  | url = http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/05/11/125927/1637229/1093/glenn-fredly-menjadi-produser-album-maluku-hip-hop-community\n  | access-date = 7 September 2011\n  | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20110517214210/http://rollingstone.co.id/read/2011/05/11/125927/1637229/1093/glenn-fredly-menjadi-produser-album-maluku-hip-hop-community\n  | archive-date = 17 May 2011\n  | url-status = dead\n  }}</ref>\n\n==Career==\nIn 1995, he won the [[Cipta Pesona Bintang]] singing contest.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} That same year, he joined the rock band Funk Section.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} The following year, he was a finalist in the [[Asia Song Festival]].{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} In 1998, Fredly left Funk Section to be a solo R&B singer, feeling that it suited his vocal style better. He released his first album, ''GLENN'', that year. It was relatively well received, selling 50 thousand copies; R&B was generally not popular in Indonesia at the time.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}}\n\nIn 2000, Fredly released his second solo album, ''Kembali'' (''Return''), with the single \"Kasih Putih\" (\"White Love\") receiving much airplay.{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} In 2001, he placed third in the Russian Asia Dauzy International Song Festival.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}\n\nHe married singer [[Dewi Sandra]] in [[Uluwatu]], [[Bali]] on 3 April 2006. Glenn filed for divorce in 2009.{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-25, Glenn files}}\n\nIn March 2009, Fredly was one of the main performers in a tribute concert to deceased Indonesian singer [[Chrisye]] during the [[Java Jazz Festival]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}} That same year, he performed tribute concerts to [[Michael Jackson]] in five cities throughout Indonesia, covering Jackson's hit songs.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}}\n\nIn 2011, he joined with Tompi and [[Sandhy Sondoro]] to perform a set of concerts under the name Trio Lestari (The Eternal Trio).{{sfn|Fawilia 2011-06-26, An evening}}\n\nFredly celebrated his 17th anniversary in the music business with a sold-out concert in front of 7,500 people at [[Istora Gelora Bung Karno]] on 2 September 2012.\n\nIn 2014, he entered film producing with the film ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]'', which received the best movie award from the [[Indonesian Film Festival]].\n\n==Death==\nFredly died on 8 April 2020 at the age of 44 in Jakarta. It was reported that his cause of death was [[meningitis]].<ref>{{cite web|title=Glenn Fredly Meninggal karena Sakit Meningitis|url=https://kumparan.com/kumparanhits/glenn-fredly-meninggal-karena-sakit-meningitis-1tBV6Z3yxZD|language=id|website=Kumparan.com|date=8 April 2020}}</ref> He is survived by his wife for 7.5 months (married on 19 August 2019), the 25-year-old Mutia Ayu, and their 40-day-old daughter, who was born on 28 February 2020.\n\n==Influences==\nFredly credited [[Michael Jackson]] as being one of his influences, saying that Jackson inspired him \"through his music, his style, his dancing, everything\". He also credited Jackson's humanitarian work for inspiring his own charitable work.{{sfn|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} He also admired [[Marvin Gaye]] and [[Quincy Jones]],{{sfn|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}} and was a fan of [[Chrisye]].{{sfn|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}}\n\n==Discography==\n[[File:G.Fredly.jpg|150px|thumb|right|Fredly during performance in the Netherlands in 2011.]]\n===Music===\n*''GLENN'' (1998)\n*''Kembali'' (''Return'', 2000)\n*''Selamat Pagi, Dunia'' (''Good Morning, World'', 2003)\n*''Selamat Pagi, Dunia Repackaged'' (2004)\n*DVD & CD Selamat Pagi,Dunia Repackaged (2004)\n*''OST Cinta Silver'' (2005)\n*''Aku dan Wanita'' (''Women and I'', 2006)\n*''Terang'' (''Clear'',  2006)\n*''Happy Sunday (2007)\n*''Private Collection (2008)\n*''DVD Tribute to Chrisye (2009)\n*''Lovevolution'' (2010)\n*DVD Lovevolution Live in Esplanade  (2010)\n*''Luka, Cinta & Merdeka'' (2012)\n*''DVD Glenn Fredly & The Bakuucakar live at Lokananta'' (2012)\n\n===Movies===\n* ''[[Tanda Tanya]]'' (2011)\n* ''[[Cahaya Dari Timur: Beta Maluku]]'' (2014)\n\n==References==\n;Footnotes\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n;Bibliography\n{{refbegin}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2011/06/26/an-evening-with-trio-lestari.html|last=Fawilia|first=Aliendheasja |title=An evening with Trio Lestari |date=26 June 2011 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|Fawilia 2011-06-26, An evening}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/03/25/glenn-files-divorce.html|title=Glenn files for divorce|date=25 March 2009|work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-25, Glenn files}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web|url=http://selebriti.indonesiaselebriti.com/selebriti/bio/283212744214/Glenn-Fredly|title=Glenn Fredly|date=|work=IndonesiaSelebriti.com|ref={{harvid|IndonesiaSelebriti.com, Glenn Fredly}}|language=Indonesian|accessdate=29 August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120316153631/http://selebriti.indonesiaselebriti.com/selebriti/bio/283212744214/Glenn-Fredly|archive-date=16 March 2012|url-status=dead}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/03/07/glenn-sing-chrisye-java-jazz.html|title=Glenn to sing for Chrisye in Java Jazz|date=7 March 2009 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|The Jakarta Post 2009-03-07, Glenn to sing}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n*{{cite web |url=http://www.thejakartapost.com/news/2009/08/09/glenn-fredly-get-ready-welcome-new-glenn039.html|last=Kurniasari|first=Titik |title=Glenn Fredly: Get ready to welcome the `new Glenn' |date=9 August 2009 |work=The Jakarta Post |ref={{harvid|Kurniasari 2009-08-07, Get ready}} |accessdate=29 August 2011}}\n{{refend}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{official|http://www.glennfredly.com/v4/ }}\n\n{{The Voice Indonesia}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fredly, Glenn}}\n[[Category:1975 births]]\n[[Category:2020 deaths]]\n[[Category:Moluccan people]]\n[[Category:Indonesian Christians]]\n[[Category:Indonesian male singers]]\n[[Category:Anugerah Musik Indonesia winners]]\n[[Category:People from Ambon]]\n[[Category:Deaths from meningitis]]\n", "name_user": "Goudotmobi", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Glenn_Fredly"}
{"title_page": "Eggs Benedict", "text_new": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Eggs Benedict\n| image            = Eggs_Benedict-01-cropped.jpg\n| image_size       = 300px\n| caption          = Eggs Benedict with bacon, topped with a minute amount of sprouts. Sliced [[cherry tomato]]es can be seen on the side of the plate.\n| alternate_name   =\n| country          = [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n| region           =\n| creator          =\n| course           = [[Breakfast]], [[brunch]]\n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = [[Egg as food|Eggs]], [[English muffin]], [[Hollandaise sauce]]\n| variations       = Multiple\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n\n'''Eggs Benedict''' is an [[Cuisine of the United States|American]] [[breakfast]] or [[brunch]] dish, consisting of an open-faced sandwich of two halves of an [[English muffin]] topped with a [[poached egg]], and bloody BACON and [[hollandaise sauce]].  The dish was popularized in [[New York City]].\n\n== Origin and history ==\nThere are conflicting accounts as to the origin of Eggs Benedict.\n\n[[Delmonico's]] in [[lower Manhattan]] says on its menu that \"Eggs Benedict was first created in our ovens in 1860.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Delmonico's Menu|url=http://www.delmonicosrestaurant.com/menus.html|website=Delmonico's Restaurant|accessdate=2016-09-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927081231/http://www.delmonicosrestaurant.com/menus.html|archive-date=2016-09-27|url-status=dead}}</ref> One of its former chefs, [[Charles Ranhofer]], also published the recipe for ''Eggs \u00e0 la Benedick'' in 1894.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/epicureancomplet00ranhrich#page/309/mode/1up |title=The epicurean\u2014A complete treatise of analytical and practical studies on the culinary art, including table and wine service, how to prepare and cook dishes, etc., and a selection of interesting bills of fare of Delmonico's from 1862 to 1894 |publisher=The Internet Archive |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview recorded in the \"Talk of the Town\" column of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' in 1942, the year before his death,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.echonyc.com/~jkarpf/eggs/feedback.html#lemuel | title = Eggs Benedict New York: Feedback | accessdate = February 23, 2007 | last = Benedict | first = Cutts | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/19981201223133/http://www.echonyc.com/~jkarpf/eggs/feedback.html#lemuel | archivedate = December 1, 1998 }}</ref> Lemuel Benedict, a retired [[Wall Street]] stock broker, said that he had wandered into the [[Waldorf\u2013Astoria (New York, 1893)|Waldorf Hotel]] in 1894 and, hoping to find a cure for his morning hangover, ordered \"buttered toast, poached eggs, crisp bacon, and a hooker of hollandaise\". [[Oscar Tschirky]], the ''[[ma\u00eetre d'h\u00f4tel]]'', was so impressed with the dish that he put it on the breakfast and luncheon menus but substituted ham for the bacon and a toasted [[English muffin]] for the toast.<ref name = newyorker1942>{{Cite news | last = | first = | author-link = | date = December 19, 1942 | title = Talk of the Town | periodical = [[The New Yorker]] | pages = | postscript = <!--None--> }} '''Notes:''' ''This hasn't been verified at the source, but is instead taken from the letter to Karpf by Cutts Benedict and the page of J. J. Schnebel.''</ref>\n\n[[File:Flickr sekimura 2390523527--Smoked salmon eggs Benedict.jpg|thumb|right|Eggs Benedict with [[smoked salmon]], also known as Eggs Royale]]\n\nA later claim to the creation of Eggs Benedict was circuitously made by Edward P. Montgomery on behalf of [[Elias Cornelius Benedict|Commodore E. C. Benedict]]. In 1967 Montgomery wrote a letter to then ''[[The New York Times]]'' food columnist [[Craig Claiborne]] which included a recipe he said he had received through his uncle, a friend of the commodore. Commodore Benedict's recipe\u2014by way of Montgomery\u2014varies greatly from Ranhofer's version, particularly in the hollandaise sauce preparation\u2014calling for the addition of a \"hot, hard-cooked egg and ham mixture\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Claiborne |first=Craig |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/09/24/archives/american-classic-eggs-benedict.html |title=American Classic: Eggs Benedict|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 9, 1967 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Variations==\n[[File:Hollandaise sauce.jpg|thumb|right|Eggs Benedict with bacon, with paprika sprinkled on top]]\nSeveral variations of Eggs Benedict exist:\n* Eggs Blackstone adds [[Gammon of bacon|streaky bacon]] and a [[tomato]] slice.<ref>{{cite book | last = Rombauer | first = Irma S. | authorlink = Irma S. Rombauer |author2=Marion Rombauer Becker | others = Illustrated by Ginnie Hofmann and Ikki Matsumoto | title = [[The Joy of Cooking]] | origyear = 1975 | edition = 1st Scribner Edition 1995 | year = 1995 | publisher = [[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner]] | location = New York, New York | isbn = 0-02-604570-2 | page = 222 | chapter = Egg Dishes }} '''Notes:''' ''Title of recipe is poached eggs Blackstone. Uses fried slice of flour dipped tomato, minced bacon, poached eggs, and hollandaise. No bread for base.''</ref>\n* Eggs Blanchard adds [[B\u00e9chamel]] sauce for Hollandaise.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hirtzler|first1=Victor|title=The 1910 Hotel St. Francis cook book|date=1988|publisher=Windgate Press|location=Sausalito, Calif.|isbn=978-0915269068|edition=1st}}</ref>\n* Eggs Florentine adds [[spinach]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = | first = | title = Rich mix of patrons makes Moto's special | newspaper = [[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution]] | pages = A/6 | date = December 18, 1986 | url = | postscript = <!--None--> }} \"eggs Florentine ($3.95), eggs poached and topped with Hollandaise sauce, served on spinach and English muffin\" '''Notes:''' ''Not directly verified. Viewed through Google News Archive snippet view.''</ref> Older versions of eggs Florentine add spinach to poached or [[shirred eggs]].\n* Eggs Chesapeake adds a Maryland blue [[crab cake]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=The Editors of Saveur Magazine|title=SAVEUR: The New Classics Cookbook: 1,000 Recipes + Expert Advice, Tips, and|date=28 October 2014|publisher=Weldon Owen|isbn=978-1616287351|page=461|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=z4PtCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT1493&lpg=PT1493&dq=crab+%22Eggs+Chesapeake%22&source=bl&ots=WiFK_Xpnmu&sig=7ws0DCYGgxENfkXeMbEUtHJNe_w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjC9ezXkavVAhWJi5QKHYBECws4ChDoAQghMAA#v=onepage&q=crab%20%22Eggs%20Chesapeake%22&f=false|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Eggs Mornay substitutes [[Mornay sauce|Mornay (cheese) sauce]] for the Hollandaise.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Claiborne | first = Craig | author-link = Craig Claiborne | title = Maligned Vegetable Has Loyal Fans | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | page = 28 | date = May 26, 1960 | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20E1FF83E5916738DDDAF0A94DD405B808AF1D3 | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref>\n*Eggs Trivette adds [[Creole mustard]] to the Hollandaise and a topping of [[Crayfish as food|crayfish]].<ref>{{ cite web | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/10/08/eggs-benedict-recipe_n_1663098.html | title = 17 Twists On The Classic Eggs Benedict Recipe | last = Thomson | first = Julie R. }}</ref>\n* Eggs Omar (also known as a steak benedict) adds a small steak, and sometimes replaces the hollandaise with b\u00e9arnaise.\n* Eggs Atlantic, Eggs [[Ernest Hemingway|Hemingway]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Eggs Hemingway (or eggs Atlantic) with smoked salmon {{!}} Shelf5|url=http://www.shelf5.com/2013/01/19/eggs-hemingway-or-eggs-atlantic-with-smoked-salmon/|website=Shelf5|accessdate=September 28, 2016}}</ref> or Eggs Norv\u00e9gienne (also known as Eggs Royale and Eggs Montreal in New Zealand) adds [[Salmon (food)|salmon]], which may be [[smoked salmon|smoked]]. This is a common variation found in [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Canada]] and the [[United Kingdom]], and in [[Kosher]] restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eggs Hemingway|url=http://www.instructables.com/id/Eggs-Hemingway/|website=Instructables|accessdate=September 28, 2016}}</ref> This is also known as \"Eggs Benjamin\" in some restaurants in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eggs Benjamin breakfast - Picture of Symposium Cafe Restaurant & Lounge, Markham - TripAdvisor|url=https://www.tripadvisor.com/LocationPhotoDirectLink-g181720-d6167596-i175147995-Symposium_Cafe_Restaurant_Lounge-Markham_Ontario.html|website=www.tripadvisor.com|accessdate=September 28, 2016}}</ref>\n* Huevos Benedictos adds sliced avocado and/or Mexican [[chorizo]], and is topped with both a salsa (such as [[Salsa (sauce)#Types|''salsa roja'']] or [[Salsa (sauce)#Types|''salsa brava'']]) and hollandaise sauce.<ref>{{cite web|title=Huevos Benedictos|url=http://www.instructables.com/id/Huevos-Benedictos-Mexican-Eggs-Benedict/|website=Instructables}}</ref>\n* Eggs Hussarde substitutes [[rusk|Holland rusks]] for the English muffin and adds [[Bordelaise sauce]].<ref name = demers1998>{{cite book | last = DeMers | first = John | others = Food photography by John Hay | title = Food of New Orleans: Authentic Recipes from the Big Easy | edition = 1st | year = 1998 | publisher = [[Tuttle Publishing|Periplus Editions]] | location = Boston | isbn = 962-593-227-5 | page = 44 }}</ref><ref name = Brennans >{{cite web |url = http://www.brennansneworleans.com/r_eggshussarde.html | title = Recipes \u2013 Eggs Hussarde | accessdate = September 28, 2016 | publisher = [[Brennan's| Brennan's Restaurant]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060206235002/http://brennansneworleans.com/r_eggshussarde.html | archivedate = February 6, 2006 }} '''Notes:''' ''Located in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]].''</ref>\n* Irish Benedict adds [[corned beef]] or [[Irish bacon]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Townsend | first = Elisabeth | title = Dining Out | newspaper = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = July 24, 2005 | url = | postscript = <!--None--> }} \"Irish Benedict ($7.50): two poached Eggs and corned beef hash on an English muffin covered with hollandaise sauce\" '''Notes:''' ''Not directly verified. Viewed through Google News Archive snippet view.''</ref>\n* Eggs Cochon, a variation from [[New Orleans]] restaurants which adds pork \"debris\" (slow roasted pork shredded in its own juices) and replaces the English muffin with a large buttermilk biscuit.<ref>[http://eatyourworld.com/destinations/united_states/louisiana/new_orleans/what_to_eat/eggs_cochon_de_lait \"Eggs Cochon du Lait\"] ''Eat Your World''</ref><ref>[http://www.bestofneworleans.com/gambit/five-places-for-great-cochon-de-lait/Content?oid=1278937 \"Five places for great cochon du lait\"] ''Gambit''</ref>\n* California Eggs Benedict adds sliced [[Hass avocado]]. Variations include adding sliced tomato.\n* Avocado Toast Benedict substitutes toast for the muffin and adds sliced avocado.\n* New Jersey Benedict adds Taylor [[Pork Roll]].\n* Eggs Woodhouse includes two eggs and artichoke hearts, creamed spinach, bechamel sauce, Ib\u00e9rico ham, black truffle and beluga caviar. The recipe is featured in the book ''How To Archer'', inspired by the television series [[Archer_(2009_TV_series)|Archer]] on [[FXX]].\n* Eggs Zenedict, a specialty of restaurants in the largely-defunct Canadian retail chain [[Zellers]]. Poached eggs on a toasted [[scone]] with peameal back bacon ([[Canadian bacon]]), smothered in a sundried tomato Hollandaise sauce. <ref> http://zellersfamilydiner.foodpages.ca/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[List of breakfast foods]]\n* [[List of brunch foods]]\n* [[List of egg dishes]]\n* [[List of foods named after people]]\n* [[List of regional dishes of the United States]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Eggs Benedict and variations}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040303153709/http://members.cox.net/jjschnebel/eggsbene.html Who Cooked That Up?] page on origin of the dish with a recipe\n*\u201c[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/08/nyregion/thecity/08eggs.html?ex=1333684800&amp;en=475ce1da09cb6767&amp;ei=5090&amp;partner=rssuserland&amp;emc=rss Was He the Eggman?]\u201d An account in ''The New York Times'' about Lemuel Benedict and the efforts of Jack Benedict, the son of Lemuel's first cousin, to promote Lemuel's story.  Article includes link to an audio slide show.\n\n{{Eggs}}\n{{Lists of prepared foods}}\n\n[[Category:Egg dishes]]\n[[Category:American cuisine]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox prepared food\n| name             = Eggs Benedict\n| image            = Eggs_Benedict-01-cropped.jpg\n| image_size       = 300px\n| caption          = Eggs Benedict with bacon, topped with a minute amount of sprouts. Sliced [[cherry tomato]]es can be seen on the side of the plate.\n| alternate_name   =\n| country          = [[New York City]], [[United States]]\n| region           =\n| creator          =\n| course           = [[Breakfast]], [[brunch]]\n| served           =\n| main_ingredient  = [[Egg as food|Eggs]], [[English muffin]], [[Hollandaise sauce]]\n| variations       = Multiple\n| calories         =\n| other            =\n}}\n\n'''Eggs Benedict''' is an [[Cuisine of the United States|American]] [[breakfast]] or [[brunch]] dish, consisting of an open-faced sandwich of two halves of an [[English muffin]] topped with a [[poached egg]] and [[hollandaise sauce]].  The dish was popularized in [[New York City]].\n\n== Origin and history ==\nThere are conflicting accounts as to the origin of Eggs Benedict.\n\n[[Delmonico's]] in [[lower Manhattan]] says on its menu that \"Eggs Benedict was first created in our ovens in 1860.\"<ref>{{cite web|title=Delmonico's Menu|url=http://www.delmonicosrestaurant.com/menus.html|website=Delmonico's Restaurant|accessdate=2016-09-28|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160927081231/http://www.delmonicosrestaurant.com/menus.html|archive-date=2016-09-27|url-status=dead}}</ref> One of its former chefs, [[Charles Ranhofer]], also published the recipe for ''Eggs \u00e0 la Benedick'' in 1894.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://archive.org/stream/epicureancomplet00ranhrich#page/309/mode/1up |title=The epicurean\u2014A complete treatise of analytical and practical studies on the culinary art, including table and wine service, how to prepare and cook dishes, etc., and a selection of interesting bills of fare of Delmonico's from 1862 to 1894 |publisher=The Internet Archive |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>\n\nIn an interview recorded in the \"Talk of the Town\" column of ''[[The New Yorker]]'' in 1942, the year before his death,<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.echonyc.com/~jkarpf/eggs/feedback.html#lemuel | title = Eggs Benedict New York: Feedback | accessdate = February 23, 2007 | last = Benedict | first = Cutts | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/19981201223133/http://www.echonyc.com/~jkarpf/eggs/feedback.html#lemuel | archivedate = December 1, 1998 }}</ref> Lemuel Benedict, a retired [[Wall Street]] stock broker, said that he had wandered into the [[Waldorf\u2013Astoria (New York, 1893)|Waldorf Hotel]] in 1894 and, hoping to find a cure for his morning hangover, ordered \"buttered toast, poached eggs, crisp bacon, and a hooker of hollandaise\". [[Oscar Tschirky]], the ''[[ma\u00eetre d'h\u00f4tel]]'', was so impressed with the dish that he put it on the breakfast and luncheon menus but substituted ham for the bacon and a toasted [[English muffin]] for the toast.<ref name = newyorker1942>{{Cite news | last = | first = | author-link = | date = December 19, 1942 | title = Talk of the Town | periodical = [[The New Yorker]] | pages = | postscript = <!--None--> }} '''Notes:''' ''This hasn't been verified at the source, but is instead taken from the letter to Karpf by Cutts Benedict and the page of J. J. Schnebel.''</ref>\n\n[[File:Flickr sekimura 2390523527--Smoked salmon eggs Benedict.jpg|thumb|right|Eggs Benedict with [[smoked salmon]], also known as Eggs Royale]]\n\nA later claim to the creation of Eggs Benedict was circuitously made by Edward P. Montgomery on behalf of [[Elias Cornelius Benedict|Commodore E. C. Benedict]]. In 1967 Montgomery wrote a letter to then ''[[The New York Times]]'' food columnist [[Craig Claiborne]] which included a recipe he said he had received through his uncle, a friend of the commodore. Commodore Benedict's recipe\u2014by way of Montgomery\u2014varies greatly from Ranhofer's version, particularly in the hollandaise sauce preparation\u2014calling for the addition of a \"hot, hard-cooked egg and ham mixture\".<ref>{{cite news|last=Claiborne |first=Craig |url=https://www.nytimes.com/1967/09/24/archives/american-classic-eggs-benedict.html |title=American Classic: Eggs Benedict|newspaper=[[The New York Times]] |date=September 9, 1967 |accessdate=2014-04-17}}</ref>\n\n==Variations==\n[[File:Hollandaise sauce.jpg|thumb|right|Eggs Benedict with bacon, with paprika sprinkled on top]]\nSeveral variations of Eggs Benedict exist:\n* Eggs Blackstone adds [[Gammon of bacon|streaky bacon]] and a [[tomato]] slice.<ref>{{cite book | last = Rombauer | first = Irma S. | authorlink = Irma S. Rombauer |author2=Marion Rombauer Becker | others = Illustrated by Ginnie Hofmann and Ikki Matsumoto | title = [[The Joy of Cooking]] | origyear = 1975 | edition = 1st Scribner Edition 1995 | year = 1995 | publisher = [[Charles Scribner's Sons|Scribner]] | location = New York, New York | isbn = 0-02-604570-2 | page = 222 | chapter = Egg Dishes }} '''Notes:''' ''Title of recipe is poached eggs Blackstone. Uses fried slice of flour dipped tomato, minced bacon, poached eggs, and hollandaise. No bread for base.''</ref>\n* Eggs Blanchard adds [[B\u00e9chamel]] sauce for Hollandaise.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Hirtzler|first1=Victor|title=The 1910 Hotel St. Francis cook book|date=1988|publisher=Windgate Press|location=Sausalito, Calif.|isbn=978-0915269068|edition=1st}}</ref>\n* Eggs Florentine adds [[spinach]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = | first = | title = Rich mix of patrons makes Moto's special | newspaper = [[The Atlanta Journal-Constitution|The Atlanta Journal and The Atlanta Constitution]] | pages = A/6 | date = December 18, 1986 | url = | postscript = <!--None--> }} \"eggs Florentine ($3.95), eggs poached and topped with Hollandaise sauce, served on spinach and English muffin\" '''Notes:''' ''Not directly verified. Viewed through Google News Archive snippet view.''</ref> Older versions of eggs Florentine add spinach to poached or [[shirred eggs]].\n* Eggs Chesapeake adds a Maryland blue [[crab cake]].<ref>{{cite book|last1=The Editors of Saveur Magazine|title=SAVEUR: The New Classics Cookbook: 1,000 Recipes + Expert Advice, Tips, and|date=28 October 2014|publisher=Weldon Owen|isbn=978-1616287351|page=461|url=https://books.google.co.nz/books?id=z4PtCQAAQBAJ&pg=PT1493&lpg=PT1493&dq=crab+%22Eggs+Chesapeake%22&source=bl&ots=WiFK_Xpnmu&sig=7ws0DCYGgxENfkXeMbEUtHJNe_w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=0ahUKEwjC9ezXkavVAhWJi5QKHYBECws4ChDoAQghMAA#v=onepage&q=crab%20%22Eggs%20Chesapeake%22&f=false|accessdate=28 July 2017}}</ref>\n* Eggs Mornay substitutes [[Mornay sauce|Mornay (cheese) sauce]] for the Hollandaise.<ref>{{Cite news | last = Claiborne | first = Craig | author-link = Craig Claiborne | title = Maligned Vegetable Has Loyal Fans | newspaper = [[The New York Times]] | page = 28 | date = May 26, 1960 | url = http://select.nytimes.com/gst/abstract.html?res=F20E1FF83E5916738DDDAF0A94DD405B808AF1D3 | postscript = <!--None--> }}</ref>\n*Eggs Trivette adds [[Creole mustard]] to the Hollandaise and a topping of [[Crayfish as food|crayfish]].<ref>{{ cite web | url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/2014/10/08/eggs-benedict-recipe_n_1663098.html | title = 17 Twists On The Classic Eggs Benedict Recipe | last = Thomson | first = Julie R. }}</ref>\n* Eggs Omar (also known as a steak benedict) adds a small steak, and sometimes replaces the hollandaise with b\u00e9arnaise.\n* Eggs Atlantic, Eggs [[Ernest Hemingway|Hemingway]],<ref>{{cite web|title=Eggs Hemingway (or eggs Atlantic) with smoked salmon {{!}} Shelf5|url=http://www.shelf5.com/2013/01/19/eggs-hemingway-or-eggs-atlantic-with-smoked-salmon/|website=Shelf5|accessdate=September 28, 2016}}</ref> or Eggs Norv\u00e9gienne (also known as Eggs Royale and Eggs Montreal in New Zealand) adds [[Salmon (food)|salmon]], which may be [[smoked salmon|smoked]]. This is a common variation found in [[Australia]], [[New Zealand]], [[Canada]] and the [[United Kingdom]], and in [[Kosher]] restaurants.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eggs Hemingway|url=http://www.instructables.com/id/Eggs-Hemingway/|website=Instructables|accessdate=September 28, 2016}}</ref> This is also known as \"Eggs Benjamin\" in some restaurants in Canada.<ref>{{cite web|title=Eggs Benjamin breakfast - Picture of Symposium Cafe Restaurant & Lounge, Markham - TripAdvisor|url=https://www.tripadvisor.com/LocationPhotoDirectLink-g181720-d6167596-i175147995-Symposium_Cafe_Restaurant_Lounge-Markham_Ontario.html|website=www.tripadvisor.com|accessdate=September 28, 2016}}</ref>\n* Huevos Benedictos adds sliced avocado and/or Mexican [[chorizo]], and is topped with both a salsa (such as [[Salsa (sauce)#Types|''salsa roja'']] or [[Salsa (sauce)#Types|''salsa brava'']]) and hollandaise sauce.<ref>{{cite web|title=Huevos Benedictos|url=http://www.instructables.com/id/Huevos-Benedictos-Mexican-Eggs-Benedict/|website=Instructables}}</ref>\n* Eggs Hussarde substitutes [[rusk|Holland rusks]] for the English muffin and adds [[Bordelaise sauce]].<ref name = demers1998>{{cite book | last = DeMers | first = John | others = Food photography by John Hay | title = Food of New Orleans: Authentic Recipes from the Big Easy | edition = 1st | year = 1998 | publisher = [[Tuttle Publishing|Periplus Editions]] | location = Boston | isbn = 962-593-227-5 | page = 44 }}</ref><ref name = Brennans >{{cite web |url = http://www.brennansneworleans.com/r_eggshussarde.html | title = Recipes \u2013 Eggs Hussarde | accessdate = September 28, 2016 | publisher = [[Brennan's| Brennan's Restaurant]] | archiveurl = https://web.archive.org/web/20060206235002/http://brennansneworleans.com/r_eggshussarde.html | archivedate = February 6, 2006 }} '''Notes:''' ''Located in [[New Orleans]], [[Louisiana]].''</ref>\n* Irish Benedict adds [[corned beef]] or [[Irish bacon]].<ref>{{Cite news | last = Townsend | first = Elisabeth | title = Dining Out | newspaper = [[The Boston Globe]] | date = July 24, 2005 | url = | postscript = <!--None--> }} \"Irish Benedict ($7.50): two poached Eggs and corned beef hash on an English muffin covered with hollandaise sauce\" '''Notes:''' ''Not directly verified. Viewed through Google News Archive snippet view.''</ref>\n* Eggs Cochon, a variation from [[New Orleans]] restaurants which adds pork \"debris\" (slow roasted pork shredded in its own juices) and replaces the English muffin with a large buttermilk biscuit.<ref>[http://eatyourworld.com/destinations/united_states/louisiana/new_orleans/what_to_eat/eggs_cochon_de_lait \"Eggs Cochon du Lait\"] ''Eat Your World''</ref><ref>[http://www.bestofneworleans.com/gambit/five-places-for-great-cochon-de-lait/Content?oid=1278937 \"Five places for great cochon du lait\"] ''Gambit''</ref>\n* California Eggs Benedict adds sliced [[Hass avocado]]. Variations include adding sliced tomato.\n* Avocado Toast Benedict substitutes toast for the muffin and adds sliced avocado.\n* New Jersey Benedict adds Taylor [[Pork Roll]].\n* Eggs Woodhouse includes two eggs and artichoke hearts, creamed spinach, bechamel sauce, Ib\u00e9rico ham, black truffle and beluga caviar. The recipe is featured in the book ''How To Archer'', inspired by the television series [[Archer_(2009_TV_series)|Archer]] on [[FXX]].\n* Eggs Zenedict, a specialty of restaurants in the largely-defunct Canadian retail chain [[Zellers]]. Poached eggs on a toasted [[scone]] with peameal back bacon ([[Canadian bacon]]), smothered in a sundried tomato Hollandaise sauce. <ref> http://zellersfamilydiner.foodpages.ca/</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{portal|Food}}\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n* [[List of breakfast foods]]\n* [[List of brunch foods]]\n* [[List of egg dishes]]\n* [[List of foods named after people]]\n* [[List of regional dishes of the United States]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Eggs Benedict and variations}}\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://web.archive.org/web/20040303153709/http://members.cox.net/jjschnebel/eggsbene.html Who Cooked That Up?] page on origin of the dish with a recipe\n*\u201c[https://www.nytimes.com/2007/04/08/nyregion/thecity/08eggs.html?ex=1333684800&amp;en=475ce1da09cb6767&amp;ei=5090&amp;partner=rssuserland&amp;emc=rss Was He the Eggman?]\u201d An account in ''The New York Times'' about Lemuel Benedict and the efforts of Jack Benedict, the son of Lemuel's first cousin, to promote Lemuel's story.  Article includes link to an audio slide show.\n\n{{Eggs}}\n{{Lists of prepared foods}}\n\n[[Category:Egg dishes]]\n[[Category:American cuisine]]\n", "name_user": "2a02:c7f:c032:a900:a96c:3693:3d78:e46e", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eggs_Benedict"}
{"title_page": "Raffaele Illiano", "text_new": "{{short description|Italian cyclist}}\n{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Raffaele Illiano\n| image         =\n| fullname      = Raffaele Illiano\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1977|2|11}}\n| birth_place   = [[Naples]], [[Italy]]\n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     = 2002\u20132006\n| proteam1      = Colombia-Selle Italia\n| proyears2     = 2007\n| proteam2      = Ceramica Flaminia\n| proyears3     = 2008\u20132009\n| proteam3      = Serramenti Diquigiovanni\n| proyears4     = 2010\n| proteam4      = Aktio Group Mostostal Pu\u0142awy\n| majorwins     =\n}}\n'''Raffaele Illiano''' (born February 11, 1977 in [[Naples]]) is an [[Italy|Italian]] professional road racing cyclist.\n\n==Palmares==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n; 2003\n: 1st, [[Giro del Lago Maggiore]]\n: [[Tour du S\u00e9n\u00e9gal]], 2 stages\n;2004\n: 1st, [[GP Bradlo]]\n: 1st on 6 and 8 stages [[Tour'd S\u00e9n\u00e9gal]]\n: Win Prolog Tour'd Senegal\n: Classifica Intergiro del Giro d'Italia\n;2008\n: 1st, Stage 2, [[2008 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico|Tirreno\u2013Adriatico]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==After retirement==\nRaffaele Illiano was arrested on 30 August 2011 for his involvement in a doping scandal.<ref>[http://corrieredelmezzogiorno.corriere.it/napoli/notizie/cronaca/2011/30-agosto-2011/doping-atleti-quattro-arresti--1901391587421.shtml Doping to young athletes, arrested ex-cyclist]</ref>\n\n==References==\n*{{Cycling archives|1123}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Illiano, Raffaele}}\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Naples]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1970s-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox cyclist\n| name          = Raffaele Illiano\n| image         =\n| fullname      = Raffaele Illiano\n| nickname      =\n| birth_date    = {{birth date and age|1977|2|11}}\n| birth_place   = [[Naples]], [[Italy]]\n| height        =\n| weight        =\n| currentteam   =\n| discipline    = Road\n| role          = Rider\n| ridertype     =\n| amateuryears1 =\n| amateurteam1  =\n| proyears1     = 2002\u20132006\n| proteam1      = Colombia-Selle Italia\n| proyears2     = 2007\n| proteam2      = Ceramica Flaminia\n| proyears3     = 2008\u20132009\n| proteam3      = Serramenti Diquigiovanni\n| proyears4     = 2010\n| proteam4      = Aktio Group Mostostal Pu\u0142awy\n| majorwins     =\n}}\n'''Raffaele Illiano''' (born February 11, 1977 in [[Naples]]) is an [[Italy|Italian]] professional road racing cyclist.\n\n==Palmares==\n{{div col|colwidth=30em}}\n; 2003\n: 1st, [[Giro del Lago Maggiore]]\n: [[Tour du S\u00e9n\u00e9gal]], 2 stages\n;2004\n: 1st, [[GP Bradlo]]\n: 1st on 6 and 8 stages [[Tour'd S\u00e9n\u00e9gal]]\n: Win Prolog Tour'd Senegal\n: Classifica Intergiro del Giro d'Italia\n;2008\n: 1st, Stage 2, [[2008 Tirreno\u2013Adriatico|Tirreno\u2013Adriatico]]\n{{div col end}}\n\n==After retirement==\nRaffaele Illiano was arrested on 30 August 2011 for his involvement in a doping scandal.<ref>[http://corrieredelmezzogiorno.corriere.it/napoli/notizie/cronaca/2011/30-agosto-2011/doping-atleti-quattro-arresti--1901391587421.shtml Doping to young athletes, arrested ex-cyclist]</ref>\n\n==References==\n*{{Cycling archives|1123}}\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Illiano, Raffaele}}\n[[Category:Italian male cyclists]]\n[[Category:1977 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Naples]]\n[[Category:Giro d'Italia cyclists]]\n{{Italy-cycling-bio-1970s-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Lepricavark", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200etop:added short description", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Raffaele_Illiano"}
{"title_page": "Brooks Newmark", "text_new": "{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Brooks Newmark\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Brooks Newmark.jpg\n| caption =\n| office = [[Minister for Civil Society]]\n| term_start = 15 July 2014\n| term_end = 27 September 2014\n| predecessor = [[Nick Hurd]]\n| successor = [[Rob Wilson]]\n| primeminister = [[David Cameron]]\n| office1 = [[Lord of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister1 = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Frank Roy]]\n| successor1 = [[David Evennett]]\n| term_start1 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end1 = 4 September 2012\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Braintree (UK Parliament constituency)|Braintree]]\n| parliament2 =\n| term_start2 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end2 = 30 March 2015\n| predecessor2 = [[Alan Hurst (politician)|Alan Hurst]]\n| successor2 = [[James Cleverly]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1958|05|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Westport, Connecticut|Westport]], [[Connecticut]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Lucy Keegan\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations =\n| children = 5<ref name=\"BBC11/10/2014\"/>\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = [[Harvard University]]<br />[[Worcester College, Oxford]]<br />[[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Brooks Phillip Victor Newmark'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |date=13 May 2010 |page=8741}}</ref> (born 8 May 1958) is a homelessness campaigner and member of the Rough Sleeper's Advisory Committee that advises the Home Office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.essexlive.news/news/essex-news/several-chelmsford-roughsleepers-could-die-2108963|title=Several Chelmsford rough sleepers 'could die this winter', says homeless charity|work=Essex Live|accessdate=25 April 2019|date=October 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425082636/https://www.essexlive.news/news/essex-news/several-chelmsford-roughsleepers-could-die-2108963|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A former British politician, Newmark served as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Braintree (UK Parliament constituency)|Braintree]] until 2015. Prior to entering politics, he was involved in various businesses and was previously a Senior Partner at an International Private Equity firm.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sant.ox.ac.uk/events/europe-state-play|title=Europe: State of Play|work=University of Oxford|accessdate=25 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925090449/https://www.sant.ox.ac.uk/events/europe-state-play|archive-date=25 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Newmark is currently a visiting academic at the [[University of Oxford]] and became a guest lecturer in politics after finishing his parliamentary career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17418060.former-government-ministers-home-ransacked-by-thief-court-hears/|title=Former Government minister's home 'ransacked' by thief, court hears|work=Oxford Mail|accessdate=7 May 2019|date=8 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507095533/https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17418060.former-government-ministers-home-ransacked-by-thief-court-hears/|archive-date=7 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/cis/people.html|title=Centre for International Studies|work=University of Oxford|accessdate=7 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507095535/https://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/cis/people.html|archive-date=7 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> First elected in 2005, he served in various positions including as [[Minister for Civil Society]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/voluntary-sector-network/2014/jul/15/nick-hurd-resigns-what-do-charities-want-from-next-civil-society-minister|title=Nick Hurd resigns: what do charities want from next civil society minister?|last=Meade|first=Aimee|date=15 July 2014|website=Guardian|language=en|access-date=12 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612144514/https://www.theguardian.com/voluntary-sector-network/2014/jul/15/nick-hurd-resigns-what-do-charities-want-from-next-civil-society-minister|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> government [[Whip (politics)|whip]], and foreign affairs whip in [[Her Majesty's Most Loyal Opposition (United Kingdom)|opposition]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/8604145/Foreign-Office-defends-Conservative-MPs-Syria-visit.html|title=Foreign Office defends Conservative MP's Syria visit|last=McElroy|first=Damien|date=28 June 2011|access-date=12 June 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616220436/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/8604145/Foreign-Office-defends-Conservative-MPs-Syria-visit.html|archive-date=16 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 11 October 2014, following fresh allegations of sending sexually-explicit text messages, Newmark announced that he would stand down at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref name=\"BBC11/10/2014\">{{cite news|title=Tory Brooks Newmark to quit as MP|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29585203|accessdate=11 October 2014|work=BBC News|date=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011175010/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29585203|archive-date=11 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Newmark is a founder of the charity ''A Partner in Education'', which helps Rwandan teachers deliver a better education to Rwandan children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charitytimes.com/ct/Brooks_Newmark_new_minister_for_civil_society%20.php|title=Brooks Newmark is the new minister for civil society|date=15 July 2014|website=Charity Times|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Bedfordschoolmainbuilding.JPG|left|thumb|Bedford School]]\nNewmark was born in [[Westport, Connecticut]], in the United States, on 8 May 1958 to Howard Newmark and Gilda Gourlay (n\u00e9e Rames).{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} He is of Jewish heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/31914/brooks-newmark-mp-gets-business-role|title=Brooks Newmark MP gets business role|last=Rosen|first=Robyn|date=21 May 2010|website=The Jewish Chronicle|access-date=12 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926060907/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/31914/brooks-newmark-mp-gets-business-role|archive-date=26 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He moved to the UK aged nine and attended [[Caldicott School|Caldicott Preparatory School]] and [[Bedford School]] and graduated from [[Harvard College]], receiving a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in History in 1980 and was a member of the [[Delphic Club]]. He was a Research Graduate in Politics at [[Worcester College, Oxford]], from 1980 to 1982, and has an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] in Finance from [[Harvard Business School]] and an [[Master of Science|MSc]] in Education from Oxford University.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n==Business interests==\nNewmark was Vice President in the International Division of [[Shearson Lehman Brothers]] from 1984 to 1987, a Managing Director of Newmark Brothers Ltd., a corporate finance advisory company, from 1988 to 1993, and then a director of Stellican Ltd from 1993 to 1998. From 1998 to 2005, Newmark was a senior partner at [[Apollo Management]] (UK) [[Limited Partnership|LP]], an international private equity firm.\n\nHe was a director of Telesis Management Ltd and AAA MIP Limited.<ref name=WPRNPC>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Brooks-Newmark/366#Non-Parliamentary-Career|title=Non-Parliamentary Occupations|accessdate=29 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201175430/http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Brooks-Newmark/366#Non-Parliamentary-Career#Non-Parliamentary-Career|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He has been a director of Connaught Brown since 2015 and a director of the Catholic Herald since 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/wn06C3dN42fnArSEXenEVzFa054/appointments |title=Brooks Newmark |publisher=Companies House|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/00288446/officers |title=Catholic Herald |publisher=Companies House|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nNewmark contested [[Newcastle upon Tyne Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle Central]] in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]], and Braintree in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]. He was elected as the Member of Parliament for Braintree (in mid Essex) in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] over the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] incumbent, [[Alan Hurst (politician)|Alan Hurst]],{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} and was re-elected in [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]] with a greater majority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/bnp-and-mpac-fail-to-sway-electorate-1.15539|title=BNP and MPAC fail to sway electorate|last=Symons|first=Leon|date=13 May 2010|website=The Jewish Chronicle|access-date=12 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162110/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/bnp-and-mpac-fail-to-sway-electorate-1.15539|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe served as a Government Whip for Office of the Deputy Prime Minister, Department for International Development, Department for Business, and Innovation & Skills. In opposition, Newmark served as the Foreign Affairs Whip (2009\u201310) and Treasury Whip (2007\u201408). Newmark had previously served as a Member of the Treasury Select Committee (2006\u201407) and the Science & Technology Select Committee (2005\u201407). Newmark was re-elected onto the Treasury Select Committee in 2012 after 5 years in the Whips' Office.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} In mid July 2014, Newmark was appointed as the [[Minister for Civil Society]], in the [[Cabinet Office]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28303854 \"Reshuffle at-a-glance: In, out and moved about\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706134358/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28303854 |date=6 July 2018 }}, BBC News, 15 July 2014</ref><ref>Aimme Meade [https://www.theguardian.com/voluntary-sector-network/2014/jul/15/nick-hurd-resigns-what-do-charities-want-from-next-civil-society-minister \"\"Nick Hurd resigns: what do charities want from next civil society minister?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706090721/https://www.theguardian.com/voluntary-sector-network/2014/jul/15/nick-hurd-resigns-what-do-charities-want-from-next-civil-society-minister |date=6 July 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'' (Professional), 15 July 2014</ref> In response to a question, following his first public speech in that role, he said that charities should \"stick to their knitting\" and \"keep out of the realm of politics\". It was later argued that these quotations were taken out of context, and in fact suggested that politicians should support charities, but not interfere.<ref>[http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/governance/news/content/18092/brooks_newmark_charities_should_stick_to_their_knitting_and_keep_out_of_politics Brooks Newmark: charities should keep out of politics] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923204630/http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/governance/news/content/18092/brooks_newmark_charities_should_stick_to_their_knitting_and_keep_out_of_politics |date=23 September 2015 }} ''Civil Society Magazine'' 3 September 2014</ref>\n\nDuring his time as an MP, Newmark co-founded and co-chaired [[Women2Win]], an organisation established to encourage women into politics and public service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/fe51f084-d330-11e4-9b0a-00144feab7de|title=Women in Westminster: the gender gap|last=Rigby|first=Elizabeth|date=27 March 2015|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=12 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143536/https://www.ft.com/content/fe51f084-d330-11e4-9b0a-00144feab7de|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Newmark is credited for increasing the number of Conservative female MPs from 17 to 68 between 2005 and 2015. {{citation needed|date=January 2018}} He also co-founded the Million Jobs Campaign to address the need for more to be done regarding youth unemployment. In the 2015 budget, the Chancellor abolished National Insurance for anyone 18\u201425 and newly employed following a recommendation by Newmark.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nNewmark resigned as Minister for Civil Society on 27 September 2014, a day before the [[Conservative Party Conference]] in Birmingham. David Cameron accepted Newmark's resignation following allegations, published by the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'', that he had been [[sexting]] with a \u2018female party activist\u2019 who was in fact a male undercover reporter who was posing as a female to deliberately target Newmark, having failed with various other male MPs, over social media.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-mp-brooks-newmark-quits-ministerial-position-following-sunday-newspaper-sting-9759860.html |title=Tory MP Brooks Newmark quits ministerial position following Sunday newspaper sting |newspaper=The Independent |date=27 September 2014 |accessdate=28 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927184013/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-mp-brooks-newmark-quits-ministerial-position-following-sunday-newspaper-sting-9759860.html |archive-date=27 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/sep/27/brooks-newmark-mp-braintree-resigns-minister-civil-society |title=Cabinet Office minister Brooks Newmark resigns |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 September 2014 |accessdate=28 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927224952/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/sep/27/brooks-newmark-mp-braintree-resigns-minister-civil-society |archive-date=27 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/sexting-brooks-newmark-dick-pics-explicit-photos-myself-get-rid-attempts-online-end-in-failure-a7325031.html|title=Brooks Newmark, I once tried to get rid of explicit photos of myself too \u2013 it won't work|last=Street-Porter|first=Janet|date=23 September 2016|work=The Independent|access-date=12 June 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612201747/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/sexting-brooks-newmark-dick-pics-explicit-photos-myself-get-rid-attempts-online-end-in-failure-a7325031.html|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFellow Conservative MP [[Mark Pritchard (politician)|Mark Pritchard]] announced that he would make a formal complaint against the newspaper saying that \"questionable techniques\" had been involved in the paper's report. An [[Independent Press Standards Organisation|IPSO]] investigation later cleared the ''Sunday Mirror'' of any wrongdoing in an announcement that came three weeks after the regulator was formed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/mar/26/sunday-mirror-cleared-by-ipso-over-tory-minister-sex-sting |title=Sunday Mirror cleared by Ipso over Tory minister sex sting |newspaper=The Guardian |date=26 March 2015 |access-date=22 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031115/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/mar/26/sunday-mirror-cleared-by-ipso-over-tory-minister-sex-sting |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following a new \"text-and-tell story\" in October 2014 involving a young mother, Newmark announced he would not seek re-election to Parliament in the forthcoming [[2015 United Kingdom general election|general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29585203|title=Tory Brooks Newmark to quit as MP|date=12 October 2014|work=BBC News|access-date=12 June 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702042310/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29585203|archive-date=2 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Life after Parliament==\nNewmark is currently a Research Associate at the University of Oxford in the Department of Politics and International Relations. He is also guest lecturing at the Said Business School on private equity, and frequently travels to universities outside the UK to lecture in either politics or finance. He is the author of various articles on the [[Syrian Civil War|war in Syria]], [[Brexit]], [[Politics of the United States|US politics]] and [[homelessness]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nIn April 2016, Newmark was made President of the new Braintree District Community Foundation, an organisation led by local people supporting community projects.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nHe has authored a report on homelessness at the Centre for Social Justice. The report was for a think-tank and it highlighted the long-term nature of homelessness and also that homelessness has become normalised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cf591084-de4d-11e7-a8a4-0a1e63a52f9c|title=Chill wind blows through Britain's growing homeless camps|work=Financial Times|accessdate=17 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417101300/https://www.ft.com/content/cf591084-de4d-11e7-a8a4-0a1e63a52f9c|archive-date=17 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nNewmark's special interests include: Economic Policy, Foreign Affairs (Middle East, India, China and USA); Poverty Reduction & International Development (Micro Finance), Special Needs Education and Women & Equality (Founder and Co-Chairman of Women2Win). Many female candidates in the 2015 general election were subsequently successful in their bid to become MPs.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nPublications include: ''Direct Democracy: An Agenda for a New Model Party'' (2005); ''Simply Red; The True State of the Public Finances'' (CPS, 2006); ''The Price of Irresponsibility'' (CPS, 2008) and the ''Hidden Debt Bombshell'' (CPS, 2009).{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nNewmark is involved with charity work in Rwanda and also helps homeless charities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/by/cathy-newman/blogs/sexting-depression-ambition-brooks-newmark-words|title=Sexting, depression and ambition \u2013 Brooks Newmark MP in his own words|publisher=Channel 4|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723181605/https://www.channel4.com/news/by/cathy-newman/blogs/sexting-depression-ambition-brooks-newmark-words|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Newmark co-founded the charity ''A Partner in Education'', which helps Rwandan teachers to give the nation's children an improved education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charitytimes.com/ct/Brooks_Newmark_new_minister_for_civil_society%20.php|title=Brooks Newmark is the new minister for civil society|publisher=Charity Times|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>  It supports training for teachers and provides an inclusive environment for children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rencp.org/about/member-organizations-1/a-partner-in-education/|title=A Partner in Education|publisher=RENCP|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529093706/http://www.rencp.org/about/member-organizations-1/a-partner-in-education/|archive-date=29 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The charity has built a school in Rwanda that caters for over 300 children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cfid.org.uk/brooks-newmark/|title=BROOKS NEWMARK \"FROM UMUBANO PRIMARY SCHOOL TO UMUBANO ACADEMY: REFLECTIONS ON THE PAST 10 YEARS\"|publisher=Conservative Friends of International Develpoment|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has volunteered for the Braintree Salvation Army and the homeless charity Crisis in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.braintreeandwithamtimes.co.uk/news/11705472.brooks-newmark-aims-to-combat-nations-homelessness-after-standing-down-as-mp/|title=Brooks Newmark aims to combat nation's homelessness after standing down as MP|publisher=Braintree & Witham Times|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723181601/https://www.braintreeandwithamtimes.co.uk/news/11705472.brooks-newmark-aims-to-combat-nations-homelessness-after-standing-down-as-mp/|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> His report for the Centre for Social Justice think-tank on rough sleeping highlighted the growth of \u2018tent cities\u2019 and the normalisation of rough sleeping.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cf591084-de4d-11e7-a8a4-0a1e63a52f9c|title=Chill wind blows through Britain's growing homeless camps|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726123215/https://www.ft.com/content/cf591084-de4d-11e7-a8a4-0a1e63a52f9c|archive-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to Lucy Keegan, daughter of the military historian Sir [[John Keegan]], and has four sons - Benjamin,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TweetBrooks/status/14687545353|title=Off to airport to Boston as my eldest son Benjamin graduates from Harvard 2morrow.|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527212748/https://twitter.com/TweetBrooks/status/14687545353|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Sam, Max and Zachary - and one daughter, Lily.\n\nNewmark is involved in various charities including PARC, a respite centre based in Braintree for Children with severe disabilities, Farleigh Hospice and A Partner in Education, which he founded in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apartnerineducation.org/page/story-apie |title=The Story of APIE |access-date=5 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110203043448/http://www.apartnerineducation.org/page/story-apie |archive-date=3 February 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=mr-brooks-newmark/1488 |publicwhip=Brooks_Newmark |theywork=brooks_newmark}}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-5790,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Brooks Newmark MP]\n* [https://archive.is/20130421064929/http://parliament.telegraph.co.uk/mpsexpenses/mp-details/Brooks-Newmark/mp-11443 Brooks Newmark] (''The Telegraph'')\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140201175430/http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Brooks-Newmark/366#Personal Brooks Newmark MP] ( Westminster Parliamentary Research)\n* {{YouTube|user=BrooksNewmarkMP}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/brooks-newmark?INTCMP=SRCH Contributor page] at [[The Guardian]]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alan Hurst (politician)|Alan Hurst]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Braintree (UK Parliament constituency)|Braintree]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[James Cleverly]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newmark, Brooks}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Worcester College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford School]]\n[[Category:People from Westport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Political sex scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Civil Society]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use British English|date=January 2013}}\n{{Infobox officeholder\n| honorific-prefix =\n| name = Brooks Newmark\n| honorific-suffix = \n| image = Brooks Newmark.jpg\n| caption =\n| office = [[Minister for Civil Society]]\n| term_start = 15 July 2014\n| term_end = 27 September 2014\n| predecessor = [[Nick Hurd]]\n| successor = [[Rob Wilson]]\n| primeminister = [[David Cameron]]\n| office1 = [[Lord of the Treasury|Lord Commissioner of the Treasury]]\n| primeminister1 = [[David Cameron]]\n| predecessor1 = [[Frank Roy]]\n| successor1 = [[David Evennett]]\n| term_start1 = 6 May 2010\n| term_end1 = 4 September 2012\n| office2 = [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] <br /> for [[Braintree (UK Parliament constituency)|Braintree]]\n| parliament2 =\n| term_start2 = 5 May 2005\n| term_end2 = 30 March 2015\n| predecessor2 = [[Alan Hurst (politician)|Alan Hurst]]\n| successor2 = [[James Cleverly]]\n| birth_date = {{Birth date and age|1958|05|8|df=yes}}\n| birth_place = [[Westport, Connecticut|Westport]], [[Connecticut]], U.S.\n| death_date =\n| death_place =\n| nationality = British\n| spouse = Lucy Keegan\n| party = [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]]\n| relations =\n| children = 5<ref name=\"BBC11/10/2014\"/>\n| residence =\n| alma_mater = [[Harvard University]]<br />[[Worcester College, Oxford]]<br />[[Harvard Business School]]\n| occupation =\n| profession =\n| religion =\n| signature =\n| website =\n| footnotes =\n}}\n'''Brooks Phillip Victor Newmark'''<ref>{{London Gazette |issue=59418 |date=13 May 2010 |page=8741}}</ref> (born 8 May 1958) is a homelessness campaigner and member of the Rough Sleeper\u2019s Advisory Committee that advises the Home Office.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.essexlive.news/news/essex-news/several-chelmsford-roughsleepers-could-die-2108963|title=Several Chelmsford rough sleepers 'could die this winter', says homeless charity|work=Essex Live|accessdate=25 April 2019|date=October 20, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190425082636/https://www.essexlive.news/news/essex-news/several-chelmsford-roughsleepers-could-die-2108963|archive-date=25 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> A former British politician, Newmark served as the [[Conservative Party (UK)|Conservative]] [[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Braintree (UK Parliament constituency)|Braintree]] until 2015. Prior to entering politics, he was involved in various businesses and was previously a Senior Partner at an International Private Equity firm.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=https://www.sant.ox.ac.uk/events/europe-state-play|title=Europe: State of Play|work=University of Oxford|accessdate=25 September 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190925090449/https://www.sant.ox.ac.uk/events/europe-state-play|archive-date=25 September 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Newmark is currently a visiting academic at the [[University of Oxford]] and became a guest lecturer in politics after finishing his parliamentary career.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17418060.former-government-ministers-home-ransacked-by-thief-court-hears/|title=Former Government minister's home 'ransacked' by thief, court hears|work=Oxford Mail|accessdate=7 May 2019|date=8 February 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507095533/https://www.oxfordmail.co.uk/news/17418060.former-government-ministers-home-ransacked-by-thief-court-hears/|archive-date=7 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/cis/people.html|title=Centre for International Studies|work=University of Oxford|accessdate=7 May 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190507095535/https://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/cis/people.html|archive-date=7 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> First elected in 2005, he served in various positions including as [[Minister for Civil Society]],<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.theguardian.com/voluntary-sector-network/2014/jul/15/nick-hurd-resigns-what-do-charities-want-from-next-civil-society-minister|title=Nick Hurd resigns: what do charities want from next civil society minister?|last=Meade|first=Aimee|date=15 July 2014|website=Guardian|language=en|access-date=12 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612144514/https://www.theguardian.com/voluntary-sector-network/2014/jul/15/nick-hurd-resigns-what-do-charities-want-from-next-civil-society-minister|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> government [[Whip (politics)|whip]], and foreign affairs whip in [[Her Majesty's Most Loyal Opposition (United Kingdom)|opposition]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/8604145/Foreign-Office-defends-Conservative-MPs-Syria-visit.html|title=Foreign Office defends Conservative MP's Syria visit|last=McElroy|first=Damien|date=28 June 2011|access-date=12 June 2018|language=en-GB|issn=0307-1235|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180616220436/https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/worldnews/middleeast/syria/8604145/Foreign-Office-defends-Conservative-MPs-Syria-visit.html|archive-date=16 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> On 11 October 2014, following fresh allegations of sending sexually-explicit text messages, Newmark announced that he would stand down at the [[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015 general election]].<ref name=\"BBC11/10/2014\">{{cite news|title=Tory Brooks Newmark to quit as MP|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29585203|accessdate=11 October 2014|work=BBC News|date=11 October 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141011175010/http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29585203|archive-date=11 October 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Newmark is a founder of the charity ''A Partner in Education'', which helps Rwandan teachers deliver a better education to Rwandan children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charitytimes.com/ct/Brooks_Newmark_new_minister_for_civil_society%20.php|title=Brooks Newmark is the new minister for civil society|date=15 July 2014|website=Charity Times|access-date=20 June 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Early life==\n[[File:Bedfordschoolmainbuilding.JPG|left|thumb|Bedford School]]\nNewmark was born in [[Westport, Connecticut]], in the United States, on 8 May 1958 to Howard Newmark and Gilda Gourlay (n\u00e9e Rames).{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} He is of Jewish heritage.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/31914/brooks-newmark-mp-gets-business-role|title=Brooks Newmark MP gets business role|last=Rosen|first=Robyn|date=21 May 2010|website=The Jewish Chronicle|access-date=12 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170926060907/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/31914/brooks-newmark-mp-gets-business-role|archive-date=26 September 2017|url-status=live}}</ref> He moved to the UK aged nine and attended [[Caldicott School|Caldicott Preparatory School]] and [[Bedford School]] and graduated from [[Harvard College]], receiving a [[Bachelor of Arts|BA]] in History in 1980 and was a member of the [[Delphic Club]]. He was a Research Graduate in Politics at [[Worcester College, Oxford]], from 1980 to 1982, and has an [[Master of Business Administration|MBA]] in Finance from [[Harvard Business School]] and an [[Master of Science|MSc]] in Education from Oxford University.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\n==Business interests==\nNewmark was Vice President in the International Division of [[Shearson Lehman Brothers]] from 1984 to 1987, a Managing Director of Newmark Brothers Ltd., a corporate finance advisory company, from 1988 to 1993, and then a director of Stellican Ltd from 1993 to 1998. From 1998 to 2005, Newmark was a senior partner at [[Apollo Management]] (UK) [[Limited Partnership|LP]], an international private equity firm.\n\nHe was a director of Telesis Management Ltd and AAA MIP Limited.<ref name=WPRNPC>{{cite web|url=http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Brooks-Newmark/366#Non-Parliamentary-Career|title=Non-Parliamentary Occupations|accessdate=29 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140201175430/http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Brooks-Newmark/366#Non-Parliamentary-Career#Non-Parliamentary-Career|archive-date=1 February 2014|url-status=dead}}</ref> He has been a director of Connaught Brown since 2015 and a director of the Catholic Herald since 2016.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/officers/wn06C3dN42fnArSEXenEVzFa054/appointments |title=Brooks Newmark |publisher=Companies House|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://beta.companieshouse.gov.uk/company/00288446/officers |title=Catholic Herald |publisher=Companies House|accessdate=10 September 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Parliamentary career==\nNewmark contested [[Newcastle upon Tyne Central (UK Parliament constituency)|Newcastle Central]] in [[1997 United Kingdom general election|1997]], and Braintree in [[2001 United Kingdom general election|2001]]. He was elected as the Member of Parliament for Braintree (in mid Essex) in the [[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005 general election]] over the [[Labour Party (UK)|Labour]] incumbent, [[Alan Hurst (politician)|Alan Hurst]],{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} and was re-elected in [[2010 United Kingdom general election|2010]] with a greater majority.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/bnp-and-mpac-fail-to-sway-electorate-1.15539|title=BNP and MPAC fail to sway electorate|last=Symons|first=Leon|date=13 May 2010|website=The Jewish Chronicle|access-date=12 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612162110/https://www.thejc.com/news/uk-news/bnp-and-mpac-fail-to-sway-electorate-1.15539|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nHe served as a Government Whip for Office of the Deputy Prime Minister, Department for International Development, Department for Business, and Innovation & Skills. In opposition, Newmark served as the Foreign Affairs Whip (2009\u201310) and Treasury Whip (2007\u201408). Newmark had previously served as a Member of the Treasury Select Committee (2006\u201407) and the Science & Technology Select Committee (2005\u201407). Newmark was re-elected onto the Treasury Select Committee in 2012 after 5 years in the Whips' Office.{{Citation needed|date=June 2018}} In mid July 2014, Newmark was appointed as the [[Minister for Civil Society]], in the [[Cabinet Office]].<ref>[https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28303854 \"Reshuffle at-a-glance: In, out and moved about\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180706134358/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-28303854 |date=6 July 2018 }}, BBC News, 15 July 2014</ref><ref>Aimme Meade [https://www.theguardian.com/voluntary-sector-network/2014/jul/15/nick-hurd-resigns-what-do-charities-want-from-next-civil-society-minister \"\"Nick Hurd resigns: what do charities want from next civil society minister?\"] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170706090721/https://www.theguardian.com/voluntary-sector-network/2014/jul/15/nick-hurd-resigns-what-do-charities-want-from-next-civil-society-minister |date=6 July 2017 }}, ''The Guardian'' (Professional), 15 July 2014</ref> In response to a question, following his first public speech in that role, he said that charities should \"stick to their knitting\" and \"keep out of the realm of politics\". It was later argued that these quotations were taken out of context, and in fact suggested that politicians should support charities, but not interfere.<ref>[http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/governance/news/content/18092/brooks_newmark_charities_should_stick_to_their_knitting_and_keep_out_of_politics Brooks Newmark: charities should keep out of politics] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150923204630/http://www.civilsociety.co.uk/governance/news/content/18092/brooks_newmark_charities_should_stick_to_their_knitting_and_keep_out_of_politics |date=23 September 2015 }} ''Civil Society Magazine'' 3 September 2014</ref>\n\nDuring his time as an MP, Newmark co-founded and co-chaired [[Women2Win]], an organisation established to encourage women into politics and public service.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/fe51f084-d330-11e4-9b0a-00144feab7de|title=Women in Westminster: the gender gap|last=Rigby|first=Elizabeth|date=27 March 2015|website=Financial Times|language=en-GB|access-date=12 June 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612143536/https://www.ft.com/content/fe51f084-d330-11e4-9b0a-00144feab7de|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Newmark is credited for increasing the number of Conservative female MPs from 17 to 68 between 2005 and 2015. {{citation needed|date=January 2018}} He also co-founded the Million Jobs Campaign to address the need for more to be done regarding youth unemployment. In the 2015 budget, the Chancellor abolished National Insurance for anyone 18\u201425 and newly employed following a recommendation by Newmark.{{citation needed|date=January 2018}}\n\nNewmark resigned as Minister for Civil Society on 27 September 2014, a day before the [[Conservative Party Conference]] in Birmingham. David Cameron accepted Newmark\u2019s resignation following allegations, published by the ''[[Sunday Mirror]]'', that he had been [[sexting]] with a \u2018female party activist\u2019 who was in fact a male undercover reporter who was posing as a female to deliberately target Newmark, having failed with various other male MPs, over social media.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-mp-brooks-newmark-quits-ministerial-position-following-sunday-newspaper-sting-9759860.html |title=Tory MP Brooks Newmark quits ministerial position following Sunday newspaper sting |newspaper=The Independent |date=27 September 2014 |accessdate=28 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927184013/http://www.independent.co.uk/news/uk/politics/tory-mp-brooks-newmark-quits-ministerial-position-following-sunday-newspaper-sting-9759860.html |archive-date=27 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/sep/27/brooks-newmark-mp-braintree-resigns-minister-civil-society |title=Cabinet Office minister Brooks Newmark resigns |newspaper=The Guardian |date=27 September 2014 |accessdate=28 September 2014 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140927224952/http://www.theguardian.com/politics/2014/sep/27/brooks-newmark-mp-braintree-resigns-minister-civil-society |archive-date=27 September 2014 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/sexting-brooks-newmark-dick-pics-explicit-photos-myself-get-rid-attempts-online-end-in-failure-a7325031.html|title=Brooks Newmark, I once tried to get rid of explicit photos of myself too \u2013 it won't work|last=Street-Porter|first=Janet|date=23 September 2016|work=The Independent|access-date=12 June 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180612201747/https://www.independent.co.uk/voices/sexting-brooks-newmark-dick-pics-explicit-photos-myself-get-rid-attempts-online-end-in-failure-a7325031.html|archive-date=12 June 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nFellow Conservative MP [[Mark Pritchard (politician)|Mark Pritchard]] announced that he would make a formal complaint against the newspaper saying that \"questionable techniques\" had been involved in the paper's report. An [[Independent Press Standards Organisation|IPSO]] investigation later cleared the ''Sunday Mirror'' of any wrongdoing in an announcement that came three weeks after the regulator was formed.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/mar/26/sunday-mirror-cleared-by-ipso-over-tory-minister-sex-sting |title=Sunday Mirror cleared by Ipso over Tory minister sex sting |newspaper=The Guardian |date=26 March 2015 |access-date=22 November 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171201031115/https://www.theguardian.com/media/2015/mar/26/sunday-mirror-cleared-by-ipso-over-tory-minister-sex-sting |archive-date=1 December 2017 |url-status=live }}</ref> Following a new \"text-and-tell story\" in October 2014 involving a young mother, Newmark announced he would not seek re-election to Parliament in the forthcoming [[2015 United Kingdom general election|general election]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29585203|title=Tory Brooks Newmark to quit as MP|date=12 October 2014|work=BBC News|access-date=12 June 2018|language=en-GB|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180702042310/https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/uk-politics-29585203|archive-date=2 July 2018|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Life after Parliament==\nNewmark is currently a Research Associate at the University of Oxford in the Department of Politics and International Relations. He is also guest lecturing at the Said Business School on private equity, and frequently travels to universities outside the UK to lecture in either politics or finance. He is the author of various articles on the [[Syrian Civil War|war in Syria]], [[Brexit]], [[Politics of the United States|US politics]] and [[homelessness]].{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nIn April 2016, Newmark was made President of the new Braintree District Community Foundation, an organisation led by local people supporting community projects.{{citation needed|date=September 2017}}\n\nHe has authored a report on homelessness at the Centre for Social Justice. The report was for a think-tank and it highlighted the long-term nature of homelessness and also that homelessness has become normalised.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cf591084-de4d-11e7-a8a4-0a1e63a52f9c|title=Chill wind blows through Britain's growing homeless camps|work=Financial Times|accessdate=17 April 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190417101300/https://www.ft.com/content/cf591084-de4d-11e7-a8a4-0a1e63a52f9c|archive-date=17 April 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Political views==\nNewmark's special interests include: Economic Policy, Foreign Affairs (Middle East, India, China and USA); Poverty Reduction & International Development (Micro Finance), Special Needs Education and Women & Equality (Founder and Co-Chairman of Women2Win). Many female candidates in the 2015 general election were subsequently successful in their bid to become MPs.{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\nPublications include: ''Direct Democracy: An Agenda for a New Model Party'' (2005); ''Simply Red; The True State of the Public Finances'' (CPS, 2006); ''The Price of Irresponsibility'' (CPS, 2008) and the ''Hidden Debt Bombshell'' (CPS, 2009).{{citation needed|date=August 2017}}\n\n==Philanthropy==\nNewmark is involved with charity work in Rwanda and also helps homeless charities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.channel4.com/news/by/cathy-newman/blogs/sexting-depression-ambition-brooks-newmark-words|title=Sexting, depression and ambition \u2013 Brooks Newmark MP in his own words|publisher=Channel 4|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723181605/https://www.channel4.com/news/by/cathy-newman/blogs/sexting-depression-ambition-brooks-newmark-words|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nIn 2009 Newmark co-founded the charity ''A Partner in Education'', which helps Rwandan teachers to give the nation\u2019s children an improved education.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.charitytimes.com/ct/Brooks_Newmark_new_minister_for_civil_society%20.php|title=Brooks Newmark is the new minister for civil society|publisher=Charity Times|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>  It supports training for teachers and provides an inclusive environment for children.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.rencp.org/about/member-organizations-1/a-partner-in-education/|title=A Partner in Education|publisher=RENCP|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190529093706/http://www.rencp.org/about/member-organizations-1/a-partner-in-education/|archive-date=29 May 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> The charity has built a school in Rwanda that caters for over 300 children.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cfid.org.uk/brooks-newmark/|title=BROOKS NEWMARK \"FROM UMUBANO PRIMARY SCHOOL TO UMUBANO ACADEMY: REFLECTIONS ON THE PAST 10 YEARS\"|publisher=Conservative Friends of International Develpoment|accessdate=23 July 2019}}</ref>\n\nHe has volunteered for the Braintree Salvation Army and the homeless charity Crisis in London.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.braintreeandwithamtimes.co.uk/news/11705472.brooks-newmark-aims-to-combat-nations-homelessness-after-standing-down-as-mp/|title=Brooks Newmark aims to combat nation's homelessness after standing down as MP|publisher=Braintree & Witham Times|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190723181601/https://www.braintreeandwithamtimes.co.uk/news/11705472.brooks-newmark-aims-to-combat-nations-homelessness-after-standing-down-as-mp/|archive-date=23 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> His report for the Centre for Social Justice think-tank on rough sleeping highlighted the growth of \u2018tent cities\u2019 and the normalisation of rough sleeping.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ft.com/content/cf591084-de4d-11e7-a8a4-0a1e63a52f9c|title=Chill wind blows through Britain's growing homeless camps|publisher=Financial Times|accessdate=23 July 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190726123215/https://www.ft.com/content/cf591084-de4d-11e7-a8a4-0a1e63a52f9c|archive-date=26 July 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nHe is married to Lucy Keegan, daughter of the military historian Sir [[John Keegan]], and has four sons - Benjamin,<ref>{{cite web|url=https://twitter.com/TweetBrooks/status/14687545353|title=Off to airport to Boston as my eldest son Benjamin graduates from Harvard 2morrow.|publisher=|accessdate=29 September 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140527212748/https://twitter.com/TweetBrooks/status/14687545353|archive-date=27 May 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> Sam, Max and Zachary - and one daughter, Lily.\n\nNewmark is involved in various charities including PARC, a respite centre based in Braintree for Children with severe disabilities, Farleigh Hospice and A Partner in Education, which he founded in 2010.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.apartnerineducation.org/page/story-apie |title=The Story of APIE |access-date=5 October 2012 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110203043448/http://www.apartnerineducation.org/page/story-apie |archive-date=3 February 2011 |url-status=dead  }}</ref>\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist|colwidth=30em}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{UK MP links |parliament=mr-brooks-newmark/1488 |publicwhip=Brooks_Newmark |theywork=brooks_newmark}}\n* [http://politics.guardian.co.uk/person/0,9290,-5790,00.html Guardian Unlimited Politics - Ask Aristotle: Brooks Newmark MP]\n* [https://archive.is/20130421064929/http://parliament.telegraph.co.uk/mpsexpenses/mp-details/Brooks-Newmark/mp-11443 Brooks Newmark] (''The Telegraph'')\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20140201175430/http://www.parliamentaryrecord.com/content/profiles/mp/Brooks-Newmark/366#Personal Brooks Newmark MP] ( Westminster Parliamentary Research)\n* {{YouTube|user=BrooksNewmarkMP}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/profile/brooks-newmark?INTCMP=SRCH Contributor page] at [[The Guardian]]\n\n{{S-start}}\n{{s-par|uk}}\n{{s-bef|before=[[Alan Hurst (politician)|Alan Hurst]]}}\n{{s-ttl|title=[[Member of Parliament (United Kingdom)|Member of Parliament]] for [[Braintree (UK Parliament constituency)|Braintree]]|years=[[2005 United Kingdom general election|2005]]\u2013[[2015 United Kingdom general election|2015]]}}\n{{s-aft|after=[[James Cleverly]]}}\n{{S-end}}\n\n{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2019}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Newmark, Brooks}}\n[[Category:1958 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Worcester College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American emigrants to England]]\n[[Category:American Jews]]\n[[Category:Conservative Party (UK) MPs for English constituencies]]\n[[Category:English Jews]]\n[[Category:Harvard Business School alumni]]\n[[Category:Jewish British politicians]]\n[[Category:People educated at Bedford School]]\n[[Category:People from Westport, Connecticut]]\n[[Category:Political sex scandals in the United Kingdom]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2005\u20132010]]\n[[Category:UK MPs 2010\u20132015]]\n[[Category:Ministers for Civil Society]]\n[[Category:Harvard College alumni]]\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: \u2019s \u2192 's (3)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Brooks_Newmark"}
{"title_page": "Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences", "text_new": "{{short description|Division of New York University}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences (CIMS)\n| image = <!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:NyuTorch.png|75px|New York University]] -->\n| established = 1935\n| director = [[Russel Caflisch]]\n| type = [[Private university|Private]] research institute\n| city = [[New York City]]\n| state = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| country = [[United States|USA]]\n| campus = Urban\n| undergrad = 1,500\n| postgrad = 600\n| faculty = 82\n| academic_affiliation = [[New York University]]\n| website = {{url|cims.nyu.edu}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences (48072654781).jpg|thumb|View of Warren Weaver Hall, Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences from Gould Plaza]]\n\nThe '''Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences''' ('''CIMS''') is a research school of [[New York University]] (NYU) under the [[New York University College of Arts & Science|College of Arts & Science]]. It is among the most prestigious mathematics schools and mathematical sciences research centers in the world, and serves as a center for research and advanced training in computer science and mathematics.<ref name=\"shanghairanking.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/Shanghairanking-Subject-Rankings/mathematics.html|title=ShanghaiRanking's Global Ranking of Academic Subjects 2017 - Mathematics - Shanghai Ranking - 2017|author=|date=|website=www.shanghairanking.com}}</ref> It is named after [[Richard Courant]], one of the founders of the Courant Institute and also a mathematics professor at New York University from 1936 to 1972.\n\nIt is ranked #1 in [[applied mathematical research]] in US,<ref name=\"grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com\">{{cite magazine|url = http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/search?program=top-mathematics-programs&specialty=applied-mathematics-rankings&name=&zip=&program_rank=Any&sort=&sortdir=|title = Search: Sciences Programs {{!}} US News|magazine = US News|accessdate = 2015-05-06}}</ref> #5 in citation impact worldwide, and #12 in citation worldwide. On the [[Faculty Scholarly Productivity Index]], it is ranked #3 with an index of 1.84.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.com/stats/productivity/page.php?byinst=true&institution=2478&year=2007 |title=Faculty Scholarly Productivity Index |publisher=The Chronicle |date=2007-11-16 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> It is also known for its extensive research in pure mathematical areas, such as [[partial differential equations]], [[probability]] and [[geometry]], as well as applied mathematical areas, such as [[computational biology]], [[computational neuroscience]], and [[mathematical finance]]. The Mathematics Department of the Institute has 18 members of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences]] (more than any other mathematics department in the U.S.) and five members of the [[National Academy of Engineering]]. Four faculty members have been awarded the National Medal of Science, one was honored with the Kyoto Prize, and nine have received career awards from the National Science Foundation. Courant Institute professors [[Peter Lax]], [[S. R. Srinivasa Varadhan]], [[Mikhail Gromov (mathematician)|Mikhail Gromov]], [[Louis Nirenberg]]  won the 2005, 2007, 2009 and 2015 [[Abel Prize]] respectively for their research in partial differential equations, probability and geometry.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/01/nyregion/01nyu.html | work=The New York Times | first=Lisa W. | last=Foderaro | title=Complex Math, Simple Sum: 3 Awards in 5 Years | date=2009-06-01}}</ref> [[Louis Nirenberg]] also received the [[Chern Medal]] in 2010, and [[Subhash Khot]] won the [[Nevanlinna Prize]] in 2014.\n\nThe Director of the Courant Institute directly reports to New York University's Provost and President and works closely with deans and directors of other NYU colleges and divisions respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/about/courant.html|title=NYU > Courant Institute > About > Courant and NYU|date=|publisher=Cims.nyu.edu|accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> The undergraduate programs and graduate programs at the Courant Institute are run independently by the Institute, and formally associated with the [[NYU College of Arts and Science]] and [[NYU Graduate School of Arts and Science]] respectively.\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Rankings===\nThe Courant Institute specializes in [[applied mathematics]], [[mathematical analysis]] and [[scientific computation]]. There is emphasis on [[partial differential equations]] and their applications.  The mathematics department is consistently ranked in the United States as #1 in applied mathematics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/applied-mathematics-rankings |title=Best Applied Mathematics Programs &#124; Top Math Schools &#124; US News Best Graduate Schools |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> Other strong points are  analysis (currently #6)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/mathematical-analysis-rankings |title=Best Mathematical Analysis Programs &#124; Top Math Schools &#124; US News Best Graduate Schools |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> and  geometry (currently #10).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/geometry-rankings |title=Best Geometry Programs &#124; Top Math Schools &#124; US News Best Graduate Schools |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref>  Within the field of [[computer science]], CIMS concentrates in [[machine learning]], [[computation|theory]], [[programming languages]], [[computer graphics]] and [[parallel computing]]. The computer science program is ranked 28th among computer science programs in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/computer-science-rankings/page+2 |title=Best Computer Science Programs &#124; Top Computer Science Schools &#124; US News Best Graduate Schools |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> In 2019, the [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]] placed the Courant Institute as #3 worldwide in the subject ranking for mathematics.<ref name=\"shanghairanking.com\"/>\n\n===Admissions===\nThe Courant Institute offers [[Bachelor of Arts]], [[Bachelor of Science]], [[Master of Science]] and [[Ph.D.]] degree programs in both [[mathematics]] and [[computer science]] with program acceptance rates ranging from 3% to 29%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegradcafe.com/survey/index.php?q=NYU+computer+science&t=a&pp=50&o=p |title=NYU computer science \u2022 |publisher=Thegradcafe.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> The overall acceptance rate for all CIMS graduate programs is 15%, and program admissions reviews are holistic. A high undergraduate GPA and high GRE score are typically prerequisites to admission to its graduate programs but are not required. Majority of accepted candidates met these standards. However, character and personal qualities and evidence of strong quantitative skills are very important admission factors. Consistent with its scientific breadth, the Institute welcomes applicants whose primary background is in quantitative fields such as economics, engineering, physics, or biology, as well as mathematics. Undergraduate program admissions are not directly administrated by the Institute but by the NYU undergraduate admissions office of College of Arts and Science.<ref name=\"math.nyu.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/financial_mathematics/content/05_prospectiveStudents/04.html |title=Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences NYU |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/degree/phd/application.html |title=Graduate Mathematics Courses |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/webapps/content/academic/graduate/admissions/admission |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Graduate Admissions Information |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.petersons.com/graduate-schools/new-york-university-courant-institute-of-mathematical-sciences-department-of-mathematics-admissions-000_10014124_10088.aspx |title=Department of Mathematics Admissions - New York University (Department of Mathematics) |publisher=Petersons.com |accessdate=2011-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629083544/http://www.petersons.com/graduate-schools/new-york-university-courant-institute-of-mathematical-sciences-department-of-mathematics-admissions-000_10014124_10088.aspx |archive-date=2011-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Graduate program===\nThe Department of Mathematics at the Courant Institute offers PhDs in Mathematics, Atmosphere-Ocean Science, and Computational Biology; Masters of Science in Mathematical Finance, Mathematics, and Scientific Computing.\n\n[[File:CIMS Lecture Hall.jpg|thumb|Lecture Hall at Warren Weaver Hall]]\nThe Graduate Department of Computer Science offers a PhD in computer science. In addition it offers Master of Science degrees in computer science, information systems (in conjunction with the [[Stern School of Business]]), and in scientific computing. For the PhD program, every PhD computer science student must receive a grade of A or A- on the final examination for algorithms, systems, applications, and a PhD-level course chosen by the student that does not satisfy the first three requirements, such as cryptography and numerical methods. Students may take the final exam for any these courses without being enrolled in the course.\n\nThe Computer Science Masters program offers instruction in the fundamental principles, design and applications of computer systems and computer technologies. Students who obtain an MS degree in computer science are qualified to do significant development work in the computer industry or important application areas. Those who receive a doctoral degree are in a position to hold faculty appointments and do research and development work at the forefront of this rapidly changing and expanding field. The emphasis for the MS in Information Systems program is on the use of computer systems in business. For the Master of Science in Scientific Computing, it is designed to provide broad training in areas related to scientific computing using modern computing technology and mathematical modeling arising in various applications. The core of the curriculum for all computer science graduate students consists of courses in algorithms, programming languages, compilers, artificial intelligence, database systems, and operating systems. Advanced courses are offered in many areas such as natural language processing, the theory of computation, computer vision, software engineering, compiler optimization techniques, computer graphics, distributed computing, multimedia, networks, cryptography and security, groupware and [[computational finance]]. Adjunct faculty, drawn from outside academia, teach special topics courses in their areas of expertise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/webapps/content/academic/graduate/overview |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Graduate Programs in Computer Science |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\nUnless outside fellowships or scholarships are available to the students, all admitted Courant PhD students are granted with the GSAS MacCracken award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.math.nyu.edu/dynamic/phd/admissions-financial-support/financial-support/|title=Financial Support - Department of Mathematics - NYU Courant|author=|date=|website=www.math.nyu.edu}}</ref> The fellowship covers the tuition and provides 9 months of stipend along with other benefits such as health insurance and special housing opportunies. The MacCracken funding is renewable for a period of up to five years, assuming satisfactory progress toward the degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gsas.nyu.edu/content/nyu-as/gsas/admissions/financial-aid/maccracken-housing-program-for-doctoral-students.html|title=MacCracken Housing Program for Doctoral Students|author=|date=|website=gsas.nyu.edu}}</ref>\n\nDoctoral students take advanced courses in their areas of specialization, followed by a period of research and the preparation and defense of the doctoral thesis. Courant Students in Ph.D. programs may earn a master's degree while in progress toward the Ph.D program. Areas where there are special funding opportunities for graduate students include: Mathematics, Mechanics, and Material Sciences, Number Theory, Probability, and Scientific Computing. All PhD candidates are required to take a written comprehensive examination, oral preliminary examination, and create a dissertation defense. Each supported doctoral student has access to his or her own dedicated Unix workstation. Many other research machines provide for abundant access to a variety of computer architectures, including a distributed computing laboratory.<ref name=\"autogenerated2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/degree/phd/ |title=The Ph.D. Program |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Undergraduate program===\nThe Courant Institute houses New York University's undergraduate programs in computer science and mathematics. In addition, CIMS provides opportunities and facilities for undergraduate students to do and discuss mathematical research, including an undergraduate math lounge on the 11th floor and an undergraduate computer science lounge on the 3rd floor of Warren Weaver Hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://math.nyu.edu/degree/undergrad/MathLounge.html |title=Math Lounge |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2011-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718174327/http://math.nyu.edu/degree/undergrad/MathLounge.html |archive-date=2011-07-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.global-derivatives.com/index.php?Itemid=5&id=91&option=com_content&task=view |title=New York University - MSc Mathematics in Finance |publisher=Global-derivatives.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n[[File:CIMS Classroom.jpg|thumb|Classroom at Warren Weaver Hall]]\nThe mathematics and computer science undergraduate and graduate programs at the Courant Institute has a strong focus on building quantitative and problem-solving skills through teamwork.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/web/Academic/Undergrad/ |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Undergraduate Program |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://math.nyu.edu/degree/undergrad/ |title=Department of Mathematics, Courant Institute |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> An undergraduate computer science course on Computer Vision, for example, requires students to be in small teams to use and apply recently developed algorithms by researchers around the world on their own. One example assignment requires a student to study a paper written by researchers from [[Microsoft Research Cambridge]] in order to do an assignment on Segmentation and Graph Cut. To encourage innovation, students in advanced coursework are allowed to use any means to complete their assignment, such as a programming language of their choice and hacking a [[Kinect]] through legal means.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/courses/spring11/V22.0480-001/index.html |title=V22.0480-001 |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\nThe Courant Institute's undergraduate program also encourages students to engage in research with professors and graduate students. About 30% of undergraduate students participate in academic research through the competitive [[Research Experiences for Undergraduates]] program funded by the [[National Science Foundation]] or research funded primarily by the Dean's Undergraduate Research Fund. The Courant Institute has one of the highest percentage of undergraduate students doing research within [[New York University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cas.nyu.edu/page/ug.DeansResearchFund.html |title=NYU > A & S > Dean's Undergraduate Research Fund |publisher=Cas.nyu.edu |accessdate=2011-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629120916/http://cas.nyu.edu/page/ug.DeansResearchFund.html |archive-date=2011-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/web/Academic/Undergrad/spotlight.html |title=Undergraduate Student Spotlight - NYU Computer Science Department |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>[http://www.quantnet.com/review-nyu-mathematical-finance-program ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531134706/http://www.quantnet.com/review-nyu-mathematical-finance-program |date=May 31, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/webapps/content/academic/undergrad/ |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Undergraduate Program |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> With permission of their advisers or faculty, undergraduate students may take graduate-level courses. Courant undergraduate students through the years and alumni contribute greatly to the vitality of the Mathematics and Computer Science departments. Some accomplishments by current and former undergraduate Courant students include an Apple Worldwide Developers Conference Scholarship Winner, development of Object Category Recognition Techniques to sort garbage for recycling for the NYC's trash program, placement in 7th out of 42 in the ACM International Collegiate Programming Contest (ICPC), and inventors of the [[Diaspora (software)]] social network.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nThe undergraduate division of the Department of Mathematics offers a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree in Mathematics. It consists of a wide variety of courses in pure and applied mathematics taught by a distinguished faculty with a tradition of excellence in teaching and research. Students in advanced coursework often participate in formulating models outside the field of mathematics as well as in analyzing them. For example, an advanced mathematics course in Computers in Medicine and Biology requires a student to construct two computer models selected from the following list: circulation, gas exchange in the lung, control of cell volume, and the renal countercurrent mechanism. The student uses the models to conduct simulated physiological experiments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:vGj-HafADLoJ:math.nyu.edu/degree/undergrad/Math%2520major%2520bulletin%25202010-11%2520Final.pdf+Math+undergraduate+nyu+requirements&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESi4x3xv-_X-4B0Xil4BidRNWKCKg9smDHdaXmhcPNv2gRXB173WgH0mNEM6D-RGr6C-oEz4XoRNBZvoWRQ_RWpcHpNzWxe06LDC0hc2wG0Yi5rf6AFY3cYBVAKb3_wZ-EJjvU6I&sig=AHIEtbSCuQUYJiy-dq4Yg8t8z5z6AnV2Ig |title=Powered by Google Docs |publisher=Docs.google.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\nThe undergraduate division of the Department of Computer Science offers a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree, and fours minors. These are the computer science minor, web programming and applications minor, joint minor in computer science/mathematics, and the computer science education minor available in collaboration with [[Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development|NYU Steinhardt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cs.nyu.edu/home/undergrad/minor_programs.html|title=CS Minors {{!}} NYU Computer Science|website=cs.nyu.edu|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref> The BA degree can also be pursued with honors. Students may combine the degree with other majors within the College of Arts and Science to create a personalized joint major. Two specific combined degrees are the joint major in computer science/economics and the joint major in computer science/mathematics. The Department of Computer Science also offers a BS/BE Dual Degree in computer science and engineering and an accelerated master's program available to qualifying undergraduates in conjunction with the [[Tandon School of Engineering]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/webapps/content/academic/undergrad/overview |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Undergraduate CS Program Overview |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Graduation===\nThe Courant Institute encourages students at any stage of their studies, including the very early stage, to seek summer employment opportunities at various government and industry facilities. In the past few years, Courant students have taken summer internships at the National Institute of Health, Los Alamos National Laboratory,  Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory and NASA, as well as Wall Street firms. Such opportunities can greatly expand students' understanding of the mathematical sciences, offer them possible areas of interest for thesis research, and enhance their career options. Members of the faculty (and in particular the students' academic advisors) can assist students in finding appropriate summer employment. All graduate students are given official advisers, and  undergraduates are provided mentors from Courant faculty.\n\n===Academic research===\n[[File:Games for Learning Institute.jpg|thumb|The Courant Institute along with Microsoft Research are the founders of the Games for Learning Institute]]\nThe Department of Mathematics at Courant occupies a leading position in analysis and applied mathematics, including [[partial differential equations]], [[differential geometry]], [[dynamical systems]], [[probability]] and [[stochastic processes]], [[scientific computation]], [[mathematical finance]], [[mathematical physics]], and [[fluid dynamics]]. A special feature of the Institute is its highly interdisciplinary character \u2014 with courses, seminars, and active research collaborations in areas such as [[financial mathematics]], materials science, visual neural science, atmosphere/ocean science, cardiac fluid dynamics, plasma physics, and mathematical genomics. Another special feature is the central role of [[analysis]], which provides a natural bridge between pure and applied mathematics. The Department of Computer Science has strengths in multimedia, programming languages and systems, distributed and parallel computing, and the [[analysis of algorithms]].\n\nSince 1948, Courant Institute has maintained its own research journal, [[Communications on Pure and Applied Mathematics]], which currently has the highest impact factor internationally among mathematics journals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/78504520/issue |title=Wiley Online Library |publisher=.interscience.wiley.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>   While the journal represents the full spectrum of the Institute's mathematical research activity, most articles are in  the fields of applied mathematics, mathematical analysis, or mathematical physics. Its contents over the years amount to a modern history of the theory of partial differential equations. Most articles originate within the Institute or are specially invited. The Institute also  publishes its own series of lecture notes. They are based on the research interests of the faculty and visitors of the   Institute, originated in advanced graduate courses and mini-courses offered at the Institute.\n\n==Resources==\n[[File:Applied Mathematics Lab.jpg|thumb|Applied Mathematics Laboratory]]\n\n===Warren Weaver Hall & 60 Fifth Avenue===\nCIMS consists of the [[NYU]] Departments of Mathematics and Computer Science as well as a variety of research activities. It is housed in [[Warren Weaver]] Hall on Mercer Street in NYU's [[Greenwich Village]] campus. Unlike many [[NYU]] buildings, it did not have an NYU flag, but the flag has recently been added and is waved with pride. The building contains lecture halls on the first and second floors, two meeting/seminar rooms on every floor from the 3rd floor to the 13th floor, a large common lounge on the 13th floor used for studying and open discussions in topics of mathematics and computer science, and its own extensive Courant library on the 12th floor. It also houses a variety of well-equipped laboratories and offices in Warren Weaver Hall for students and faculty to do research and discuss topics in mathematical sciences. In addition to Warren Weaver Hall, the Computer Science Department and Center for Data Science are located at 60 fifth Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/direct.html|title=Getting to the Courant Institute|date=2005-09-01|publisher=Cims.nyu.edu|accessdate=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n===Courant Institute Library===\nThe Courant Institute Library contains one of the United States's most complete mathematics collections with more than 275 journals and 54,000 volumes. Faculty and students at CIMS have access to MathSciNet and Web of Science (also known as the Science Citation Index), and a vast database containing hundred thousands of electronic journals related to mathematics and computer science.<ref>[http://www.petersons.com/gradchannel/code/ProgramVC.asp?sn=New-York-University&mu=Courant-Institute-of-Mathematical-Sciences&pn=Department-of-Mathematics&inunid=46618&sponsor=1&related=true ]{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:CenterAtmosphereSciences.jpg|thumb|Center for Atmosphere-Ocean Science]]\n\n===Computing resources===\nThe Courant Institute  has an [[IBM]] eServer BladeCenter system capable of peak performance of 4.5 TeraFlops. The acquisition of this supercomputer was funded by [[IBM]] and federal funding and is used primarily for research by the faculty and graduate and undergraduate students of the institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/public.affairs/releases/detail/694 |title=NYU Today |publisher=Nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> Computers at the Institute run [[Windows XP Professional]], [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris]], [[Mac OS X]], and [[Red Hat Enterprise Linux]] operating systems. There are also many other specialized Linux-based operating systems for research purposes. Every faculty and student office room is fully equipped with scientific software and computer stations. Wi-Fi and X terminals are available in public locations and every faculty and student office.\n\nAll graduate students are provided with an account to access computers and other resources within the Institute's network. Undergraduate students are provided CIMS accounts with the approval of their advisor, sponsorship by a Courant professor, advanced coursework, or for research purposes. The Institute's computing resources are not accessible to others without sponsorship by a CIMS professor or approval by either the Department of Mathematics or Department of Computer Science. Faculty, staff, and students with Courant account have access to free full-featured software provided by the [[MSDN Academic Alliance]] and specialized computing resources used primarily for research.<ref>[http://cs.nyu.edu/web/Academic/Graduate/computeracct.html NYU Computer Science]. Retrieved August 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cims.nyu.edu/webapps/faq/Connecting%20to%20CIMS |title=NYU > Courant Institute > Connecting to CIMS FAQ |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cims.nyu.edu/webapps/content/systems/userservices/netaccess |title=NYU > Courant Institute > Network Access |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Major research resources===\nCIMS houses an advanced multimillion-dollar Courant Applied Mathematics Laboratory that opened in 1998, co-founded by Stephen Childress and Michael Shelley, and sponsored by [[US Department of Energy]] and the [[National Science Foundation]]. It comprises an experimental facility in fluid mechanics and other applied areas and a visualization and simulation facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/aml/index.html |title=AML |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> The Center for Atmosphere-Ocean Science is also housed at CIMS and is an interdisciplinary research and graduate program within the Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caos.cims.nyu.edu/page/home |title=Center for Atmosphere Ocean Science &#124; New York University |publisher=Caos.cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==cSplash and notable student activities==\n\n===cSplash===\nEvery year, CIMS offers cSplash or Courant Splash, a festival mathematics and computer science program for high school students. It is a one-day festival of classes in the mathematical and computer sciences, designed and taught by graduate and undergraduate students, faculty, and others associated with the Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/~csplash/index.php |title=Courant Splash! - cSplash |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Extracurricular activities===\nThere are many clubs within the Courant Institute open to undergraduate and graduate students alike. These clubs include the Courant Student Organization, The ACM at NYU, Women-in-Computing (WinC), The Mathematics Society, [http://cs.nyu.edu/~macsweb/about/ Masters Association for Computer Science] and many more. Additionally, CIMS sponsors and holds seminars and colloquiums almost daily on weekdays on topics of interest, in which some of whom may be held outside of Warren Weaver Hall. Many speakers of these seminars and colloquiums are experienced researchers from corporations from a variety of industries and researchers from private and government research laboratories, top universities, and NYU. Every academic year, CIMS holds award ceremonies, showcases, and parties to celebrate their faculty and undergraduate and graduate students and keep the academic atmosphere fun and enjoyable at CIMS. One such example is the NYU Computer Science Department Showcase held every semester to showcase projects that have been completed in various computer science graduate and undergraduate courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cims.nyu.edu/events/ |title=NYU > Courant Institute > Weekly Bulletin |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.nyu.edu/~wincweb/winc.html |title=New York University - Women in Computing |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/~csstu/ |title=Courant Student Organization:: New York University |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/math_club/index.html |title=NYU Mathematics Society: Home |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date=2010-04-24 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/~acmweb/wordpress/ |title=The ACM at NYU |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date=2011-02-22 |accessdate=2011-08-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814133630/http://cs.nyu.edu/~acmweb/wordpress/ |archivedate=2011-08-14 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1934, [[Richard Courant]] left [[G\u00f6ttingen University]] in Germany to become a visiting professor at NYU. He was given the task of building up the Department of Mathematics at the [[NYU Graduate School of Arts and Science]]. He was later joined by [[Kurt O. Friedrichs]] and James J. Stoker. In 1946, the department was renamed \"Institute for Mathematics and Mechanics\". Also in 1946, NYU Professor [[Morris Kline]] focused on mathematical problems of electromagnetic wave propagation. This project gave rise to the Institute's Division of Wave Propagation and Applied Mathematics. In 1952, the [[U.S. Atomic Energy Commission]] installed one of the first (electronic) computers at New York University, which led to the creation of the Courant Mathematics and Computing Laboratory. The Division of Magnetofluid Dynamics was initiated by a project on plasma fusion by NYU Professor [[Harold Grad]] in 1954.  The Institute was in the forefront of advanced hardware use, with an early [[IBM 7094]] and the fourth produced [[CDC 6600]].  The Division of [[Computational Fluid Dynamics]] was created in 1978, arising from a project of NYU Professor [[Paul Garabedian|Paul R. Garabedian]].\n\n==Directors==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Image\n! Name\n! Timespan\n|-\n| [[File:Richard Courant.jpg|100 px|thumb]] || ''[[Richard Courant]]'' || (1935&ndash;1958) \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[James J. Stoker]]'' || (1958&ndash;1966) \n|-\n| [[File:Kurt-Friedrichs-abt-1950-O.jpg|100 px|thumb]] || ''[[Kurt O. Friedrichs]]'' || (1966&ndash;1967) \n|-\n| <!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:J\u00fcrgen Moser.JPG|100 px|thumb]] --> || ''[[J\u00fcrgen Moser]]'' ||  (1967&ndash;1970) \n|-\n| [[File:Louis Nirenberg.jpeg|100 px|thumb]] || ''[[Louis Nirenberg]]'' ||  (1970&ndash;1972)  \n|-\n| [[File:Peter Lax in Tokyo.jpg|100 px|thumb]] || ''[[Peter Lax]]'' ||  (1972&ndash;1980) \n|-\n|  || ''[[S. R. Srinivasa Varadhan]]'' || (1980&ndash;1984)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Cathleen Synge Morawetz]]'' || (1984&ndash;1988)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Henry McKean]]'' || (1988&ndash;1994)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[David W. McLaughlin]]'' || (1994&ndash;2002)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Charles M. Newman]]'' ||  (2002&ndash;2006)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Leslie Greengard]]'' || (2006&ndash;2011)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[G\u00e9rard Ben Arous]]'' || (2011&ndash;2016)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Richard J. Cole]]'' || (2016&ndash;2017)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Russel E. Caflisch]]'' || (2017&ndash;present)  \n|-\n|}\n\n==Notable Courant faculty==\nThis is a small selection of Courant's famous faculty over the years and a few of their distinctions:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/about/scientific.html |title=NYU > Courant Institute > About > Scientific Distinction |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n* [[G\u00e9rard Ben Arous]], [[Davidson Prize]]\n* [[Marsha Berger]], NASA Software of the Year, National Academy of Engineering, National Academy of Sciences\n* [[Richard Bonneau]]\n* [[Robert A. Bonic]], co-Author Freshman Calculus; Sr. research scientist and computer professor; 1972 to 1975 collaboration with Industrial Designer George A. Sgouros in the research, design, and development of the first Computer Logic Training Modules (LOGICUBES)\n* [[Fedor Bogomolov]]\n* [[Luis Caffarelli]], [[Wolf Prize]]\n* [[Sylvain Cappell]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]]\n* [[Sourav Chatterjee]], [[Davidson Prize]]\n* [[Jeff Cheeger]], [[Veblen Prize]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Sciences, [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], Max Planck Research Prize\n* [[Steven Childress]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], American Physical Society Fellow\n* [[Demetrios Christodoulou]], 1993 [[MacArthur Fellow]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Sciences, [[Shaw Prize]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]] \n* [[Richard J. Cole]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]]\n* [[Martin Davis (mathematician)|Martin Davis]], [[Steele Prize]]\n* [[Percy Deift]], [[George P\u00f3lya Prize]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Kurt O. Friedrichs]], 1976 [[National Medal of Science]]\n* [[Paul Garabedian]], NAS Prize in Applied Mathematics, National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[James Glimm]], [[Steele Prize]], 2002 [[National Medal of Science]]\n* [[Leslie Greengard]], [[Steele Prize]], Packard Foundation Fellowship, NSF Presidential Young Investigator, National Academy of Engineering, National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Mikhail Gromov (mathematician)|Mikhail Gromov]], 2009 [[Abel Prize]], [[Wolf Prize]], [[Steele Prize]], Kyoto Prize, Balzan Prize, National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Larry Guth]]\n* [[Martin Hairer]], 2014 [[Fields Medal]] \n* [[Helmut Hofer]], Ostrowski Prize, National Academy of Sciences\n* [[Fritz John]], 1984 [[MacArthur Fellow]]\n* [[Joseph B. Keller]],  1988 [[National Medal of Science]], [[Wolf Prize]]\n* [[Michel Kervaire]]\n* [[Subhash Khot]], 2010 [[Alan T. Waterman Award]], 2014 [[Nevanlinna Prize]]\n* [[Bruce Kleiner]]\n* [[Morris Kline]]\n* [[Peter Lax]], [[Abel Prize]] winner, 1986 [[National Medal of Science]], [[Steele Prize]], [[Wolf Prize]], [[Norbert Wiener Prize]]\n* [[Lin Fanghua]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]], American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Wilhelm Magnus]]\n* [[Andrew Majda]], NAS Prize in Applied Mathematics, John von Neumann Prize (SIAM)\n* [[Henry McKean]], National Academy of Science, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[David W. McLaughlin]], National Academy of Science, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Bud Mishra]], Association for Computing Machinery Fellow\n* [[Cathleen Synge Morawetz]], 1998 [[National Medal of Science]], [[Steele Prize]], [[Birkhoff Prize]], [[Noether Lecturer]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[J\u00fcrgen Moser]], [[Wolf Prize]], [[James Craig Watson Medal]]\n* [[Assaf Naor]], [[European Mathematical Society Prize]], Packard Fellowship, [[Salem Prize]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]], [[Blavatnik Award]]\n* [[Charles M. Newman|Charles Newman]], National Academy of Science, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Louis Nirenberg]], [[Crafoord Prize]], [[National Medal of Science]], [[Steele Prize]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]], [[Chern Medal]], [[Abel Prize]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Michael Overton]]\n* [[Charles S. Peskin]], 1983 [[MacArthur Fellow]], [[Birkhoff Prize]], [[National Medal of Science]],\n* [[Amir Pnueli]], National Academy of Engineering, Israel Prize, [[Turing Award]], Association for Computing Machinery Fellow\n* [[Peter Sarnak]], [[Wolf Prize]]\n* [[Jack Schwartz]], who developed the programming language [[SETL]] at NYU and was in charge of the Robotics group.\n* [[Michael Shelley (mathematician)|Michael J. Shelley]], American Physical Society Fellow, Fran\u00e7ois Naftali Frenkiel Award (APS)\n* [[Victor Shoup]], who with Ronald Cramer developed the [[Cramer\u2013Shoup cryptosystem]]\n* [[Jonathan Sondow]]\n* [[Joel Spencer]]\n* [[K. R. Sreenivasan]]\n* [[Daniel L. Stein]], Fellow of [[American Physical Society]], Fellow of [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n* [[S. R. Srinivasa Varadhan]], [[Abel Prize]] winner, [[Steele Prize]], National Academy of Sciences,  American Academy of Arts and Science, Fellow of the [[Royal Society]], [[National Medal of Science]]\n* [[Akshay Venkatesh]], [[Salem Prize]], Packard Fellowship, 2018 [[Fields Medal]] \n* [[Olof B. Widlund]]\n* [[Margaret H. Wright]], National Academy of Science, National Academy of Engineering\n* [[Lai-Sang Young]], [[Satter Prize]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], American Academy of Arts and Science\n\n==Notable Courant alumni==\nThis is a small selection of Courant's alumni:\n* [[Anjelina Belakovskaia]] (Masters in Finance 2001), U.S. Women's Chess Champion.\n* [[Anita Borg]] (PhD 1981), founding director of the Institute for Women and Technology (IWT)\n* [[Alexandre Chorin]],  (PhD 1966) [[National Medal of Science]]\n* [[Charles Epstein]] (PhD 1983), hyperbolic geometry\n* [[Kenneth M. Golden]] (PhD 1984), applied mathematics of [[sea ice]], Fellow of the [[The Explorers Club|Explorers Club]]\n* [[Corwin Hansch]] (PhD 1944), statistics\n* [[Joseph B. Keller]],  1988 [[National Medal of Science]], [[Wolf Prize]]\n* [[Barbara Keyfitz]] (PhD 1970), Director of the [[Fields Institute]]\n* [[David Korn (computer scientist)|David Korn]] (PhD 1969), creator of the [[Korn shell]],\n* [[Sergiu Klainerman]] (PhD 1978), Professor at Princeton\n* [[Morris Kline]] (PhD 1936), NYU Professor (1938&ndash;1975)\n* [[Martin Kruskal]],  (PhD 1952) [[National Medal of Science]], co-discoverer of [[solitons]] and the [[inverse scattering]] method for solving KdV\n* [[Peter Lax]] (PhD 1949), recipient of the [[Abel Prize]], National Medal of Science, Steele Prize, Wolf Prize, Norbert Wiener Prize\n* [[Chen Li-an]], (PhD 1968) [[Taiwan]]ese [[Minister of Defence]]\n* [[Brian J. McCartin]] (PhD 1981), recipient of the [[2010 Chauvenet Prize]],\n* [[Cathleen Morawetz]] (PhD 1950), National Medal of Science, Birkhoff Prize, Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[American Mathematical Society|AMS]], professor emeritus at [[Courant Institute]]\n* [[Louis Nirenberg]] (PhD 1949), [[Crafoord Prize]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]], [[National Medal of Science]], [[Chern Medal]], [[Abel Prize]]\n* [[Stanley Osher]] (PhD 1966), Level Set method, professor at [[University of California, Los Angeles]], [[Gauss Prize]]\n* [[George C. Papanicolaou]] (PhD 1969), professor at [[Stanford University]]\n* [[Susan Mary Puglia]] (BA in Computer Science and Math), Vice President at [[IBM]]\n* [[Sashi Reddi]] ([[serial entrepreneur]], [[venture capitalist]], [[angel investor]], a technologist and a [[philanthropist]])\n* [[Gary Robinson]], [[software engineer]] noted for [[anti-spam techniques|anti-spam]] algorithms<ref name=twsSepaxxf>{{cite web\n |title= Gary Robinson\n |publisher= Google\n |quote= I make the music recommendation technology at http://www.flyfi.com -- ... Schools I've attended Bard College; Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences\n |date= 2010-09-18\n |url= http://spambayes.sourceforge.net/\n |accessdate= 2010-09-18\n}}</ref><ref name=twsSepb>{{cite magazine\n |author= [[Gary Robinson]]\n |title= A Statistical Approach to the Spam Problem: Using Bayesian statistics to detect an e-mail's spamminess. \n |magazine= Linux Journal\n |quote= This article discusses one of many possible mathematical foundations for a key aspect of spam filtering\u2014generating ...\n |date= Mar 1, 2003\n |url= http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/6467\n |accessdate= 2010-09-18\n}}</ref>\n* [[Shmuel Weinberger]] (PhD 1982), topology and geometry, Professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Jacob Wolfowitz]] (PhD 1942),\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mikhail Gromov (mathematician)|Mikhail Gromov]]\n*[[Peter Lax]]\n*[[Yann LeCun]]\n*[[Louis Nirenberg]]\n*[[Amir Pnueli]]\n*[[S. R. S. Varadhan]]\n*[[List of New York University people]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cims.nyu.edu/ Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences]\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/ Department of Mathematics, New York University]\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/aml/ Applied Mathematics Laboratory]\n*[http://cs.nyu.edu/ New York University Computer Science]\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/financial_mathematics/ New York University Mathematics in Finance]\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/degree/ms/scicomputing.html New York University Scientific Computing]\n*http://www.cims.nyu.edu/~csplash/index.php\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/math_club/ NYU Mathematics Society, New York University]\n*http://www.cs.nyu.edu/~wincweb/\n*http://www.cs.nyu.edu/~macsweb/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20090414012602/http://cs.nyu.edu/~acmweb/wordpress/\n\n{{New York University}}\n{{American mathematics}}\n\n{{coord|40.72858|N|73.99552|W|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:New York University schools|Mathematical Sciences]]\n[[Category:Mathematical institutes]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Division of New York University}}\n{{Infobox university\n| name = Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences (CIMS)\n| image = <!-- Deleted image removed:  [[File:NyuTorch.png|75px|New York University]] -->\n| established = 1935\n| director = [[Russel Caflisch]]\n| type = [[Private university|Private]] research institute\n| city = [[New York City]]\n| state = [[New York (state)|New York]]\n| country = [[United States|USA]]\n| campus = Urban\n| undergrad = 1,500\n| postgrad = 600\n| faculty = 82\n| academic_affiliation = [[New York University]]\n| website = {{url|cims.nyu.edu}}\n}}\n\n[[File:Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences (48072654781).jpg|thumb|View of Warren Weaver Hall, Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences from Gould Plaza]]\n\nThe '''Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences''' ('''CIMS''') is an independent division of [[New York University]] (NYU) under the Faculty of Arts & Science that serves as a center for research and advanced training in computer science and mathematics. It is considered one of the leading and most prestigious mathematics schools and mathematical sciences research centers in the world.<ref name=\"shanghairanking.com\">{{cite web|url=http://www.shanghairanking.com/Shanghairanking-Subject-Rankings/mathematics.html|title=ShanghaiRanking's Global Ranking of Academic Subjects 2017 - Mathematics - Shanghai Ranking - 2017|author=|date=|website=www.shanghairanking.com}}</ref> It is named after [[Richard Courant]], one of the founders of the Courant Institute and also a mathematics professor at New York University from 1936 to 1972.\n\nIt is ranked #1 in [[applied mathematical research]] in US,<ref name=\"grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com\">{{cite magazine|url = http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/search?program=top-mathematics-programs&specialty=applied-mathematics-rankings&name=&zip=&program_rank=Any&sort=&sortdir=|title = Search: Sciences Programs {{!}} US News|magazine = US News|accessdate = 2015-05-06}}</ref> #5 in citation impact worldwide, and #12 in citation worldwide. On the [[Faculty Scholarly Productivity Index]], it is ranked #3 with an index of 1.84.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://chronicle.com/stats/productivity/page.php?byinst=true&institution=2478&year=2007 |title=Faculty Scholarly Productivity Index |publisher=The Chronicle |date=2007-11-16 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> It is also known for its extensive research in pure mathematical areas, such as [[partial differential equations]], [[probability]] and [[geometry]], as well as applied mathematical areas, such as [[computational biology]], [[computational neuroscience]], and [[mathematical finance]]. The Mathematics Department of the Institute has 18 members of the [[United States National Academy of Sciences]] (more than any other mathematics department in the U.S.) and five members of the [[National Academy of Engineering]]. Four faculty members have been awarded the National Medal of Science, one was honored with the Kyoto Prize, and nine have received career awards from the National Science Foundation. Courant Institute professors [[Peter Lax]], [[S. R. Srinivasa Varadhan]], [[Mikhail Gromov (mathematician)|Mikhail Gromov]], [[Louis Nirenberg]]  won the 2005, 2007, 2009 and 2015 [[Abel Prize]] respectively for their research in partial differential equations, probability and geometry.<ref>{{cite news| url=https://www.nytimes.com/2009/06/01/nyregion/01nyu.html | work=The New York Times | first=Lisa W. | last=Foderaro | title=Complex Math, Simple Sum: 3 Awards in 5 Years | date=2009-06-01}}</ref> [[Louis Nirenberg]] also received the [[Chern Medal]] in 2010, and [[Subhash Khot]] won the [[Nevanlinna Prize]] in 2014.\n\nThe Director of the Courant Institute directly reports to New York University's Provost and President and works closely with deans and directors of other NYU colleges and divisions respectively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/about/courant.html|title=NYU > Courant Institute > About > Courant and NYU|date=|publisher=Cims.nyu.edu|accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> The undergraduate programs and graduate programs at the Courant Institute are run independently by the Institute, and formally associated with the [[NYU College of Arts and Science]] and [[NYU Graduate School of Arts and Science]] respectively.\n\n==Academics==\n\n===Rankings===\nThe Courant Institute specializes in [[applied mathematics]], [[mathematical analysis]] and [[scientific computation]]. There is emphasis on [[partial differential equations]] and their applications.  The mathematics department is consistently ranked in the United States as #1 in applied mathematics.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/applied-mathematics-rankings |title=Best Applied Mathematics Programs &#124; Top Math Schools &#124; US News Best Graduate Schools |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> Other strong points are  analysis (currently #6)<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/mathematical-analysis-rankings |title=Best Mathematical Analysis Programs &#124; Top Math Schools &#124; US News Best Graduate Schools |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref> and  geometry (currently #10).<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/geometry-rankings |title=Best Geometry Programs &#124; Top Math Schools &#124; US News Best Graduate Schools |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2014-03-14}}</ref>  Within the field of [[computer science]], CIMS concentrates in [[machine learning]], [[computation|theory]], [[programming languages]], [[computer graphics]] and [[parallel computing]]. The computer science program is ranked 28th among computer science programs in the US.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com/best-graduate-schools/top-science-schools/computer-science-rankings/page+2 |title=Best Computer Science Programs &#124; Top Computer Science Schools &#124; US News Best Graduate Schools |publisher=Grad-schools.usnews.rankingsandreviews.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> In 2019, the [[Academic Ranking of World Universities]] placed the Courant Institute as #3 worldwide in the subject ranking for mathematics.<ref name=\"shanghairanking.com\"/>\n\n===Admissions===\nThe Courant Institute offers [[Bachelor of Arts]], [[Bachelor of Science]], [[Master of Science]] and [[Ph.D.]] degree programs in both [[mathematics]] and [[computer science]] with program acceptance rates ranging from 3% to 29%.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thegradcafe.com/survey/index.php?q=NYU+computer+science&t=a&pp=50&o=p |title=NYU computer science \u2022 |publisher=Thegradcafe.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> The overall acceptance rate for all CIMS graduate programs is 15%, and program admissions reviews are holistic. A high undergraduate GPA and high GRE score are typically prerequisites to admission to its graduate programs but are not required. Majority of accepted candidates met these standards. However, character and personal qualities and evidence of strong quantitative skills are very important admission factors. Consistent with its scientific breadth, the Institute welcomes applicants whose primary background is in quantitative fields such as economics, engineering, physics, or biology, as well as mathematics. Undergraduate program admissions are not directly administrated by the Institute but by the NYU undergraduate admissions office of College of Arts and Science.<ref name=\"math.nyu.edu\">{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/financial_mathematics/content/05_prospectiveStudents/04.html |title=Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences NYU |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/degree/phd/application.html |title=Graduate Mathematics Courses |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/webapps/content/academic/graduate/admissions/admission |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Graduate Admissions Information |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.petersons.com/graduate-schools/new-york-university-courant-institute-of-mathematical-sciences-department-of-mathematics-admissions-000_10014124_10088.aspx |title=Department of Mathematics Admissions - New York University (Department of Mathematics) |publisher=Petersons.com |accessdate=2011-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629083544/http://www.petersons.com/graduate-schools/new-york-university-courant-institute-of-mathematical-sciences-department-of-mathematics-admissions-000_10014124_10088.aspx |archive-date=2011-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n\n===Graduate program===\nThe Department of Mathematics at the Courant Institute offers PhDs in Mathematics, Atmosphere-Ocean Science, and Computational Biology; Masters of Science in Mathematical Finance, Mathematics, and Scientific Computing.\n\n[[File:CIMS Lecture Hall.jpg|thumb|Lecture Hall at Warren Weaver Hall]]\nThe Graduate Department of Computer Science offers a PhD in computer science. In addition it offers Master of Science degrees in computer science, information systems (in conjunction with the [[Stern School of Business]]), and in scientific computing. For the PhD program, every PhD computer science student must receive a grade of A or A- on the final examination for algorithms, systems, applications, and a PhD-level course chosen by the student that does not satisfy the first three requirements, such as cryptography and numerical methods. Students may take the final exam for any these courses without being enrolled in the course.\n\nThe Computer Science Masters program offers instruction in the fundamental principles, design and applications of computer systems and computer technologies. Students who obtain an MS degree in computer science are qualified to do significant development work in the computer industry or important application areas. Those who receive a doctoral degree are in a position to hold faculty appointments and do research and development work at the forefront of this rapidly changing and expanding field. The emphasis for the MS in Information Systems program is on the use of computer systems in business. For the Master of Science in Scientific Computing, it is designed to provide broad training in areas related to scientific computing using modern computing technology and mathematical modeling arising in various applications. The core of the curriculum for all computer science graduate students consists of courses in algorithms, programming languages, compilers, artificial intelligence, database systems, and operating systems. Advanced courses are offered in many areas such as natural language processing, the theory of computation, computer vision, software engineering, compiler optimization techniques, computer graphics, distributed computing, multimedia, networks, cryptography and security, groupware and [[computational finance]]. Adjunct faculty, drawn from outside academia, teach special topics courses in their areas of expertise.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/webapps/content/academic/graduate/overview |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Graduate Programs in Computer Science |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\nUnless outside fellowships or scholarships are available to the students, all admitted Courant PhD students are granted with the GSAS MacCracken award.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.math.nyu.edu/dynamic/phd/admissions-financial-support/financial-support/|title=Financial Support - Department of Mathematics - NYU Courant|author=|date=|website=www.math.nyu.edu}}</ref> The fellowship covers the tuition and provides 9 months of stipend along with other benefits such as health insurance and special housing opportunies. The MacCracken funding is renewable for a period of up to five years, assuming satisfactory progress toward the degree.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://gsas.nyu.edu/content/nyu-as/gsas/admissions/financial-aid/maccracken-housing-program-for-doctoral-students.html|title=MacCracken Housing Program for Doctoral Students|author=|date=|website=gsas.nyu.edu}}</ref>\n\nDoctoral students take advanced courses in their areas of specialization, followed by a period of research and the preparation and defense of the doctoral thesis. Courant Students in Ph.D. programs may earn a master's degree while in progress toward the Ph.D program. Areas where there are special funding opportunities for graduate students include: Mathematics, Mechanics, and Material Sciences, Number Theory, Probability, and Scientific Computing. All PhD candidates are required to take a written comprehensive examination, oral preliminary examination, and create a dissertation defense. Each supported doctoral student has access to his or her own dedicated Unix workstation. Many other research machines provide for abundant access to a variety of computer architectures, including a distributed computing laboratory.<ref name=\"autogenerated2005\">{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/degree/phd/ |title=The Ph.D. Program |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Undergraduate program===\nThe Courant Institute houses New York University's undergraduate programs in computer science and mathematics. In addition, CIMS provides opportunities and facilities for undergraduate students to do and discuss mathematical research, including an undergraduate math lounge on the 11th floor and an undergraduate computer science lounge on the 3rd floor of Warren Weaver Hall.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://math.nyu.edu/degree/undergrad/MathLounge.html |title=Math Lounge |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2011-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110718174327/http://math.nyu.edu/degree/undergrad/MathLounge.html |archive-date=2011-07-18 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.global-derivatives.com/index.php?Itemid=5&id=91&option=com_content&task=view |title=New York University - MSc Mathematics in Finance |publisher=Global-derivatives.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n[[File:CIMS Classroom.jpg|thumb|Classroom at Warren Weaver Hall]]\nThe mathematics and computer science undergraduate and graduate programs at the Courant Institute has a strong focus on building quantitative and problem-solving skills through teamwork.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/web/Academic/Undergrad/ |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Undergraduate Program |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://math.nyu.edu/degree/undergrad/ |title=Department of Mathematics, Courant Institute |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> An undergraduate computer science course on Computer Vision, for example, requires students to be in small teams to use and apply recently developed algorithms by researchers around the world on their own. One example assignment requires a student to study a paper written by researchers from [[Microsoft Research Cambridge]] in order to do an assignment on Segmentation and Graph Cut. To encourage innovation, students in advanced coursework are allowed to use any means to complete their assignment, such as a programming language of their choice and hacking a [[Kinect]] through legal means.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/courses/spring11/V22.0480-001/index.html |title=V22.0480-001 |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\nThe Courant Institute's undergraduate program also encourages students to engage in research with professors and graduate students. About 30% of undergraduate students participate in academic research through the competitive [[Research Experiences for Undergraduates]] program funded by the [[National Science Foundation]] or research funded primarily by the Dean's Undergraduate Research Fund. The Courant Institute has one of the highest percentage of undergraduate students doing research within [[New York University]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://cas.nyu.edu/page/ug.DeansResearchFund.html |title=NYU > A & S > Dean's Undergraduate Research Fund |publisher=Cas.nyu.edu |accessdate=2011-08-06 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110629120916/http://cas.nyu.edu/page/ug.DeansResearchFund.html |archive-date=2011-06-29 |url-status=dead }}</ref><ref name=\"autogenerated1\">{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/web/Academic/Undergrad/spotlight.html |title=Undergraduate Student Spotlight - NYU Computer Science Department |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>[http://www.quantnet.com/review-nyu-mathematical-finance-program ] {{webarchive |url=https://web.archive.org/web/20100531134706/http://www.quantnet.com/review-nyu-mathematical-finance-program |date=May 31, 2010 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/webapps/content/academic/undergrad/ |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Undergraduate Program |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> With permission of their advisers or faculty, undergraduate students may take graduate-level courses. Courant undergraduate students through the years and alumni contribute greatly to the vitality of the Mathematics and Computer Science departments. Some accomplishments by current and former undergraduate Courant students include an Apple Worldwide Developers Conference Scholarship Winner, development of Object Category Recognition Techniques to sort garbage for recycling for the NYC's trash program, placement in 7th out of 42 in the ACM International Collegiate Programming Contest (ICPC), and inventors of the [[Diaspora (software)]] social network.<ref name=\"autogenerated1\"/>\n\nThe undergraduate division of the Department of Mathematics offers a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree in Mathematics. It consists of a wide variety of courses in pure and applied mathematics taught by a distinguished faculty with a tradition of excellence in teaching and research. Students in advanced coursework often participate in formulating models outside the field of mathematics as well as in analyzing them. For example, an advanced mathematics course in Computers in Medicine and Biology requires a student to construct two computer models selected from the following list: circulation, gas exchange in the lung, control of cell volume, and the renal countercurrent mechanism. The student uses the models to conduct simulated physiological experiments.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://docs.google.com/viewer?a=v&q=cache:vGj-HafADLoJ:math.nyu.edu/degree/undergrad/Math%2520major%2520bulletin%25202010-11%2520Final.pdf+Math+undergraduate+nyu+requirements&hl=en&gl=us&pid=bl&srcid=ADGEESi4x3xv-_X-4B0Xil4BidRNWKCKg9smDHdaXmhcPNv2gRXB173WgH0mNEM6D-RGr6C-oEz4XoRNBZvoWRQ_RWpcHpNzWxe06LDC0hc2wG0Yi5rf6AFY3cYBVAKb3_wZ-EJjvU6I&sig=AHIEtbSCuQUYJiy-dq4Yg8t8z5z6AnV2Ig |title=Powered by Google Docs |publisher=Docs.google.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\nThe undergraduate division of the Department of Computer Science offers a Bachelor of Arts (BA) degree, and fours minors. These are the computer science minor, web programming and applications minor, joint minor in computer science/mathematics, and the computer science education minor available in collaboration with [[Steinhardt School of Culture, Education, and Human Development|NYU Steinhardt]].<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://cs.nyu.edu/home/undergrad/minor_programs.html|title=CS Minors {{!}} NYU Computer Science|website=cs.nyu.edu|access-date=2019-04-06}}</ref> The BA degree can also be pursued with honors. Students may combine the degree with other majors within the College of Arts and Science to create a personalized joint major. Two specific combined degrees are the joint major in computer science/economics and the joint major in computer science/mathematics. The Department of Computer Science also offers a BS/BE Dual Degree in computer science and engineering and an accelerated master's program available to qualifying undergraduates in conjunction with the [[Tandon School of Engineering]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/webapps/content/academic/undergrad/overview |title=NYU Computer Science Department > Undergraduate CS Program Overview |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Graduation===\nThe Courant Institute encourages students at any stage of their studies, including the very early stage, to seek summer employment opportunities at various government and industry facilities. In the past few years, Courant students have taken summer internships at the National Institute of Health, Los Alamos National Laboratory,  Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, Woods Hole Oceanographic Institution, Lawrence Livermore National Laboratory and NASA, as well as Wall Street firms. Such opportunities can greatly expand students' understanding of the mathematical sciences, offer them possible areas of interest for thesis research, and enhance their career options. Members of the faculty (and in particular the students' academic advisors) can assist students in finding appropriate summer employment. All graduate students are given official advisers, and  undergraduates are provided mentors from Courant faculty.\n\n===Academic research===\n[[File:Games for Learning Institute.jpg|thumb|The Courant Institute along with Microsoft Research are the founders of the Games for Learning Institute]]\nThe Department of Mathematics at Courant occupies a leading position in analysis and applied mathematics, including [[partial differential equations]], [[differential geometry]], [[dynamical systems]], [[probability]] and [[stochastic processes]], [[scientific computation]], [[mathematical finance]], [[mathematical physics]], and [[fluid dynamics]]. A special feature of the Institute is its highly interdisciplinary character \u2014 with courses, seminars, and active research collaborations in areas such as [[financial mathematics]], materials science, visual neural science, atmosphere/ocean science, cardiac fluid dynamics, plasma physics, and mathematical genomics. Another special feature is the central role of [[analysis]], which provides a natural bridge between pure and applied mathematics. The Department of Computer Science has strengths in multimedia, programming languages and systems, distributed and parallel computing, and the [[analysis of algorithms]].\n\nSince 1948, Courant Institute has maintained its own research journal, [[Communications on Pure and Applied Mathematics]], which currently has the highest impact factor internationally among mathematics journals.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www3.interscience.wiley.com/journal/78504520/issue |title=Wiley Online Library |publisher=.interscience.wiley.com |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}{{dead link|date=February 2019|bot=medic}}{{cbignore|bot=medic}}</ref>   While the journal represents the full spectrum of the Institute's mathematical research activity, most articles are in  the fields of applied mathematics, mathematical analysis, or mathematical physics. Its contents over the years amount to a modern history of the theory of partial differential equations. Most articles originate within the Institute or are specially invited. The Institute also  publishes its own series of lecture notes. They are based on the research interests of the faculty and visitors of the   Institute, originated in advanced graduate courses and mini-courses offered at the Institute.\n\n==Resources==\n[[File:Applied Mathematics Lab.jpg|thumb|Applied Mathematics Laboratory]]\n\n===Warren Weaver Hall & 60 Fifth Avenue===\nCIMS consists of the [[NYU]] Departments of Mathematics and Computer Science as well as a variety of research activities. It is housed in [[Warren Weaver]] Hall on Mercer Street in NYU's [[Greenwich Village]] campus. Unlike many [[NYU]] buildings, it did not have an NYU flag, but the flag has recently been added and is waved with pride. The building contains lecture halls on the first and second floors, two meeting/seminar rooms on every floor from the 3rd floor to the 13th floor, a large common lounge on the 13th floor used for studying and open discussions in topics of mathematics and computer science, and its own extensive Courant library on the 12th floor. It also houses a variety of well-equipped laboratories and offices in Warren Weaver Hall for students and faculty to do research and discuss topics in mathematical sciences. In addition to Warren Weaver Hall, the Computer Science Department and Center for Data Science are located at 60 fifth Avenue.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/direct.html|title=Getting to the Courant Institute|date=2005-09-01|publisher=Cims.nyu.edu|accessdate=2019-05-05}}</ref>\n\n===Courant Institute Library===\nThe Courant Institute Library contains one of the United States's most complete mathematics collections with more than 275 journals and 54,000 volumes. Faculty and students at CIMS have access to MathSciNet and Web of Science (also known as the Science Citation Index), and a vast database containing hundred thousands of electronic journals related to mathematics and computer science.<ref>[http://www.petersons.com/gradchannel/code/ProgramVC.asp?sn=New-York-University&mu=Courant-Institute-of-Mathematical-Sciences&pn=Department-of-Mathematics&inunid=46618&sponsor=1&related=true ]{{dead link|date=August 2011}}</ref>\n[[File:CenterAtmosphereSciences.jpg|thumb|Center for Atmosphere-Ocean Science]]\n\n===Computing resources===\nThe Courant Institute  has an [[IBM]] eServer BladeCenter system capable of peak performance of 4.5 TeraFlops. The acquisition of this supercomputer was funded by [[IBM]] and federal funding and is used primarily for research by the faculty and graduate and undergraduate students of the institute.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.nyu.edu/public.affairs/releases/detail/694 |title=NYU Today |publisher=Nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> Computers at the Institute run [[Windows XP Professional]], [[Solaris (operating system)|Solaris]], [[Mac OS X]], and [[Red Hat Enterprise Linux]] operating systems. There are also many other specialized Linux-based operating systems for research purposes. Every faculty and student office room is fully equipped with scientific software and computer stations. Wi-Fi and X terminals are available in public locations and every faculty and student office.\n\nAll graduate students are provided with an account to access computers and other resources within the Institute's network. Undergraduate students are provided CIMS accounts with the approval of their advisor, sponsorship by a Courant professor, advanced coursework, or for research purposes. The Institute's computing resources are not accessible to others without sponsorship by a CIMS professor or approval by either the Department of Mathematics or Department of Computer Science. Faculty, staff, and students with Courant account have access to free full-featured software provided by the [[MSDN Academic Alliance]] and specialized computing resources used primarily for research.<ref>[http://cs.nyu.edu/web/Academic/Graduate/computeracct.html NYU Computer Science]. Retrieved August 2011</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cims.nyu.edu/webapps/faq/Connecting%20to%20CIMS |title=NYU > Courant Institute > Connecting to CIMS FAQ |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cims.nyu.edu/webapps/content/systems/userservices/netaccess |title=NYU > Courant Institute > Network Access |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Major research resources===\nCIMS houses an advanced multimillion-dollar Courant Applied Mathematics Laboratory that opened in 1998, co-founded by Stephen Childress and Michael Shelley, and sponsored by [[US Department of Energy]] and the [[National Science Foundation]]. It comprises an experimental facility in fluid mechanics and other applied areas and a visualization and simulation facility.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/aml/index.html |title=AML |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref> The Center for Atmosphere-Ocean Science is also housed at CIMS and is an interdisciplinary research and graduate program within the Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://caos.cims.nyu.edu/page/home |title=Center for Atmosphere Ocean Science &#124; New York University |publisher=Caos.cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n==cSplash and notable student activities==\n\n===cSplash===\nEvery year, CIMS offers cSplash or Courant Splash, a festival mathematics and computer science program for high school students. It is a one-day festival of classes in the mathematical and computer sciences, designed and taught by graduate and undergraduate students, faculty, and others associated with the Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/~csplash/index.php |title=Courant Splash! - cSplash |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n\n===Extracurricular activities===\nThere are many clubs within the Courant Institute open to undergraduate and graduate students alike. These clubs include the Courant Student Organization, The ACM at NYU, Women-in-Computing (WinC), The Mathematics Society, [http://cs.nyu.edu/~macsweb/about/ Masters Association for Computer Science] and many more. Additionally, CIMS sponsors and holds seminars and colloquiums almost daily on weekdays on topics of interest, in which some of whom may be held outside of Warren Weaver Hall. Many speakers of these seminars and colloquiums are experienced researchers from corporations from a variety of industries and researchers from private and government research laboratories, top universities, and NYU. Every academic year, CIMS holds award ceremonies, showcases, and parties to celebrate their faculty and undergraduate and graduate students and keep the academic atmosphere fun and enjoyable at CIMS. One such example is the NYU Computer Science Department Showcase held every semester to showcase projects that have been completed in various computer science graduate and undergraduate courses.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cims.nyu.edu/events/ |title=NYU > Courant Institute > Weekly Bulletin |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cs.nyu.edu/~wincweb/winc.html |title=New York University - Women in Computing |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/~csstu/ |title=Courant Student Organization:: New York University |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date= |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.math.nyu.edu/math_club/index.html |title=NYU Mathematics Society: Home |publisher=Math.nyu.edu |date=2010-04-24 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://cs.nyu.edu/~acmweb/wordpress/ |title=The ACM at NYU |publisher=Cs.nyu.edu |date=2011-02-22 |accessdate=2011-08-06 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110814133630/http://cs.nyu.edu/~acmweb/wordpress/ |archivedate=2011-08-14 }}</ref>\n\n==History==\nIn 1934, [[Richard Courant]] left [[G\u00f6ttingen University]] in Germany to become a visiting professor at NYU. He was given the task of building up the Department of Mathematics at the [[NYU Graduate School of Arts and Science]]. He was later joined by [[Kurt O. Friedrichs]] and James J. Stoker. In 1946, the department was renamed \"Institute for Mathematics and Mechanics\". Also in 1946, NYU Professor [[Morris Kline]] focused on mathematical problems of electromagnetic wave propagation. This project gave rise to the Institute's Division of Wave Propagation and Applied Mathematics. In 1952, the [[U.S. Atomic Energy Commission]] installed one of the first (electronic) computers at New York University, which led to the creation of the Courant Mathematics and Computing Laboratory. The Division of Magnetofluid Dynamics was initiated by a project on plasma fusion by NYU Professor [[Harold Grad]] in 1954.  The Institute was in the forefront of advanced hardware use, with an early [[IBM 7094]] and the fourth produced [[CDC 6600]].  The Division of [[Computational Fluid Dynamics]] was created in 1978, arising from a project of NYU Professor [[Paul Garabedian|Paul R. Garabedian]].\n\n==Directors==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n! Image\n! Name\n! Timespan\n|-\n| [[File:Richard Courant.jpg|100 px|thumb]] || ''[[Richard Courant]]'' || (1935&ndash;1958) \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[James J. Stoker]]'' || (1958&ndash;1966) \n|-\n| [[File:Kurt-Friedrichs-abt-1950-O.jpg|100 px|thumb]] || ''[[Kurt O. Friedrichs]]'' || (1966&ndash;1967) \n|-\n| <!-- [[WP:NFCC]] violation: [[File:J\u00fcrgen Moser.JPG|100 px|thumb]] --> || ''[[J\u00fcrgen Moser]]'' ||  (1967&ndash;1970) \n|-\n| [[File:Louis Nirenberg.jpeg|100 px|thumb]] || ''[[Louis Nirenberg]]'' ||  (1970&ndash;1972)  \n|-\n| [[File:Peter Lax in Tokyo.jpg|100 px|thumb]] || ''[[Peter Lax]]'' ||  (1972&ndash;1980) \n|-\n|  || ''[[S. R. Srinivasa Varadhan]]'' || (1980&ndash;1984)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Cathleen Synge Morawetz]]'' || (1984&ndash;1988)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Henry McKean]]'' || (1988&ndash;1994)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[David W. McLaughlin]]'' || (1994&ndash;2002)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Charles M. Newman]]'' ||  (2002&ndash;2006)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Leslie Greengard]]'' || (2006&ndash;2011)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[G\u00e9rard Ben Arous]]'' || (2011&ndash;2016)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Richard J. Cole]]'' || (2016&ndash;2017)  \n|-\n| <!--  --> || ''[[Russel E. Caflisch]]'' || (2017&ndash;present)  \n|-\n|}\n\n==Notable Courant faculty==\nThis is a small selection of Courant's famous faculty over the years and a few of their distinctions:<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cims.nyu.edu/about/scientific.html |title=NYU > Courant Institute > About > Scientific Distinction |publisher=Cims.nyu.edu |date=2005-09-01 |accessdate=2011-08-06}}</ref>\n* [[G\u00e9rard Ben Arous]], [[Davidson Prize]]\n* [[Marsha Berger]], NASA Software of the Year, National Academy of Engineering, National Academy of Sciences\n* [[Richard Bonneau]]\n* [[Robert A. Bonic]], co-Author Freshman Calculus; Sr. research scientist and computer professor; 1972 to 1975 collaboration with Industrial Designer George A. Sgouros in the research, design, and development of the first Computer Logic Training Modules (LOGICUBES)\n* [[Fedor Bogomolov]]\n* [[Luis Caffarelli]], [[Wolf Prize]]\n* [[Sylvain Cappell]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]]\n* [[Sourav Chatterjee]], [[Davidson Prize]]\n* [[Jeff Cheeger]], [[Veblen Prize]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Sciences, [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], Max Planck Research Prize\n* [[Steven Childress]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], American Physical Society Fellow\n* [[Demetrios Christodoulou]], 1993 [[MacArthur Fellow]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Sciences, [[Shaw Prize]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]] \n* [[Richard J. Cole]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]]\n* [[Martin Davis (mathematician)|Martin Davis]], [[Steele Prize]]\n* [[Percy Deift]], [[George P\u00f3lya Prize]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Kurt O. Friedrichs]], 1976 [[National Medal of Science]]\n* [[Paul Garabedian]], NAS Prize in Applied Mathematics, National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[James Glimm]], [[Steele Prize]], 2002 [[National Medal of Science]]\n* [[Leslie Greengard]], [[Steele Prize]], Packard Foundation Fellowship, NSF Presidential Young Investigator, National Academy of Engineering, National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Mikhail Gromov (mathematician)|Mikhail Gromov]], 2009 [[Abel Prize]], [[Wolf Prize]], [[Steele Prize]], Kyoto Prize, Balzan Prize, National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Larry Guth]]\n* [[Martin Hairer]], 2014 [[Fields Medal]] \n* [[Helmut Hofer]], Ostrowski Prize, National Academy of Sciences\n* [[Fritz John]], 1984 [[MacArthur Fellow]]\n* [[Joseph B. Keller]],  1988 [[National Medal of Science]], [[Wolf Prize]]\n* [[Michel Kervaire]]\n* [[Subhash Khot]], 2010 [[Alan T. Waterman Award]], 2014 [[Nevanlinna Prize]]\n* [[Bruce Kleiner]]\n* [[Morris Kline]]\n* [[Peter Lax]], [[Abel Prize]] winner, 1986 [[National Medal of Science]], [[Steele Prize]], [[Wolf Prize]], [[Norbert Wiener Prize]]\n* [[Lin Fanghua]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]], American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Wilhelm Magnus]]\n* [[Andrew Majda]], NAS Prize in Applied Mathematics, John von Neumann Prize (SIAM)\n* [[Henry McKean]], National Academy of Science, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[David W. McLaughlin]], National Academy of Science, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Bud Mishra]], Association for Computing Machinery Fellow\n* [[Cathleen Synge Morawetz]], 1998 [[National Medal of Science]], [[Steele Prize]], [[Birkhoff Prize]], [[Noether Lecturer]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[J\u00fcrgen Moser]], [[Wolf Prize]], [[James Craig Watson Medal]]\n* [[Assaf Naor]], [[European Mathematical Society Prize]], Packard Fellowship, [[Salem Prize]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]], [[Blavatnik Award]]\n* [[Charles M. Newman|Charles Newman]], National Academy of Science, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Louis Nirenberg]], [[Crafoord Prize]], [[National Medal of Science]], [[Steele Prize]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]], [[Chern Medal]], [[Abel Prize]], National Academy of Sciences, American Academy of Arts and Science\n* [[Michael Overton]]\n* [[Charles S. Peskin]], 1983 [[MacArthur Fellow]], [[Birkhoff Prize]], [[National Medal of Science]],\n* [[Amir Pnueli]], National Academy of Engineering, Israel Prize, [[Turing Award]], Association for Computing Machinery Fellow\n* [[Peter Sarnak]], [[Wolf Prize]]\n* [[Jack Schwartz]], who developed the programming language [[SETL]] at NYU and was in charge of the Robotics group.\n* [[Michael Shelley (mathematician)|Michael J. Shelley]], American Physical Society Fellow, Fran\u00e7ois Naftali Frenkiel Award (APS)\n* [[Victor Shoup]], who with Ronald Cramer developed the [[Cramer\u2013Shoup cryptosystem]]\n* [[Jonathan Sondow]]\n* [[Joel Spencer]]\n* [[K. R. Sreenivasan]]\n* [[Daniel L. Stein]], Fellow of [[American Physical Society]], Fellow of [[American Association for the Advancement of Science]]\n* [[S. R. Srinivasa Varadhan]], [[Abel Prize]] winner, [[Steele Prize]], National Academy of Sciences,  American Academy of Arts and Science, Fellow of the [[Royal Society]], [[National Medal of Science]]\n* [[Akshay Venkatesh]], [[Salem Prize]], Packard Fellowship, 2018 [[Fields Medal]] \n* [[Olof B. Widlund]]\n* [[Margaret H. Wright]], National Academy of Science, National Academy of Engineering\n* [[Lai-Sang Young]], [[Satter Prize]], [[Guggenheim Fellowship]], American Academy of Arts and Science\n\n==Notable Courant alumni==\nThis is a small selection of Courant's alumni:\n* [[Anjelina Belakovskaia]] (Masters in Finance 2001), U.S. Women's Chess Champion.\n* [[Anita Borg]] (PhD 1981), founding director of the Institute for Women and Technology (IWT)\n* [[Alexandre Chorin]],  (PhD 1966) [[National Medal of Science]]\n* [[Charles Epstein]] (PhD 1983), hyperbolic geometry\n* [[Kenneth M. Golden]] (PhD 1984), applied mathematics of [[sea ice]], Fellow of the [[The Explorers Club|Explorers Club]]\n* [[Corwin Hansch]] (PhD 1944), statistics\n* [[Joseph B. Keller]],  1988 [[National Medal of Science]], [[Wolf Prize]]\n* [[Barbara Keyfitz]] (PhD 1970), Director of the [[Fields Institute]]\n* [[David Korn (computer scientist)|David Korn]] (PhD 1969), creator of the [[Korn shell]],\n* [[Sergiu Klainerman]] (PhD 1978), Professor at Princeton\n* [[Morris Kline]] (PhD 1936), NYU Professor (1938&ndash;1975)\n* [[Martin Kruskal]],  (PhD 1952) [[National Medal of Science]], co-discoverer of [[solitons]] and the [[inverse scattering]] method for solving KdV\n* [[Peter Lax]] (PhD 1949), recipient of the [[Abel Prize]], National Medal of Science, Steele Prize, Wolf Prize, Norbert Wiener Prize\n* [[Chen Li-an]], (PhD 1968) [[Taiwan]]ese [[Minister of Defence]]\n* [[Brian J. McCartin]] (PhD 1981), recipient of the [[2010 Chauvenet Prize]],\n* [[Cathleen Morawetz]] (PhD 1950), National Medal of Science, Birkhoff Prize, Lifetime Achievement Award from the [[American Mathematical Society|AMS]], professor emeritus at [[Courant Institute]]\n* [[Louis Nirenberg]] (PhD 1949), [[Crafoord Prize]], [[B\u00f4cher Memorial Prize]], [[National Medal of Science]], [[Chern Medal]], [[Abel Prize]]\n* [[Stanley Osher]] (PhD 1966), Level Set method, professor at [[University of California, Los Angeles]], [[Gauss Prize]]\n* [[George C. Papanicolaou]] (PhD 1969), professor at [[Stanford University]]\n* [[Susan Mary Puglia]] (BA in Computer Science and Math), Vice President at [[IBM]]\n* [[Sashi Reddi]] ([[serial entrepreneur]], [[venture capitalist]], [[angel investor]], a technologist and a [[philanthropist]])\n* [[Gary Robinson]], [[software engineer]] noted for [[anti-spam techniques|anti-spam]] algorithms<ref name=twsSepaxxf>{{cite web\n |title= Gary Robinson\n |publisher= Google\n |quote= I make the music recommendation technology at http://www.flyfi.com -- ... Schools I've attended Bard College; Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences\n |date= 2010-09-18\n |url= http://spambayes.sourceforge.net/\n |accessdate= 2010-09-18\n}}</ref><ref name=twsSepb>{{cite magazine\n |author= [[Gary Robinson]]\n |title= A Statistical Approach to the Spam Problem: Using Bayesian statistics to detect an e-mail's spamminess. \n |magazine= Linux Journal\n |quote= This article discusses one of many possible mathematical foundations for a key aspect of spam filtering\u2014generating ...\n |date= Mar 1, 2003\n |url= http://www.linuxjournal.com/article/6467\n |accessdate= 2010-09-18\n}}</ref>\n* [[Shmuel Weinberger]] (PhD 1982), topology and geometry, Professor at [[University of Chicago]]\n* [[Jacob Wolfowitz]] (PhD 1942),\n\n==See also==\n*[[Mikhail Gromov (mathematician)|Mikhail Gromov]]\n*[[Peter Lax]]\n*[[Yann LeCun]]\n*[[Louis Nirenberg]]\n*[[Amir Pnueli]]\n*[[S. R. S. Varadhan]]\n*[[List of New York University people]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n*[http://www.cims.nyu.edu/ Courant Institute of Mathematical Sciences]\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/ Department of Mathematics, New York University]\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/aml/ Applied Mathematics Laboratory]\n*[http://cs.nyu.edu/ New York University Computer Science]\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/financial_mathematics/ New York University Mathematics in Finance]\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/degree/ms/scicomputing.html New York University Scientific Computing]\n*http://www.cims.nyu.edu/~csplash/index.php\n*[http://www.math.nyu.edu/math_club/ NYU Mathematics Society, New York University]\n*http://www.cs.nyu.edu/~wincweb/\n*http://www.cs.nyu.edu/~macsweb/\n*https://web.archive.org/web/20090414012602/http://cs.nyu.edu/~acmweb/wordpress/\n\n{{New York University}}\n{{American mathematics}}\n\n{{coord|40.72858|N|73.99552|W|source:placeopedia|display=title}}\n\n[[Category:New York University schools|Mathematical Sciences]]\n[[Category:Mathematical institutes]]\n[[Category:Educational institutions established in 1935]]\n[[Category:1935 establishments in New York (state)]]\n", "name_user": "Andrewmoody71", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Courant_Institute_of_Mathematical_Sciences"}
{"title_page": "Irish Republican Socialist Party", "text_new": "{{Short description|Socialist party active in Ireland}}\n{{For|the early 20th-century party founded by [[James Connolly]]|Irish Socialist Republican Party}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Primary sources|date=April 2008}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| country           = the Republic of Ireland\n| country2          = Northern Ireland\n| name              = Irish Republican Socialist Party\n| native_name       = P\u00e1irt\u00ed Poblachtach S\u00f3isalach na h-\u00c9ireann\n| logo              = IRSP logo 2018.png\n| logo_size         = \n| leader            = Ard Chomhairle<br/>(National Executive)\n| chairman          = Martin McMonagle\n| leader2_title     = Founder\n| leader2_name      = [[Seamus Costello]] and others\n| secretary_general =\n| leader1_title     = Deputy leader\n| leader1_name      =\n| foundation        = {{start date|1974|12|8|df=y}}\n| dissolution       =\n| headquarters      = Costello House,<br />392b [[Falls Road, Belfast|Falls Road]],<br />[[Belfast]], BT12 6DH,<br />[[County Antrim]],<br />[[Northern Ireland]]\n| ideology          = [[Irish republicanism]]<br/>[[Socialism]]<br/>[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://irishrepublicanmarxisthistoryproject.wordpress.com/2016/12/14/irsp-speeches-and-writings-by-jim-lane-1983-1987/ |title=IRSP Speeches and Writings by Jim Lane, 1983-1987. |quote= embracing the teachings of Marx, Engels and Lenin, we are placing ourselves in line with the most advanced thought of our age and, as a consequence, are in line with the revolutionary tradition passed on by James Connolly}}</ref><br />[[Euroscepticism]]<br />[[Left-wing nationalism]]<br />[[Left-wing populism]]<br />[[Internationalism (politics)|Internationalism]]<br />[[Anti-globalization movement|Anti-globalisation]]<ref name= RSP/>\n| position          = [[Far-left politics|Far-left]]\n| newspaper         = ''[[The Starry Plough (magazine)|The Starry Plough]]''<br />''Worker's Republic'' (Belfast)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/news/?p=2390 |title='Workers\u2019 Republic\u2019. Newsletter, Belfast IRSP. Winter 2017 |publisher=Republican Socialist News |website=irsp.ie}}</ref>\n| colours           = Red, yellow and white\n| youth_wing        = [[Republican Socialist Youth Movement]]\n| wing1_title       = Paramilitary wing\n| wing1             = [[Irish National Liberation Army]]<br />(1974\u2013Present)\n| website           = [http://www.irsp.ie/ www.irsp.ie/]\n| colorcode         = #e80504\n| international     = [[Irish Republican Socialist Movement]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n}}\nThe '''Irish Republican Socialist Party''' or '''IRSP''' ({{lang-ga|P\u00e1irt\u00ed Poblachtach S\u00f3isialach na h\u00c9ireann}}) is a [[Irish republicanism|republican]] socialist party active in [[Ireland]]. It is often referred to as the \"political wing\" of the [[Irish National Liberation Army]] (INLA) paramilitary group<ref name=beeb>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/events/northern_ireland/latest_news/156435.stm UK and Ireland welcome INLA ceasefire]\", BBC News, 23 August 1998</ref>  and claims the legacy of socialist revolutionary [[James Connolly]], who founded the [[Irish Socialist Republican Party]] in 1896 and was executed after the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916.\n\n==History==\n===Early years===\n[[Image:StarryPlough.svg|200px|thumb|left|The [[Starry Plough (flag)|Starry Plough]] is often used as a symbol to represent the Irish Republican Socialist Party, its armed wing the [[Irish National Liberation Army]], and other [[Irish Republican Socialist Movement|Irish republican socialist]] groups]]\n\nThe Irish Republican Socialist Party was founded at a meeting on 8 December 1974 in the Spa Hotel in [[Lucan, Dublin|Lucan]], near [[Dublin]], by former members of [[Workers' Party of Ireland|Official Sinn F\u00e9in]], headed by [[Seamus Costello]]. According to the IRSP, 80 people were in attendance.<ref name=PD/> A paramilitary wing, the [[Irish National Liberation Army]] (INLA), was founded the same day, although its existence was intended to be kept hidden until such a time that the INLA could operate effectively. Costello was elected as the party's first chairperson and the Army's first chief of staff. Together, the IRSP and the INLA referred to themselves as the Irish Republican Socialist Movement (IRSM).{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nFormer [[Unity (Northern Ireland)|Unity]] MP for [[Mid Ulster (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid-Ulster]] [[Bernadette Devlin McAliskey|Bernadette McAliskey]] served on the executive of the IRSP.<ref>[[Tim Pat Coogan|Coogan, Tim Pat]]. ''The IRA'';  St. Martin's Griffin; revised & updated edition : 5 January 2002; {{ISBN|978-0312294168}}</ref> She resigned following the failure of a motion to be passed which would have brought the INLA under the control of the IRSP [[Ardfheis#Ard Chomhairle|''Ard Comhairle'']] (executive committee). This led to the resignation of half the ''Ard Comhairle'', which weakened the party. [[Tony Gregory]], a future Dublin [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]], was also a member for a short time.<ref>[http://www.irishleftreview.org/2009/01/06/tonygregory-1947-2009/ Tony Gregory: 1947 \u2013 2009]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Irish Left Review'', 6 January 2009.</ref> Its poor showing in the [[1977 Irish general election]], and the assassination of Seamus Costello, weakened the organisation.\n\nCostello had been expelled from the [[Official Irish Republican Army]] (OIRA) following a [[court-martial]], and from Official Sinn F\u00e9in on the same basis. Along with other activists, he was dissatisfied with the group's tactics and policies, especially on the issues surrounding the 1972 OIRA ceasefire and his growing belief that the emerging conflict was sectarian.\n\n===Clashes with other republicans and the British===\nIn 1977, Costello was shot dead in his car by a man armed with a shotgun. His supporters blamed the Official IRA for the killing.\n\nFollowing meetings between the INLA and OIRA leadership in Dublin, a truce was eventually reached, but in one of the first of the INLA's armed operations, [[Billy McMillen]], commanding officer of the OIRA Belfast Battalion, was murdered by [[Gerard Steenson]]. In the following years, the IRSP and INLA saw many of their members, including leading members [[Miriam Daly]], [[Ronnie Bunting]] and Noel Little, killed in attacks from British state forces and [[Ulster loyalism|loyalist]] paramilitaries.\n\nThree members of the INLA died in the [[1981 Irish hunger strike]] in [[Her Majesty's Prison Service|HM Prison]] [[Maze (HM Prison)|Maze]], also known as Long Kesh: [[Patsy O'Hara]], [[Kevin Lynch (hunger striker)|Kevin Lynch]], and [[Michael Devine (hunger striker)|Michael Devine]].\n\nIn 1987, the INLA and its political wing, the IRSP came under attack from the [[Irish People's Liberation Organisation]] (IPLO), an organisation founded by people who had resigned or been expelled from the INLA. The IPLO's initial aim was to destroy the IRSM and replace it with their organisation. Five members of the INLA and IRSP were killed by the IPLO, including leaders [[Ta Power]] and John O'Reilly. The INLA retaliated with several killings of their own. After the INLA killed the IPLO's leader, [[Gerard Steenson]], a truce was reached. Although severely damaged by the IPLO's attacks, the INLA continued to exist. The IPLO, which was heavily involved in drug dealing, was put out of existence by the Provisional IRA in a [[Night of the Long Knives (1992)|large scale operation in 1992]].\n\n===Recent history===\n\nIn the 2000s and 2010s, the IRSP has been involved in campaigns and political protests, mainly around [[Belfast]] and [[Derry]] but also in of parts of the [[Republic of Ireland]] as well.\n\nIn November 2016, after a number of raids on members of the party's homes, the IRSP issued a warning saying the PSNI were \"playing with fire\". IRSP's [[Lower Falls (District Electoral Area)|Lower Falls]] representative Michael Kelly claimed that \u201cBritish security forces risk bringing serious conflict onto the streets\u201d and said that \u201cThe Irish Republican Socialist Party has been in existence for over 40 years, in that time we have never tolerated attacks on our membership from any quarter,\u201d The comments drew criticism from [[Ulster Unionist Party|UUP]] MLA [[Doug Beattie]] and [[SDLP]] [[Alex Attwood]].<ref>[http://www.irishnews.com/news/northernirelandnews/2016/11/03/news/irsp-claims-police-playing-with-fire--767534/  IRSP warn police 'playing with fire' after series of house raids on members]</ref>\n\n==Elections==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!Election\n!First Preference Vote\n!Vote %\n!Seats\n|-\n| align=center|[[1981 Northern Ireland local elections|1981]]\n| align=center|3,654\n| align=center|0.5%\n| align=center|{{Composition bar|2|523|hex=#FF3300}}\n|-\n| align=center|[[2011 Northern Ireland local elections|2011]]\n| align=center|2,133\n| align=center|0.3%\n| align=center|{{Composition bar|0|572|hex=#FF3300}}\n|}\nIn [[1981 Northern Ireland local elections|1981]], party members Gerry Kelly and Sean Flynn won two seats on the [[Belfast City Council]] in a joint campaign with the [[People's Democracy (Ireland)|People's Democracy]] party. Neither councillor served a full term, with one going on the run after being implicated during the [[Supergrass (informer)|supergrass]] trials<ref name=PD>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/programme/PerspectivesDocument.pdf |title=Perspectives on the future of Republican Socialism in Ireland |website=irsp.ie |access-date=20 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000852/http://www.irsp.ie/programme/PerspectivesDocument.pdf |archive-date=2 February 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe IRSP put forward five candidates in Northern Ireland local elections, 2011, its first foray into electoral politics in almost 30 years. They failed to secure any seats. Candidate Paul Gallagher of [[Strabane]] missed out on a seat by just a single vote. He was originally elected but after a requested recount by the SDLP his election was overturned.<ref name=LE>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/news/?p=317 |title=IRSP Local Council Election Results |publisher=Republican Socialist News |website=irsp.ie |access-date=26 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102121242/http://www.irsp.ie/news/?p=317 |archive-date=2 November 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Mourne District Electoral Area Results\n |publisher   = [[Strabane District Council]]\n |date        = 9 May 2011\n |url         = http://www.strabanedc.com/filestore/documents/elections/Mourne_DEA_Results_2011.pdf\n |format      = pdf\n |accessdate  = 12 January 2013\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140401081832/http://www.strabanedc.com/filestore/documents/elections/Mourne_DEA_Results_2011.pdf\n |archivedate = 1 April 2014\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nThe IRSP has explained its lack of participation in elections as due to \"very limited\" resources.<ref name=LE/>\n\n==Policies and ideology==\nThe party is a staunch supporter of Irish republicanism, it believes a united Ireland can only be achieved through armed action. While being republican the party is also socialist and Marxist and supports the establishment of an [[all-Ireland]] \"[[Socialist state|Worker's republic]]\".\n\n===[[Physical force Irish republicanism]]===\nThe IRSP opposes both the [[Good Friday Agreement]] and the [[Northern Ireland Peace Process]], The party supports a 'No First Strike' policy, that is allowing people to see the perceived failure of the peace process for themselves without military actions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/Background/history/whatis.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630224345/http://www.irsp.ie/Background/history/whatis.html |archive-date=30 June 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of 11 October 2009, the INLA has ordered an end to the armed struggle,<ref name=beeb/> because unlike during the Troubles, the current political stance in Ulster allows the IRSP to contest fairly in new campaigns and local elections, as mentioned in their 2009 statement. INLA admitted to \"faults and grievous errors\" in their prosecution of the armed struggle, stating that \"innocent people were killed and injured\" and offering \"as revolutionaries\" a \"sincere and heartfelt apology\".<ref name=beeb/>\n\n===James Connolly===\nThe IRSP claim the legacy of Connolly and say their policies are of the same tradition of Connolly. The IRSP also see their own modern policies as the \"logical development in the twenty-first century of the programme established under Connolly\u2019s leadership by the Irish Socialist Republican Party\".<ref name= RSP/>\n\n===European Union===\nThe IRSP supported [[Brexit]] and supports the [[Republic of Ireland]] leaving the [[European Union]].<ref>\"[http://www.irsp.ie/news/?p=1978 IRSP reiterates call for full British, EU and US Military, Economic and Political withdrawal from Ireland at Moscow conference]\", ''Republican Socialist News'', 26 September 2015</ref>\n\n===Broad Front===\nThe IRSP supports the formation of what it calls the \"Broad Front\" which would oppose British occupation and imperialism in Ireland. Policies{{Clarify|reason=these look more like demands|date=October 2019}} would include:\n\n* UK must denounce all claims of sovereignty over the island\n* Withdrawal of all UK troops and release of all republican prisoners\n* UK to compensate the Irish people for the exploitation that has occurred throughout Ireland.<ref name = RSP>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irsp.ie/programme/RepublicanSocialistProgramme.pdf|title=Republican Socialist Programme for Ireland|last=|first=|date=|url-status=dead|website=irsp.ie|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000724/http://www.irsp.ie/programme/RepublicanSocialistProgramme.pdf|archive-date=2 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Policing===\nThe IRSP is in favour of an All-Ireland, democratically controlled, unarmed police force.<ref name= RSP/>\n\n===[[Abstentionism]]===\nThe IRSP are not abstentionist in principle but they would support abstentionism in certain situations for tactical reasons.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/Background/costello/interview.html |title=Interview with S\u00e9amus Costello |website=irsp.ie |quote=When we say that we are not an abstentionist party, what we mean by this is that we are not a party, in principle, committed to abstention. But there are circumstances and conditions under which is might be desirable to abstain and if we felt that it was tactically desirable at any particular point in time, in either the North or the South to abstain from Parliament, then we would do so. That would depend, however, on the circumstances existing at that particular point of time. If a situation existed, for instance, where there was a possibility of large scale dissatisfaction, on the part of the people, with either the 26 County parliament or the 6 County parliament then abstention, on our part would be a legitimate tactic. We are not, however, abstentionist in principle}}</ref>\n\n===Housing===\nIRSP believes that the right to a home is a fundamental human right and that the state has a responsibility to deal with homelessness.<ref name=PD/>\n\n===Abortion===\nThe party's policy on abortion is that it should be legalised, available on demand and free of charge.<ref name=PD/>\n\n==Membership==\nParty members are often referred to as the \"Irps\" (pronounced \"Erps\"). In the late 1970s, [[Divis Flats]] in west [[Belfast]] became colloquially known as \"the planet of the Irps\" (a reference to the IRSP and the film ''[[Planet of the Apes (1968 film)|Planet of the Apes]]'').<ref>\"[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/islandpublications/hall09-ip92.pdf Preventing a return to conflict: A discussion by ex-combatants],\" compiled by Michael Hall, Island Publications, August 2009</ref><ref>''The Lost Revolution: The Story of the Official IRA and the Workers' Party'', Brian Hanley and Scott Millar, Penguin Books, {{ISBN|1-84488-120-2}} p. 290</ref>\n\n==Representation==\nThe party is represented in North America by the [[Irish Republican Socialist Committees of North America]].\n\n==List of secretaries==\n*Kevin Morley<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/Statements/irsp_cur.html |title=IRSP OPPOSE SECOND REFERENDUM: BUT URGE A NO VOTE |publisher=irsp.ie |access-date=30 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519003450/http://www.irsp.ie/Statements/irsp_cur.html |archive-date=19 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*John Martin<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irsp.ie/Background/theory/repsocialism.html|title=IRSP Political Secretary John Martin's presentation on republican socialism to the IRSP's ideological conference 29\u201330 May 99|publisher=irsp.ie|access-date=30 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326213948/http://www.irsp.ie/Background/theory/repsocialism.html|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*Mick Plunkett<ref name= PD/>\n\n==Milestones in the IRSP's history==\n*1975: At the IRSP's inaugural convention, it becomes the first political party in Ireland to support the legalisation of abortion and equal rights for [[gays and lesbians]].\n*1981: The IRSP wins two seats on the [[Belfast City Council]], and comes close to winning a third. The IRSP runs two candidates, [[Kevin Lynch (hunger striker)|Kevin Lynch]] and Tony O'Hara, in the Irish parliamentary election as Independent [[Anti H-Block]] candidates. Neither candidate wins, but Lynch comes within 300 votes of winning a seat, while O'Hara garnered a respectable number of votes.\n*1982: Party member [[Brigid Makowski]] wins a seat on the [[Shannon Town Commission]].<ref>[http://www.shannon.ie/stcmeetings/stc_elections.html Shannon Town Commission Local Elections shannon.ie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623053615/http://www.shannon.ie/stcmeetings/stc_elections.html |date=23 June 2008 }}</ref>\n*1984: At the IRSP's convention, two motions are put forward and voted in:{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n#That the IRSP stands in the tradition of [[Marx]], [[Engels]], and [[James Connolly]]. (Drafted by party member [[John Gilligan (Mayor of Limerick)|John Gilligan]] <nowiki>[</nowiki>now an elected Independent member of [[Limerick City Council]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> and put forward by the party's [[Limerick]] branch).\n#That the IRSP stands in the tradition of Marx, Engels, and [[Lenin]]. (Drafted by the party's chairperson, [[Jim Lane (Irish republican)|Jim Lane]], and put forward by the party's [[Cork (city)|Cork]] city branch.)\nBoth motions are passed and combined into a single statement: that the IRSP stands in the tradition of Marx, Engels, Lenin, and Connolly.\n*2000: The IRSP passes a new ideological motion at its convention, which affirms that the IRSP is a \"revolutionary Marxist organisation.\"{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jim Lane (Irish republican)|Jim Lane]]\n* [[Sallins Train Robbery]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bernard, Margie. ''Daughter of Derry: The Story of Brigid Sheils Makowski''; iUniverse; 20 January 2009; {{ISBN|978-1440120008}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irsp.ie/ Irish Republican Socialist Party]'s official website\n* [http://irsm.org/history/historyofirsp.html Brief history of the IRSP]\n* [http://dublinirsp.blogspot.ie/ IRSP Dublin branch blog]\n\n{{INLA/IRSP}}\n{{OIRA/WP}}\n{{Political parties in Ireland}}\n{{Marxism\u2013Leninism}}\n\n[[Category:Irish Republican Socialist Party| ]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics in Ireland]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|Socialist party active in Ireland}}\n{{For|the early 20th-century party founded by [[James Connolly]]|Irish Socialist Republican Party}}\n{{EngvarB|date=October 2013}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=October 2019}}\n{{Primary sources|date=April 2008}}\n{{Infobox political party\n| country           = the Republic of Ireland\n| country2          = Northern Ireland\n| name              = Irish Republican Socialist Party\n| native_name       = P\u00e1irt\u00ed Poblachtach S\u00f3isalach na h-\u00c9ireann\n| logo              = IRSP logo 2018.png\n| logo_size         = \n| leader            = Ard Chomhairle<br/>(National Executive)\n| chairman          = Martin McMonagle\n| leader2_title     = Founder\n| leader2_name      = [[Seamus Costello]] and others\n| secretary_general =\n| leader1_title     = Deputy leader\n| leader1_name      =\n| foundation        = {{start date|1974|12|8|df=y}}\n| dissolution       =\n| headquarters      = Costello House,<br />392b [[Falls Road, Belfast|Falls Road]],<br />[[Belfast]], BT12 6DH,<br />[[County Antrim]],<br />[[Northern Ireland]]\n| ideology          = [[Irish republicanism]]<br/>[[Socialism]]<br/>[[Marxism\u2013Leninism]]<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://irishrepublicanmarxisthistoryproject.wordpress.com/2016/12/14/irsp-speeches-and-writings-by-jim-lane-1983-1987/ |title=IRSP Speeches and Writings by Jim Lane, 1983-1987. |quote= embracing the teachings of Marx, Engels and Lenin, we are placing ourselves in line with the most advanced thought of our age and, as a consequence, are in line with the revolutionary tradition passed on by James Connolly}}</ref><br />[[Euroscepticism]]<br />[[Left-wing nationalism]]<br />[[Left-wing populism]]<br />[[Internationalism (politics)|Internationalism]]<br />[[Anti-globalization movement|Anti-globalisation]]<ref name= RSP/>\n| position          = [[Far-left politics|Far-left]]\n| newspaper         = ''[[The Starry Plough (magazine)|The Starry Plough]]''<br />''Worker's Republic'' (Belfast)<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/news/?p=2390 |title='Workers\u2019 Republic\u2019. Newsletter, Belfast IRSP. Winter 2017 |publisher=Republican Socialist News |website=irsp.ie}}</ref>\n| colours           = Red, yellow and white\n| youth_wing        = [[Republican Socialist Youth Movement]]\n| wing1_title       = Paramilitary wing\n| wing1             = [[Irish National Liberation Army]]<br />(1974\u2013Present)\n| website           = [http://www.irsp.ie/ www.irsp.ie/]\n| colorcode         = #e80504\n| international     = [[Irish Republican Socialist Movement]]{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n}}\nThe '''Irish Republican Socialist Party''' or '''IRSP''' ({{lang-ga|P\u00e1irt\u00ed Poblachtach S\u00f3isialach na h\u00c9ireann}}) is a [[Irish republicanism|republican]] socialist party active in [[Ireland]]. It is often referred to as the \"political wing\" of the [[Irish National Liberation Army]] (INLA) paramilitary group.<ref name=beeb>\"[http://news.bbc.co.uk/2/hi/events/northern_ireland/latest_news/156435.stm UK and Ireland welcome INLA ceasefire]\", BBC News, 23 August 1998</ref>  and claims the legacy of socialist revolutionary [[James Connolly]], who founded the [[Irish Socialist Republican Party]] in 1896 and was executed after the [[Easter Rising]] of 1916.\n\n==History==\n===Early years===\n[[Image:StarryPlough.svg|200px|thumb|left|The [[Starry Plough (flag)|Starry Plough]] is often used as a symbol to represent the Irish Republican Socialist Party, its armed wing the [[Irish National Liberation Army]], and other [[Irish Republican Socialist Movement|Irish republican socialist]] groups]]\n\nThe Irish Republican Socialist Party was founded at a meeting on 8 December 1974 in the Spa Hotel in [[Lucan, Dublin|Lucan]], near [[Dublin]], by former members of [[Workers' Party of Ireland|Official Sinn F\u00e9in]], headed by [[Seamus Costello]]. According to the IRSP, 80 people were in attendance.<ref name=PD/> A paramilitary wing, the [[Irish National Liberation Army]] (INLA), was founded the same day, although its existence was intended to be kept hidden until such a time that the INLA could operate effectively. Costello was elected as the party's first chairperson and the Army's first chief of staff. Together, the IRSP and the INLA referred to themselves as the Irish Republican Socialist Movement (IRSM).{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\nFormer [[Unity (Northern Ireland)|Unity]] MP for [[Mid Ulster (UK Parliament constituency)|Mid-Ulster]] [[Bernadette Devlin McAliskey|Bernadette McAliskey]] served on the executive of the IRSP.<ref>[[Tim Pat Coogan|Coogan, Tim Pat]]. ''The IRA'';  St. Martin's Griffin; revised & updated edition : 5 January 2002; {{ISBN|978-0312294168}}</ref> She resigned following the failure of a motion to be passed which would have brought the INLA under the control of the IRSP [[Ardfheis#Ard Chomhairle|''Ard Comhairle'']] (executive committee). This led to the resignation of half the ''Ard Comhairle'', which weakened the party. [[Tony Gregory]], a future Dublin [[Teachta D\u00e1la|TD]], was also a member for a short time.<ref>[http://www.irishleftreview.org/2009/01/06/tonygregory-1947-2009/ Tony Gregory: 1947 \u2013 2009]{{Dead link|date=January 2020 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}, ''Irish Left Review'', 6 January 2009.</ref> Its poor showing in the [[1977 Irish general election]], and the assassination of Seamus Costello, weakened the organisation.\n\nCostello had been expelled from the [[Official Irish Republican Army]] (OIRA) following a [[court-martial]], and from Official Sinn F\u00e9in on the same basis. Along with other activists, he was dissatisfied with the group's tactics and policies, especially on the issues surrounding the 1972 OIRA ceasefire and his growing belief that the emerging conflict was sectarian.\n\n===Clashes with other republicans and the British===\nIn 1977, Costello was shot dead in his car by a man armed with a shotgun. His supporters blamed the Official IRA for the killing.\n\nFollowing meetings between the INLA and OIRA leadership in Dublin, a truce was eventually reached, but in one of the first of the INLA's armed operations, [[Billy McMillen]], commanding officer of the OIRA Belfast Battalion, was murdered by [[Gerard Steenson]]. In the following years, the IRSP and INLA saw many of their members, including leading members [[Miriam Daly]], [[Ronnie Bunting]] and Noel Little, killed in attacks from British state forces and [[Ulster loyalism|loyalist]] paramilitaries.\n\nThree members of the INLA died in the [[1981 Irish hunger strike]] in [[Her Majesty's Prison Service|HM Prison]] [[Maze (HM Prison)|Maze]], also known as Long Kesh: [[Patsy O'Hara]], [[Kevin Lynch (hunger striker)|Kevin Lynch]], and [[Michael Devine (hunger striker)|Michael Devine]].\n\nIn 1987, the INLA and its political wing, the IRSP came under attack from the [[Irish People's Liberation Organisation]] (IPLO), an organisation founded by people who had resigned or been expelled from the INLA. The IPLO's initial aim was to destroy the IRSM and replace it with their organisation. Five members of the INLA and IRSP were killed by the IPLO, including leaders [[Ta Power]] and John O'Reilly. The INLA retaliated with several killings of their own. After the INLA killed the IPLO's leader, [[Gerard Steenson]], a truce was reached. Although severely damaged by the IPLO's attacks, the INLA continued to exist. The IPLO, which was heavily involved in drug dealing, was put out of existence by the Provisional IRA in a [[Night of the Long Knives (1992)|large scale operation in 1992]].\n\n===Recent history===\n\nIn the 2000s and 2010s, the IRSP has been involved in campaigns and political protests, mainly around [[Belfast]] and [[Derry]] but also in of parts of the [[Republic of Ireland]] as well.\n\nIn November 2016, after a number of raids on members of the party's homes, the IRSP issued a warning saying the PSNI were \"playing with fire\". IRSP's [[Lower Falls (District Electoral Area)|Lower Falls]] representative Michael Kelly claimed that \u201cBritish security forces risk bringing serious conflict onto the streets\u201d and said that \u201cThe Irish Republican Socialist Party has been in existence for over 40 years, in that time we have never tolerated attacks on our membership from any quarter,\u201d The comments drew criticism from [[Ulster Unionist Party|UUP]] MLA [[Doug Beattie]] and [[SDLP]] [[Alex Attwood]].<ref>[http://www.irishnews.com/news/northernirelandnews/2016/11/03/news/irsp-claims-police-playing-with-fire--767534/  IRSP warn police 'playing with fire' after series of house raids on members]</ref>\n\n==Elections==\n{|class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"font-size:95%\"\n|-\n!Election\n!First Preference Vote\n!Vote %\n!Seats\n|-\n| align=center|[[1981 Northern Ireland local elections|1981]]\n| align=center|3,654\n| align=center|0.5%\n| align=center|{{Composition bar|2|523|hex=#FF3300}}\n|-\n| align=center|[[2011 Northern Ireland local elections|2011]]\n| align=center|2,133\n| align=center|0.3%\n| align=center|{{Composition bar|0|572|hex=#FF3300}}\n|}\nIn [[1981 Northern Ireland local elections|1981]], party members Gerry Kelly and Sean Flynn won two seats on the [[Belfast City Council]] in a joint campaign with the [[People's Democracy (Ireland)|People's Democracy]] party. Neither councillor served a full term, with one going on the run after being implicated during the [[Supergrass (informer)|supergrass]] trials<ref name=PD>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/programme/PerspectivesDocument.pdf |title=Perspectives on the future of Republican Socialism in Ireland |website=irsp.ie |access-date=20 January 2017 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000852/http://www.irsp.ie/programme/PerspectivesDocument.pdf |archive-date=2 February 2017 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nThe IRSP put forward five candidates in Northern Ireland local elections, 2011, its first foray into electoral politics in almost 30 years. They failed to secure any seats. Candidate Paul Gallagher of [[Strabane]] missed out on a seat by just a single vote. He was originally elected but after a requested recount by the SDLP his election was overturned.<ref name=LE>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/news/?p=317 |title=IRSP Local Council Election Results |publisher=Republican Socialist News |website=irsp.ie |access-date=26 June 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20111102121242/http://www.irsp.ie/news/?p=317 |archive-date=2 November 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref><ref>{{cite web\n |title       = Mourne District Electoral Area Results\n |publisher   = [[Strabane District Council]]\n |date        = 9 May 2011\n |url         = http://www.strabanedc.com/filestore/documents/elections/Mourne_DEA_Results_2011.pdf\n |format      = pdf\n |accessdate  = 12 January 2013\n |archiveurl  = https://web.archive.org/web/20140401081832/http://www.strabanedc.com/filestore/documents/elections/Mourne_DEA_Results_2011.pdf\n |archivedate = 1 April 2014\n |url-status     = dead\n}}</ref>\n\nThe IRSP has explained its lack of participation in elections as due to \"very limited\" resources.<ref name=LE/>\n\n==Policies and ideology==\nThe party is a staunch supporter of Irish republicanism, it believes a united Ireland can only be achieved through armed action. While being republican the party is also socialist and Marxist and supports the establishment of an [[all-Ireland]] \"[[Socialist state|Worker's republic]]\".\n\n===[[Physical force Irish republicanism]]===\nThe IRSP opposes both the [[Good Friday Agreement]] and the [[Northern Ireland Peace Process]], The party supports a 'No First Strike' policy, that is allowing people to see the perceived failure of the peace process for themselves without military actions.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/Background/history/whatis.html |title=Archived copy |access-date=9 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110630224345/http://www.irsp.ie/Background/history/whatis.html |archive-date=30 June 2011 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref>\n\nAs of 11 October 2009, the INLA has ordered an end to the armed struggle,<ref name=beeb/> because unlike during the Troubles, the current political stance in Ulster allows the IRSP to contest fairly in new campaigns and local elections, as mentioned in their 2009 statement. INLA admitted to \"faults and grievous errors\" in their prosecution of the armed struggle, stating that \"innocent people were killed and injured\" and offering \"as revolutionaries\" a \"sincere and heartfelt apology\".<ref name=beeb/>\n\n===James Connolly===\nThe IRSP claim the legacy of Connolly and say their policies are of the same tradition of Connolly. The IRSP also see their own modern policies as the \"logical development in the twenty-first century of the programme established under Connolly\u2019s leadership by the Irish Socialist Republican Party\".<ref name= RSP/>\n\n===European Union===\nThe IRSP supported [[Brexit]] and supports the [[Republic of Ireland]] leaving the [[European Union]].<ref>\"[http://www.irsp.ie/news/?p=1978 IRSP reiterates call for full British, EU and US Military, Economic and Political withdrawal from Ireland at Moscow conference]\", ''Republican Socialist News'', 26 September 2015</ref>\n\n===Broad Front===\nThe IRSP supports the formation of what it calls the \"Broad Front\" which would oppose British occupation and imperialism in Ireland. Policies{{Clarify|reason=these look more like demands|date=October 2019}} would include:\n\n* UK must denounce all claims of sovereignty over the island\n* Withdrawal of all UK troops and release of all republican prisoners\n* UK to compensate the Irish people for the exploitation that has occurred throughout Ireland.<ref name = RSP>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irsp.ie/programme/RepublicanSocialistProgramme.pdf|title=Republican Socialist Programme for Ireland|last=|first=|date=|url-status=dead|website=irsp.ie|publisher=|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170202000724/http://www.irsp.ie/programme/RepublicanSocialistProgramme.pdf|archive-date=2 February 2017}}</ref>\n\n===Policing===\nThe IRSP is in favour of an All-Ireland, democratically controlled, unarmed police force.<ref name= RSP/>\n\n===[[Abstentionism]]===\nThe IRSP are not abstentionist in principle but they would support abstentionism in certain situations for tactical reasons.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/Background/costello/interview.html |title=Interview with S\u00e9amus Costello |website=irsp.ie |quote=When we say that we are not an abstentionist party, what we mean by this is that we are not a party, in principle, committed to abstention. But there are circumstances and conditions under which is might be desirable to abstain and if we felt that it was tactically desirable at any particular point in time, in either the North or the South to abstain from Parliament, then we would do so. That would depend, however, on the circumstances existing at that particular point of time. If a situation existed, for instance, where there was a possibility of large scale dissatisfaction, on the part of the people, with either the 26 County parliament or the 6 County parliament then abstention, on our part would be a legitimate tactic. We are not, however, abstentionist in principle}}</ref>\n\n===Housing===\nIRSP believes that the right to a home is a fundamental human right and that the state has a responsibility to deal with homelessness.<ref name=PD/>\n\n===Abortion===\nThe party's policy on abortion is that it should be legalised, available on demand and free of charge.<ref name=PD/>\n\n==Membership==\nParty members are often referred to as the \"Irps\" (pronounced \"Erps\"). In the late 1970s, [[Divis Flats]] in west [[Belfast]] became colloquially known as \"the planet of the Irps\" (a reference to the IRSP and the film ''[[Planet of the Apes (1968 film)|Planet of the Apes]]'').<ref>\"[http://cain.ulst.ac.uk/islandpublications/hall09-ip92.pdf Preventing a return to conflict: A discussion by ex-combatants],\" compiled by Michael Hall, Island Publications, August 2009</ref><ref>''The Lost Revolution: The Story of the Official IRA and the Workers' Party'', Brian Hanley and Scott Millar, Penguin Books, {{ISBN|1-84488-120-2}} p. 290</ref>\n\n==Representation==\nThe party is represented in North America by the [[Irish Republican Socialist Committees of North America]].\n\n==List of secretaries==\n*Kevin Morley<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.irsp.ie/Statements/irsp_cur.html |title=IRSP OPPOSE SECOND REFERENDUM: BUT URGE A NO VOTE |publisher=irsp.ie |access-date=30 December 2016 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150519003450/http://www.irsp.ie/Statements/irsp_cur.html |archive-date=19 May 2015 |url-status=dead }}</ref>\n*John Martin<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.irsp.ie/Background/theory/repsocialism.html|title=IRSP Political Secretary John Martin's presentation on republican socialism to the IRSP's ideological conference 29\u201330 May 99|publisher=irsp.ie|access-date=30 December 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150326213948/http://www.irsp.ie/Background/theory/repsocialism.html|archive-date=26 March 2015|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n*Mick Plunkett<ref name= PD/>\n\n==Milestones in the IRSP's history==\n*1975: At the IRSP's inaugural convention, it becomes the first political party in Ireland to support the legalisation of abortion and equal rights for [[gays and lesbians]].\n*1981: The IRSP wins two seats on the [[Belfast City Council]], and comes close to winning a third. The IRSP runs two candidates, [[Kevin Lynch (hunger striker)|Kevin Lynch]] and Tony O'Hara, in the Irish parliamentary election as Independent [[Anti H-Block]] candidates. Neither candidate wins, but Lynch comes within 300 votes of winning a seat, while O'Hara garnered a respectable number of votes.\n*1982: Party member [[Brigid Makowski]] wins a seat on the [[Shannon Town Commission]].<ref>[http://www.shannon.ie/stcmeetings/stc_elections.html Shannon Town Commission Local Elections shannon.ie] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20080623053615/http://www.shannon.ie/stcmeetings/stc_elections.html |date=23 June 2008 }}</ref>\n*1984: At the IRSP's convention, two motions are put forward and voted in:{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n#That the IRSP stands in the tradition of [[Marx]], [[Engels]], and [[James Connolly]]. (Drafted by party member [[John Gilligan (Mayor of Limerick)|John Gilligan]] <nowiki>[</nowiki>now an elected Independent member of [[Limerick City Council]]<nowiki>]</nowiki> and put forward by the party's [[Limerick]] branch).\n#That the IRSP stands in the tradition of Marx, Engels, and [[Lenin]]. (Drafted by the party's chairperson, [[Jim Lane (Irish republican)|Jim Lane]], and put forward by the party's [[Cork (city)|Cork]] city branch.)\nBoth motions are passed and combined into a single statement: that the IRSP stands in the tradition of Marx, Engels, Lenin, and Connolly.\n*2000: The IRSP passes a new ideological motion at its convention, which affirms that the IRSP is a \"revolutionary Marxist organisation.\"{{Citation needed|date=January 2017}}\n\n==See also==\n* [[Jim Lane (Irish republican)|Jim Lane]]\n* [[Sallins Train Robbery]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==Further reading==\n* Bernard, Margie. ''Daughter of Derry: The Story of Brigid Sheils Makowski''; iUniverse; 20 January 2009; {{ISBN|978-1440120008}}\n\n==External links==\n* [http://www.irsp.ie/ Irish Republican Socialist Party]'s official website\n* [http://irsm.org/history/historyofirsp.html Brief history of the IRSP]\n* [http://dublinirsp.blogspot.ie/ IRSP Dublin branch blog]\n\n{{INLA/IRSP}}\n{{OIRA/WP}}\n{{Political parties in Ireland}}\n{{Marxism\u2013Leninism}}\n\n[[Category:Irish Republican Socialist Party| ]]\n[[Category:Far-left politics in Ireland]]\n", "name_user": "Jaydavidmartin", "label": "safe", "comment": "removed erroneous comma", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Irish_Republican_Socialist_Party"}
{"title_page": "Timeline of South Asian and diasporic LGBT history", "text_new": "{{short description|LGBT Timeline South Asia}}\n<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the issue is settled -->\n<!-- For administrator use only: {{Old AfD multi|page=Timeline of global South Asian LGBT and queer history|date=29 July 2014|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n\nThis is a timeline of notable events in the history of non-heterosexual conforming [[South Asia|people of South Asian ancestry]], who may identify as [[LGBT]]IQGNC ([[lesbian]], [[gay]], [[Bisexuality|bisexual]], [[transgender]], [[intersex]], queer, [[third gender]], [[Gender variance|gender nonconforming]]), [[men who have sex with men]], or related culturally-specific identities<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Suleiman|first1=Gee Ameena|title=Non-'hijra' transgenders struggle for identity|journal=DNA|date=18 September 2011|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report-non-hijra-transgenders-struggle-for-identity-1588421|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> such as [[Hijra (South Asia)|Hijra]], Aravani, Thirunangaigal, Khwajasara, [[Kothi (gender)|Kothi]], Thirunambigal, [[LGBT topics and Hinduism#The Jogappa|Jogappa]], Jogatha, or Shiva Shakti.<ref>[http://roundtableindia.co.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7185 Round Table India article: Letter by trans men to the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment]</ref><ref>[http://iglhrc.org/sites/default/files/PakistanCC.pdf \"Violence: Through the Lens of Lesbians, Bisexual Women, and Trans People in Asia\"] - Pakistan. IGLHRC, 2014.</ref> The recorded history traces back at least two millennia.\n\nThis timeline includes events both in South Asia and in the global South Asian diaspora, as the histories are deeply linked.<ref name=\"desiq-2006-timeline\">{{cite web|last1=Roy|first1=Sandip|title=Desi Queer Datebook|url=http://archive.berkeleysouthasian.org/lgbt.html|website=Berkeley South Asian History Archive|accessdate=17 July 2014|date=2006}}</ref><ref name=\"desiq-2013-timeline\">{{cite web|title=DesiQ 2013 History Timeline|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/anirvan/galleries/72157645335742347/|website=Flickr|publisher=DesiQ|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> South Asia includes the modern day nations of [[Bangladesh]], [[Bhutan]], [[India]], [[Maldives]], [[Nepal]], [[Pakistan]], [[Sri Lanka]]; in some references, the South Asian subcontinent will also include [[Afghanistan]], [[Burma]] (Myanmar), and [[Tibet]]. The South Asian diaspora includes, but is not limited to South Asian LGBTQ communities in the [[United States]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[Australia]], [[Caribbean]] Islands, [[Southeast Asia]], and elsewhere.\n\n==Early history==\n\n'''400 BCE - 200 BCE'''\n* [[V\u0101tsy\u0101yana|Vatsyayana]]'s ''[[Kama Sutra|The Kama Sutra]]'' devotes an entire chapter to homosexuality with explicit detailed instructions on how to perform homosexual acts.<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\">{{cite web|author1=New England Publishing Associates|title=GLBTQ Encyclopedia: South Asian Literatures: Diaspora|url=http://www.glbtq.com/literature/south_asian_lit.html|website=glbtq: an encyclopedia of gay, lesbian, bisexual, transgender & queer culture|accessdate=22 June 2014|year=2002}}</ref>\n\n'''3rd century BC to c. 4th century AD'''\n* [[Sangam literature|Tamil Sangam literature]] refers to relationships between two men and explores the lives of [[trans women]] in the [[Aravani|Aravan]] cult in [[Koovagam]] village in [[Tamil Nadu]].<ref name=\"thehindu.com\">{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/no-more-under-siege/article5247859.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=A. | last=Shrikumar | title=No more under siege | date=2013-10-18}}</ref>\n\n'''1015'''\n* Sultan [[Mahmud of Ghazni|Mahmud]] of [[Ghazni]], who was the first [[Muslim]] ruler of the Indian subcontinent, has a non-sexual close friendship with his slave [[Malik Ayaz]]. This relationship has become an Islamic legend and Mahmud later appointed Malik Ayaz as the sultan of [[Lahore]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jama|first1=Afdhere|title=5 Ways Pakistan Has Been Gay Friendly|url=http://islamandhomosexuality.com/5-ways-pakistan-gay-friendly/|website=LGBT Muslims: Information on Sexual Diversity in the Muslim community|accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Encyclopedia of World Biography|url=http://biography.yourdictionary.com/mahmud-of-ghazni|website=Your Dictionary Resource|publisher=The Gale Group|accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''~1529'''\n* Emperor [[Babur]]'s memoirs, the ''[[Baburnama]],'' include a recollection of his erotic love for a teenage boy.<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\" />\n\n'''1538'''\n* [[Shah Hussain]], a Punjabi Sufi poet regarded as a saint, was described as being close relationship with a Brahmin boy called \"Madho\" or \"Madho Lal\". They are often referred to as a single person with the composite name \"Madho Lal Hussain\". But no mention of sexual relations or homosexual tendencies are made.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mohan|first1=Lal|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature, Vol. 5|date=2006|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-1221-3}}</ref>\n\n'''1740s'''\n* [[Dargah Quli Khan]]'s personal diary ''Muraqqa-e-Delhi: The Mughal Capital in Muhammad Shah's Time'' \"briefly documents his foray into the pederastic circles of Delhi.\"<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Pur\u0101n\u012b Dihl\u012b ke \u1e25\u0101l\u0101t : \u0101j se do sau baras pehle N\u0101dir Sh\u0101h\u012b qatal-i \u02bb\u0101m ke vaqt ... /|url = http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n88176437/|website = www.worldcat.org|accessdate = 2015-08-08}}</ref>\n\n'''1750-1830'''\n* Emergence of Rekhti chapti-namahs, or female same-sex narratives, in [[Urdu]] poetry.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://iaws.org/wp-content/themes/pdf/newsletters/NLC042-2007.pdf|title = Of Begums and Tawaifs|date = |accessdate = |website = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n'''1861'''\n* Anti-sodomy section of [[Offences against the Person Act 1861]] imposed on entire British Empire, that says \"Whosoever shall be convicted of the abominable Crime of Buggery, committed either with Mankind or with any Animal, shall be liable, at the Discretion of the Court, to be kept in Penal Servitude for Life or for any Term not less than Ten Years.\" This section is credited with giving birth to the controversial [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1861/100/pdfs/ukpga_18610100_en.pdf|title = An Act to consolidate and amend the Statute Law of England and Ireland relating to Offences Against the Person.|date = |accessdate = |website = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n'''1871'''\n* [[Hijra (South Asia)|Hijras]] labeled a \"criminal tribe\" under the [[Criminal Tribes Act|Criminal Tribes Act, 1871]], meaning they could be arrested as criminals anywhere in British India.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gayatri Reddy|title=With Respect to Sex: Negotiating Hijra Identity in South India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SyqTnL9jTFoC&pg=PA26|date=15 May 2010|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-70754-9|pages=26\u2013}}</ref>\n'''1897'''\n* [[Criminal Tribes Act|Criminal Tribes Act of 1871]] amended, with the subtitle \"An Act for the Registration of Criminal Tribes and Eunuchs,\" ordering that \"criminal\" eunuchs \u201cdressed or ornamented like a woman in a public street\u2026be arrested without warrant\u201d and imprisoned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://planettransgender.com/transindia-who-are-the-hijras-2/|title=Transindia: Who Are the Hijras?|date=January 31, 2015|website=Planet Transgender|language=|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://paper-bird.net/2014/11/28/buggery-and-beggary/|title=Buggery and beggary, and Ferguson|last=Scott Long|date=November 28, 2014|website=a paper bird|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.countercurrents.org/gen-narrain141003.htm|title=Being A Eunuch In India|last=Narrain|first=Siddarth|date=October 14, 2003|website=Countercurrents|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/apr/16/india-third-gender-claims-place-in-law|title=Hijra: India's third gender claims its place in law|last=Khaleeli|first=Homa|date=2014-04-16|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref>\n'''1918'''\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Earliest known records of South Asian [[Men who have sex with men|MSM]] in North America, as Tara Singh and Jamil Singh are separately arrested for interracial sodomy in [[Sacramento, CA]].<ref name=\"Shah_Stranger_Intimacy\">{{cite book|last=Shah|first=Nayan|title=Stranger Intimacy: Contesting Race, Sexuality, and the Law in the North American West|year=2011|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, California|isbn=978-0-520-27087-9|pages=74\u201378|chapter=Policing Strangers and Borderlands|authorlink=Nayan Shah}}</ref>\n\n'''1922'''\n* ''Poems Written in Prison'' by [[Gopabandhu Das]], a freedom fighter and Gandhian, is published. At least two poems address male friends and co-workers, and the author describes these relationships in terms that are intense and erotically charged though not overtly sexual. These poems are sometimes included in [[Odia language]] literature textbooks.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\">[http://saathii.org/gensex/calcutta/lgbthistory.html Saathii Indian LGBT Movement page]</ref>\n\n'''1924'''\n* \"Chocolate\", a short story in Hindi written by nationalist and social reformer [[Pandey Bechan Sharma|Pandey Bechan]] Sharma (under the penname Ugra), is published in the nationalist newspaper ''Matvala''. Ugra's crusade against male-to-male sex sparks debate in Hindi newspapers and magazines, resulting in perhaps the first public debate in Hindi on homosexuality.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|journal = International Journal of Hindu Studies|volume = 14|issue = 2/3|pages = 343\u2013345|jstor = 41476628|last1 = Knight|first1 = Lisa I.|title = Reviewed work: \"Ugra,\" Chocolate and Other Writings on Male Homoeroticism, Pandey Bechan Sharma, Ruth Vanita|year = 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''1929'''\n* [[Mahatma Gandhi]] speaks out against same-sex relations in a ''[[Young India]]'' letter, in response to queries on \"unnatural vices\" in schools.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1936'''\n* Urdu poet [[Firaq Gorakhpuri]] writes an essay defending the [[Ghazal]] form of poetry that includes a defence of homosexuality, citing renowned philosophers, poets and other luminaries across the East and the West who were homosexual or had expressed homosexual desire in well-known works.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1942'''\n* [[Ismat Chugtai]]'s short story \"[[Lihaaf]]\" is published.\n'''1944'''\n* [[Ismat Chughtai]] faces obscenity trial for [[Lihaaf]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Aamer Hussein reviews Ismat Chughtai's Short Stories - Asymptote|url = http://www.asymptotejournal.com/article.php?cat=Criticism&id=63&curr_index=259&curPage=contributors|website = www.asymptotejournal.com|accessdate = 2015-07-18}}</ref>\n'''1945'''\n* [[Ismat Chughtai]] publishes her semi-autobiographical ''Tehri Lakeer'' (\"The Crooked Line\"), an Urdu novel that does not shy away from sexuality and depiction of same-sex attraction.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1962'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Rajendra Yadav]], a leading Hindi novelist, publishes his story \"Prateeksha\" (\"Waiting\") that depicts a homosexual relation between two women without censure and in detail.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1968'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Bhupen Khakhar]], a painter and writer of [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] fiction, as one of the few openly homosexual luminaries, writes an untitled story depicting bisexuality in a quotidian, lower middle-class context.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n==1970s==\n\n'''~1970s'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} ''Gay Scene'' journal published in Calcutta (only a few issues published)<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1972'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} Indian poet [[Kamala Surayya|Kamala Das]] first published her semi-fictionalized autobiography ''[[My Story (Kamala Das book)|My Story]]'' in 1972, creating a minor scandal. The autobiography revealed her extramarital heterosexual affairs and her adolescent crush on a female teacher and a brief lesbian encounter with an older student.<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiruvananthapuram/My-Story-made-Kamala-Surayya-celebrity-Malayalanadu-editor/articleshow/4604457.cms|title='My Story' made Kamala Surayya celebrity: Malayalanadu editor|last=|first=|date=Jun 1, 2009|website=Times of India|access-date=2016-08-07}}</ref>\n\n'''1974'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Malayalam]] novel ''Randu Penkuttikal'' (\"Two Girls\") by [[V. T. Nandakumar]] is published in India. The novel gives a positive picture of lesbian relationships in [[Kerala]], and became very popular among young women.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1976'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} Indian poet [[Kamala Surayya|Kamala Das]] published ''My Story'' in 1976, creating a minor scandal. The autobiography revealed her extramarital heterosexual affairs and her adolescent crush on a female teacher and a brief lesbian encounter with an older student.<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\" />\n\n'''1978'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Shakuntala Devi|Noted math prodigy Shakuntala Devi]] publishes ''[http://orinam.net/content/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/SD_World_of-homosexuals_lowres.pdf The World of Homosexuals].'' The book is primarily a collection of interviews with homosexual men and advocates for societal acceptance of homosexuality.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The world of homosexuals|last = Devi|first = Shakuntala|publisher = Vikas Pub. House|year = 1977|isbn = |location = New Delhi|pages = |authorlink = Shakuntala Devi|oclc=3554716}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Devi|first1=Shakuntala|title=The World of Homosexuals|url=http://orinam.net/content/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/SD_World_of-homosexuals_lowres.pdf|website=Orinam|accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''1979'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} ''Begum Barve'', a Marathi play written and directed by [[Satish Alekar]], is performed for the first time by Theatre Academy, Pune, at Shriram Centre in New Delhi. Begum Barve, the central character, plays female parts and desires to live a woman's life.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n* {{flagicon|India}} The story \"A Double Life\" by well known Rajasthani author [[Vijay Dan Detha]] is published, depicting a romantic-sexual relationship between two women \"married\" to each other in rural [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n==1980s==\n'''Late 1970s / early 1980s'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} ''Partner'', a one-act play written by Dr. Anand Nadkarni, explores the relationship between two male hostel inmates in love, and the complications when one of them gets married<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n* {{flagicon|India}} Two college students in love, Mallika and Lalitatambika, attempt suicide.<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\">[https://www.academia.edu/3674963/Rescaling_Transnational_Queerdom_Lesbian_and_Lesbian_Identitary-Positionalities_in_Delhi_in_the_1980s Rescaling Transnational \"Queerdom\": Lesbian and \"Lesbian\" Identitary-Positionalities in Delhi in the 1980s by Paola Bacchetta, University of Kentucky]</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} The Delhi Group formed; Red Rose Rendezvous Group started. Indian women in Delhi active in creating spaces, dialogue, or research: Giti, Kanchana, Gita, Abha, and Paola<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\" />\n\n'''1981'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} All-India Hijra Conference in [[Agra]] brings together over 50,000 hijras from across South Asia.<ref name=\"Livia_Hall_Queerly_Phrased\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=1G_dVlJ2KhcC&pg=PA431&lpg=PA431&dq=hijra+conference+bhopal&source=bl&hl=en Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality, Pg 431. Edited by Anna Livia and Kira Hall. 1997.]</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} \"''[[Mitrachi Goshta]]''\", a lesbian theme play in Marathi written by eminent playwright [[Vijay Tendulkar]] opens in Mumbai and Thane. The play portrays the inner conflict of a woman who realizes she is lesbian. It was well received, and ran for 26 shows. (August 15)<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1982/1983/1984'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} Uma, a New Zealand lesbian of Indian descent interviewed in ''Conexions: Global Context'' issue 10. Uma established first Lesbian Line in Australia in the early 1980s, and later served on ILGA World Board as the Regional Representative of Oceania.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alison Kim|chapter=Pacific/Asian Lesbian Bibliography|editor1=Cristy Chung|editor2=Alison Kim|editor3=A. Kaweah Lemeshewsky|title=Between the lines: an anthology by Pacific/Asian lesbians of Santa Cruz, California|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=crUfAQAAIAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Dancing Bird Press|page=54}}</ref><ref name=Millett_NewZealand>{{cite web|title=Bibliography on Homosexuality in New Zealand, 1770-2012|url=http://tonymillett.tripod.com/bibhom.html|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=ILGA_WorldBoard>{{cite web|title=ILGA'S WORLD BOARD Uma Kali Shakti Regional Representative Oceania|url=http://old.ilga.org/news_results.asp?LanguageID=1&FileCategory=6&FileID=96|website=ILGA Archive|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} Article in ''[[Spare Rib]]'', a grassroots British feminist magazine, \"...NO, WE NEVER GO OUT OF FASHION ... FOR EACH OTHER!\" Interview with [[Audre Lorde]], Dorothea, [[Jackie Kay]] and Uma.<ref>[http://www.lesbianinformationservice.org/blackrl.htm Black and Minority Ethnic Lesbians Resource List]</ref>\n* [[Vikram Seth]] writes in the poem \"Dubious,\" which appears in his first collection [[Mappings (poetry)|Mappings]], about bisexuality: \"In the strict ranks of Gay and Straight / What is my status? / Stray? or Great?\"<ref>Rita Joshi, [http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+writer+as+traveler%3A+the+world+of+Vikram+Seth.-a0178898739 \"The writer as Traveler: the world of Vikram Seth\"], in ''[[World Literature Today]]'', 2008.</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[flickruser:hounslowartsco-op/|HAC Asian Theatre]] tours ''On the Road to Nowhere'' with sketches and visuals on race, power, sexuality, gender non-conforming roles, being gay, to Asian audiences that cause a press storm and calls for censorship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeterpress.co.uk/en/Book/475/British_South_Asian_Theatres.html|title=The University of Exeter Press - British South Asian Theatres|website=www.exeterpress.co.uk|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n'''1984'''\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} Zami, first Canadian group formed for Black and West Indian gays and lesbians (Toronto).<ref>[http://www.algi.qc.ca/asso/zami/page200_home.html Zami Women]</ref>\n\n'''1985'''\n* {{flagicon|United States}} ''[[Anamika (newsletter)|Anamika]]'', a newsletter for South Asian lesbians and queer women publishes the first of its three issues, mailed free to women in South Asia.<ref name=\"AnuBetweenTheLines1987\">{{cite book|author=Anu|chapter=Sexuality, Lesbianism, and South Asian Feminism|editor1=Cristy Chung|editor2=Alison Kim|editor3=A. Kaweah Lemeshewsky|title=Between the lines: an anthology by Pacific/Asian lesbians of Santa Cruz, California|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=crUfAQAAIAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Dancing Bird Press}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} Films: ''[[My Beautiful Laundrette]]'' directed by [[Stephen Frears]], based on a screenplay written by [[Hanif Kureishi]], depicts an interracial relationship between two men.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF048448/|title = \"MY BEAUTIFUL LAUNDRETTE (15)\". British Board of Film Classification|date = |accessdate = |website = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* Books: ''The [https://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/070433979X/ Conversations of Cow]'' by [[Suniti Namjoshi]] (some references to first publication in 1984)\n\n'''1986'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[HIV/AIDS in India#History|First case of HIV reported in India, in Chennai]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = USATODAY.com - HIV scars India's vast population|url = http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/health/2005-02-23-aids-india_x.htm|website = usatoday30.usatoday.com|accessdate = 2015-07-18}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Trikone|Trikon]] (later renamed Trikone) is formed by Arvind Kumar and Suvir, and print newsletter established<ref name=\"Orinam_Magazines_and_Journals\">{{cite web |title=Orinam.net: Magazines and Journals |url=http://orinam.net/resources-for/lgbt/magazines-and-journals/ |website=Orinam.net |publisher=Orinam |accessdate=22 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} First issue of [https://books.google.com/books?id=ShaGAAAAIAAJ&dq=editions:0AFLRE73D6sjvLq_NHAv0J6qdOAXvGJhWWK_9K9_9m0XcBse9gppjBR4&lr= Trikon newsletter], editors Arvind Kumar and Suvir (January)<ref name=Shah_Social_Perspectives_Reader>{{cite book |author1=Nayan Shah |authorlink1=Sexuality, Identity, and the Uses of History |editor1-last=Nardi |editor1-first=Peter M |editor2-last=Schneider |editor2-first=Beth E |title=Social Perspectives in Lesbian and Gay Studies: A Reader |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-136-21931-3 |page=489 |edition=2013 |date=2013-09-13 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=Nayan Shah |authorlink1=Sexuality, Identity, and the Uses of History |editor1-last=Hom |editor1-first=Alice |editor2-last=Eng |editor2-first=David |title=Q&A: Queer in Asian America |isbn=978-1-56639-640-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/qqueerinasianam00engd/page/155 155] |date=1998-08-24 |url=https://archive.org/details/qqueerinasianam00engd/page/155 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Bose |first1=Brinda |last2=Bhattacharyya |first2=Subhabrata |title=The Phobic and the Erotic: The Politics of Sexualities in Contemporary India |date=2007 |publisher=Seagull |isbn=978-1-905422-14-2 |page=323 }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Ashok Row Kavi]] discusses his homosexuality in [[Savvy (magazine)|''Savvy'' magazine]] (February)<ref>{{cite book|author=Naisargi N. Dave|title=Queer Activism in India: A Story in the Anthropology of Ethics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x6g776i3A34C&pg=PA42|date=8 October 2012|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-5319-5|pages=42\u201343}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Hijra conference in Bhopal, India (April)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QGJ68sbWFVUC&pg=PA108&dq=hijras+bhopal+1986&hl=en Dance, Sex, and Gender: Signs of Identity, Dominance, Defiance, and Desire]</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Trikone marches in [[San Francisco Pride]] parade for the first time ever (June).<ref>Referred to in Sandip Roy's [https://books.google.com/books?id=sOaRLVate9cC&pg=PA168&lpg=PA168&dq=%22a+call+for+rice%22+sandip+roy&source=bl&hl=en#v=onepage A Call For Rice], in [https://books.google.com/books?id=sOaRLVate9cC&pg=PA168&lpg=PA168&dq=%22a+call+for+rice%22+sandip+roy&source=bl&hl=en A Part, Yet Apart: South Asians in America edited by Lavina Dhingra Shankar and Rajini Srikanth]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sfpride.org/heritage/1986.html|title=SF Pride {{!}} Heritage {{!}} 1986 International Lesbian & Gay Freedom Day|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305230532/http://sfpride.org/heritage/1986.html|archive-date=2016-03-05|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Trikone Los Angeles (later [http://www.satrang.org/ Satrang]) formed <!--MN: add founders if available-->(Nov){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Trikone Chicago (later Sangat, and then reformed [http://www.trikonechicago.org/ Trikone Chicago]) formed by [[Ifti Nasim]] (Dec){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|United States}} ''[[Conditions (magazine)|Conditions: Thirteen]]'' publishes interview with Khayal and Utsa, \"There Are, Always Have Been, Always Will Be Lesbians in India\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Khayal|last2=Utsa|last3=Heske|first3=Susan|date=1986|editor-last=Utsa|title=There Are, Always Have Been, Always Will Be Lesbians in India|url=http://voices.revealdigital.com/cgi-bin/independentvoices?a=d&d=DCDCDIG19860101.1.147|journal=Conditions|volume=|issue=13|pages=135\u2013146|doi=|issn=0147-8311|oclc=3232386|pmid=|access-date=September 10, 2016|via=Independent Voices}}</ref><ref>[Referenced in [http://library.ucsc.edu/sites/default/files/betweenthelines_0.pdf Between the Lines]</ref>\n* Kanchana researches Hindu text for women loving women references.<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\" />\n* Books\n** {{flagicon|Canada}} ''Flesh and Paper'' by [[Suniti Namjoshi|Suniti Namoshi]] and Gillian Eve Hanscombe<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ykaGAAAACAAJ|title=Flesh and Paper|last=Namjoshi|first=Suniti|last2=Hanscombe|first2=Gillian Eve|date=1986|publisher=Ragweed Press|isbn=9780920304648|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''1987'''\n* {{flagicon|India}}Sneha Sangam gay group forms in Bangalore<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.berkeleysouthasian.org/uploads/8/3/1/3/8313602/queer-history-datebook-06061.pdf|title=The Desi Queer Datebook|last=Newsnotes|date=2006-05-08|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Society (magazine)|''Society'']] magazine in India prints a story about Trikone (Jan){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Khush: South Asian Lesbian and Gay Association|Khush]], an organization that created safe spaces for South Asian gays and lesbians in [[Toronto]] was formed (July).<ref name=\"Warner_Never_Going_Back_Again\">Tom Warner, [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0802084605 ''Never Going Back: A History of Queer Activism in Canada''.]</ref><ref>http://dailyxtra.com/toronto/arts-and-entertainment/khush-show-love Daily Xtra</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/events/222815294422388/ | title=Aanmelden of registreren om te bekijken}}</ref><ref name=\"Brown_Canada\">{{Cite web|title = Queer & Trans|url = http://www.browncanada.com/content.php?pg=24&pid=4|website = Brown Canada|accessdate = 2015-04-04|publisher = Council of Agencies Serving South Asians (CASSA)}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Trikon becomes [http://501c3lookup.org/trikone/ incorporated] as Trikone (Nov){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|India}}Bhopal policewomen Lila and Urmila marry with religious priest and get fired from police job (Dec)<ref>Naisargi N. Dave, [https://books.google.com/books?id=x6g776i3A34C&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=lila+urmila+lesbian&source=bl&hl=en ''Queer Activism in India: A Story in the Anthropology of Ethics''.]</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Village teachers Aruna Sombhai Jaisinghbhai Gohil, aged 31, and Sudha Amarsinh Mohansinh Ratanwadia, aged 29, entered maitri karar (friendship agreement) before a notary public in 1987 after nine years together<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\" />\n*{{Flagicon|United Kingdom}} London Borough of Ealing Race Equality Unit holds the first London South Asian LGBTQ poetry festival organised by Race Equality Campaigns Officer, [[Poulomi Desai]] with the bookshop, Bogle L'overture in defiance of Section 28<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.janinebooth.com/content/story-section-28|title=The Story of Section 28|last=Janine|date=2014-08-30|website=Janine Booth|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/things-to-do/london-metropolitan-archives/visitor-information/Documents/21-black-caribbean-community-archives.pdf|title=Archives}}</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|United Kingdom}} SAGALG set up by [https://queerbio.com/wiki/index.php?title=Shivananda_Khan Shivananda Khan] and Poulomi Desai which later becomes Shakti\n* Books\n** ''Between the Lines: An Anthology by Pacific/Asian lesbians of Santa Cruz, California'' includes Anu's chapter \"Sexuality, Lesbianism, and South Asian Feminism\"<ref name=\"AnuBetweenTheLines1987\"/>\n\n'''1988'''\n*{{Flagicon|United Kingdom}} Shakti formed in London by [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HwxCfUXEq5M Shivananda Khan], [http://www.usurp.org.uk Poulomi Desai], Sunil Gupta, Atul Sarin, Manjit Rooprah, Savi Hensman, Pratibha Parmar - the first South Asian LGBT organisation in Europe (June)<ref name=\"Shivananda_Khan_Culture\">Shivananda Khan, [https://books.google.com/books?id=1RzcAAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=shakti&f=false \"Culture, Sexualities, and Identities: Men Who Have Sex with Men in India\"], in Gerald Sullivan and Peter Ackson (eds), ''Gay and Lesbian Asia: Culture, Identity, and Community''.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Trikone (San Francisco), Khush (Toronto), Shakti (London) and Urvashi Vaid make the ''Illustrated Weekly of India''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=x6g776i3A34C&pg=PA44&lpg=PA44&dq=Illustrated+Weekly+of+India+khush+gay&source=bl&hl=en Queer Activism in India: A Story in the Anthropology of Ethics]</ref> (September)\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} First Shakti Bhangra disco in London organised by [https://queerbio.com/wiki/index.php?title=Shivananda_Khan Shivananda Khan], Poulomi Desai with DJ Ritu. Seed funding given to Shakti by the Ealing Race Equality Unit. (Oct)<ref>{{cite web|title=LSE Library's archive holdings|url=http://archives.lse.ac.uk/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=HCA%2FEPHEMERA%2F721|website=British Library of Political and Economic Science Library Services CalmView|publisher=Shakti|accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ulme-mini-verlag.de/music2.htm#clubs|title=The Rough Guide to Bhangra|website=www.ulme-mini-verlag.de|access-date=2016-08-21}}</ref>\n<!--* ~Asian Lesbians of Vancouver --><!--MN: add founders if available {{citation needed|date=June 2015}}-->\n<!--* ~Monsoon --> <!--MN: add founders if available {{citation needed|date=June 2015}}-->\n* Gita Darji and Kishori Shah RIP<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\" />\n\n'''1989'''\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} ''Khush Kahayal'', newsletter of Khush South Asian gay men of Toronto, is established.<ref name=\"Orinam_Magazines_and_Journals\" /><ref name=\"Brown_Canada\" />\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} ''Shakti Khabar'' published in London.<ref name=Shivananda_Khan_Culture /><ref name=A_People_Stronger /><!--\"People Stronger\" citation references 1988 (pg 51); Shivananda Khan reference indicates 1989 (pg 104) -->\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Dominic d'Souza|Dominic D\u2019Souza]] arrested placed in solitary confinement in India because he is HIV+ (Feb)<ref>[http://thenightchild.blogspot.com/2012/09/my-friend-dominic-trikone-california.html \"My Friend...Dominic\"], published in ''Trikone Magazine'' summer of 2012; republished in the Nightchild Nexus blog.</ref><ref>Ashok Row Kavi and Dinyar Godrej, [http://newint.org/features/1993/12/05/bigots/ \"Bigots Take the Temple\"], ''New Internationalist Magazine'', Issue 250, December 1993.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} Khush organizes Salaam Toronto! Festival (May)<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://archivesfa.library.yorku.ca/fonds/ON00370-f0000522.htm |title = F0522 - Desh Pardesh fonds}}</ref><ref>http://archivescanada.accesstomemory.org/desh-pardesh-2</ref><ref>http://dailyxtra.com/toronto/deshs-mid-life-crisis</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Urvashi Vaid]] becomes Executive Director of the [[National Gay and Lesbian Task Force]] (July)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vaid|first1=Urvashi|authorlink1=Urvashi Vaid|title=Urvashi Vaid: Curriculum Vitae|url=http://urvashivaid.net/wp/?page_id=578|website=Urvashi Vaid|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} [http://asaap.ca/about/our-history/ South Asian AIDS Coalition] (later ASAAP) formed in Toronto (Jul)<ref>http://munkschool.utoronto.ca/cphs/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/CPHS-JP-2010-11.pdf pg6</ref>