ion: Same-Sex Marriage and Hinduism|journal=Hinduism Today|date=January 2016|volume=January/February/March 2016|url=http://www.hinduismtoday.com/modules/smartsection/item.php?itemid=5650|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>\n*  {{flagicon|Nepal}} Nepal explicitly puts equal rights and freedom from discrimination for LGBT individuals in the constitution<ref name=Hinduism_Today_2016 /><ref>{{cite news|last1=R|first1=Vansundara|title=Nepal's New LGBT Non-Discriminatory Laws Leave India Far Behind|url=http://www.idiva.com/news-work-life/nepal-brings-in-new-lgbt-non-discriminatory-laws-that-leave-india-far-behind/15092282|accessdate=22 December 2015|date=September 22, 2015}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|India}}Jawaharlal Nehru University, New Delhi, started offering \"Others\" option in the gender column of the application form. Due to the efforts of [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] of Srishti Madurai and the student community at JNU.<ref name=\"One Who Fights For an Other\"/>\n*  {{flagicon|India}} Srishti Madurai urged [[Lok Sabha]] MP's  to include [[intersex]] people in a bill to protect the rights of trans people.<ref>http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/List-Intersex-in-Transgender-Bill-Urges-NGO/2015/08/29/article2998899.ece</ref><ref>http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/08/29/india-urged-to-include-intersex-people-in-bill-protecting-trans-rights/</ref>\n* Books\n** {{flagicon|United States}} ''Don't Let Him Know'' by [[Sandip Roy (author)|Sandip Roy]]<ref>{{Cite book|title = Don't Let Him Know|last = Roy|first = Sandip|publisher = Bloomsbury|year = 2015|isbn = 9781620408988|location = |pages = |url = }}</ref>\n** {{flagicon|United States}} [https://storify.com/movingtruths/moving-truth-s-queer-and-transgender-desi-writings Moving Truth(s): Queer and Transgender Desi Writings on Family], an anthology of writing by queer and transgender Desis about family, edited by Aparajeeta Duttchoudhury and Rukie Hartman<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Duttchoudhury|editor1-first=Aparajeeta|editor2-last=Hartman|editor2-first=Rukie|title=Moving Truth(s): Queer and Transgender Desi Writings on Family|date=April 2015|publisher=Flying Chickadee|isbn=978-0989626354|url=http://www.flyingchickadee.com/books.html|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n* Film\n**{{flagicon|India}} The film ''[[Naanu Avanalla...Avalu]]'', about the life of [[Living Smile Vidya]], won two awards at the [[62nd National Film Awards]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/nat-film-awards-ceremony-to-be-held-on-may-3-every-year-soni-112050300505_1.html|title=Nat Film Awards ceremony to be held on May 3 every year: Soni|last=India|first=Press Trust of|date=2012-05-03|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2017-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/62nd-national-film-awards-winners-haider-wins-five-queen-two/|title=62nd National Film Awards' winners: 'Haider' wins five, Kangana Ranaut's 'Queen' two|date=2015-03-24|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-04-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n** {{flagicon|Pakistan}} First ever movie on Pakistan's hidden LGBT community: ''[[Poshida: Hidden LGBT Pakistan]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=First ever movie on Pakistan's hidden LGBT community|url=http://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/lifestyle/first-ever-movie-on-pakistans-hidden-lgbt-community-594/|accessdate=22 September 2015|publisher=Daily Pakistan Global|date=August 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McCray|first1=Rebecca|title=Hidden in Plain Sight: Documentary Sheds Light on Pakistan's LGBT Community|url=http://www.takepart.com/article/2015/08/17/new-documentary-exposes-challenges-faced-pakistan-s-lgbt-community|website=takepart|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''2016'''\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Nergis Mavalvala]], a queer Pakistani American MIT astrophysicist, was part of the team of scientists who [[First observation of gravitational waves|observed gravitational waves for the first time]]<ref>{{cite journal | collaboration = LIGO Scientific Collaboration and Virgo Collaboration | last1 = Abbott | first1 = Benjamin P.  |title=Observation of Gravitational Waves from a Binary Black Hole Merger |journal=[[Phys. Rev. Lett.]] |volume=116 | issue = 6 |pages=061102 |year=2016 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.116.061102 | arxiv=1602.03837 | pmid=26918975|bibcode=2016PhRvL.116f1102A }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nergis Mavalvala: The Karachiite who went on to detect Einstein's gravitational waves|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1239270|accessdate=14 February 2016|work=Dawn|date=February 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Vijaysree|first=Venkatraman|title=Just Herself|magazine=Science|date=June 1, 2012|accessdate=14 February 2016|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/careers/2012/06/just-herself}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} On March 6, 2016 Srishti Madurai's new website was launched by Dalit activist and Ambedkarite Ma. Venkatesan from BJP in the presence of Central Minister [[Pon Radhakrishnan]], Vanathi Srinivasan, [[Aravindan Neelakandan]], [[Joe D'Cruz]] and scores of [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] volunteers at Chennai.<ref>http://www.firstpost.com/living/rss-flip-flop-on-homosexuality-indicates-gay-men-in-india-remain-in-exile-writes-ashok-row-kavi-2685296.html</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]], a 25 years old gender activist made a bid to contest as one of the youngest candidates in the Tamil Nadu Assembly election and also the first openly [[Intersex]] & [[Genderqueer]] person to do so. Ze secured 14th place out of 21 candidates by securing 1% vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/intersex-person-to-contest-from-madurai-north/article8539185.ece |title=Intersex person to contest from Madurai North - TAMIL NADU |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2016-04-30 |accessdate=2016-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Share on FacebookShare on Twitter |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/elections-2016/tamil-nadu-elections-2016/news/3rd-gender-gets-a-new-champion-in-Tamil-Nadu-poll-ring/articleshow/51935940.cms |title=3rd gender gets a new champion in Tamil Nadu poll ring - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2016-04-22 |accessdate=2016-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Share on FacebookShare on Twitter |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Intersex-candidate-alleges-harassment/articleshow/52197962.cms |title=Intersex candidate alleges harassment - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2016-05-10 |accessdate=2016-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/intersex-person-contesting-tn-polls-ze-wants-change-your-mind-sexual-minorities-42103 |title=This intersex person is contesting TN polls, 'ze' wants to change your mind on sexual minorities |publisher=The News Minute |date=2016-04-24 |accessdate=2016-05-22}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Bangladesh}} [[Xulhaz Mannan]] and Tanay Fahim murdered in Dhaka, Bangladesh<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/25/editor-bangladesh-first-lgbt-magazine-killed-reports-say-roopbaan|title=Editor of Bangladesh's first and only LGBT magazine killed|last=Gani|first=Saad Hammadi Aisha|date=2016-04-25|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://humanism.org.uk/2016/04/25/more-individuals-hacked-to-death-in-bangladesh-as-islamists-broaden-their-hit-list/|title=More individuals hacked to death in Bangladesh as Islamists broaden their hit list|website=British Humanist Association|access-date=2016-04-26}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} On July 15, 2016 For the first time Srishti Madurai along with [[Tamil Nadu Theological Seminary]] in Madurai a conglomerate of the [[Church of South India]] (CSI), and the [[Lutheran Church]] organised an Introductory seminar for church pastors on LGBT issues.<ref>http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/awesome-tamil-nadu-seminary-teaching-pastors-accept-lgbt-community-46577</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] of Srishti Madurai shortlisted for [[The Commonwealth]] Youth Worker Award as regional finalist for Asia.<ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/Gender-rights-activist-shortlisted-for-international-award/articleshow/54968127.cms</ref><ref>http://thecommonwealth.org/media/news/finalists-2016-commonwealth-youth-worker-awards-announced</ref>\n\n'''2017'''\n* {{flagicon|Pakistan}} Pakistan issues first passport with transgender category.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Maizland|first1=Lindsay|title=Pakistan just issued its first passport with a transgender category|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/6/23/15861620/pakistan-transgender-passport-human-rights|website=Vox|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Indian Supreme Court declares privacy is an intrinsic right, and that sexual orientation is an essential attribute of privacy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/right-to-privacy-verdict-a-fundamental-shift-on-gay-rights/articleshow/60215853.cms|title=Right to privacy verdict: A fundamental shift on gay rights - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-05}}</ref>\n\n'''2018'''\n*{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} First South Asian LGBTI Conference held at Queen Elizabeth Hospital Birmingham, organised by [https://BritishAsianLGBTI.org British Asian LGBTI], Finding A Voice and Gaysian Faces on 28th July 2018, with eighteen speakers, two films (Sisak and Planchette) <ref>https://britishasianlgbti.org/south-asian-lgbti-conference/| South Asian LGBTI Conference</ref> <ref>https://britishasianlgbti.org/south-asian-lgbti-conference/south-Asian-LGBTI_conference-2018| South Asian LGBTI Conference 2018</ref> \n\n*{{flagicon|India}} Indian Supreme Court [[LGBT rights in India#Contemporary times|legalizes gay sex]] and reads down Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code, which criminalized same-sex relations. India's Outgoing chief justice Dipak Misra, regarding the ruling, said: \"Criminalising carnal intercourse is irrational, arbitrary and manifestly unconstitutional.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-45429664|title=Historic India ruling legalises gay sex|date=2018-09-06|access-date=2019-04-08|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Timeline of Asian and Pacific Islander Diasporic LGBT History]]\n* [[Timeline of African and diasporic LGBT history]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{LGBT history}}\n\n[[Category:History of South Asia]]\n[[Category:LGBT history in India]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:LGBT in India]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Nepal]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:LGBT timelines|South Asia]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|LGBT Timeline South Asia}}\n<!-- Please do not remove or change this AfD message until the issue is settled -->\n<!-- For administrator use only: {{Old AfD multi|page=Timeline of global South Asian LGBT and queer history|date=29 July 2014|result='''keep'''}} -->\n<!-- End of AfD message, feel free to edit beyond this point -->\n\nThis is a timeline of notable events in the history of non-heterosexual conforming [[South Asia|people of South Asian ancestry]], who may identify as [[LGBT]]IQGNC ([[lesbian]], [[gay]], [[Bisexuality|bisexual]], [[transgender]], [[intersex]], queer, [[third gender]], [[Gender variance|gender nonconforming]]), [[men who have sex with men]], or related culturally-specific identities<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Suleiman|first1=Gee Ameena|title=Non-'hijra' transgenders struggle for identity|journal=DNA|date=18 September 2011|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/lifestyle/report-non-hijra-transgenders-struggle-for-identity-1588421|accessdate=29 July 2014}}</ref> such as [[Hijra (South Asia)|Hijra]], Aravani, Thirunangaigal, Khwajasara, [[Kothi (gender)|Kothi]], Thirunambigal, [[LGBT topics and Hinduism#The Jogappa|Jogappa]], Jogatha, or Shiva Shakti.<ref>[http://roundtableindia.co.in/index.php?option=com_content&view=article&id=7185 Round Table India article: Letter by trans men to the Ministry of Social Justice and Empowerment]</ref><ref>[http://iglhrc.org/sites/default/files/PakistanCC.pdf \"Violence: Through the Lens of Lesbians, Bisexual Women, and Trans People in Asia\"] - Pakistan. IGLHRC, 2014.</ref> The recorded history traces back at least two millennia.\n\nThis timeline includes events both in South Asia and in the global South Asian diaspora, as the histories are deeply linked.<ref name=\"desiq-2006-timeline\">{{cite web|last1=Roy|first1=Sandip|title=Desi Queer Datebook|url=http://archive.berkeleysouthasian.org/lgbt.html|website=Berkeley South Asian History Archive|accessdate=17 July 2014|date=2006}}</ref><ref name=\"desiq-2013-timeline\">{{cite web|title=DesiQ 2013 History Timeline|url=https://www.flickr.com/photos/anirvan/galleries/72157645335742347/|website=Flickr|publisher=DesiQ|accessdate=17 July 2014}}</ref> South Asia includes the modern day nations of [[Bangladesh]], [[Bhutan]], [[India]], [[Maldives]], [[Nepal]], [[Pakistan]], [[Sri Lanka]]; in some references, the South Asian subcontinent will also include [[Afghanistan]], [[Burma]] (Myanmar), and [[Tibet]]. The South Asian diaspora includes, but is not limited to South Asian LGBTQ communities in the [[United States]], [[United Kingdom]], [[Canada]], [[Australia]], [[Caribbean]] Islands, [[Southeast Asia]], and elsewhere.\n\n==Early history==\n\n'''400 BCE - 200 BCE'''\n* [[V\u0101tsy\u0101yana|Vatsyayana]]'s ''[[Kama Sutra|The Kama Sutra]]'' devotes an entire chapter to homosexuality with explicit detailed instructions on how to perform homosexual acts.<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\">{{cite web|author1=New England Publishing Associates|title=GLBTQ Encyclopedia: South Asian Literatures: Diaspora|url=http://www.glbtq.com/literature/south_asian_lit.html|website=glbtq: an encyclopedia of gay, lesbian, bisexual, transgender & queer culture|accessdate=22 June 2014|year=2002}}</ref>\n\n'''3rd century BC to c. 4th century AD'''\n* [[Sangam literature|Tamil Sangam literature]] refers to relationships between two men and explores the lives of [[trans women]] in the [[Aravani|Aravan]] cult in [[Koovagam]] village in [[Tamil Nadu]].<ref name=\"thehindu.com\">{{cite news| url=http://www.thehindu.com/features/metroplus/no-more-under-siege/article5247859.ece | location=Chennai, India | work=The Hindu | first=A. | last=Shrikumar | title=No more under siege | date=2013-10-18}}</ref>\n\n'''1015'''\n* Sultan [[Mahmud of Ghazni|Mahmud]] of [[Ghazni]], who was the first [[Muslim]] ruler of the Indian subcontinent, has a non-sexual close friendship with his slave [[Malik Ayaz]]. This relationship has become an Islamic legend and Mahmud later appointed Malik Ayaz as the sultan of [[Lahore]].<ref>{{cite web|last1=Jama|first1=Afdhere|title=5 Ways Pakistan Has Been Gay Friendly|url=http://islamandhomosexuality.com/5-ways-pakistan-gay-friendly/|website=LGBT Muslims: Information on Sexual Diversity in the Muslim community|accessdate=9 April 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=The Encyclopedia of World Biography|url=http://biography.yourdictionary.com/mahmud-of-ghazni|website=Your Dictionary Resource|publisher=The Gale Group|accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''~1529'''\n* Emperor [[Babur]]'s memoirs, the ''[[Baburnama]],'' include a recollection of his erotic love for a teenage boy.<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\" />\n\n'''1538'''\n* [[Shah Hussain]], a Punjabi Sufi poet regarded as a saint, was described as being close relationship with a Brahmin boy called \"Madho\" or \"Madho Lal\". They are often referred to as a single person with the composite name \"Madho Lal Hussain\". But no mention of sexual relations or homosexual tendencies are made.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Mohan|first1=Lal|title=Encyclopaedia of Indian Literature, Vol. 5|date=2006|publisher=Sahitya Akademi|location=Delhi|isbn=978-81-260-1221-3}}</ref>\n\n'''1740s'''\n* [[Dargah Quli Khan]]'s personal diary ''Muraqqa-e-Delhi: The Mughal Capital in Muhammad Shah's Time'' \"briefly documents his foray into the pederastic circles of Delhi.\"<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\" /><ref>{{Cite web|title = Pur\u0101n\u012b Dihl\u012b ke \u1e25\u0101l\u0101t : \u0101j se do sau baras pehle N\u0101dir Sh\u0101h\u012b qatal-i \u02bb\u0101m ke vaqt ... /|url = http://www.worldcat.org/identities/lccn-n88176437/|website = www.worldcat.org|accessdate = 2015-08-08}}</ref>\n\n'''1750-1830'''\n* Emergence of Rekhti chapti-namahs, or female same-sex narratives, in [[Urdu]] poetry.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://iaws.org/wp-content/themes/pdf/newsletters/NLC042-2007.pdf|title = Of Begums and Tawaifs|date = |accessdate = |website = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n'''1861'''\n* Anti-sodomy section of [[Offences against the Person Act 1861]] imposed on entire British Empire, that says \"Whosoever shall be convicted of the abominable Crime of Buggery, committed either with Mankind or with any Animal, shall be liable, at the Discretion of the Court, to be kept in Penal Servitude for Life or for any Term not less than Ten Years.\" This section is credited with giving birth to the controversial [[Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code]].<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.legislation.gov.uk/ukpga/1861/100/pdfs/ukpga_18610100_en.pdf|title = An Act to consolidate and amend the Statute Law of England and Ireland relating to Offences Against the Person.|date = |accessdate = |website = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n\n'''1871'''\n* [[Hijra (South Asia)|Hijras]] labeled a \"criminal tribe\" under the [[Criminal Tribes Act|Criminal Tribes Act, 1871]], meaning they could be arrested as criminals anywhere in British India.<ref>{{cite book|author=Gayatri Reddy|title=With Respect to Sex: Negotiating Hijra Identity in South India|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=SyqTnL9jTFoC&pg=PA26|date=15 May 2010|publisher=University of Chicago Press|isbn=978-0-226-70754-9|pages=26\u2013}}</ref>\n'''1897'''\n* [[Criminal Tribes Act|Criminal Tribes Act of 1871]] amended, with the subtitle \"An Act for the Registration of Criminal Tribes and Eunuchs,\" ordering that \"criminal\" eunuchs \u201cdressed or ornamented like a woman in a public street\u2026be arrested without warrant\u201d and imprisoned.<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://planettransgender.com/transindia-who-are-the-hijras-2/|title=Transindia: Who Are the Hijras?|date=January 31, 2015|website=Planet Transgender|language=|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://paper-bird.net/2014/11/28/buggery-and-beggary/|title=Buggery and beggary, and Ferguson|last=Scott Long|date=November 28, 2014|website=a paper bird|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.countercurrents.org/gen-narrain141003.htm|title=Being A Eunuch In India|last=Narrain|first=Siddarth|date=October 14, 2003|website=Countercurrents|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/society/2014/apr/16/india-third-gender-claims-place-in-law|title=Hijra: India's third gender claims its place in law|last=Khaleeli|first=Homa|date=2014-04-16|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-03-14}}</ref>\n'''1918'''\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Earliest known records of South Asian [[Men who have sex with men|MSM]] in North America, as Tara Singh and Jamil Singh are separately arrested for interracial sodomy in [[Sacramento, CA]].<ref name=\"Shah_Stranger_Intimacy\">{{cite book|last=Shah|first=Nayan|title=Stranger Intimacy: Contesting Race, Sexuality, and the Law in the North American West|year=2011|publisher=University of California Press|location=Berkeley, California|isbn=978-0-520-27087-9|pages=74\u201378|chapter=Policing Strangers and Borderlands|authorlink=Nayan Shah}}</ref>\n\n'''1922'''\n* ''Poems Written in Prison'' by [[Gopabandhu Das]], a freedom fighter and Gandhian, is published. At least two poems address male friends and co-workers, and the author describes these relationships in terms that are intense and erotically charged though not overtly sexual. These poems are sometimes included in [[Odia language]] literature textbooks.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\">[http://saathii.org/gensex/calcutta/lgbthistory.html Saathii Indian LGBT Movement page]</ref>\n\n'''1924'''\n* \"Chocolate\", a short story in Hindi written by nationalist and social reformer [[Pandey Bechan Sharma|Pandey Bechan]] Sharma (under the penname Ugra), is published in the nationalist newspaper ''Matvala''. Ugra's crusade against male-to-male sex sparks debate in Hindi newspapers and magazines, resulting in perhaps the first public debate in Hindi on homosexuality.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" /><ref>{{Cite journal|journal = International Journal of Hindu Studies|volume = 14|issue = 2/3|pages = 343\u2013345|jstor = 41476628|last1 = Knight|first1 = Lisa I.|title = Reviewed work: \"Ugra,\" Chocolate and Other Writings on Male Homoeroticism, Pandey Bechan Sharma, Ruth Vanita|year = 2010}}</ref>\n\n'''1929'''\n* [[Mahatma Gandhi]] speaks out against same-sex relations in a ''[[Young India]]'' letter, in response to queries on \"unnatural vices\" in schools.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1936'''\n* Urdu poet [[Firaq Gorakhpuri]] writes an essay defending the [[Ghazal]] form of poetry that includes a defence of homosexuality, citing renowned philosophers, poets and other luminaries across the East and the West who were homosexual or had expressed homosexual desire in well-known works.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1942'''\n* [[Ismat Chugtai]]'s short story \"[[Lihaaf]]\" is published.\n'''1944'''\n* [[Ismat Chughtai]] faces obscenity trial for [[Lihaaf]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = Aamer Hussein reviews Ismat Chughtai's Short Stories - Asymptote|url = http://www.asymptotejournal.com/article.php?cat=Criticism&id=63&curr_index=259&curPage=contributors|website = www.asymptotejournal.com|accessdate = 2015-07-18}}</ref>\n'''1945'''\n* [[Ismat Chughtai]] publishes her semi-autobiographical ''Tehri Lakeer'' (\"The Crooked Line\"), an Urdu novel that does not shy away from sexuality and depiction of same-sex attraction.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1962'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Rajendra Yadav]], a leading Hindi novelist, publishes his story \"Prateeksha\" (\"Waiting\") that depicts a homosexual relation between two women without censure and in detail.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1968'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Bhupen Khakhar]], a painter and writer of [[Gujarati language|Gujarati]] fiction, as one of the few openly homosexual luminaries, writes an untitled story depicting bisexuality in a quotidian, lower middle-class context.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n==1970s==\n\n'''~1970s'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} ''Gay Scene'' journal published in Calcutta (only a few issues published)<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1972'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} Indian poet [[Kamala Surayya|Kamala Das]] first published her semi-fictionalized autobiography ''[[My Story (Kamala Das book)|My Story]]'' in 1972, creating a minor scandal. The autobiography revealed her extramarital heterosexual affairs and her adolescent crush on a female teacher and a brief lesbian encounter with an older student.<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\" /><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/thiruvananthapuram/My-Story-made-Kamala-Surayya-celebrity-Malayalanadu-editor/articleshow/4604457.cms|title='My Story' made Kamala Surayya celebrity: Malayalanadu editor|last=|first=|date=Jun 1, 2009|website=Times of India|access-date=2016-08-07}}</ref>\n\n'''1974'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Malayalam]] novel ''Randu Penkuttikal'' (\"Two Girls\") by [[V. T. Nandakumar]] is published in India. The novel gives a positive picture of lesbian relationships in [[Kerala]], and became very popular among young women.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1976'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} Indian poet [[Kamala Surayya|Kamala Das]] published ''My Story'' in 1976, creating a minor scandal. The autobiography revealed her extramarital heterosexual affairs and her adolescent crush on a female teacher and a brief lesbian encounter with an older student.<ref name=\"GLBTQ_Encyclopedia\" />\n\n'''1978'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Shakuntala Devi|Noted math prodigy Shakuntala Devi]] publishes ''[http://orinam.net/content/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/SD_World_of-homosexuals_lowres.pdf The World of Homosexuals].'' The book is primarily a collection of interviews with homosexual men and advocates for societal acceptance of homosexuality.<ref>{{Cite book|title = The world of homosexuals|last = Devi|first = Shakuntala|publisher = Vikas Pub. House|year = 1977|isbn = |location = New Delhi|pages = |authorlink = Shakuntala Devi|oclc=3554716}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Devi|first1=Shakuntala|title=The World of Homosexuals|url=http://orinam.net/content/wp-content/uploads/2013/04/SD_World_of-homosexuals_lowres.pdf|website=Orinam|accessdate=11 April 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''1979'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} ''Begum Barve'', a Marathi play written and directed by [[Satish Alekar]], is performed for the first time by Theatre Academy, Pune, at Shriram Centre in New Delhi. Begum Barve, the central character, plays female parts and desires to live a woman's life.<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n* {{flagicon|India}} The story \"A Double Life\" by well known Rajasthani author [[Vijay Dan Detha]] is published, depicting a romantic-sexual relationship between two women \"married\" to each other in rural [[Rajasthan]].<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n==1980s==\n'''Late 1970s / early 1980s'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} ''Partner'', a one-act play written by Dr. Anand Nadkarni, explores the relationship between two male hostel inmates in love, and the complications when one of them gets married<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n* {{flagicon|India}} Two college students in love, Mallika and Lalitatambika, attempt suicide.<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\">[https://www.academia.edu/3674963/Rescaling_Transnational_Queerdom_Lesbian_and_Lesbian_Identitary-Positionalities_in_Delhi_in_the_1980s Rescaling Transnational \"Queerdom\": Lesbian and \"Lesbian\" Identitary-Positionalities in Delhi in the 1980s by Paola Bacchetta, University of Kentucky]</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} The Delhi Group formed; Red Rose Rendezvous Group started. Indian women in Delhi active in creating spaces, dialogue, or research: Giti, Kanchana, Gita, Abha, and Paola<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\" />\n\n'''1981'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} All-India Hijra Conference in [[Agra]] brings together over 50,000 hijras from across South Asia.<ref name=\"Livia_Hall_Queerly_Phrased\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=1G_dVlJ2KhcC&pg=PA431&lpg=PA431&dq=hijra+conference+bhopal&source=bl&hl=en Queerly Phrased: Language, Gender, and Sexuality, Pg 431. Edited by Anna Livia and Kira Hall. 1997.]</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} \"''[[Mitrachi Goshta]]''\", a lesbian theme play in Marathi written by eminent playwright [[Vijay Tendulkar]] opens in Mumbai and Thane. The play portrays the inner conflict of a woman who realizes she is lesbian. It was well received, and ran for 26 shows. (August 15)<ref name=\"Saathi_LGBT_History\" />\n\n'''1982/1983/1984'''\n* {{flagicon|New Zealand}} Uma, a New Zealand lesbian of Indian descent interviewed in ''Conexions: Global Context'' issue 10. Uma established first Lesbian Line in Australia in the early 1980s, and later served on ILGA World Board as the Regional Representative of Oceania.<ref>{{cite book|author=Alison Kim|chapter=Pacific/Asian Lesbian Bibliography|editor1=Cristy Chung|editor2=Alison Kim|editor3=A. Kaweah Lemeshewsky|title=Between the lines: an anthology by Pacific/Asian lesbians of Santa Cruz, California|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=crUfAQAAIAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Dancing Bird Press|page=54}}</ref><ref name=Millett_NewZealand>{{cite web|title=Bibliography on Homosexuality in New Zealand, 1770-2012|url=http://tonymillett.tripod.com/bibhom.html|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref><ref name=ILGA_WorldBoard>{{cite web|title=ILGA'S WORLD BOARD Uma Kali Shakti Regional Representative Oceania|url=http://old.ilga.org/news_results.asp?LanguageID=1&FileCategory=6&FileID=96|website=ILGA Archive|accessdate=31 July 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} Article in ''[[Spare Rib]]'', a grassroots British feminist magazine, \"...NO, WE NEVER GO OUT OF FASHION ... FOR EACH OTHER!\" Interview with [[Audre Lorde]], Dorothea, [[Jackie Kay]] and Uma.<ref>[http://www.lesbianinformationservice.org/blackrl.htm Black and Minority Ethnic Lesbians Resource List]</ref>\n* [[Vikram Seth]] writes in the poem \"Dubious,\" which appears in his first collection [[Mappings (poetry)|Mappings]], about bisexuality: \"In the strict ranks of Gay and Straight / What is my status? / Stray? or Great?\"<ref>Rita Joshi, [http://www.thefreelibrary.com/The+writer+as+traveler%3A+the+world+of+Vikram+Seth.-a0178898739 \"The writer as Traveler: the world of Vikram Seth\"], in ''[[World Literature Today]]'', 2008.</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|United Kingdom}} [[flickruser:hounslowartsco-op/|HAC Asian Theatre]] tours ''On the Road to Nowhere'' with sketches and visuals on race, power, sexuality, gender non-conforming roles, being gay, to Asian audiences that cause a press storm and calls for censorship.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.exeterpress.co.uk/en/Book/475/British_South_Asian_Theatres.html|title=The University of Exeter Press - British South Asian Theatres|website=www.exeterpress.co.uk|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref>\n\n'''1984'''\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} Zami, first Canadian group formed for Black and West Indian gays and lesbians (Toronto).<ref>[http://www.algi.qc.ca/asso/zami/page200_home.html Zami Women]</ref>\n\n'''1985'''\n* {{flagicon|United States}} ''[[Anamika (newsletter)|Anamika]]'', a newsletter for South Asian lesbians and queer women publishes the first of its three issues, mailed free to women in South Asia.<ref name=\"AnuBetweenTheLines1987\">{{cite book|author=Anu|chapter=Sexuality, Lesbianism, and South Asian Feminism|editor1=Cristy Chung|editor2=Alison Kim|editor3=A. Kaweah Lemeshewsky|title=Between the lines: an anthology by Pacific/Asian lesbians of Santa Cruz, California|chapter-url=https://books.google.com/books?id=crUfAQAAIAAJ|year=1987|publisher=Dancing Bird Press}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} Films: ''[[My Beautiful Laundrette]]'' directed by [[Stephen Frears]], based on a screenplay written by [[Hanif Kureishi]], depicts an interracial relationship between two men.<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.bbfc.co.uk/AFF048448/|title = \"MY BEAUTIFUL LAUNDRETTE (15)\". British Board of Film Classification|date = |accessdate = |website = |last = |first = }}</ref>\n* Books: ''The [https://www.amazon.com/exec/obidos/ASIN/070433979X/ Conversations of Cow]'' by [[Suniti Namjoshi]] (some references to first publication in 1984)\n\n'''1986'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[HIV/AIDS in India#History|First case of HIV reported in India, in Chennai]].<ref>{{Cite web|title = USATODAY.com - HIV scars India's vast population|url = http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/news/health/2005-02-23-aids-india_x.htm|website = usatoday30.usatoday.com|accessdate = 2015-07-18}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Trikone|Trikon]] (later renamed Trikone) is formed by Arvind Kumar and Suvir, and print newsletter established<ref name=\"Orinam_Magazines_and_Journals\">{{cite web |title=Orinam.net: Magazines and Journals |url=http://orinam.net/resources-for/lgbt/magazines-and-journals/ |website=Orinam.net |publisher=Orinam |accessdate=22 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} First issue of [https://books.google.com/books?id=ShaGAAAAIAAJ&dq=editions:0AFLRE73D6sjvLq_NHAv0J6qdOAXvGJhWWK_9K9_9m0XcBse9gppjBR4&lr= Trikon newsletter], editors Arvind Kumar and Suvir (January)<ref name=Shah_Social_Perspectives_Reader>{{cite book |author1=Nayan Shah |authorlink1=Sexuality, Identity, and the Uses of History |editor1-last=Nardi |editor1-first=Peter M |editor2-last=Schneider |editor2-first=Beth E |title=Social Perspectives in Lesbian and Gay Studies: A Reader |publisher=Routledge |isbn=978-1-136-21931-3 |page=489 |edition=2013 |date=2013-09-13 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |author1=Nayan Shah |authorlink1=Sexuality, Identity, and the Uses of History |editor1-last=Hom |editor1-first=Alice |editor2-last=Eng |editor2-first=David |title=Q&A: Queer in Asian America |isbn=978-1-56639-640-0 |page=[https://archive.org/details/qqueerinasianam00engd/page/155 155] |date=1998-08-24 |url=https://archive.org/details/qqueerinasianam00engd/page/155 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book |last1=Bose |first1=Brinda |last2=Bhattacharyya |first2=Subhabrata |title=The Phobic and the Erotic: The Politics of Sexualities in Contemporary India |date=2007 |publisher=Seagull |isbn=978-1-905422-14-2 |page=323 }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Ashok Row Kavi]] discusses his homosexuality in [[Savvy (magazine)|''Savvy'' magazine]] (February)<ref>{{cite book|author=Naisargi N. Dave|title=Queer Activism in India: A Story in the Anthropology of Ethics|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=x6g776i3A34C&pg=PA42|date=8 October 2012|publisher=Duke University Press|isbn=978-0-8223-5319-5|pages=42\u201343}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Hijra conference in Bhopal, India (April)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=QGJ68sbWFVUC&pg=PA108&dq=hijras+bhopal+1986&hl=en Dance, Sex, and Gender: Signs of Identity, Dominance, Defiance, and Desire]</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Trikone marches in [[San Francisco Pride]] parade for the first time ever (June).<ref>Referred to in Sandip Roy's [https://books.google.com/books?id=sOaRLVate9cC&pg=PA168&lpg=PA168&dq=%22a+call+for+rice%22+sandip+roy&source=bl&hl=en#v=onepage A Call For Rice], in [https://books.google.com/books?id=sOaRLVate9cC&pg=PA168&lpg=PA168&dq=%22a+call+for+rice%22+sandip+roy&source=bl&hl=en A Part, Yet Apart: South Asians in America edited by Lavina Dhingra Shankar and Rajini Srikanth]</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://sfpride.org/heritage/1986.html|title=SF Pride {{!}} Heritage {{!}} 1986 International Lesbian & Gay Freedom Day|date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160305230532/http://sfpride.org/heritage/1986.html|archive-date=2016-03-05|access-date=2016-06-06}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Trikone Los Angeles (later [http://www.satrang.org/ Satrang]) formed <!--MN: add founders if available-->(Nov){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Trikone Chicago (later Sangat, and then reformed [http://www.trikonechicago.org/ Trikone Chicago]) formed by [[Ifti Nasim]] (Dec){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|United States}} ''[[Conditions (magazine)|Conditions: Thirteen]]'' publishes interview with Khayal and Utsa, \"There Are, Always Have Been, Always Will Be Lesbians in India\".<ref>{{Cite journal|last=Khayal|last2=Utsa|last3=Heske|first3=Susan|date=1986|editor-last=Utsa|title=There Are, Always Have Been, Always Will Be Lesbians in India|url=http://voices.revealdigital.com/cgi-bin/independentvoices?a=d&d=DCDCDIG19860101.1.147|journal=Conditions|volume=|issue=13|pages=135\u2013146|doi=|issn=0147-8311|oclc=3232386|pmid=|access-date=September 10, 2016|via=Independent Voices}}</ref><ref>[Referenced in [http://library.ucsc.edu/sites/default/files/betweenthelines_0.pdf Between the Lines]</ref>\n* Kanchana researches Hindu text for women loving women references.<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\" />\n* Books\n** {{flagicon|Canada}} ''Flesh and Paper'' by [[Suniti Namjoshi|Suniti Namoshi]] and Gillian Eve Hanscombe<ref>{{Cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=ykaGAAAACAAJ|title=Flesh and Paper|last=Namjoshi|first=Suniti|last2=Hanscombe|first2=Gillian Eve|date=1986|publisher=Ragweed Press|isbn=9780920304648|language=en}}</ref>\n\n'''1987'''\n* {{flagicon|India}}Sneha Sangam gay group forms in Bangalore<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://archive.berkeleysouthasian.org/uploads/8/3/1/3/8313602/queer-history-datebook-06061.pdf|title=The Desi Queer Datebook|last=Newsnotes|date=2006-05-08|access-date=2019-07-10}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Society (magazine)|''Society'']] magazine in India prints a story about Trikone (Jan){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} [[Khush: South Asian Lesbian and Gay Association|Khush]], an organization that created safe spaces for South Asian gays and lesbians in [[Toronto]] was formed (July).<ref name=\"Warner_Never_Going_Back_Again\">Tom Warner, [https://books.google.com/books?isbn=0802084605 ''Never Going Back: A History of Queer Activism in Canada''.]</ref><ref>http://dailyxtra.com/toronto/arts-and-entertainment/khush-show-love Daily Xtra</ref><ref>{{Cite web | url=https://www.facebook.com/events/222815294422388/ | title=Aanmelden of registreren om te bekijken}}</ref><ref name=\"Brown_Canada\">{{Cite web|title = Queer & Trans|url = http://www.browncanada.com/content.php?pg=24&pid=4|website = Brown Canada|accessdate = 2015-04-04|publisher = Council of Agencies Serving South Asians (CASSA)}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Trikon becomes [http://501c3lookup.org/trikone/ incorporated] as Trikone (Nov){{citation needed|date=June 2015}}\n* {{flagicon|India}}Bhopal policewomen Lila and Urmila marry with religious priest and get fired from police job (Dec)<ref>Naisargi N. Dave, [https://books.google.com/books?id=x6g776i3A34C&pg=PA43&lpg=PA43&dq=lila+urmila+lesbian&source=bl&hl=en ''Queer Activism in India: A Story in the Anthropology of Ethics''.]</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Village teachers Aruna Sombhai Jaisinghbhai Gohil, aged 31, and Sudha Amarsinh Mohansinh Ratanwadia, aged 29, entered maitri karar (friendship agreement) before a notary public in 1987 after nine years together<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\" />\n*{{Flagicon|United Kingdom}} London Borough of Ealing Race Equality Unit holds the first London South Asian LGBTQ poetry festival organised by Race Equality Campaigns Officer, [[Poulomi Desai]] with the bookshop, Bogle L'overture in defiance of Section 28<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.janinebooth.com/content/story-section-28|title=The Story of Section 28|last=Janine|date=2014-08-30|website=Janine Booth|language=en|access-date=2019-08-29}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.cityoflondon.gov.uk/things-to-do/london-metropolitan-archives/visitor-information/Documents/21-black-caribbean-community-archives.pdf|title=Archives}}</ref>\n*{{Flagicon|United Kingdom}} SAGALG set up by [https://queerbio.com/wiki/index.php?title=Shivananda_Khan Shivananda Khan] and Poulomi Desai which later becomes Shakti\n* Books\n** ''Between the Lines: An Anthology by Pacific/Asian lesbians of Santa Cruz, California'' includes Anu's chapter \"Sexuality, Lesbianism, and South Asian Feminism\"<ref name=\"AnuBetweenTheLines1987\"/>\n\n'''1988'''\n*{{Flagicon|United Kingdom}} Shakti formed in London by [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=HwxCfUXEq5M Shivananda Khan], [http://www.usurp.org.uk Poulomi Desai], Sunil Gupta, Atul Sarin, Manjit Rooprah, Savi Hensman, Pratibha Parmar - the first South Asian LGBT organisation in Europe (June)<ref name=\"Shivananda_Khan_Culture\">Shivananda Khan, [https://books.google.com/books?id=1RzcAAAAQBAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=shakti&f=false \"Culture, Sexualities, and Identities: Men Who Have Sex with Men in India\"], in Gerald Sullivan and Peter Ackson (eds), ''Gay and Lesbian Asia: Culture, Identity, and Community''.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Trikone (San Francisco), Khush (Toronto), Shakti (London) and Urvashi Vaid make the ''Illustrated Weekly of India''.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=x6g776i3A34C&pg=PA44&lpg=PA44&dq=Illustrated+Weekly+of+India+khush+gay&source=bl&hl=en Queer Activism in India: A Story in the Anthropology of Ethics]</ref> (September)\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} First Shakti Bhangra disco in London organised by [https://queerbio.com/wiki/index.php?title=Shivananda_Khan Shivananda Khan], Poulomi Desai with DJ Ritu. Seed funding given to Shakti by the Ealing Race Equality Unit. (Oct)<ref>{{cite web|title=LSE Library's archive holdings|url=http://archives.lse.ac.uk/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=HCA%2FEPHEMERA%2F721|website=British Library of Political and Economic Science Library Services CalmView|publisher=Shakti|accessdate=11 August 2015}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=http://www.ulme-mini-verlag.de/music2.htm#clubs|title=The Rough Guide to Bhangra|website=www.ulme-mini-verlag.de|access-date=2016-08-21}}</ref>\n<!--* ~Asian Lesbians of Vancouver --><!--MN: add founders if available {{citation needed|date=June 2015}}-->\n<!--* ~Monsoon --> <!--MN: add founders if available {{citation needed|date=June 2015}}-->\n* Gita Darji and Kishori Shah RIP<ref name=\"Bacchetta_Rescaling\" />\n\n'''1989'''\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} ''Khush Kahayal'', newsletter of Khush South Asian gay men of Toronto, is established.<ref name=\"Orinam_Magazines_and_Journals\" /><ref name=\"Brown_Canada\" />\n* {{flagicon|United Kingdom}} ''Shakti Khabar'' published in London.<ref name=Shivananda_Khan_Culture /><ref name=A_People_Stronger /><!--\"People Stronger\" citation references 1988 (pg 51); Shivananda Khan reference indicates 1989 (pg 104) -->\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Dominic d'Souza|Dominic D\u2019Souza]] arrested placed in solitary confinement in India because he is HIV+ (Feb)<ref>[http://thenightchild.blogspot.com/2012/09/my-friend-dominic-trikone-california.html \"My Friend...Dominic\"], published in ''Trikone Magazine'' summer of 2012; republished in the Nightchild Nexus blog.</ref><ref>Ashok Row Kavi and Dinyar Godrej, [http://newint.org/features/1993/12/05/bigots/ \"Bigots Take the Temple\"], ''New Internationalist Magazine'', Issue 250, December 1993.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} Khush organizes Salaam Toronto! Festival (May)<ref>{{Cite web | url=http://archivesfa.library.yorku.ca/fonds/ON00370-f0000522.htm |title = F0522 - Desh Pardesh fonds}}</ref><ref>http://archivescanada.accesstomemory.org/desh-pardesh-2</ref><ref>http://dailyxtra.com/toronto/deshs-mid-life-crisis</ref>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Urvashi Vaid]] becomes Executive Director of the [[National Gay and Lesbian Task Force]] (July)<ref>{{cite web|last1=Vaid|first1=Urvashi|authorlink1=Urvashi Vaid|title=Urvashi Vaid: Curriculum Vitae|url=http://urvashivaid.net/wp/?page_id=578|website=Urvashi Vaid|accessdate=24 June 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} [http://asaap.ca/about/our-history/ South Asian AIDS Coalition] (later ASAAP) formed in Toronto (Jul)<ref>http://munkschool.utoronto.ca/cphs/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/CPHS-JP-2010-11.pdf pg6</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} Khush and gay Asians organize Unity Among Asians conference in Toronto<ref>{{cite book|author=Tom Warner|title=Never Going Back: A History of Queer Activism in Canada|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=mdo-95q2EYgC&pg=PA326|year=2002|publisher=University of Toronto Press|isbn=978-0-8020-8460-6|pages=326\u2013}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Canada}} \"Salaam Toronto\" conference<ref name=\"Warner_Never_Going_Back_Again\" />\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[SALGA NYC|South Asian Gay Association]] (SAGA, later renamed SALGA) founded in New York City<ref name=\":0\" />\n* ''Sojourner'' publishes \"Breaking Silence: Coming Out in India\", Sharmeen Islam<ref>{{cite web|title=Black and Minority Lesbian's Resource List|url=http://www.lesbianinformationservice.org/blackrl.htm|publisher=Lesbian Information Service}}</ref>\n* South Asian Gay Association formed by 12 South Asians<ref>[http://dev-dl-pa.home.nyu.edu/tamimentapa/?q=node/189 SALGA-NYC, Serving the Queer Desi Community Report]</ref>\n\n==1990s==\n'''1990'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} Red Rose Meetings start in New Delhi for gay men<ref name=\"Joseph_Social_Work_Practice\">{{cite book|last1=Joseph|first1=Sherry|title=Social Work Practice and Men Who Have Sex With Men|date=2005 |publisher=SAGE|isbn=978-0761933526|url=https://books