-first-lgbt-youth-leadership-summit-held-in-mumbai/|website=Mission for Indian Gay & Lesbian Empowerment|accessdate=21 October 2014}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} In July 2014 first book on [[genderqueer]] in Tamil and first Tamil book on LGBTQIA from Srishti Madurai was released by BJP's state general secretary [[Vanathi Srinivasan]] at the Hindu spiritual service foundation's sixth service fair, Chennai<ref>[http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/Its-a-great-honour-to-be-awarded-for-book-on-gender-variants-Gopi-Shankar/articleshow/38769130.cms \"It's a great honour to be awarded for book on gender variants: Gopi Shankar\"], ''The Times of India'', July 21, 2014.</ref><ref>http://www.asianage.com/india/bjp-supports-tn-leader-book-lgbt-157</ref><ref>Gladwin Emmanuel,[http://www.mumbaimirror.com/news/india/BJP-leader-launches-LGBT-rights-book-in-TN/articleshow/38157614.cms \"BJP Leader Launches LGBT Rights Book in TN\"], ''Mumbai Mirror'', 11 July 2014.</ref>\n* {{flagicon|UK}} British born gay doctor, Dr Nazim Mahmood, takes his own life after being confronted about his sexuality by his family, leading the launch of the charity [[Naz and Matt Foundation]] <ref>{{cite news|title=Interview: Matt Ogston's Partner Took His Own Life After Coming Out As Gay|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=gvg7N_tlRng|accessdate=18 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=December 9, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Naz Mahmood death: Support group for gay Asians created|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/uk-30563537/naz-mahmood-death-support-group-for-gay-asians-created|accessdate=18 October 2019|work=BBC News|date=December 20, 2014}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=My boyfriend killed himself because his family couldn't accept that he was gay|url=https://www.theguardian.com/lifeandstyle/2015/mar/21/my-boyfriend-killed-himself-because-his-family-couldnt-accept-that-he-was-gay|accessdate=18 October 2019|work=The Guardian|date=March 21, 2015}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Supreme Court of India rules in the [[National Legal Services Authority v. Union of India|NALSA vs. Union of India]] case, declaring that transgender people have all rights granted by the Indian constitution, the right to determine their gender (man, woman, third-gender) regardless of surgery, hormones or attire<ref>{{Cite web|url = http://www.lawyerscollective.org/updates/supreme-court-recognises-the-right-to-determine-and-express-ones-gender-grants-legal-status-to-third-gender.html|title = Supreme Court recognises the right to determine and express one's gender; grants legal status to 'third gender'|date = April 17, 2014|accessdate = October 20, 2014|website = Lawyers Collective|last = |first = }}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}}In October 2014, A month long celebrations commenced to celebrate LGBT History Month at The American College with a lecture on Gender and sexual minorities organised by Srishti Madurai.<ref name=\"ReferenceA\"/>\n* {{flagicon|United States}} Aaditi Hardikar named first woman of color as White House LGBT Liaison <ref>{{cite web|last1=Toce|first1=Sarah|title=First Woman of Color to Serve White House as LGBT Liaison|url=http://theseattlelesbian.com/first-woman-of-color-to-serve-white-house-as-lgbt-liaison/|website=The Seattle Lesbian|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n* Books\n** {{flagicon|India}} ''Maraikappata Pakkangal'' (Hidden Pages) is the first book on LGBTQIA & Gendervariants in Tamil penned by [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] of Srishti Madurai.\n\n'''2015'''\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Madhu Kinnar]], India's first transgender mayor and a member of the Dalit community, elected as mayor of [[Raigarh]], [[Chhattisgarh]] (Jan)<ref>{{cite news| first=Ashutosh| last=Bhardwaj| url=http://indianexpress.com/article/india/india-others/third-option-transgender-is-raigarh-mayor/ |title=Third option: Transgender is Raigarh mayor |work=The Indian Express |date=January 7, 2015}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} India's [[Rajya Sabha]] passes the [[Rights of Transgender Persons Bill, 2014]], paving the way for a potential future law (Apr)<ref>{{cite news|author1=Jatin Gandhi|author2=Smriti Kak Ramachandran|title=RS passes Bill on transgender rights|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/national/rajya-sabha-passes-private-bill-on-transgenders/article7138056.ece|accessdate=22 June 2015|work=The Hindu|date=April 25, 2015}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Manabi Bandyopadhyay]] celebrated as India's first openly transgender college principal (May)<ref>{{cite news|last1=Dasgupta|first1=Priyanka|title=India gets its first transgender college principal|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/India-gets-its-first-transgender-college-principal/articleshow/47436427.cms|accessdate=22 June 2015|work=The Times of India|agency=TNN|date=May 27, 2015}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} First ad featuring two lesbians in India<ref>{{cite web |last=E-Li |title=Watch The First Indian Ad Featuring A Lesbian Couple|url=http://www.lezbelib.com/tv-movies/watch-the-first-indian-ad-featuring-a-lesbian-couple|website=Lezbelib|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Dalit queer activists Dhrubo Jyoti, Akhil Khang, and Dhiren Borisa speak out at Delhi Pride Parade (Nov)<ref>{{Cite web|url=http://orinam.net/dalit-queer-pride-at-delhi-queer-pride-2015/|title=Dalit Queer Pride at Delhi Queer Pride 2015|date=Nov 30, 2015|website=Orinam|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204003404/http://orinam.net/dalit-queer-pride-at-delhi-queer-pride-2015/|archive-date=2015-12-04|url-status=dead|access-date=April 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=SsQIq2_Di7A|title=Dalit Queer Pride at Delhi Queer Pride 2015|last=|first=|date=November 30, 2015|website=YouTube|access-date=April 15, 2017}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://drambedkarbooks.com/2016/05/02/dalit-history-month-dalit-queer-proud/|title=Dalit History Month \u2013 Dalit, Queer, Proud|date=2016-05-02|website=Dr. B. R. Ambedkar's Caravan|access-date=2017-04-15}}</ref>\n*  {{flagicon|Nepal}} Nepal issues its first \"third-gender\" passport<ref>{{cite journal|last1=Pandey|first1=Lekhanath|title=Passports for third gender|journal=The Himalayan Times|date=August 6, 2015|url=http://thehimalayantimes.com/kathmandu/passports-for-third-gender/|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite journal|last1=Plucinska|first1=Joanna|title=Nepal Is the Latest Country to Acknowledge Transgender Citizens on Its Passports|journal=Time|date=August 11, 2015|url=http://time.com/3992104/nepal-passport-third-gender-transgender/|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref><ref name=Hinduism_Today_2016>{{cite journal|last1=Shekar|first1=Madhuri|last2=Venkatachalam|first2=Hari|title=Tradition: Same-Sex Marriage and Hinduism|journal=Hinduism Today|date=January 2016|volume=January/February/March 2016|url=http://www.hinduismtoday.com/modules/smartsection/item.php?itemid=5650|accessdate=22 December 2015}}</ref>\n*  {{flagicon|Nepal}} Nepal explicitly puts equal rights and freedom from discrimination for LGBT individuals in the constitution<ref name=Hinduism_Today_2016 /><ref>{{cite news|last1=R|first1=Vansundara|title=Nepal's New LGBT Non-Discriminatory Laws Leave India Far Behind|url=http://www.idiva.com/news-work-life/nepal-brings-in-new-lgbt-non-discriminatory-laws-that-leave-india-far-behind/15092282|accessdate=22 December 2015|date=September 22, 2015}}</ref> \n* {{flagicon|India}}Jawaharlal Nehru University, New Delhi, started offering \"Others\" option in the gender column of the application form. Due to the efforts of [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] of Srishti Madurai and the student community at JNU.<ref name=\"One Who Fights For an Other\"/>\n*  {{flagicon|India}} Srishti Madurai urged [[Lok Sabha]] MP's  to include [[intersex]] people in a bill to protect the rights of trans people.<ref>http://www.newindianexpress.com/states/tamil_nadu/List-Intersex-in-Transgender-Bill-Urges-NGO/2015/08/29/article2998899.ece</ref><ref>http://www.pinknews.co.uk/2015/08/29/india-urged-to-include-intersex-people-in-bill-protecting-trans-rights/</ref>\n* Books\n** {{flagicon|United States}} ''Don't Let Him Know'' by [[Sandip Roy (author)|Sandip Roy]]<ref>{{Cite book|title = Don't Let Him Know|last = Roy|first = Sandip|publisher = Bloomsbury|year = 2015|isbn = 9781620408988|location = |pages = |url = }}</ref>\n** {{flagicon|United States}} [https://storify.com/movingtruths/moving-truth-s-queer-and-transgender-desi-writings Moving Truth(s): Queer and Transgender Desi Writings on Family], an anthology of writing by queer and transgender Desis about family, edited by Aparajeeta Duttchoudhury and Rukie Hartman<ref>{{cite book|editor1-last=Duttchoudhury|editor1-first=Aparajeeta|editor2-last=Hartman|editor2-first=Rukie|title=Moving Truth(s): Queer and Transgender Desi Writings on Family|date=April 2015|publisher=Flying Chickadee|isbn=978-0989626354|url=http://www.flyingchickadee.com/books.html|accessdate=18 August 2015}}</ref>\n* Film\n**{{flagicon|India}} The film ''[[Naanu Avanalla...Avalu]]'', about the life of [[Living Smile Vidya]], won two awards at the [[62nd National Film Awards]]<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.business-standard.com/article/pti-stories/nat-film-awards-ceremony-to-be-held-on-may-3-every-year-soni-112050300505_1.html|title=Nat Film Awards ceremony to be held on May 3 every year: Soni|last=India|first=Press Trust of|date=2012-05-03|work=Business Standard India|access-date=2017-04-15}}</ref><ref>{{Cite news|url=http://indianexpress.com/article/entertainment/bollywood/62nd-national-film-awards-winners-haider-wins-five-queen-two/|title=62nd National Film Awards' winners: 'Haider' wins five, Kangana Ranaut's 'Queen' two|date=2015-03-24|work=The Indian Express|access-date=2017-04-15|language=en-US}}</ref>\n** {{flagicon|Pakistan}} First ever movie on Pakistan's hidden LGBT community: ''[[Poshida: Hidden LGBT Pakistan]]''<ref>{{cite news|title=First ever movie on Pakistan's hidden LGBT community|url=http://en.dailypakistan.com.pk/lifestyle/first-ever-movie-on-pakistans-hidden-lgbt-community-594/|accessdate=22 September 2015|publisher=Daily Pakistan Global|date=August 14, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=McCray|first1=Rebecca|title=Hidden in Plain Sight: Documentary Sheds Light on Pakistan's LGBT Community|url=http://www.takepart.com/article/2015/08/17/new-documentary-exposes-challenges-faced-pakistan-s-lgbt-community|website=takepart|accessdate=22 September 2015}}</ref>\n\n'''2016'''\n* {{flagicon|United States}} [[Nergis Mavalvala]], a queer Pakistani American MIT astrophysicist, was part of the team of scientists who [[First observation of gravitational waves|observed gravitational waves for the first time]]<ref>{{cite journal | collaboration = LIGO Scientific Collaboration and Virgo Collaboration | last1 = Abbott | first1 = Benjamin P.  |title=Observation of Gravitational Waves from a Binary Black Hole Merger |journal=[[Phys. Rev. Lett.]] |volume=116 | issue = 6 |pages=061102 |year=2016 |doi=10.1103/PhysRevLett.116.061102 | arxiv=1602.03837 | pmid=26918975|bibcode=2016PhRvL.116f1102A }}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Nergis Mavalvala: The Karachiite who went on to detect Einstein's gravitational waves|url=http://www.dawn.com/news/1239270|accessdate=14 February 2016|work=Dawn|date=February 13, 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite magazine|last=Vijaysree|first=Venkatraman|title=Just Herself|magazine=Science|date=June 1, 2012|accessdate=14 February 2016|url=http://www.sciencemag.org/careers/2012/06/just-herself}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} On March 6, 2016 Srishti Madurai's new website was launched by Dalit activist and Ambedkarite Ma. Venkatesan from BJP in the presence of Central Minister [[Pon Radhakrishnan]], Vanathi Srinivasan, [[Aravindan Neelakandan]], [[Joe D'Cruz]] and scores of [[Rashtriya Swayamsevak Sangh]] volunteers at Chennai.<ref>http://www.firstpost.com/living/rss-flip-flop-on-homosexuality-indicates-gay-men-in-india-remain-in-exile-writes-ashok-row-kavi-2685296.html</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]], a 25 years old gender activist made a bid to contest as one of the youngest candidates in the Tamil Nadu Assembly election and also the first openly [[Intersex]] & [[Genderqueer]] person to do so. Ze secured 14th place out of 21 candidates by securing 1% vote.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.thehindu.com/todays-paper/tp-national/tp-tamilnadu/intersex-person-to-contest-from-madurai-north/article8539185.ece |title=Intersex person to contest from Madurai North - TAMIL NADU |newspaper=The Hindu |date=2016-04-30 |accessdate=2016-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Share on FacebookShare on Twitter |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/elections-2016/tamil-nadu-elections-2016/news/3rd-gender-gets-a-new-champion-in-Tamil-Nadu-poll-ring/articleshow/51935940.cms |title=3rd gender gets a new champion in Tamil Nadu poll ring - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2016-04-22 |accessdate=2016-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|author=Share on FacebookShare on Twitter |url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/chennai/Intersex-candidate-alleges-harassment/articleshow/52197962.cms |title=Intersex candidate alleges harassment - Times of India |publisher=Timesofindia.indiatimes.com |date=2016-05-10 |accessdate=2016-05-22}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/intersex-person-contesting-tn-polls-ze-wants-change-your-mind-sexual-minorities-42103 |title=This intersex person is contesting TN polls, 'ze' wants to change your mind on sexual minorities |publisher=The News Minute |date=2016-04-24 |accessdate=2016-05-22}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|Bangladesh}} [[Xulhaz Mannan]] and Tanay Fahim murdered in Dhaka, Bangladesh<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/world/2016/apr/25/editor-bangladesh-first-lgbt-magazine-killed-reports-say-roopbaan|title=Editor of Bangladesh's first and only LGBT magazine killed|last=Gani|first=Saad Hammadi Aisha|date=2016-04-25|newspaper=The Guardian|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077|access-date=2016-04-26}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://humanism.org.uk/2016/04/25/more-individuals-hacked-to-death-in-bangladesh-as-islamists-broaden-their-hit-list/|title=More individuals hacked to death in Bangladesh as Islamists broaden their hit list|website=British Humanist Association|access-date=2016-04-26}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} On July 15, 2016 For the first time Srishti Madurai along with [[Tamil Nadu Theological Seminary]] in Madurai a conglomerate of the [[Church of South India]] (CSI), and the [[Lutheran Church]] organised an Introductory seminar for church pastors on LGBT issues.<ref>http://www.thenewsminute.com/article/awesome-tamil-nadu-seminary-teaching-pastors-accept-lgbt-community-46577</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} [[Gopi Shankar Madurai]] of Srishti Madurai shortlisted for [[The Commonwealth]] Youth Worker Award as regional finalist for Asia.<ref>http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/madurai/Gender-rights-activist-shortlisted-for-international-award/articleshow/54968127.cms</ref><ref>http://thecommonwealth.org/media/news/finalists-2016-commonwealth-youth-worker-awards-announced</ref>\n\n'''2017'''\n* {{flagicon|Pakistan}} Pakistan issues first passport with transgender category.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Maizland|first1=Lindsay|title=Pakistan just issued its first passport with a transgender category|url=https://www.vox.com/world/2017/6/23/15861620/pakistan-transgender-passport-human-rights|website=Vox|accessdate=29 June 2017}}</ref>\n* {{flagicon|India}} Indian Supreme Court declares privacy is an intrinsic right, and that sexual orientation is an essential attribute of privacy.<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/india/right-to-privacy-verdict-a-fundamental-shift-on-gay-rights/articleshow/60215853.cms|title=Right to privacy verdict: A fundamental shift on gay rights - Times of India|work=The Times of India|access-date=2017-09-05}}</ref>\n\n'''2018'''\n*{{flagicon|United Kingdom}} First South Asian LGBTI Conference held at Queen Elizabeth Hospital Birmingham, organised by [https://BritishAsianLGBTI.org British Asian LGBTI], Finding A Voice and Gaysian Faces on 28th July 2018, with eighteen speakers, two films (Sisak and Planchette) <ref>https://britishasianlgbti.org/south-asian-lgbti-conference/| South Asian LGBTI Conference</ref> <ref>https://britishasianlgbti.org/south-asian-lgbti-conference/south-Asian-LGBTI_conference-2018| South Asian LGBTI Conference 2018</ref> \n\n*{{flagicon|India}} Indian Supreme Court [[LGBT rights in India#Contemporary times|legalizes gay sex]] and reads down Section 377 of the Indian Penal Code, which criminalized same-sex relations. India's Outgoing chief justice Dipak Misra, regarding the ruling, said: \"Criminalising carnal intercourse is irrational, arbitrary and manifestly unconstitutional.\"<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.bbc.com/news/world-asia-india-45429664|title=Historic India ruling legalises gay sex|date=2018-09-06|access-date=2019-04-08|language=en-GB}}</ref>\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Timeline of Asian and Pacific Islander Diasporic LGBT History]]\n* [[Timeline of African and diasporic LGBT history]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n{{LGBT history}}\n\n[[Category:History of South Asia]]\n[[Category:LGBT history in India]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Bangladesh]]\n[[Category:LGBT in India]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Pakistan]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Nepal]]\n[[Category:LGBT in Sri Lanka]]\n[[Category:LGBT timelines|South Asia]]\n", "name_user": "Arvtoronto", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Timeline_of_South_Asian_and_diasporic_LGBT_history"}
{"title_page": "Diego Tryno", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Diego Tryno\n| image            = Diego Tryno.jpeg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Diego Tryno at StarFm\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Diego Tinotenda Chikombeka\n| Also_known_as    = Mr Coffee Please, The Future Billionaire\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1998|2|05}}\n| origin           = [[Harare]], Zimbabwe\n| genre            = [[Urban Contemporary]]\n| occupation       = Musician, recording artist, [[rapper]]\n| years_active     = 2014 \u2013 present\n| associated_acts  = \n| label            = Independent {{small|(current)}}\n}}\n\n'''Diego Tinotenda Chikombeka''' (born {{birth date|1998|2|5}}), professionally known as '''Diego Tryno'''<ref name=Bulawayo24>{{Cite web|url=https://bulawayo24.com/index-id-news-sc-national-byo-171686.html|title=Coffee Lover 'Diego Tryno' Promises Epidemic|website=Bulawayo24 News|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pindula.co.zw/Diego_Tryno|title=Diego Tryno - Pindula|website=www.pindula.co.zw|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> is a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[urban contemporary]] and [[hip-hop]] musician. He is also known locally by stage names including \"Mr. Coffee Please\" and \"The Future Billionaire\".<ref>Norman,Chiutsi (2016). ''Catch up with Zimbabwean Diego Chikombeka'', p. 32. Zambezi Magazine, Harare. {{ISBN|410: 1674938034}}.</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nDiego was born in [[Mutare]], Zimbabwe at the [[Sakubva]] District Hospital.<ref name =newsguard>{{Cite web | url=http://newsguard.co.zw/2019/12/02/manicaland-artiste-defies-odds/ |title = Manicaland Artiste defies odds|date = 2019-12-02}}</ref> He was the first child born to his mother Fungisai Kanjera and his father Christopher Chikombeka. While attending primary school, he moved to [[Zvishavane]] temporarily and moved back to Mutare to finish his primary education. He attended Chikanga High School before moving to [[Harare]], and finished high school at Living Waters High School.<ref name=storify>{{Cite web | url=https://www.storifynews.com/the-curious-tale-of-the-southern-african-star-diego-and-his-industry/ |title = The Curious Tale of the Southern African star Diego and his industry &#124; Storify News|date = 2019-11-21}}</ref> During his schooling, Tryno practiced music privately, as his parents were not tolerant of his decision to pursue music.<ref name=newsday2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.co.zw/2019/10/diego-known-abroad-stranger-at-home/|title = Diego: Known abroad, stranger at home|date = 2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n== Music career ==\nHe once did [[Zimdancehall]]music under the name Ricky D before switching to hip-hop.<ref name=\"newsguard\" /> Tryno recorded his first hip-hop track in 2014 called \"Go Diego Go\" and won his first regional award at Zambezi Music Awards the same year.<ref name=newsday1>{{Cite web|url = https://www.newsday.co.zw/2019/08/musicians-fight-against-graft|title = Musician's fight against graft|date = 26 August 2019}}</ref> In 2015 he did his first live show at Summer Jam followed by \"I wanna see you\" dance tour.<ref name=\"Bulawayo24\" /> He does music in [[English language|English]], [[Shona language|Shona]], and [[Northern Ndebele language|Ndebele]] and his first Shona track was in 2015 when he featured in a song with singer TC.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://zimmagazine.com/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-diego-tryno-zimmagazine/ |title = 10 Things you didn't know about Diego Tryno-Zimmagazine|date = 2019-09-17}}</ref><ref name=\"newsguard\" /> Tryno has worked with regional and international producers in the production of his music. One notable producer was Dry AFM from Botswana who contributed in the mixing of his song Yolo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lounge263.co.zw/diegotryno/|title=Diego Tryno Dates Botswana Producer|last=Lounge263|date=2016-10-20|website=Lounge263 Mag|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722005012/https://www.lounge263.co.zw/diegotryno/|archive-date=2019-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 ===\nIn October 2018, Tryno released his debut album ''Lazarus (Age Volume 1)'' which was the first contribution of his ''All Generations Entwined'' project.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://blownaija.com/e-news-diego-tryno-and-all-generations-entwined-volumes-1-5-age-vol-1-5/|title = [E-News] Diego Tryno and All Generations Entwined volumes 1-5 (Age Vol 1-5)|last = Blow|first = Baba|date = 15 September 2019|website = Blow Naija|language = en|access-date = 15 November 2019}}</ref> The album was released in collaboration with Zimbabwean Hip-hop artist Ti Gonzi's album \"Best Mero\" on the same day and venue and the debut was mistakenly believed to be a Gospel Album.<ref name=\"Hallelujahmag\">{{cite web|url=https://hallelujahmag.com/2019/12/05/musicians-blind-to-genre-identification-for-evangelisms-sake-the-case-of-diego-tryno/|title=Musicians blind to genre identification for evangelisms sake|work=Hallelujahmag|date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.co.zw/i-sing-hipu-hopu-not-hip-hop-ti-gonzi/|title=I sing hipu hopu not hip hop \u2013 Ti Gonzi|last=H-Metro|website=H-Metro|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref> Tryno's debut album was considerably circulated on radio stations including Star Fm, ZiFm, Hevoi Fm in Masvingo and SA's Metro Fm.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://globenews24.online/broken-promises-threatens-artistes-career/ | title=Broken promises threatens artiste's career &#124; Globenews24}}</ref> After his first album, Tryno attempted to mix urban contemporary, sungura, gospel, and Zimbabwean traditional music.<ref name=\"oyosnews\">{{cite web|url=http://oyos.news/make-way-for-the-new-hip-hop-influencers-diego-tryno-on-an-anti-graft-note|title = Make way for the new Hip-hop influencers- Diego Tryno on an anti-graft note - OyOsNews - all your Zim Celebrity News|last = Codingest|date = 11 November 2019|website = OyOsNews|language = en|access-date = 15 November 2019}}</ref> October 30, 2018, Diego released his debut video \"Mabvuta\" live on ZiFm Stereo and Zimbabwe's [[ZBC TV]].\n\n=== 2019 ===\nIn year 2019 Tryno released his single ''Cooler Box'' which made its way to Zimbabwean radio charts and he promised to release his sophomore album ''Stories (Age Vol 2)'' which he failed to release on the promised date and it attracted negative feedback from his fans.<ref>https://www.thehararetimes.com/zim-hip-hop-artist-diego-tryno-delays-album-release-manager-blames-power-cuts/</ref> December 2019 he dismissed rumors about a tour in Kenya and cancelled any other rumored tours.<ref>https://koenzagh.com/2019/12/17/diego-tryno-cancels-xmas-tour-clears-rumours/</ref>\n\n== Nationality and identity ==\nTryno was forbade to do music by his family and because of the ban he did music privately and he did not identify as Zimbabwean.<ref name=\"storify\" /> He engaged with radio station managers in other countries for airplay and marketing. In South Africa they marketed him as South African on radios and online mediums and in Zambia they marketed him as Zambian.<ref name=\"storify\" /> He came out publicly as Zimbabwean in 2018.<ref name=\"newsday2\" />\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Albums ===\n* Lazarus (Age Volume 1) (2018)\n\n=== Singles ===\n* Lazarus\n* Mabvuta\n* Sungai\n* Hell Naw\n* Yolo\n* Mama\n\n== Videography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n!Ref\n|-\n|2018\n|Mabvuta\n|Media Empire\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|Sungai ft Dj Monte\n|Denford Mkasi\n|\n|}\n\n== Awards and Nominations ==\n{| class=\" wikitable plainrowheaders \" style=\"table-layout: fixed; margin-right: 0; \"\n|+\n! scope=\"col\" |Year\n! scope=\"col\" |Ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" |Award\n! scope=\"col\" |Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2014\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Zambezi Music Awards<ref name=\"Hallelujahmag\" /><ref name=\"newsday1\" /><ref name=\"oyosnews\" />\n|Best Upcoming\n|style=\"background: #99FF99; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center; \" class=\"yes table-yes2\" |Won\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of songs, with selected chart positions, showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 style=\"width:22em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=3 | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | Star Fm top 50|Zim<br />\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | Yami Fm  Top 10|UK<br />\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | Hevoi Fm top 50|Zim<br />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Lazarus\"\n|| 2016\n| \u2014 || 8 || \u2014\n| \"Single\"<br />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|  \"Coolerbox\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://nehandaradio.com/2019/12/06/zim-hip-hop-artist-diego-tryno-delays-album-release-manager-blames-power-cuts/ | title=Zim hip-hop artist Diego Tryno delays album release.... Manager blames power cuts| date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n|| 2018\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| ''Lazarus (Age vol1)''<br />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|  \"Mama\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://raddio.net/218582-yami-radio/ |title = Yami Radio - United Kingdom - Listen Live Online Free Radio Station}}</ref>\n|| 2019\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| \"Single\"<br />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.afro.video/en/artist/diego-tryno/ Video]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6FKTP34EKFU Bio]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zrsbl9UXGcw Interview on Star FM]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DEfrfvZJq88 Interview on Hevoi FM]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tryno, Diego}}\n[[Category:Zimbabwean musicians]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "text_old": "{{Orphan|date=January 2020}}\n\n{{Infobox musical artist\n| name             = Diego Tryno\n| image            = Diego Tryno.jpeg\n| image_size       = \n| caption          = Diego Tryno at StarFm\n| background       = solo_singer\n| birth_name       = Diego Tinotenda Chikombeka\n| Also_known_as    = Mr Coffee Please, The Future Billionaire\n| birth_date       = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1998|2|05}}\n| origin           = [[Harare]], Zimbabwe\n| genre            = [[Urban Contemporary]]\n| occupation       = Musician, recording artist, [[rapper]]\n| years_active     = 2014 \u2013 present\n| associated_acts  = \n| label            = Independent {{small|(current)}}\n}}\n\n'''Diego Tinotenda Chikombeka''' (born {{birth date|1998|2|5}}), professionally known as '''Diego Tryno'''<ref name=Bulawayo24>{{Cite web|url=https://bulawayo24.com/index-id-news-sc-national-byo-171686.html|title=Coffee Lover 'Diego Tryno' Promises Epidemic|website=Bulawayo24 News|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.pindula.co.zw/Diego_Tryno|title=Diego Tryno - Pindula|website=www.pindula.co.zw|access-date=15 November 2019}}</ref> is a [[Zimbabwe]]an [[urban contemporary]] and [[hip-hop]] musician. He is also known locally by stage names including \"Mr. Coffee Please\" and \"The Future Billionaire\".<ref>Norman,Chiutsi (2016). ''Catch up with Zimbabwean Diego Chikombeka'', p. 32. Zambezi Magazine, Harare. {{ISBN|410: 1674938034}}.</ref>\n\n== Early life ==\nDiego was born in [[Mutare]], Zimbabwe at the [[Sakubva]] District Hospital.<ref name =newsguard>{{Cite web | url=http://newsguard.co.zw/2019/12/02/manicaland-artiste-defies-odds/ |title = Manicaland Artiste defies odds|date = 2019-12-02}}</ref> He was the first child born to his mother Fungisai Kanjera and his father Christopher Chikombeka. While attending primary school, he moved to [[Zvishavane]] temporarily and moved back to Mutare to finish his primary education. He attended Chikanga High School before moving to [[Harare]], and finished high school at Living Waters High School.<ref name=storify>{{Cite web | url=https://www.storifynews.com/the-curious-tale-of-the-southern-african-star-diego-and-his-industry/ |title = The Curious Tale of the Southern African star Diego and his industry &#124; Storify News|date = 2019-11-21}}</ref> During his schooling, Tryno practiced music privately, as his parents were not tolerant of his decision to pursue music.<ref name=newsday2>{{Cite web|url=https://www.newsday.co.zw/2019/10/diego-known-abroad-stranger-at-home/|title = Diego: Known abroad, stranger at home|date = 2019-10-17}}</ref>\n\n== Music career ==\nHe once did [[Zimdancehall]]music under the name Ricky D before switching to hip-hop.<ref name=\"newsguard\" /> Tryno recorded his first hip-hop track in 2014 called \"Go Diego Go\" and won his first regional award at Zambezi Music Awards the same year.<ref name=newsday1>{{Cite web|url = https://www.newsday.co.zw/2019/08/musicians-fight-against-graft|title = Musician's fight against graft|date = 26 August 2019}}</ref> In 2015 he did his first live show at Summer Jam followed by \"I wanna see you\" dance tour.<ref name=\"Bulawayo24\" /> He does music in [[English language|English]], [[Shona language|Shona]], and [[Northern Ndebele language|Ndebele]] and his first Shona track was in 2015 when he featured in a song with singer TC.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://zimmagazine.com/10-things-you-didnt-know-about-diego-tryno-zimmagazine/ |title = 10 Things you didn't know about Diego Tryno-Zimmagazine|date = 2019-09-17}}</ref><ref name=\"newsguard\" /> Tryno has worked with regional and international producers in the production of his music. One notable producer was Dry AFM from Botswana who contributed in the mixing of his song Yolo.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.lounge263.co.zw/diegotryno/|title=Diego Tryno Dates Botswana Producer|last=Lounge263|date=2016-10-20|website=Lounge263 Mag|language=en-US|access-date=2019-07-21|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190722005012/https://www.lounge263.co.zw/diegotryno/|archive-date=2019-07-22|url-status=dead}}</ref>\n\n=== 2018 ===\nIn October 2018, Tryno released his debut album ''Lazarus (Age Volume 1)'' which was the first contribution of his ''All Generations Entwined'' project.<ref>{{Cite web|url = https://blownaija.com/e-news-diego-tryno-and-all-generations-entwined-volumes-1-5-age-vol-1-5/|title = [E-News] Diego Tryno and All Generations Entwined volumes 1-5 (Age Vol 1-5)|last = Blow|first = Baba|date = 15 September 2019|website = Blow Naija|language = en|access-date = 15 November 2019}}</ref> The album was released in collaboration with Zimbabwean Hip-hop artist Ti Gonzi's album \"Best Mero\" on the same day and venue and the debut was mistakenly believed to be a Gospel Album.<ref name=\"Hallelujahmag\">{{cite web|url=https://hallelujahmag.com/2019/12/05/musicians-blind-to-genre-identification-for-evangelisms-sake-the-case-of-diego-tryno/|title=Musicians blind to genre identification for evangelisms sake|work=Hallelujahmag|date=2019-12-05}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.hmetro.co.zw/i-sing-hipu-hopu-not-hip-hop-ti-gonzi/|title=I sing hipu hopu not hip hop \u2013 Ti Gonzi|last=H-Metro|website=H-Metro|language=en-GB|access-date=2019-07-21}}</ref> Tryno's debut album was considerably circulated on radio stations including Star Fm, ZiFm, Hevoi Fm in Masvingo and SA's Metro Fm.<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://globenews24.online/broken-promises-threatens-artistes-career/ | title=Broken promises threatens artiste's career &#124; Globenews24}}</ref> After his first album, Tryno attempted to mix urban contemporary, sungura, gospel, and Zimbabwean traditional music.<ref name=\"oyosnews\">{{cite web|url=http://oyos.news/make-way-for-the-new-hip-hop-influencers-diego-tryno-on-an-anti-graft-note|title = Make way for the new Hip-hop influencers- Diego Tryno on an anti-graft note - OyOsNews - all your Zim Celebrity News|last = Codingest|date = 11 November 2019|website = OyOsNews|language = en|access-date = 15 November 2019}}</ref> October 30, 2018, Diego released his debut video \"Mabvuta\" live on ZiFm Stereo and Zimbabwe's [[ZBC TV]].\n\n=== 2019 ===\nIn 2019 Tryno released his single ''Cooler Box'' which made its way to Zimbabwean radio charts and he promised to release his sophomore album ''Stories (Age Vol 2)'' which he failed to release on the promised date and it attracted negative feedback from his fans.<ref>https://www.thehararetimes.com/zim-hip-hop-artist-diego-tryno-delays-album-release-manager-blames-power-cuts/</ref> December 2019 he dismissed rumors about a tour in Kenya and cancelled any other rumored tours.<ref>https://koenzagh.com/2019/12/17/diego-tryno-cancels-xmas-tour-clears-rumours/</ref>\n\n== Nationality and identity ==\nTryno was forbade to do music by his family and because of the ban he did music privately and he did not identify as Zimbabwean.<ref name=\"storify\" /> He engaged with radio station managers in other countries for airplay and marketing. In South Africa they marketed him as South African on radios and online mediums and in Zambia they marketed him as Zambian.<ref name=\"storify\" /> He came out publicly as Zimbabwean in 2018.<ref name=\"newsday2\" />\n\n== Discography ==\n=== Albums ===\n* Lazarus (Age Volume 1) (2018)\n\n=== Singles ===\n* Lazarus\n* Mabvuta\n* Sungai\n* Hell Naw\n* Yolo\n* Mama\n\n== Videography ==\n{| class=\"wikitable\"\n|+\n!Year\n!Title\n!Director\n!Ref\n|-\n|2018\n|Mabvuta\n|Media Empire\n|\n|-\n|2019\n|Sungai ft Dj Monte\n|Denford Mkasi\n|\n|}\n\n== Awards and Nominations ==\n{| class=\" wikitable plainrowheaders \" style=\"table-layout: fixed; margin-right: 0; \"\n|+\n! scope=\"col\" |Year\n! scope=\"col\" |Ceremony\n! scope=\"col\" |Award\n! scope=\"col\" |Result\n|-\n| rowspan=\"2\" |2014\n| rowspan=\"2\" |Zambezi Music Awards<ref name=\"Hallelujahmag\" /><ref name=\"newsday1\" /><ref name=\"oyosnews\" />\n|Best Upcoming\n|style=\"background: #99FF99; color: black; vertical-align: middle; text-align: center; \" class=\"yes table-yes2\" |Won\n|}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center;\"\n|+ List of songs, with selected chart positions, showing year released and album name\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 style=\"width:22em;\" | Title\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 | Year\n! scope=\"col\" colspan=3 | Peak chart positions\n! scope=\"col\" rowspan=2 | Album\n|-\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | Star Fm top 50|Zim<br />\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | Yami Fm  Top 10|UK<br />\n! scope=\"col\" style=\"width:3em;font-size:90%;\" | Hevoi Fm top 50|Zim<br />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| \"Lazarus\"\n|| 2016\n| \u2014 || 8 || \u2014\n| \"Single\"<br />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|  \"Coolerbox\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://nehandaradio.com/2019/12/06/zim-hip-hop-artist-diego-tryno-delays-album-release-manager-blames-power-cuts/ | title=Zim hip-hop artist Diego Tryno delays album release.... Manager blames power cuts| date=2019-12-06}}</ref>\n|| 2018\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| ''Lazarus (Age vol1)''<br />\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"|  \"Mama\"<ref>{{Cite web | url=https://raddio.net/218582-yami-radio/ |title = Yami Radio - United Kingdom - Listen Live Online Free Radio Station}}</ref>\n|| 2019\n| \u2014 || \u2014 || \u2014\n| \"Single\"<br />\n|}\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [https://www.afro.video/en/artist/diego-tryno/ Video]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=6FKTP34EKFU Bio]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=Zrsbl9UXGcw Interview on Star FM]\n* [https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=DEfrfvZJq88 Interview on Hevoi FM]\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Tryno, Diego}}\n[[Category:Zimbabwean musicians]]\n[[Category:Zimbabwean hip hop musicians]]\n[[Category:1998 births]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n", "name_user": "BeckGoldberg", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Diego_Tryno"}
{"title_page": "Serudung language", "text_new": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Serudung Murut\n|nativename=''Tidong''\n|states=[[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]]\n|region=[[Borneo]]\n|ethnicity=1,000 [[Tidung people]] (2015)<ref name=e19/>\n|speakers=400|date=2015|ref=e19\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3=[[North Bornean languages|North Bornean]]\n|fam4=[[Southwest Sabahan languages|Southwest Sabahan]]\n|fam5=[[Paitanic languages|Paitanic]]\n|iso3=srk\n|glotto=seru1246\n|glottorefname=Serudung Murut\n|script=Unwritten\n}}\n\n'''Serudung Murut''', or '''Serudung''', is one of several [[Sabahan language]] of [[Borneo]] spoken by the [[Tidong people]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bornean languages}}\n{{Languages of Indonesia}}\n{{Languages of Malaysia}}\n\n{{au-lang-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Paitanic languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Sabah]]\n[[Category:Languages of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Endangered Austronesian languages]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox language\n|name=Serudung Murut\n|nativename=Tidong\n|states=[[Indonesia]], [[Malaysia]]\n|region=[[Borneo]]\n|ethnicity=1,000 [[Tidung people]] (2015)<ref name=e19/>\n|speakers=400|date=2015|ref=e19\n|familycolor=Austronesian\n|fam2=[[Malayo-Polynesian languages|Malayo-Polynesian]]\n|fam3=[[North Bornean languages|North Bornean]]\n|fam4=[[Southwest Sabahan languages|Southwest Sabahan]]\n|fam5=[[Paitanic languages|Paitanic]]\n|iso3=srk\n|glotto=seru1246\n|glottorefname=Serudung Murut\n|script=Unwritten\n}}\n\n'''Serudung Murut''', or '''Serudung''', is one of several [[Sabahan language]] of [[Borneo]] spoken by the [[Tidong people]].\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Bornean languages}}\n{{Languages of Indonesia}}\n{{Languages of Malaysia}}\n\n{{au-lang-stub}}\n\n[[Category:Paitanic languages]]\n[[Category:Languages of Sabah]]\n[[Category:Languages of Malaysia]]\n[[Category:Languages of Indonesia]]\n[[Category:Endangered Austronesian 